<DIV1 N="6" TYPE="tract"><PB REF="00000180.tif" N="114">
<HEAD>VI. OF CLERKS POSSESSIONERS.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>I HESITATE to pronounce an opinion as to the authorship of this tract. In expression it often resembles IV. and VII., but it has points of likeness to others which I cannot assign to the same hand. The mention of the voice heard at the first endowment of the Church (Chap. IX.), and the reference to the parallel between the three estates and the persons of the Trinity (see opening of Chapters XXXI. XXXII. XXXIII.), connect it with No. XXVI.</P><P>There are touches of irony (<I>e.g.</I> Chap. VIII.) which are like Wyclif, and the phrase "Antichrist's martyrs" (Chap. X.) is applied to the "irreligious that have possessions," in a tract on the Seven Works of Mercy, which is probably genuine (S. E. W., III. 171).</P><P>If the tract be Wyclif's, we may date it rather before 1380. The friars are already a bad set who "bear the banner" for subtlety and sham poverty, but they are not yet the habitual adversaries whom Wyclif cannot refrain from attacking.</P><P>Copied from the Corpus MS. X. and collated with the Dublin MS. AA.</P><P><TABLE>
<HEAD>SUMMARY.</HEAD>
<ROW>
<CELL>CHAP. I.</CELL>
<CELL>Clerks possessioners destroy priesthood, knighthood, and the commonalty.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL></CELL>
<CELL>Priesthood, by giving themselves to worldly business, by appropriation and its consequences, by luxurious life and neglect of preaching.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL></CELL>
<CELL>Knighthood, by taking into amortisement lands which should sustain knights to govern the people.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL></CELL>
<CELL>The commons by depriving them of the services of priests and knights, by oppression in rents and fines, and by wasteful expenditure.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>II.</CELL>
<CELL>They say by their deeds that Christ's example is insufficient.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>III.</CELL>
<CELL>They disobey God, and teach that lords may not amend them, nor commons withdraw their tithes.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>IV.</CELL>
<CELL>They set their rules above Christ's, and punish breaking them more severely than idle swearing.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>V.</CELL>
<CELL>They shelter themselves under the names of saints, but live wickedly.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>VI.</CELL>
<CELL>They tell lies about saints to colour their own worldly life.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>VII.</CELL>
<CELL>They get goods under pretence of spending them in alms and spend them on pomp.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>VIII.</CELL>
<CELL>They take upon themselves heavier burdens than did Christ, since they add worldly lordship to the duties of the priesthood; and of these conflicting calls they attend most to the unworthy.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>IX.</CELL>
<CELL>Secular lordships in the church lead to simony, and wealth of the orders brings men to them for ease and luxurious life.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>X.</CELL>
<CELL>The possessioners are Antichrist's martyrs, dead to holiness, who will spend money and life to maintain their worldly possessions.</CELL>

<PB REF="00000181.tif" N="115">
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>CHAP. XI.</CELL>
<CELL>They preach seldom, and then for show, and hinder those who would truly preach the gospel.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>XII.</CELL>
<CELL>Monks and canons profess a rule of community of goods, yet they hold property.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>XIII.</CELL>
<CELL>They hold rules made by sinful men more perfect than those made by Christ, letting a monk become a friar, while he may not become a simple priest.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>XIV.</CELL>
<CELL>They care more for the praise of men than for the praise of God.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>XV.</CELL>
<CELL>They bind themselves to contradictories, to be dead to the world, and to do worldly business at command of the abbot.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>XVI.</CELL>
<CELL>They set the worse above the better, man's rule above Christ's; and if any will leave their order for a better life, they persecute him.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>XVII.</CELL>
<CELL>Their wasteful use of goods belonging to the poor, in dress that is too costly and much too large and loose.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>XVIII.</CELL>
<CELL>They engross to themselves all the good books, and will neither lend nor use them.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>XIX.</CELL>
<CELL>They give hospitality only to the rich and oppress the poor.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>XX.</CELL>
<CELL>They visit widows and orphans, but only to get their property.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>XXI.</CELL>
<CELL>They mislead lords into persecuting God's servants.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>XXII.</CELL>
<CELL>They claim licence to commit crime, by denying the right of the civil power to deprive them of property.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>XXIII.</CELL>
<CELL>They make men leave the study of holy things to attend to worldly business.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>XXIV.</CELL>
<CELL>They are insatiable, trying to get all property into their dead hands.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>XXV.</CELL>
<CELL>They are quick to plead in the courts, and, beside, are ready to damn those who deny their demands.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>XXVI.</CELL>
<CELL>They incite to war and so slay men.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>XXVII.</CELL>
<CELL>They oppress the meek and uphold the proud.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>XXVIII.</CELL>
<CELL>They pretend to watch, but sleep more than other men.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>XXIX.</CELL>
<CELL>They inveigle young children into their orders.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>XXX.</CELL>
<CELL>Their deceits as to special prayer.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>XXXI.</CELL>
<CELL>They persecute Christ in the persons of his true disciples.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>XXXII.</CELL>
<CELL>They blaspheme against the Holy Ghost by stopping preaching.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>XXXIII.</CELL>
<CELL>They blaspheme the Father by preventing lords from maintaining God's ordinance as to the clergy.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>XXXIV.</CELL>
<CELL>They do away with the rule, on which they are founded, of abstinence, poverty and labour.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>XXXV.</CELL>
<CELL>They are strong thieves who rob the church of the spiritual goods of poverty, simplicity, and meekness.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>XXXVI.</CELL>
<CELL>They mislead lords, interpreting the oath to maintain the church as up|holding them in their possessions even if wrongful.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>XXXVII.</CELL>
<CELL>They are heretics, but they bring charges of heresy against true preachers to blind the people.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>XXXVIII.</CELL>
<CELL>They accuse true preachers of stirring up strife, but it is themselves who are in fault.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>XXXIX.</CELL>
<CELL>They care more that respect should be paid to them than to God, and, like the Jews, persecute for fear of losing their possessions and honour.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>XL.</CELL>
<CELL>They get all lordships into their hands, but will not pay taxes.</CELL>
</ROW>
</TABLE></P></HEADNOTE>

<PB REF="00000182.tif" N="116">
<EPIGRAPH>
<Q>&THORN;is is of clerkis possessioneris.</Q>
</EPIGRAPH>
<DIV2 N="1" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum primum.</HEAD>
<P><MILESTONE N="107" UNIT="page">Clerkis possessioneris fordon presthod, kny&yogh;thod &amp; comineris; for &thorn;ei taken &thorn;e ordre of presthod &amp; bynden hem to kepe &thorn;is<NOTE PLACE="foot">his X.</NOTE> ordre &amp; holi lif &amp; techynge of goddis peple aftir cristis lif &amp; his apostlis, &amp; specialy in verrey mekenesse &amp; <NOTE PLACE="foot">in AA.</NOTE> wilful pouert &amp; bisi traueile in techynge of goddis lawe &amp; wilful de&thorn; suffrynge &thorn;er-fore. But bi &thorn;es worldly possessions and lordischipis &thorn;ei ben turned to pompe &amp; pride &amp; coueitise &amp; grete bisynesse of worldly plees &amp; worldly festis &amp; seculer lawis, &thorn;at deuocion &amp; holy meditacion &amp; studyynge &amp; techynge of cristis holy gospel is for&yogh;eten, &amp; discencion among cristene men brou&yogh;t in, &amp; meyntenynge of wrongis &amp; oppressynge of pore men bi here worldly power and cautelis holden vp. also &thorn;ei taken benefices wi&thorn; cure bi appropriacion, &thorn;at is maad bi fals suggestion &amp; symonye, &amp; techen not &thorn;e parischenes goddis lawe ne mynystre hem sacramentis ne releuen pore men wi&thorn; residue of ti&thorn;es &amp; offrynges. But setten &thorn;er a viker or a parische prest for litel cost, &thorn;ou&yogh; he be vnable bo&thorn;e of kunnynge and lif to reule his owene soule, &amp; for pouert of benefis he may not go to scole, ne lerne at hom for bisynesse of newe syngynge &amp; gedrynge of ty&thorn;es &amp; mynystringe of sacramentis &amp; o&thorn;ere occupacions. &amp; &thorn;us wise clerkis ben putt out fro benefices &thorn;at my&yogh;ten, couden and wolden teche &thorn;e peple &thorn;e gospel &amp; goddis hestis, &amp; blynde lederis ful of coueitise, lecherie &amp; o&thorn;ere synnes brou&yogh;t in; &amp; almes doynge to pore men of &thorn;e parische &amp; hospitalite &amp; fyndynge of pore children to scole &amp; so clergie aftirward ben outlawid. also &thorn;ei taken &thorn;e ordre of presthod to seie massis for money, &amp; whanne &thorn;ei schulden be gostly li&yogh;t of &thorn;e world bi opyn ensaumple of holy lif &amp; trewe prechynge of holy writt, as crist comaundid to alle his apostlis &amp; disciplis, &thorn;ei hiden hem self in gay cloistris &amp; lyuen in lustis of flech &amp; glotonye, 
<PB REF="00000183.tif" N="117"> drounkenesse &amp; ydelnesse &amp; sleep. &amp; as &thorn;ei feynen &thorn;ei ben exempt from prechynge, &thorn;at crist comaunde&thorn; to prestis, bi profession maad to synful foolis &amp; in cas to sathanas &thorn;at teche&thorn; hem &thorn;e contrarie of goddis comaundementis; &amp; &yogh;if ony such religious be stirid bi charite &amp; conscience to goo to cristene peple &amp; preche hem goddis lawe he schal be lettid bi anticristis obedience vp peyne of dedly synne &amp; prisonynge &amp; sumtyme of bodely de&thorn;. &amp; &thorn;us &thorn;es possessioneris, &amp; namely religious, leuen goddis comaundement &amp; <MILESTONE N="108" UNIT="page">werkis of mercy &amp; charite vndon for obedience of synful men, And distroien presthod &amp; trewe techynge &amp; holi lif of &thorn;e peple in eche degree. &para; Also &thorn;ei distroien kny&yogh;thod bi wiles of &thorn;e fend, for &thorn;ei<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted X.</NOTE> han grete lordischipis amorteised to hem; bi whiche lord|schipis kny&yogh;tis schulden be susteyned to gouerne &thorn;e peple &amp; &thorn;ei moten now faile bo&thorn;e in noumbre &amp; power; &amp; &thorn;is amorteisynge come&thorn; in bi ypocrisie of preiynge be mou&thorn; &thorn;at is preised of hem more &thorn;an prechynge of &thorn;e gospel; but certis &thorn;is is<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted X.</NOTE> merueile, for none of alle &thorn;es &thorn;at preien &thorn;us whot where his preiynge schal turne in-to his owene damp|nacion, and &thorn;an is it litel wor&thorn; to o&thorn;ere synful men; &amp; almy&yogh;tti god sei&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;e sacrafices of wickid men ben abhomi|nable<NOTE PLACE="marg">Prov. xv. 8.</NOTE> and that he schal curse to here blissynges; &amp; &thorn;e preire of &thorn;at man &thorn;at turne&thorn; awey his erris to here not goddis lawe<NOTE PLACE="marg">Prov. xxviii. 9.</NOTE> is abhominable or cursed; &amp;<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted AA.</NOTE> &thorn;anne si&thorn; god comaundi&thorn; so often in his lawe bo&thorn;e olde &amp; newe &thorn;at clerkis ne schulden haue non seculer lordischipis &amp; &thorn;ei hauen so many, &amp; so faste meyntenen hem, here preynge is cursed &amp; abhominable. And &yogh;if seynt austyn, seynt gregory &amp; seynt bernard &amp; o&thorn;ere seyntis &amp; reson wi&thorn; manere of lyuynge of &thorn;es proude posses|sioneris ben wel sou&yogh;t in matere of preiynge, &thorn;ere wole seue a sentence of grete wepynge &amp; mornynge, schewynge how men ben disceyued bi ypocritis preire bo&thorn;e in fei&thorn; hope &amp; charite &amp; worldely goodis &amp; pees &amp; reste. for &yogh;if a lord or a laborer loue betere god &thorn;an &thorn;es veyn religious &amp; proude &amp; lecherous possessioneris, &thorn;e lewid manys preiere is betere 
<PB REF="00000184.tif" N="118"> &thorn;an alle here criynge &amp; knackynge; &amp; certis it were ra&thorn;ere almes to lordis to hire suche proude clerkis to seie nei&thorn;er masse ne matines in &thorn;is cursed lif &thorn;an to holde &amp; to meyntene hem in &thorn;is manere preiynge; for her lyf<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted X.</NOTE> is blasphemye vnto god, as austyn sei&thorn;; &amp; &thorn;ei stiren god of treu&thorn;e ra&thorn;ere to vengaunce &thorn;an to mercy, as seynt gregori sei&thorn;. And &thorn;erfore seynt ierom criede &amp; wrot to his de&thorn; &thorn;at clerkis schulden lyue on dymes &amp; offrynges &thorn;at is goddis part &amp; not haue seculer lordischipis ne worldly richesses, but in pouert sue cristis cros: &amp; seynt bede wrot to &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted X.</NOTE> erchebischop of &yogh;ork &thorn;at &yogh;ifte of kynges whanne &thorn;ei &yogh;auen temporaltes to clerkis was most fool &yogh;euynge, &amp; telli&thorn; many harmes comynge &thorn;er-of; &amp; &thorn;erfore whanne seynt austyn sey<NOTE PLACE="foot">se&thorn; X.</NOTE> his clerkis wexe proude for litel rente &thorn;at &thorn;ei hadden he priede &thorn;e peple of his cite to taken &thorn;e rentis a&yogh;en and suffre hem lyue on goddis part, &thorn;at ben ti&thorn;es &amp; offrynges, as &thorn;e holy martir possidonye writti&thorn; of seynt austynes lif. &THORN;anne si&thorn; trewe techynge of curatis is leid doun by apropriacion of parische chirches, &amp; kny&yogh;tthod bi amorteysynge of temporal|tees is mochel distroied, &amp; &thorn;e pore peple hard piled bi coueitouse clerkis opynly; it sue&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;es proude posses|sioneris distroien &thorn;e comunes of &thorn;e lond, si&thorn; &thorn;ei fordon trewe techynge bi curatis &amp; clerkis &amp; good <MILESTONE N="109" UNIT="page">gouernaile bi kny&yogh;ttis, &amp; ben cruel in gedrynge of here rentis &amp; mercymentis more &thorn;an lordis wolden, and &yogh;euen ensaumple of pride &amp; coueitise &amp; wrongful meyntenynge of worldly plees a&yogh;enst ri&yogh;t &amp; good conscience, &amp; letten almes of curatis, &amp; wasten pore mennys liflode in pride &amp; glotonye &amp; worldly array more &thorn;an grete lordis may wel atteynen to.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="2" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum 2<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>Also &thorn;es possessioneris seyn in dede &thorn;at cristis lif &amp; en|saumpel &thorn;er-of is insufficient &amp; lif sikerere<NOTE PLACE="foot">sikere X.</NOTE> bi worldly lawes is betre; for &thorn;ei forsaken pore lif &amp; meke aftir crist &amp; his 
<PB REF="00000185.tif" N="119"> apostlis, &amp; taken worldly sykernesse for &thorn;e betre; &amp; her<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;er AA.</NOTE> &thorn;ei blasphemen crist &amp; ben out of ri&yogh;t fei&thorn;. And &yogh;if &thorn;ei witten &thorn;at cristis lyf<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted X.</NOTE> and trewe<NOTE PLACE="foot">treule X.</NOTE> lif of clerkis ensaumplid &thorn;er-aftir is best &amp; most esy &amp; most siker for &thorn;e soule, &thorn;ei ben oute of charite to forsake &thorn;e best tau&yogh;t [&amp;] ensaumplid of crist, and to take a lif ordeyned of synful foolis &amp; coueitouse of worldly pride &amp; name &amp; auer; &amp; &yogh;if &thorn;ei meyntenen stifly &thorn;is errour &thorn;ei ben stronge heretikis.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="3" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum 3<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>Proude possessioners ben traitours of god, of lordis &amp; of &thorn;e comune peple. &thorn;ei ben traitours of god, for &thorn;ei distroien his ordynaunce &thorn;at he made for clerkis, &amp; in stede of mekenesse &amp; wilful pouert &amp; discrete penaunce brengen in coueitise, pride &amp; wombe ioie and ydelnesse. &amp; &thorn;ei bryngen lordis<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted X.</NOTE> in &thorn;is errour of bileue, &thorn;at &thorn;ei ben in dette to meyn|tenen hem in &thorn;is worldly lif, &amp; &thorn;at lordis may not mayntene<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted X.</NOTE> cristis ordynaunce in clerkis for drede of anticristis curs &amp; brekyng of here o&thorn; bi whiche &thorn;ei ben sworne to meyntene holy chirche; for &thorn;at &thorn;at is &thorn;e fendis chirc[he], &thorn;at ben proude clerkis &amp; coueitouse, &thorn;ei clepen holy chirche to turnen alle &thorn;ing vpsodoun as anticristis disciplis. &amp; &thorn;at &thorn;at is holy chirche, &thorn;at ben trewe techeris of cristis mekenesse, wilful pouert &amp; gostly traueile &amp; meyntenours of cristis ordynaunce, &thorn;ei clepen heretikis &amp; pursuen hem to &thorn;e de&thorn; worse &thorn;an don he&thorn;ene men, for no man schulde be hardi to teche &amp; meyn|tene holy writt a&yogh;enst here cursed lif. &amp; &thorn;ei bryngen comunes in &thorn;is errour, &thorn;at &yogh;if &thorn;ei taken ony &thorn;ing preuely or apertly fro anticristis chirche &amp; his clerkis &thorn;ei schullen be cursed &amp; prisoned &amp; dampnyd in helle; &yogh;e, &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;es worldly coueitouse clerkis lyuen neuere so opynly a&yogh;enst goddis lawe, &amp; techen opynly cursed heresie. &amp; &thorn;ei techen &thorn;e comune peple &thorn;at &thorn;ei schullen haue goddis blissyng &amp; blisse of heuene &yogh;if &thorn;ei paien treuly here ti&thorn;es &amp; offryngis to hem, whanne &thorn;ei lyuen in opyn lecherie &amp; coueitise &amp; don no &thorn;ing here 
<PB REF="00000186.tif" N="120"> gostly office, but bi word &amp; ensaumple of euyl lif leden &thorn;e peple to helle.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="4" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum 4<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>Also &thorn;es possessioners setten more pris bi reulis of synful men &thorn;an bi reulis of ih&umacr; crist god &amp; man; for &thorn;ei taken reulis of synful men as benetis &amp; o&thorn;ere popis and holden hem more perfit &thorn;an &thorn;e clene reule of crist. &amp; &thorn;ei cha[r]gen more to breke suche tradiciouns <MILESTONE N="110" UNIT="page">maad of synful men &thorn;an to breke &thorn;e comaundementis of god &amp; poyntis of charite; &amp; for to proue &thorn;is, loke where a prest or monk schal ben hardere ponyschid for brekynge of &thorn;e popis lawe or of benetis reule, &yogh;e, for brekynge of here owene statutis, &thorn;an for ydel sweryng of herte &amp; bonys of crist &amp; brekynge of &thorn;e holy day; &amp; here-bi may men see where &thorn;es possessioners louen &amp; dreden more goddis hestis or synful mennys tradicions.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="5" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum 5<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>&YOGH;it &thorn;es possessioners entren vnder colour of seyntis &amp; lyuen alle a&yogh;enst &thorn;es seyntis; for &thorn;ei comen in vnder colour of seynt benet &amp; seynt austyn to lyue in mekenesse &amp; pouert &amp; bi labour of here hondis for her liflode, and bi ypocrisie &thorn;ei rennen in-to pride, coueitise, worldly worschipe &amp; welfare &amp; idelnesse, &amp; ben wode whanne men tellen &thorn;e so&thorn;e of cristis gospel &amp; his pore lif &amp; &thorn;e so&thorn;e of here owene reule &amp; profes|sion; for bi &thorn;is techynge here ypocrise and lesyngis schulde be knowen, &amp; &thorn;ei be turned to here first ground or ellis for|saken al. &amp; &thorn;is wheren grete peyne for proude men &amp; delicat; &amp; &thorn;erfore &thorn;ei maken a scheld of ypocrisie &amp; worldly frendischipe a&yogh;enst &thorn;is treu&thorn;e.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="6" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum 6<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>Also &thorn;es proude possessioners lien on seyntis &amp; sclaundren hem wi&thorn; worldly lif to coloure &thorn;er-by here owene false pride; for &thorn;ei writen &thorn;at &thorn;is is benetis lif &amp; thomas of canterburies, 
<PB REF="00000187.tif" N="121"> whanne &thorn;ei lyueden &amp; endeden in contrarie manere. And &thorn;ei bryngen for&thorn; poyntis of here worldlynesse whanne &thorn;ei diden a&yogh;enst holy lif &amp; techynge of crist, &amp; hiden here grete sorowe &amp; penaunce &thorn;at &thorn;ei diden for s[i]ch wildenessis; &amp; alle &thorn;is is for &thorn;ei wolden coloure here owene synne bi &thorn;es seyntis &amp; maken &thorn;e peple wene &thorn;at &thorn;es seyntis camen to heuene bi &thorn;is mir&thorn;e of worldly lyuynge &amp; likynge of here flesch; &amp; &thorn;us &thorn;ei brengen cristene<NOTE PLACE="foot">cristis AA.</NOTE> peple in errour a&yogh;enst &thorn;e fei&thorn; bi lesyngis putt on seyntis.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="7" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum 7<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>&THORN;es proude possessioners ben &thorn;eues &amp; heretikis; for &thorn;ei comen bi false menys as ypocrisie &amp; lesyngis to &thorn;es grete lordischipes &amp; bi colour to spende hem in almes of pore men, but &thorn;ei wasten hem in glotonye &amp; pompe &amp; pride &amp; worldely gaynesse, as pelure &amp; costelewe<NOTE PLACE="foot">costelewo X.</NOTE> clo&thorn;is &amp; proude slitterede squyerys &amp; haukis &amp; hondis &amp; mynstralis &amp; ryche men; &amp; bi colour &thorn;at crist was &thorn;us worldly lord, &thorn;erfore &thorn;ei schulden haue &thorn;us seculer lordischipis bi heritage of crist as his most wor&thorn;i seruauntis; but crist sei&thorn; in &thorn;e gospel of seynt ion<NOTE PLACE="marg">John xviii. 36.</NOTE> &thorn;at his kyngdom is not of &thorn;is world, &amp; hadde not bi worldly lordischipis where onne to resten his owene hed; &thorn;erfore it is heresie to putten &thorn;is seculer lordischipe on crist, &amp; herbi disceyuen cristene men in fei&thorn; &amp; worldly goodis, &amp; maken hem to meyntenen clerkis in here<NOTE PLACE="foot">his X (corrected by a later hand).</NOTE> heresie.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="8" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum 8<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>Also &thorn;es ypocrit is possessionerschargen hem self more &thorn;an crist <MILESTONE N="111" UNIT="page">and his apostelis wolden or my&yogh;tten, &amp; wittyngly take &thorn;e werse &amp; leuen &thorn;e betre. For bi als moche as &thorn;ei haue seculer possessions more &thorn;an crist &amp; his apostlis hadden &thorn;ei ben bi &thorn;at bounden &thorn;e more, &amp; &thorn;ei ben bounden to holy lif &amp; trewe techynge bi presthod in as mochil as &thorn;ei may &thorn;erfore; &amp; &thorn;ei taken bisynesse of &thorn;e world &amp; leuen studiynge &amp; 
<PB REF="00000188.tif" N="122"> techynge of holy writt &amp; deuocioun in preiere &amp; &thorn;inkynge of heuenely swettenesse; &amp; &thorn;ei chesen ra&thorn;ere to lyue vnder synguler obedience &amp; profession maad to worldly foolis &thorn;an to lyue bi forne of &thorn;e gospel in &thorn;at fredom &thorn;at crist &yogh;af to prestis. &amp; &thorn;erfore &thorn;ei ben many times nedid &amp; bi ypocrisie disceyued to leue goddis hestis vndon &amp; to performe &thorn;e wrongful biddynge of anticrist; &amp; bi &thorn;is feyned obedience is strif &amp; enuye brou&yogh;t in and pride &amp; worldly lordischipe meyntened in dede men; &amp; &thorn;us &thorn;ei risen fro vertue to synne, fro mekenes to pride, fro wilful pouert to coueitise &amp; lordischipe, fro grete penaunce &amp; gostly traueile to glotonye &amp; ydelnesse.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="9" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum 9<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>&THORN;es seculer lordischipis in clerkis bryngen<NOTE PLACE="foot">brengynne X.</NOTE> in symonye, coueytise &amp; glotonye &amp; ydolatrie, &thorn;at is worschipynge of false goddis; for bi cause of &thorn;is lordischipis men comen to grete prelacies &amp; o&thorn;ere degres of &thorn;e chirche bi money &amp; worldly fauour &amp; pledynge &amp; fi&yogh;ttynge, where &thorn;ei schulden come to hem bi mekenesse and holy lif &amp; bisy traueile in studiynge &amp; techynge of goddis lawe; &amp; feyned religious possessioners comen to &thorn;es ordris for sikernesse of worldly welfare &amp; pride &amp; eise of body, where &thorn;e schulden come to hem to be dede to &thorn;e world &amp; to lyuen in penaunce &amp;<NOTE PLACE="foot">of X.</NOTE> streit pouert as cristis apostlis, &amp; &thorn;us &thorn;ei suen &thorn;is holy staat of pouert &amp; penaunce for worldly richesse &amp; wombe ioie. And herfore &thorn;ei ben ful of symonye &amp; heresie, as reson &amp; lawe techen, &amp; &thorn;ei wasten moche good in ryot &amp; glotonye &amp; pledynde &amp; meyntenynge of wrongis a&yogh;enst pore gentil men &amp; comunes. And si&thorn; al &thorn;es wastid goodis ben pore mennus liflode, as ierom &amp; lawe techen, &amp; he &thorn;at defraude&thorn; pore men &thorn;er-of is a man of blood spilid, &thorn;es possessioners ben mansleeris &amp; irreguler &amp; cursed of god; &amp; si&thorn; coueitise &amp; glotonye ben seruage of maunmetrie, as poul sei&thorn;, &thorn;es possessioners honouren false goddis. for &thorn;es<NOTE PLACE="marg">Colossians iii. 5.</NOTE> skillis &amp; many mo &thorn;e angel seyd ful so&thorn;e whanne &thorn;e chirche 
<PB REF="00000189.tif" N="123"> was dowid &thorn;at &thorn;is day is venym sched in-to &thorn;e chirche; for &thorn;ei &thorn;at schulden be most meke &amp; wilful pore &amp; in most deuocion &amp; myrrour of alle vertues to worldly men ben now turned in-to luciferis pride &amp; sathanas coueitise and anticristis ypocrisie &amp; ydelnesse, &amp; ben myrrour of alle synnes, &amp; no tonge in &thorn;is lif can telle &thorn;e harmes her-of.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="10" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum 10<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>&YOGH;it &thorn;es proude possessioners ben anticristis martiris, for &thorn;ei <MILESTONE N="112" UNIT="page">ben reised bi hym fro de&thorn; of<NOTE PLACE="foot">or X.</NOTE> worldlynesse and vanyte to lif of lordis and werris &amp; falsnesse; for in here profession &thorn;ei ben holden dede to &thorn;e world &amp; vanyte &amp;<NOTE PLACE="foot">of X.</NOTE> likynge &thorn;er-of. But in desirynge &amp; holdynge seculer lordischipis &amp; worldly honour &amp; delicat mete &amp; drynk &amp; gaye clo&thorn;is &thorn;ei schewen in dede &thorn;at &thorn;ei ben ri&yogh;t freisch in bodely lif, but I suppose &thorn;at &thorn;ei ben dede to holynesse &amp; penaunce &amp; profitynge to o&thorn;ere men; &amp; namely &thorn;ei schewen &thorn;is reisynge in pledynge &amp; werrynge in here owene persones, &amp; in counseilynge o&thorn;ere men to werre on cristene men for worldly goodis; for &thorn;at &thorn;ei don more cruelly &thorn;an worldly lordis, as men knowen of pletynge &amp; conseilynge to werris. &thorn;erfore it seme&thorn; to summe men &thorn;at &thorn;ei feynen hem dede to gete pray of worldly lordi|schipis &amp; richesse; as &thorn;e fox feyne&thorn; hym dede til<NOTE PLACE="foot">to X.</NOTE> briddis comen to his tounge, &amp; &thorn;anne he schewi&thorn; hym on lyue deuourynge &amp; swelwynge of hem; &amp; &thorn;us &thorn;ei ben dede to profitynge of o&thorn;ere men &amp; here temporaltees ben mortesid, &thorn;at is confermyd in &thorn;is de&thorn;, for &thorn;ei comen neuere to seculer men &yogh;if &thorn;ei may, &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;ei ben getyn bi neuere so fals title &amp; a&yogh;enst conscience; for &thorn;ei wolen not see mennys ri&yogh;t, ne worsche aftir good<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted X.</NOTE> conscience, but bosten of &thorn;ousand markis &amp; &thorn;ousand poundis &thorn;at &thorn;ei wolen coste in plee bi-fore &thorn;at &thorn;ei lesen ony fote of lond; &amp; of suche religious wrecchis sei&thorn; Robert grosted &thorn;at siche on is a dede careyne gon out of his sepulcre wlappid with clo&thorn;is of mornynge,<NOTE PLACE="foot">morynge X.</NOTE> dryuen &amp; stirid 
<PB REF="00000190.tif" N="124"> of &thorn;e deuyl among men. And for &thorn;is worldly lif &amp; coueitise &thorn;ei wolen coste &amp; die to meyntene it; but for to meyntene &thorn;e treu&thorn;e of cristis lif in mekenesse &amp; pouert &amp; bisi traueile in prechynge &thorn;e gospel &thorn;ei wolen not traueile, but ra&thorn;ere pursue hem to de&thorn; &thorn;at traueilen for &thorn;is holy lif; &amp; &thorn;us &thorn;ei lyuen in delices of &thorn;e world &amp; here flech, &amp; &thorn;erfore &thorn;ei ben dede to god as poul sei&thorn;, &amp; so &thorn;ei lyuen anticristis lif &amp;<NOTE PLACE="marg">Romans viii. 13.</NOTE> meyntene &thorn;at to here de&thorn; a&yogh;enst cristis lif and lawe &amp; techeris &thorn;er-of.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="11" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum 11<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>&YOGH;it proude possessioners ben anticristis, for &thorn;ei letten trewe men to preche &thorn;e gospel of ih&umacr; crist &amp; suffren not &thorn;e peple knowe goddis lawe bi whiche &thorn;ei schulden be sauyd. For prestis &thorn;us dowid ben so occupied aboute &thorn;e world and newe seruyce and song &amp; feyned obedience to worldly foolis &thorn;at &thorn;ei may not studie &amp; preche goddis lawe in contre to cristis peple. &para;And &yogh;if &thorn;ei preche selde whanne &thorn;ei prechen cronyclis &amp; poisies &amp; newe fyndynges<NOTE PLACE="foot">feyndyngis AA.</NOTE> of hem self, &amp; maken false comendaciones of dede men for to geten a name of veyn sotilte &amp; worldly &thorn;ank, &amp; leuen to preche cristis gospel and his lywynge; &amp; &yogh;if o&thorn;ere men wolen treuly &amp; frely preche &thorn;e gospel &amp; dispise synne, as crist comaunde&thorn;, &thorn;es proude possessioneris<NOTE PLACE="foot">possioners X.</NOTE> letten hem bi cautelis of anticristis censuris &amp; worldly power &amp; sclaundrynge &amp; prisonynge, &amp; dryuen hem <MILESTONE N="113" UNIT="page">out of londe &amp; ellis brennen hem &yogh;if &thorn;ei may. &amp; &thorn;is is for drede leeste cristis pore lif &amp; meke &amp; traueilous &amp; peyneful be knowen, &amp; hou clerkis &amp; namely religious ben bounden to holde sich pore lif &amp; meke &amp; peyneful in<NOTE PLACE="foot">and X.</NOTE> reson|able abstynence, &amp; traueile in<NOTE PLACE="foot">and X.</NOTE> studiynge &amp; prechynge of holy writt, &amp; ellis as crist sei&thorn; &thorn;ei schulde be put out &amp; dispised of men; for bi &thorn;is prechynge here worldly lif &amp; coueitise schulde awey &amp; penaunce &amp; traueyle come a&yogh;en.</P>


</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="12" TYPE="chapter"><PB REF="00000191.tif" N="125">
<HEAD>Capitulum 12<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>&THORN;es proude possessioners ben rotid in lesyngis a&yogh;enst crist &amp; his trew&thorn;e, for as seynt bernard &amp; anselme seyn monkis &amp; chanons ben bounden to &thorn;e same lif &thorn;at pore men of ierusalem helden after sendynge doun of &thorn;e holy gost. And &thorn;ei selden<NOTE PLACE="foot">senden X.</NOTE> her possessions &amp; putten &thorn;e pris to alle cristene in comyn conuertid &amp; &thorn;er was no nedy man amongis hem. For it was &yogh;ouen to eche man as<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted X.</NOTE> it was nede, &amp; non of hem seide &thorn;at ony &thorn;ing was his owene; but alle &thorn;ingis weren in comune to hem. but monkis &amp; chanons appropren alle &thorn;ingis to hem self &amp; not to comunete of cristene men; &amp; &thorn;es possessioners seyn in word &thorn;at alle &thorn;ingis ben comune, but in dede &thorn;ei han proprete &amp; stryuen &amp; pleden &thorn;erfore; &yogh;it seynt ierom &amp; anselm seyn &thorn;at &thorn;e croune of clerkis crie&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">treith (?), <I>may be</I> creith X.</NOTE> pouert, &amp; here clo&thorn;inge crie&thorn; honeste, holynesse &amp; forsakynge of &thorn;e world, &amp; helles here signes ben false &amp; &thorn;ei ben lesyng|mongeris &amp; lesynge in it-self. but now &thorn;ei ben riche &amp; proude &amp; coueitouse &amp; ful of enuye &amp; glotonye, &amp; ben &thorn;e fendis children for &thorn;ei louen &thorn;us lesyngis, as seynt ambrose sei&thorn;, &amp; &thorn;us &thorn;ei disceyuen &thorn;e peple bi ypocrisie.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="13" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum 13<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>Possessioners holden &thorn;at religion &thorn;at crist made lesse perfit &thorn;an is religioun founden of a synful man, for &thorn;ei holden a reule maade not of seyntis but of here owene worldly hedis more perfit &thorn;an religion of presthod &thorn;at crist<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted X.</NOTE> made in his fredom; for &thorn;ei holden here owene tradicions more perfit &thorn;an reulis &thorn;at crist made in &thorn;e gospel. for &yogh;if reulis of presthod maad in &thorn;e gospel were more perfit &thorn;an &thorn;e reules of newe monkis, it were laweful for a prest to leue here reules &amp; gon to reulis of presthod as crist made hym in &thorn;e gospel, for it is laweful to passe fro &thorn;e lasse perfit to &thorn;e more perfit, but monkis wolen not suffre for no reson, but &thorn;ei 
<PB REF="00000192.tif" N="126"> w[olen] suffre a monk goo to beggeris ordre whanne he axi&thorn; leue, &thorn;ou&yogh; hee gete it neuere; &amp; &thorn;us &thorn;ei holden &thorn;e ordre of beggeris maad of synful men more perfit &thorn;an religion of presthod maad of ih&umacr; crist god &amp; man.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="14" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum 14<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>Also &thorn;es possessioners dreden more lesynge of here tem|poraltees &thorn;an loos of goodis of vertue &amp; of charite, &amp; chargen more name &amp; preisynge of men &thorn;an preisynge and &thorn;ank of god; for &thorn;ei dreden more to displese lordis &amp; my&yogh;tty men, bi seynge &amp; meyntenynge of a profitable treu&thorn;e, for loos of here temporaltees &thorn;an to displese god bi suffrynge of opyn synne &amp; domnpnesse, for whiche &thorn;ei ben <MILESTONE N="114" UNIT="page">dampnable, as seynt poul sei&thorn;; &amp; &thorn;ei chargen more kepynge of here veyn sygnys<NOTE PLACE="marg">Romans i. 32.</NOTE> &amp; customes, for to haue preisynge of men &thorn;at &thorn;ei holden wele here religion, &thorn;an kepynge of goddis hestis &amp; poyntis of charite &amp; discret penaunce for preisynge &amp; &thorn;ank of god; &amp; here is<NOTE PLACE="foot">his X.</NOTE> foule ypocrisie &amp; cursed blaspheme &amp; forsakynge of god as seynt poul witnesse&thorn; plenerly in holy writt.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="15" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum 15<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>&THORN;es possessioners bynden hem self to contradiccion &amp; &thorn;ing &thorn;at is imposible; for &thorn;ei bynden hem self to be dede to &thorn;e world &amp; forsaken it &amp; bysynesse, &amp; on &thorn;e to&thorn;er side &thorn;ei bynden hem to obedience for to take worldli bisynesse aftir biddynge<NOTE PLACE="foot">byndynge X.</NOTE> of a worldly &amp; synful &amp; coueitous &amp; vnkunnynge abbot or priour, &amp; &thorn;is &thorn;ei moten do bi vertue of &thorn;is obedience, &thorn;ou&yogh; god stire hem to be betre occupied aboute studiynge &amp; techynge of holy writt, &amp; &thorn;us mannus comaundement is performyd bi blyndnesse &amp; ypocrisie &amp; goddis comaundement &amp; more profit of cristene soules is putte bihynde. But it seme&thorn; &thorn;ei forsaken hunger &amp; &thorn;urst<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;rest X.</NOTE> &amp; penaunce &amp; traueile to be lordis &amp; riche &amp; lyue in bodyli ayse on alle sidis; &amp; &thorn;us &thorn;e fend bi his worldly clerkis disceyue&thorn; men by colour 
<PB REF="00000193.tif" N="127"> of holynesse, &amp; brynge&thorn; hem to worldly lyuynge whanne &thorn;ei wenen to come out &thorn;er-of, &amp; &thorn;us caste&thorn; hem bi here owene turn.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="16" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum 16<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>&YOGH;it religious possessioners ben groundid &amp; holden for&thorn; bi blasphemye &amp; heresie; for &thorn;ei ben groundid on &thorn;is, &thorn;at statutis maad of a synful fool ben betere in here dom &thorn;an &thorn;e lawis &thorn;at crist ordeynede for prestis &amp; clerkis, for ellis &thorn;ei wittyngly forsoken<NOTE PLACE="foot">forsaken X.</NOTE> &thorn;e betre &amp; token<NOTE PLACE="foot">taken X.</NOTE> &thorn;e worse &amp; helden<NOTE PLACE="foot">holden X.</NOTE> it forth, &amp; weren out of charite. And &yogh;if &thorn;ei meyn|tenen an errour a&yogh;enst charite &thorn;ei ben heretikis; &amp; &yogh;if &thorn;ei seyn &thorn;at here reulis ben betre &thorn;an cristis reulis &yogh;ouen to prestis &amp; clerkis, &thorn;ei blasphemen a&yogh;enst god, &amp; so at &thorn;e begynnynge &thorn;ei ben blasphemys on alle sides or at &thorn;e leste knowen not cristene bileue; &amp; in holdynge for&thorn; comynly &thorn;ei ben blasphemys, for &thorn;ei letten a prest to lyue &amp; teche as crist comaundid in &thorn;e gospel, &amp; &thorn;ei letten a cristene man to serue his god in &thorn;e beste manere. For &yogh;if a prest of her feyned ordre wole lyue poreli &amp; iustly &amp; goo freli aboute &amp; teche frely goddis lawes, &thorn;ei holden him apostata &amp; prisonen hym, &amp; holden hym cursed for &thorn;is prestis lif comaundid, ensaumplid of crist &amp; his apostlis; &amp; so &yogh;if a cristene man wole forsake a wickid worldly couent ful of pride, ypocrisie, coueitise &amp; symonye, after snybbynge as crist teche&thorn; in &thorn;e gospel, &thorn;ei pursuen him<NOTE PLACE="foot">hem X.</NOTE> as apostata &amp; cursed man, for he do&thorn; as crist &amp; his apostelis techen; &amp; &thorn;is is cursed blasphemye of god. &amp; ne were &thorn;is prison &amp; sclaundrynge fewe goode men or none schulden dwelle amonge suche couentis for drede of consentynge to<NOTE PLACE="foot">consenynte of X.</NOTE> here synnes.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="17" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum 17<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P><MILESTONE N="115" UNIT="page">Also &thorn;es possessioners wasten bi ypocrisie nedeles many pore mennys goodis, for seculer possessioneris han many precious clo&thorn;is &amp; costy &amp; riche peluris; &amp; alle &thorn;is is wast 
<PB REF="00000194.tif" N="128"> of pore mennys goodis, si&thorn; bi here owen lawe what euere clerkis han is pore mennys, &amp; &thorn;ei schulde teche to cristene men bo&thorn;e in word<NOTE PLACE="foot">world X.</NOTE> &amp; ensaumple of here owene dedis &thorn;e pouert &amp; symplenesse of crist &amp; his apostlis. Also religious possessioneris wasten pore mennus goodis in wide clo&thorn;is &amp; precious, &thorn;at foure or fyue nedy men my&yogh;tten welle be clo&thorn;ed wi&thorn; o cope &amp;<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted X.</NOTE> hood of a monke, &amp; &thorn;at large clo&thorn; serue&thorn; to gidre wynd &amp; lette him to go &amp; do his dedis; &amp; &yogh;it &thorn;ei ben brou&yogh;t in-to chirche to reise vp cristis pouert &amp; his apostlis &amp; lyuen in mornynge and penaunce and to be deed to &thorn;e world;<NOTE PLACE="foot">worldly AA.</NOTE> but by ypocrisie al &thorn;is is turned vpsodoun, what in wast meyne and proude and hi&yogh;e houses and glotonie and ydulnesse. And so in ensaumple and dede &thorn;ey techen heresie and blynden<NOTE PLACE="foot">bynden X.</NOTE> &thorn;e people in feith and lyf of crist and his apostles to &thorn;e contrarie as cursed disciples of antecrist.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="18" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum 18.</HEAD>
<P>&YOGH;yt &thorn;es possessioners ben &thorn;eues and so striers of clergye and of good lif in the people, for &thorn;ei han manie bokes, and namely of holy writt, Summe by bygging and some by &yogh;ifte and testamentis and some bi<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted X.</NOTE> o&thorn;ere disceitis and sutiltees, and hyden hem from seculer clerkis &amp; suffren &thorn;es noble bokes wexe roten in here libraries, &amp; nei&thorn;er wolen sillen<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted X.</NOTE> hem ne lenen hem to o&thorn;ere clerkis &thorn;at wolden profiten bi studiynge in hem &amp; techen cristene peple &thorn;e weie to heuene. &amp; in &thorn;is defaute ben religious mendynauntis as principal &thorn;euys &amp; forgoeris of anticrist, &thorn;at seculeris &amp; curatis may almost gete no bok of value, and herby, as seynt Richard primat of<NOTE PLACE="marg">Defensio Cura|torum. Brown's Fasciculus, ii. 474.</NOTE> irland witnesse&thorn;, &thorn;ei casten to distroie clergie<NOTE PLACE="foot">clergise AA.</NOTE> of seculeris and trewe techynge of &thorn;e peple. lord si&thorn; &thorn;es bokis ben more nedeful to mannys good lif &thorn;an gold or siluer, &amp; he<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted X.</NOTE> is out of charite &thorn;at see&thorn; his bro&thorn;er haue nede of worldly sustenaunce &amp; helpi&thorn; him not whanne he may esely; hou moche more ben &thorn;es religious out of charite, &thorn;at helpen not 
<PB REF="00000195.tif" N="129"> seculer clerkis &amp; curatis of &thorn;es bokis nei&thorn;er be &yogh;ifte ne lenyng ne sillyng for no<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted X.</NOTE> money.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="19" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum 19<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>Clerkis possessioners ben foule out of charite &amp; blynden foule &thorn;e peple; for &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;ei han many grete houses, costlewe &amp; wasty, &amp; alle &thorn;at &thorn;ei han ouer here strecte<NOTE PLACE="foot">streyte AA.</NOTE> liflode is pore mennys, as here owen seyntis &amp; lawis seyn, &yogh;it pore men may not be herbwerid amongis hem in here grete castelis or paleis, but lordis, &amp; ladies namely, schullen soiouren<NOTE PLACE="foot">soiornen AA.</NOTE> amongis hem many &yogh;eris. lord, hou schulde &thorn;es traitours ben excused at domesday, si&thorn; crist sei&thorn; &thorn;o men &thorn;at not herberwid suche pore herberweles schullen be dampnyd. where ypocrisie &amp; worldli pride &amp; <MILESTONE N="116" UNIT="page">coueitise &amp; lecherie schullen make him exempt fro dedis of mercy &amp; comaundement of god; for a bayli, stiward &amp; riche men of lawe schullen haue festis &amp; robis &amp; mynystralis, riche clo&thorn;is &amp; huge &yogh;iftis, but pore men schullen stonde with oute &amp; goo dailes but &yogh;if &thorn;ei geten knockis &amp; reprouynge &amp; wrong extorsions &amp; euyl paynge of here hire; &amp; &yogh;it &thorn;es mendynauntis passen alle o&thorn;ere posses|sioners in &thorn;is ypocrisie &amp; defaute of pite for to gete worldly &thorn;ank &amp; grete wynnynge.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="20" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum 20<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>&THORN;es possessioners ben foule ypocritis vnder name of religion &amp; cursed of crist for here disceitis bi whiche &thorn;ei disceyuen cristene peple; for whanne seynt iame techi&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;is is clene religion<NOTE PLACE="marg">James i. 27.</NOTE> anemtis god, to visite fadirles children &amp; moderles &amp; wedewis in here tribulacion, &amp; to kepe hym<NOTE PLACE="foot">hem AA.</NOTE> self vnblekkid or defoulid fro &thorn;is world; &thorn;ei visiten riche men, &amp; namely wydewis, for to haue here goodis to caymes castel, &amp; sikeren hem of so many massis &amp; preieris durynge &thorn;e world; &amp; &yogh;it &thorn;ei witte not where here preiere turne to here owene<NOTE PLACE="foot">men X.</NOTE> dampnacion, &amp; be cursed of god, &amp; stire god of holynesse &amp; treu&thorn;e to vengaunce 
<PB REF="00000196.tif" N="130"> for here owene wickid lif &amp; ypocrisie. &THORN;erfore crist curse&thorn; scribis &amp; pharisees, ypocritis, &thorn;at eten<NOTE PLACE="foot">heten X.</NOTE> widewis houses bi<NOTE PLACE="marg">Matt. xxiii. 14.</NOTE> suche longe preieris. &amp; &thorn;ei visiten not fadirles children &amp; moderles and widewis to releue hem bi almes &yogh;euynge, but enqueren siche children &amp; widewis &yogh;if &thorn;ei may disceyue hem in purchasynge of here rentis &amp; o&thorn;ere goodis bi flaterynge wordis &amp; sikernesse of gostly helpe; &amp; in &thorn;is ypocrisie &thorn;es mendynauntis beren &thorn;e baner for svtilte &amp; feyned pouert.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="21" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum 21<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>&YOGH;it &thorn;es possessioners blynden lordis &amp; my&yogh;tty men to turmenten goddis seruauntis, bi prisonynge &amp; o&thorn;ere bodily peyne, whanne &thorn;ei forsaken proude &amp; coueitouse men endurid in here synnes &amp; seruen god in &thorn;e beste manere after here power &amp; kunnynge bi fredom of &thorn;e gospel; &amp; &thorn;us &thorn;ei disceyuen lordis in fei&thorn;, hope &amp; charite, &amp; maken lordis &thorn;e deuylis<NOTE PLACE="foot">deuel X.</NOTE> turmentours wanne &thorn;ei hopen to plese god in meyn|tenynge of holy religion.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="22" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum 22<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>Also &thorn;es possessioners, wi&thorn; helpe of false freris, sotil ypocritis, &amp; cursed heretikis, dampnen holy writt, &thorn;e kyngis regalie &amp; wise men of oure lond, for to meyntene here false geten possessions &amp; worldly lif; for &thorn;ei crien &thorn;at it is heresie or errour a&yogh;enst goddis lawe &thorn;at seculer lordis may take temperal goodis fro clerkis trespasynge bi longe custome; &amp; certis &yogh;if seculer lordis may not take temperal goodis fro clerkis, &thorn;anne &thorn;ou&yogh; clerkis trespassen neuere so moche, &yogh;e in traiterie, conspirynge &thorn;e kyngis de&thorn; &amp; quenys &amp; alle &thorn;e lordis &amp; ladies &amp; comunes of oure lond, &thorn;e kyng may not ponysche hem bi o fer&thorn;ing wor&thorn;, &amp; &thorn;anne is goddis lawe fals &thorn;at &yogh;eue&thorn; power to kyngis &amp; seculer <MILESTONE N="117" UNIT="page">lordes to ponysche generaly, outaki&thorn; no man; &amp; many mo orible conclusions suen of &thorn;is dampnynge, as men han writen in many placis.</P>


</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="23" TYPE="chapter"><PB REF="00000197.tif" N="131">
<HEAD>Capitulum 23<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>Possessioners also constreynen prestis to leue studiynge of holy writt &amp; deuocion &amp; prechynge, &amp; neden hem bi vertue of obedience &amp; peyne of prisonynge, &amp; dampnacion as &thorn;ei feynen, to bisien hem nedles ny&yogh;t &amp; day wi&thorn; worldly occu|pacion, a&yogh;enst cristis reule &amp; here owene profession, for ellis &thorn;ei seyn here couent schulde perische &amp; here religion goo doun; &amp; &thorn;us bi obedience maad to synful man, &amp; in cas to fendis, &thorn;ei fordon obedience to god lord of al &thorn;ingis. &amp; &yogh;if a synful ydiot bidde hem do &thorn;e lesse goode, &amp; god bidde&thorn; hem do &thorn;e more goode, &thorn;ei schullen leue &thorn;e more good &amp; sterynge of crist &amp; &thorn;e holy gost for &thorn;is feyned obedience to a synful caitif; &amp; &thorn;us whanne &thorn;ei<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;is AA.</NOTE> bynden hem to forsake &thorn;e world &amp; be dede &thorn;er-to, &thorn;ei ben quekenyd bi anticristis obedience &amp; maade more worldly &thorn;an ony o&thorn;ere men.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="24" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum 24<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>Also &thorn;es possessioners ben neuere ful of worldly goodis &amp; seculer lordischipis, but euere purchasen, be it ri&yogh;t be it wrong, bi gold, be ypocrisie <SUP>2</SUP>of preiere<SUP>2</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot">2_2 omitted X.</NOTE> &amp; bi pardons; for &thorn;e coueitouse man schal not be fulfillid wi&thorn; money, as god sei&thorn;;<NOTE PLACE="marg">Ecclus. xiv. 9.</NOTE> &amp; so &thorn;ei breken &thorn;e reule of crist tau&yogh;t &amp; comaundid bi seint poul to alle prestis: we hawynge liflode &amp; couerynge be we<NOTE PLACE="marg">I. Tim. vi. 8.</NOTE> apeied wi&thorn; &thorn;es &thorn;inges; &amp; &thorn;us is ieromyes prophecie fulfillid<NOTE PLACE="marg">Jer. vi. 13.</NOTE> &thorn;at fro &thorn;e leste to &thorn;e moste &thorn;ei studien to coueitise. &amp; si&thorn; &thorn;ei may not gouerne wel &thorn;e peple as lordis schulden, &thorn;ei wolle not cesse til alle be conquerid in-to here dede hondis to distroie lordis &amp; comunes &amp; holy lif of prestis; &amp; certis o&thorn;er &thorn;ei ben of more my&yogh;t &amp; witt to do bo&thorn;e temperal office &amp; spiritual to-gidre &thorn;an weren crist &amp; his apostlis, or elles &thorn;ei ben foolis disceyued bi pride &amp; coueitise of &thorn;is world; for crist &amp; his apostlis couden not or my&yogh;t not or wolde not do<NOTE PLACE="foot">to X. corrected by a later hand.</NOTE> &thorn;es offices to-gidre, but weren fully occupyed wi&thorn; spiritual office; &amp; &thorn;us &thorn;es possessioners sclaundren cristis lif &amp; ben out of fei&thorn;, hope &amp; charite, &amp; harde rotid in heresie.</P>


</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="25" TYPE="chapter"><PB REF="00000198.tif" N="132">
<HEAD>Capitulum 25<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>&THORN;es possessioners &thorn;at bynden hem to perfit conseilis of crist &amp; to forsake &thorn;e world ben moste bisy to stryue and plede for worldly possessions bi londis lawe, &amp; curse also for dymes, &yogh;e, for foure<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted X.</NOTE> penywor&thorn; good curse many &thorn;ousand soules to helle. lord! hou ben &thorn;ei in charite, for so litel good damp|nynge so many soulis, as moche as in hem is; si&thorn; &thorn;ei schulden lese alle worldly goodis, &yogh;e and here owene lif, for to saue o soule bi &thorn;e lawe of charite. certes &thorn;es ben religious of anti|cristis &amp; sathanas &thorn;at maken so grete stryues &amp; discencions, &amp; to brynge men out of charite for to geten to hem a litel drit of temperal goodis. litil setten &thorn;ei bi seynt bernardis word, &thorn;at what euere &thorn;ou haldest to &thorn;e of ty&thorn;es &amp; offryngis ouer symple liflode <MILESTONE N="118" UNIT="page">&amp; streit clo&thorn;ing, it is not &thorn;in; it is &thorn;efte, raueyne &amp; sacrelegie. in many casis<NOTE PLACE="foot">caas X.</NOTE> sugetis may leffly wi&thorn;|holde<NOTE PLACE="foot">stonde X.</NOTE> ti&thorn;is by goddis lawe &amp; mannys also; &thorn;an it is sathanas werk &amp; anticristis to curse a man for he wole not paie his ti&thorn;es to a cursed man, a&yogh;enst goddis lawe &amp; mannys &amp; a&yogh;enst his conscience ry&yogh;tfully groundid, &amp; &thorn;erfore bereue him his catel, peyne his body, &amp; dampne his soule. Si&thorn; crist &amp; his apostlis curseden neuere ne tau&yogh;ten to curse for ti&thorn;es, but &thorn;e contrarie, as &thorn;e gospel teche&thorn;; &amp; si&thorn; &thorn;es te&thorn;es ben geten to hem bi fals suggestion &amp; meny tymes by symonye, &amp; &yogh;it ben superflue to hem, alle &thorn;es ti&thorn;es ben pore menus liflode, &amp; &thorn;ei ben manquelleris in defraudynge it &amp; manyfold cursed &amp; groundid in gret heresie.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="26" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum 26<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>Also &thorn;es possessioners ben counseillours to many &thorn;ousand mennus de&thorn; for to meyntene here possessions &amp; worldly lif; for &thorn;ei conseilen lordis to werre vpon cristene men for to kepe here lordischipis &amp; worldly lif in reste; &amp; si&thorn; fi&yogh;ttere &amp; conseilere &thorn;er-to ben mansleeris bi goddis lawe &amp; mannys, alle &thorn;es possessioners ben manquelleris &amp; irreguler, &amp; as 
<PB REF="00000199.tif" N="133"> ysaye sei&thorn;, for here hondis ben ful of blode god schal not<NOTE PLACE="marg">Isaiah i. 15.</NOTE> here hem in preieris; but as god sei&thorn; be &thorn;e prophete malechie<NOTE PLACE="marg">Malachi ii. 2.</NOTE> god schal curse to here blysyngis; &amp; whanne siche men gon wi&thorn; ora pro nobis in procession<NOTE PLACE="foot">profession X.</NOTE> &thorn;ei blasphemen god &amp; stiren him to vengaunce, as austyn &amp; gregori techen pleynly.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="27" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum 27<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>&THORN;es possessioners ben specyaly cristis enemys &amp; anticristis, for &thorn;ei dispisen &amp; sclaundren &amp; pursuen meke men &amp; pore, &amp; enhaunsen &amp; preisen &amp; fauoren proude men<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted X.</NOTE> &amp; disolute; for &yogh;if &thorn;er be ony among hem &thorn;at drawe hem<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted AA.</NOTE> to pouert &amp; deuocion &amp; reproue here pride &amp; ypocrisie, he schal be clepid ypocrite, distroier of holy chirche, &amp; sumtyme prisoned, &thorn;at it were betre to him dwellen among he&thorn;ene &thorn;an in suche congregacions; &amp; he &thorn;at is glorious to &thorn;e world &amp; sotil to gete worldly muk or drit of worldly frendischipe, &thorn;ou&yogh; he leue his deuocion &amp; goddis seruyce, he is a noble man &amp; wole meyntene holy chirche; &amp; &thorn;us &thorn;ei ben cursed of god, for &thorn;ei seyn &thorn;at good is euyl &amp; euyl good.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="28" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum 28<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>&YOGH;it &thorn;es possessioners disceyuen men by ypocrisie &amp; wasten moche good in veyn; for &thorn;ei feynen hem to rise at mydny&yogh;t, &amp; spenden li&yogh;t &amp; o&thorn;ere costis maken, &amp; bi day slepen moche more &thorn;er-fore, &thorn;at alle &thorn;ingis accountid &thorn;ei han moche more tyme to slepe &thorn;an ony o&thorn;ere commen men. &amp; &thorn;us &thorn;ei faren as &thorn;eues, slepynge on &thorn;e day &amp; wagynge in &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted AA.</NOTE> ny&yogh;t to robbe men of here catel by ypocrisie of &thorn;is wakynge &amp; preiynge, &amp; herbi &thorn;ei turnen &thorn;e ny&yogh;t in-to day &amp; day in-to ny&yogh;t &amp; maken moche wast.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="29" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum 29<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>Also &thorn;es possessioners maken goddis houses a deen of &thorn;eues; <MILESTONE N="119" UNIT="page">for &thorn;ey maken here chirches placis of marchaundise for wynnynge and bryngenge in &yogh;onge children in-to here 
<PB REF="00000200.tif" N="134"> religion, bi &yogh;iftis &amp; certeyn of welfare &amp; eise of bodi, &amp; norischen hem in glotonye &amp; coueitise; &amp; geten priuylegies of kyngis to meyntene eche &thorn;ef in here place wi&thorn;-outen restitucion, &amp; stryuen &amp; pleden to meyntenen &thorn;is wrong priuylegie more &thorn;an &thorn;e best reule of here ordren or ony poynt of charite.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="30" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum 30<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>&YOGH;it &thorn;es possessioners disceyuen lordis bi feynynge<NOTE PLACE="foot">fyninge X.</NOTE> of special preieris; for &thorn;ei maken lordis to bileue &thorn;at here special preiere, as famulorum &amp; benefactorum, schal turne to lordis aftir grauntynge &amp; lymytynge of synful foolis, &amp; more principaly to hem for here worldly goodis &yogh;euynge &thorn;an to o&thorn;ere men &thorn;at ben in more charite; &amp; &thorn;us &thorn;e ri&yogh;tful delynge of god for &thorn;e goode lif of men is for&yogh;eten, &amp; delynge of synful foolis &thorn;at knowen not &thorn;e ablenesse of men &amp; ri&yogh;tful dom of god is holden for&thorn;; &amp; herby my&yogh;tty men ben brou&yogh;t out of bileue to triste more in special preynge &amp; appliynge of synful men &thorn;an in &thorn;e ri&yogh;tful partynge of god &amp; ri&yogh;twis|nesse of here owene lif, &amp; bi trist of suche special preieris lordis vnderstonden &thorn;at &thorn;ei schulden be excused &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;ei don euyl in here owen lif. lorde! si&thorn; none of alle &thorn;es religious whot where his preiere turne to his owene dampnacion, hou doren &thorn;ei chaffaren &thorn;us wi&thorn; worldly possessions &amp; rentis for here preieris; si&thorn; &thorn;ei owen to wyten &thorn;at here preieris ben cursed &amp; abhominable to god, for &thorn;ei breken cristis hestis in holdynge &thorn;us seculer lordischipis, &amp; lyuen in pride, coueitise, ypocrisie, glotonye &amp; ydelnesse, &thorn;at drawen hem to synne of sodom &amp; maken hem worschiperis<NOTE PLACE="foot">worchiperis X.</NOTE> of false goddis.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="31" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum 31<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>Clerkis possessioners pursuen crist to de&thorn; &amp; bitraien him for stynkynge drit; for &thorn;ei sclaundren, cursen &amp; pursuen falsly to de&thorn; trewe techeris of cristis lif &amp; goddis hestis &thorn;at 
<PB REF="00000201.tif" N="135"> wolden saue mennys soulis bi trewe &amp; free prechynge of &thorn;e gospel wi&thorn;-outen glosynge &amp; beggynge; &amp; &thorn;ei suffren, helpen &amp; meyntenen false prechouris, gloseris, to robbe &thorn;e peple bi fals beggynge, bi symonye &amp; ypocrisie &amp; blasphemye putt vpon crist; so &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">X inserts &thorn;e.</NOTE> possessioners may holden for&thorn;e here seculer lordischipis &amp; worldli lif a&yogh;enst goddis lawe, in dis|troiynge &amp; blasphemynge of cristis lif and cristene fei&thorn;, in distroiynge of seculer lordis &amp; o&thorn;ere prestis &amp; curatis &amp; of comunes also, as it is seid bifore; &amp; as crist sei&thorn; &thorn;is false sclaundrynge &amp; pursuynge of cristis disciplis for &thorn;is ende is pursuynge of crist &amp; of &thorn;e holy trinyte.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="32" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum 32<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>&YOGH;it &thorn;es possessioners blasphemen a&yogh;enst &thorn;e holy gost; for &thorn;ei wolen not suffre men to fulfille his wille ne his &yogh;iftis &amp; saue mennus soulis bi trewe techynge of goddis hestis &amp; poyntis of charite, <MILESTONE N="120" UNIT="page">but constreynen men bi gret violence &amp; turment to leue goddis stirynge<NOTE PLACE="foot">surynge X.</NOTE> &amp; goddis lawe &amp; wille vndon. For &thorn;ei feynen &thorn;at men schulden not teche goddis lawe wi&thorn;-outen here leue. And &thorn;ei wolen &yogh;eue no leue whanne men wolen vtterly teche &thorn;e pouert &amp; mekenesse &amp; bisy traueile of crist &amp; his apostlis &amp; prechynge &thorn;e gospel, &amp; dampnen here coueitise &amp; pride &amp; worldly lif &amp; ydelnesse &amp; ypocrisie; &amp; &thorn;us as moche as is in hem &thorn;ei distroien &thorn;e holy gost &amp; &thorn;e holy trinyte; &amp; <SUP>3</SUP>specialy bi<SUP>3</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot">3_3 special al AA.</NOTE> &thorn;is ypocrisie &thorn;at no man schul preche wi&thorn;-outen here leue. for si&thorn; &thorn;ei ben ennemyes of crist &amp; his lawe, as it is schewid bi here opyn euyl lif, &amp; in caas deuelis of helle, &thorn;ei casten &thorn;at no man schal teche trewely cristis lawe wi&thorn;-outen leue of cristis traitour &amp; of deuelis in helle; &amp; so prestis ben con|streyned bi bodily peynes &amp; de&thorn; to leue goddis wille &amp; precept for contrarie comaundement of goddis traitour, &amp; in caas a deuyl in flech, as ih&umacr; crist sei&thorn; of iudas scario&thorn;.<NOTE PLACE="marg">John vi. 70.</NOTE></P>


</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="33" TYPE="chapter"><PB REF="00000202.tif" N="136">
<HEAD>Capitulum 33<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>&THORN;es proude possessioners blasphemen a&yogh;enst &thorn;e my&yogh;t of &thorn;e fadir; for bi here worldly power &amp; sotilte &amp; malice &thorn;ei letten lordis power, &thorn;at &thorn;ei may not meyntene goddis ordy|nannce in &thorn;e clergie &amp; saue here owene soulis &amp; gouerne wel here<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted AA.</NOTE> tenauntis &amp; comunes; &amp; bi &thorn;e same cautel &thorn;ei letten prestis to teche treuely &amp; freely goddis lawe &amp; his ordynaunce bi power grauntid of god, last here pride &amp; worldly worschipe be brou&yogh;t doun, &amp; mekenesse &amp; holynesse ensaumplid of crist and his apostlis knowen &amp; kept, &amp; ypocrisie &amp; o&thorn;ere synnes aspied<NOTE PLACE="foot">aspie X.</NOTE> &amp; distroied; &amp; so as anticrist &thorn;ei magnyfyen hem self &amp; here power more &thorn;an god &amp; his power.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="34" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum 34<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>&YOGH;it &thorn;es possessioners turnen abstinence &amp; penaunce in-to glotonye, &amp; traueile in-to ydelnesse, &amp; pouert in-to coueitise; for &thorn;ei ben groundid in abstynence after crist &amp; his apostlis, &amp; namely &thorn;es newe religious, &amp; &thorn;ei turnen hem in-to glotonye &amp; delicat liflode more comynly &thorn;an o&thorn;ere men; &amp; &thorn;ei ben groundid on pouert aftir crist &amp; his apostlis, but &thorn;ei ben turned in-to worldly coueitise bi <NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>and</I> AA.</NOTE>many sotiltes &amp; ypocrisie; &amp; &thorn;ei ben groundid on labor of here hondis bi here owene reule, &amp; &yogh;it &thorn;ei turnen &thorn;at labor in-to preieris bi mou&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">monye X.</NOTE> &amp; ben idel &amp; veyn; &amp; &thorn;us bi colour of holynesse &thorn;ei sti&yogh;en in-to synnes on eche side.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="35" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum 35<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>Proude possessioners ben perilous &thorn;eues &amp; cursed heretikis; for &thorn;ei affermen who euer taki&thorn; ony temperal goodis fro holy chirche, &thorn;at is &thorn;e comynte<NOTE PLACE="foot">comutiete X.</NOTE> of clerkis aftir here dom, he is a &thorn;eef<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;eef X.</NOTE> &amp; cursed in dede; &thorn;anne si&thorn; &thorn;ei taken awey &thorn;e noble gostly good of wilful pouert &amp; symplenesse &amp; mekenesse, in 
<PB REF="00000203.tif" N="137"> whiche vertues crist groundid holy chirche, &thorn;ei ben stronge &thorn;eues &amp; anticristis disciplis. &amp; si&thorn; &thorn;ei meyntenen so harde &thorn;is wickid &thorn;eefte, &amp; robben holy chirche fro &thorn;is noble tresor of pouert &amp; mekenesse, and defoulen it wi&thorn; drit of worldly lordischipe a&yogh;enst &thorn;e <MILESTONE N="121" UNIT="page">wille of ih&umacr; crist here spouse, &thorn;ei ben cursed heretikis &amp; here meyntenours also, &amp; &thorn;us &thorn;ei ben anticristis peruertynge cristendom.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="36" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum 36<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>&YOGH;it &thorn;es possessioners bryngen lordis out of bileue, &amp; maken hem bi blynde swerynge meyntene &thorn;e coueitise &amp; worldly lif of anticristis clerkis, whanne bi vertue of here o&thorn; &thorn;ei schulden distroie &thorn;e false coueitise &amp; pride of worldly clerkis: for &thorn;es lordis sweren to meyntenen &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;er X.</NOTE> priuylegyes &amp; fre|domos &amp; ri&yogh;ttis of holy chirche; &amp; bi &thorn;is o&thorn; &thorn;ei moten nedis meyntenen &thorn;e perfit fredom of holy lif, of mekenesse &amp; pouert &amp; o&thorn;ere goode vertues &thorn;at crist ordeyned to &thorn;e chirche; but anticristis clerkis chalengen<NOTE PLACE="foot">chalagen X.</NOTE> bi &thorn;is o&thorn; &thorn;at lordis owen to meyntene here false lordischipis, pride &amp; coueitise, &amp; wrong customes of prescripcion a&yogh;enst goddis lawe<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted X.</NOTE> &amp; good con|science; for &yogh;if &thorn;es anticristis clerkis han holden wrongfully a cristene mannys good lond o&thorn;er rentis<NOTE PLACE="foot">trentis AA.</NOTE> or o&thorn;er goodis bi &thorn;ritti &yogh;eer or fourty with-outen ony axynge, &thorn;ei seyn &thorn;is synful possession so longe contynued maki&thorn; hem worldly lordis of &thorn;is good; &amp; &thorn;us &thorn;ei maken lordis to meyntene fraudis &amp; falsnesse a&yogh;enst goddis hestis, whanne lordis wenen to meyntene ri&yogh;tful lawes for worschipe of god; but certis here is moche &thorn;efte, moche treson &amp; moche harm of soulis on eche side meyntened bi &thorn;is blynde swerynge.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="37" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum 37<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>Also &thorn;es possessioners dampnen trewe men techynge frely &amp; trewely &thorn;e gospel &amp; goddis hestis for heretikis, for to coloure here owen worldly<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted X.</NOTE> lif, but &thorn;ei hem self ben foule 
<PB REF="00000204.tif" N="138"> heretikis for here cursed pride, coueitise &amp; enuye &thorn;at &thorn;ei dwellen inne &amp; meyntenen strongly; but of &thorn;is verry heresie &amp; most perilous wolen &thorn;ei not &thorn;enke ne speke, ne suffre o&thorn;ere trewe men to speke a&yogh;enst it for to saue here soulis &amp; helpe o&thorn;ere men out of synne. &amp; &thorn;us &thorn;ei faren wi&thorn; cristene men &amp; holy writt as diden scribis &amp; phariseis wi&thorn; crist &amp; his apostlis &amp; his gospel, &amp; whanne &thorn;es pharisees, scribis &amp; hi&yogh;e prestis weren ful of heresie &amp; blasphemye &thorn;ei putten alle &thorn;es synnes on crist &amp; his apostlis to blynde &thorn;e comune peple, &amp; so &thorn;es possessioners don now bi more ypocrisie &amp; more sotilte &amp; more cruelte.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="38" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum 38<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>&THORN;es proude possessioners disclaundren trewe prechours of &thorn;e gospel &amp; cristis lif for makeris of discencion &amp; debate among nei&yogh;eboris in &thorn;e lond; whanne &thorn;ei hem self wi&thorn; here cursed lif &amp; confederacie wi&thorn; tirauntis for here gold ben cause of discencion &amp; enemyte. for wi&thorn; pore mennus liflode &thorn;ei hiren my&yogh;tty men to stryue &amp; plede a&yogh;enst goddis techynge, &amp; helpe &amp; releuynge &amp; encressynge of seculer lordis, &amp; helpe &amp; releuynge of pore comunes; &amp; &thorn;us as cursed pharisees &amp; scribis &amp; hi&yogh;e prestis &thorn;ei putten here owen cursed synnes vpon trewe men to lette goddis lawe to be knowen, &amp; hiden &amp; colouren &amp;<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted AA.</NOTE> <MILESTONE N="122" UNIT="page">meyntenen here olde synnes and traitere bi strong pursuynge to de&thorn; of alle trewe men as moche as &thorn;ei may, &amp; herbi &thorn;ei ben manquelleris &amp; pursueris of crist &amp; endurid in<NOTE PLACE="foot">X inserts "he."</NOTE> old heresie.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="39" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum 39<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>Also &thorn;es possessioners magnifyen hem self more &thorn;an ih&umacr; crist, &amp; seken more here owene name &amp; honour &thorn;an honour of god &amp; helpe of cristene soulis; for &thorn;ei axen &amp; coueiten name of holynesse &amp; reuerence wi&thorn; &thorn;is proude worldly lif, &amp; &thorn;at schal no man reproue hem of here opyn ypocrisie, symonye &amp; coueytise: &amp; ih&umacr; crist my&yogh;tte not kepe holynesse 
<PB REF="00000205.tif" N="139"> wi&thorn; suche worldly lif &amp; axe such worldly reuerence as &thorn;es possessioners don. And ih&umacr; crist was redy to be reproued of his enemyes &yogh;if &thorn;ei my&yogh;tten fynde ony defaute in him. but &yogh;it<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted AA.</NOTE> &thorn;es possessioners ben ful of synne, &amp; &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;ei ben most bounden to pacience, mekenesse &amp; charite &yogh;it &thorn;ei ben wode whanne men wolen amende here cursed lif bi techynge of &thorn;e gospel; &amp; &yogh;if men dispisen hem or don not worldly reuerence to hem &thorn;ei ben wode wro&thorn; &amp; wolen be vengid vp al here my&yogh;t; but &thorn;ou&yogh; men dispisen god in here presence bi cursed swerynge or o&thorn;ere synnes &thorn;ei chargen not, &amp; &yogh;it &thorn;ou&yogh; here owene seruauntis do so, &thorn;at is worse to hem, &thorn;ei chargen it<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted X.</NOTE> not. but as &thorn;e iewis diden crist to de&thorn; for drede of lesyng of here lordischipe &amp; worldly name &amp; honour, so &thorn;es possessioners don here power to do alle trewe men to de&thorn; &thorn;at techen cristis gospel &amp; mekenesse &amp; pouert a&yogh;enst here false newe lawis &amp; pride &amp; coueitise, &amp; hou &thorn;ei enuenymyn cristendom bi word &amp; dede.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="40" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum 40<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>&YOGH;it &thorn;es ypocritis possessioners ben traitouris to god, to lordis, &amp; to comunes also; for &thorn;ei han almost &thorn;e tresor of &thorn;e lond &amp; worldly lordischipe, a&yogh;enst goddis lawe; &amp; whanne &thorn;e kyng ha&thorn; nede of a taxe, &thorn;ei wolen not paie for pore men, not wi&thorn;stondynge &thorn;at &thorn;ei ben procuratouris of pore men, &amp; al &thorn;at &thorn;ei han<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted X.</NOTE> ouer here owen symple liflode is pore mennus good, as goddis lawe &amp; mannus techen opynly, but for to plede &amp; meyntene wrongis &amp; putten men out of here lond &amp; meyntenen false prauelegies a&yogh;enst charite &amp; good conscience &thorn;ei han &thorn;ousand markis &amp; poundis; &amp; here &thorn;ei chalengen aboue crist &amp; alle his apostlis &thorn;at &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;ei han almost alle<NOTE PLACE="foot">alle is added in X. by a later hand.</NOTE> lordischipis amorteised to hem, &yogh;it &thorn;ei wolen not paien tribute ne taxe<NOTE PLACE="foot">axe AA.</NOTE> to &thorn;e kyng for meyntenaunce of &thorn;e rewme &amp; sauynge of pore mennus lif; &amp; &yogh;it crist paide for him &amp; his disciplis tribute to &thorn;e emperoure, &thorn;ou&yogh; he hadde 
<PB REF="00000206.tif" N="140"> non such temperaltees. &amp; &thorn;is exempcion &thorn;ei chalengen bi anticristis power &amp; not bi god almy&yogh;tty, for he constreyne&thorn; clerkis to be suget to seculer lordis &amp; to lyue a iust lif &amp; symple &amp; pore wi&thorn;-outen worldly lordschipe <MILESTONE N="123" UNIT="page">&amp; opyn beggynge in a<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted AA.</NOTE> vertuous mene. god almy&yogh;tty stire&thorn; prestis, lordis &amp; comunes to knowe ypocrisie, heresie &amp; treson of anticristis worldly clerkis, &amp; knowen &amp; meyntenen &thorn;e ri&yogh;tful ordynaunce of god &amp; &thorn;e perfit fredom of &thorn;e gospel. Amen.</P>


</DIV2>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="7" TYPE="tract"><PB REF="00000207.tif" N="141">
<HEAD>VII. HOW THE OFFICE OF CURATES IS ORDAINED OF GOD.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>I HAVE already said (in the Preface to No. IV.) that I think this tract to be by another hand than Wyclif's, but the tone of thought is very like his. The date of it is evidently after 1383, as Bishop Spenser's crusade in Flanders is mentioned as a thing of the past (Chapter XVI.).</P><P>When we read the complaint (Chap. XXII.) of the clergy who leave their parishes and go to school (that is, of course, to the University), in order to lead a loose life there, we are not suppose that the writer had any dislike to the Universities. Oxford was a chief centre of Wyclifite influence, and Wyclif himself, in 1368, received from his bishop two years' leave of absence from his living (Fillingham) to study at Oxford, where, our tract tells us, "good priests traveilen faste to lerne goddis lawe." Its author had rubbed shoulders with the men who went to study "Civil and Canon," and did little good thereat, or at most learned to "crack a little Latin in Consistories." The scholar is as indignant against fast men who degrade the seat of learning, as the reformer against priests who neglect their parishes. We may suppose the writer to be one of Wyclif's Oxford friends&mdash;perhaps Herford or Purvey.</P><P>Copied from the Corpus MS. X. and collated with the Dublin MS. AA.</P><P><TABLE>
<HEAD>SUMMARY.</HEAD>
<ROW>
<CELL>CHAP. I.</CELL>
<CELL>Curates care too much for worldly goods.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>II.</CELL>
<CELL>Men run about after benefices and buy them. The money thus spent would be better employed in reducing taxation.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>III.</CELL>
<CELL>Wayward curates are Satans transformed into angels of light&mdash;angels not of God but of the devil.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>IV.</CELL>
<CELL>Curates study law books instead of the Bible.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>V.</CELL>
<CELL>They go to law for trifles of tithe, bringing heavy charges on their subjects, or cursing and imprisoning them.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>VI.</CELL>
<CELL>They set their parishioners an example of worldliness.</CELL>

<PB REF="00000208.tif" N="142">
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>CHAP. VII.</CELL>
<CELL>They teach men to war; they despise the poor and flatter the rich.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>VIII.</CELL>
<CELL>They will not teach Holy Writ nor let others teach it.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>IX.</CELL>
<CELL>They waste the money of the poor in pomp and luxury.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>X.</CELL>
<CELL>They serve lords in worldly business and neglect God's work.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>XI.</CELL>
<CELL>They welcome cheating pardoners, but hinder true preachers.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>XII.</CELL>
<CELL>They neglect God's command to preach.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>XIII.</CELL>
<CELL>They excommunicate for not paying tithes, but not for sin.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>XIV.</CELL>
<CELL>They waste the money of the poor in hawking and hunting.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>XV.</CELL>
<CELL>They haunt taverns, play games of chance, and get drunk.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>XVI.</CELL>
<CELL>Refuse the sacrament to those who do not pay tithes, or will not con|tribute to wars such as Spenser's crusade.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>XVII.</CELL>
<CELL>They take benefices without knowing the gospel, and teach the people evil.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>XVIII.</CELL>
<CELL>They relate chronicles and stories of false miracles to mislead the people.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>XIX.</CELL>
<CELL>They go shares with pardoners, who deceive the people.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>XX.</CELL>
<CELL>They hate good priests and love bad ones.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>XXI.</CELL>
<CELL>Wicked curates take refuge in lords' courts, and use the protection of lords to avoid discipline.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>XXII.</CELL>
<CELL>They go under pretence of study to the Universities, and lead a riotous life there.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>XXIII.</CELL>
<CELL>The more learned of them use the Civil and Canon Law to annoy the poor, and neither have nor care for knowledge of the Bible.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>XXIV.</CELL>
<CELL>They let worldly clerks condemn God's law, and stop true preachers; while they preach the traditions of Antichrist.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>XXV.</CELL>
<CELL>They study Civil and Canon Law and neglect God's law.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>XXVI.</CELL>
<CELL>They forbid the people to judge their words or deeds.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>XXVII.</CELL>
<CELL>They forbid laymen to read the Gospel in their mother-tongue.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>XXVIII.</CELL>
<CELL>They deceive men as to absolution, leading them to trust in shrift and gifts rather than in contrition and amendment.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>XXIX.</CELL>
<CELL>They rob people by their pitiless excommunications.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>XXX.</CELL>
<CELL>They take tithes according to neither Testament, but according to sinful laws.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>XXXI.</CELL>
<CELL>They get benefices by simony, and neglect them afterwards.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>XXXII.</CELL>
<CELL>Under pretence of liberties of the Church they make the people main|tain bad priests in their evil ways.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>XXXIII.</CELL>
<CELL>They say that if these bad ways are maintained, priests' prayers will bring reward, but any attempt to reform priests is cursed. Final apostrophe to curates.</CELL>
</ROW>
</TABLE></P></HEADNOTE>

<PB REF="00000209.tif" N="143">
<EPIGRAPH>
<Q>Hou &thorn;e office of curatis is ordeyned of god. In dei nomine. Amen.</Q>
</EPIGRAPH>
<DIV2 N="1" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>[Capitulum 1.]</HEAD>
<P>For &thorn;e office of curatis is ordeyned of god &amp; fewe don it wele &amp; many ful euyle, &thorn;erfore telle we summe defautis<NOTE PLACE="foot">defaute AA.</NOTE> to amende hem wi&thorn; goddis helpe. First &thorn;ei ben more bisi aboute worldly goodis &thorn;an vertues &amp; goode kepynge of mennus soulis; for he &thorn;at can best geten richesses of &thorn;is world to-gidre &amp; holde grete houshold &amp; worldly aray, he is holden a wor&thorn;i man of holy chirche, &thorn;ou&yogh; he conne not &thorn;e leste<NOTE PLACE="foot">beste X.</NOTE> poynt of &thorn;e gospel; &amp; such on is preised &amp; born vp of &thorn;e bischop &amp; here officeris at &thorn;e fulle; but &thorn;at curat &thorn;at &yogh;eue&thorn; him to studie holy writt &amp; teche his<NOTE PLACE="foot">is X.</NOTE> paryschenys to saue here soulis, &amp; lyue&thorn; in mekenesse, penaunce &amp; bisi traueile a boute gostly &thorn;ingis, &amp; recki&thorn; not of worldly worschipe &amp; richesse, is holden a fool &amp; distroiere of holy chirche, &amp; is<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted X.</NOTE> dispised &amp; pursued of hi&yogh;e prestis &amp; prelatis &amp; here officeris, &amp; hatid of o&thorn;ere curatis in contre; &amp; &thorn;is maki&thorn; many curatis to be necgligent in here gostly cure &amp; &yogh;eue hem to occupacion &amp; bisynesse of worldly goodis. &thorn;es necgligent curatis &thorn;enken ful<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted AA.</NOTE> litel hou dere crist bou&yogh;te mannys soule wi&thorn; his precious blood &amp; de&thorn;, &amp; hou harde rekenynge schal he make at domes day for &thorn;es soulis. certis it seme&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;ei ben out of cristene mennys fei&thorn;; for &thorn;ei maken hem not redy to come &thorn;edir &amp; answere wel hou &thorn;ei camen in-to here benefices &amp; hou &thorn;ei lyueden &amp; tau&yogh;ten &amp; spendiden pore mennus goodis; for &yogh;if &thorn;ei hadden &thorn;is fei&thorn; redy in here mynde &thorn;ei wolden bigynne a betre lif &amp; con|tynue &thorn;er-inne.</P>


</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="2" TYPE="chapter"><PB REF="00000210.tif" N="144">
<HEAD>Capitulum 2<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>&THORN;e secunde defaute. &THORN;ei rennen faste bi lond &amp; watir in grete perilis of bodi &amp; soule for to geten fatte benefices, but &thorn;ei wolen not goo comunly a myle for to preche &thorn;e gospel, &thorn;ou&yogh; cristene men rennen to helle for defaute of knowynge &amp; kepynge of goddis lawe. &amp; certis here &thorn;ei schewen in dede &thorn;at &thorn;ei ben foule blend<NOTE PLACE="foot">blent AA.</NOTE> with coueitise, &amp; worschipen false<NOTE PLACE="foot">falser X.</NOTE> goddis, as seynt poul sei&thorn;, si&thorn; &thorn;e[i] louen so moche worldly<NOTE PLACE="marg">Col. iii. 5.</NOTE> richesses &amp; so moche traueilen &thorn;erfore ny&yogh;t &amp; day in &thorn;ou&yogh;t &amp; dede, &amp; so litel traueilen for goddis worschipe &amp; sauynge of cristene soulis. but who may excuse &thorn;es coueitouse clerkis fro symonye &amp; heresie in &thorn;is poynt? nei&thorn;er goddis lawe ne mannys, ne reson, ne good conscience. &amp; hou myche gold go&thorn; out of oure lond for purchasynge of benefices in-to <MILESTONE N="124" UNIT="page">aliens hondis, &amp; hou moche is &yogh;ouen priuely to men in &thorn;e lond, late &thorn;e kyng &amp; his witti conseil enquere, &amp; &thorn;ei schal fynde many &thorn;ousand poundis: &amp; late alle &thorn;at helpe &thorn;e comunes in &thorn;is grete talliage, &amp; late alle clerkis be warnyd &amp; charged <SUP>3</SUP>by &thorn;e kyng<SUP>3</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot">3_3 omitted X.</NOTE> <SUP>4</SUP>&amp; lordes of &thorn;e rewme<SUP>4</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot">4_4 omitted AA.</NOTE> &thorn;at &thorn;ei don no more symonye for benefices, vp peyne of lesynge of here benefices &amp; prison|ynge &amp; exilynge; si&thorn; &thorn;is symonye maki&thorn; hem chef heretikis as here owene lawe sei&thorn; plenerly, &amp; &thorn;at &thorn;ei may not be sauyd but &yogh;if &thorn;ei forsake &thorn;e benefice geten bi symonye, and alle here fautours &amp; consentours to &thorn;is symonye rennen in &thorn;e same dampnacion as goddis lawe &amp; mannus witnessen.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="3" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum 3<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>&THORN;e &thorn;ridde defaute of weiward curatis &thorn;at &thorn;ei ben aungelis of helle &amp; ben sathanas transfigurid in-to an aungel of li&yogh;t to<NOTE PLACE="foot">and AA.</NOTE> lede men queyntely to helle; for in-stede of trewe techynge of cristis gospel &thorn;ei ben doumbe, or elles tellen lesyngis of mennys tradicions for pride &amp; coueitise of worldly goodis; &amp; for ensaumple of good lif &thorn;ei sclaundren here parischenys 
<PB REF="00000211.tif" N="145"> many weies bi ensaumple of pride, enuye, coueitise &amp; vnre|sonable vengaunce, so cruely cursynge for ti&thorn;es &amp; euyl customes; &amp; for ensaumple of holy deuocion &amp; deuout preiere &amp; werkis of mercy &thorn;ei techen in-dede ydelnesse, glotonye, dronkenesse &amp; lecherie, &amp; meyntenynge of &thorn;es synnes &amp; many moo. For si&thorn; prestis ben clepid aungelis in holy writt, &amp; &thorn;es<NOTE PLACE="marg">Malachi ii. 7.</NOTE> curatis bryngen not message of god but of &thorn;e fend, as here wickid lif scewi&thorn;,<NOTE PLACE="foot">schewi&thorn; AA.</NOTE> &thorn;ei ben not aungelis of god but aungelis of &thorn;e fend; &amp; &thorn;e trewe clerk robert grosted writi&thorn; to &thorn;e pope &thorn;at curatis ben sathanas transfigurid in-to aungel of li&yogh;t for &thorn;ei prechen<NOTE PLACE="foot">techen AA.</NOTE> not cristis gospel bi word &amp; good lif, &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;ei diden no more synne<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted X.</NOTE>; and<NOTE PLACE="foot">in X.</NOTE> si&thorn; seynt petir was clepid sathanas of crist, as &thorn;e gospel telli&thorn;, for he was contrarie to goddis<NOTE PLACE="marg">Matt. xvi. 23.</NOTE> wille &amp; sauourid not heuenly &thorn;ingis, wel ben &thorn;es euele curatis clepid sathanas, si&thorn; &thorn;ei ben more contrarie to goddis wille &amp; sauouren less gostly &thorn;ingis &amp; sauynge of cristene soulis.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="4" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum 4<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>&THORN;e four&thorn;e errour; &thorn;at &thorn;ei chargen more statutis of synful men &thorn;an &thorn;e moste resonable lawe of god almy&yogh;tty; for &thorn;ei dreden more &thorn;e popis lawe &amp; statutis maad of bischopis &amp; <SUP>5</SUP>of o&thorn;ere<SUP>5</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot">5_5 her AA.</NOTE> officeris &thorn;an &thorn;e noble lawe of the gospel, &amp; herefore &thorn;ei han many grete bokis &amp; costy of mannus lawe &amp; studien hem faste. But fewe curatis han &thorn;e bible &amp; exposiciouns<NOTE PLACE="foot">expositours X.</NOTE> of &thorn;e gospelis, <SUP>7</SUP>&amp; litel studien on hem<NOTE PLACE="foot">7_7 omitted AA.</NOTE> &amp; lesse donne after hem. But wolde god &thorn;at euery parische chirche in &thorn;is<NOTE PLACE="foot">AA. inserts werld.</NOTE> lond hadde a good bible &amp; good expositouris on &thorn;e gospellis, &amp; &thorn;at &thorn;e prestis studiende<NOTE PLACE="foot">studien AA.</NOTE> hem wel &amp; tau&yogh;ten trewely &thorn;e <MILESTONE N="125" UNIT="page">gospel &amp; goddis hestis to &thorn;e peple; for &thorn;anne schulde good lif regne, &amp; reste &amp; pees &amp; charite; &amp; synne &amp; falsnesse putt a bak. god brynge &thorn;is ende to his peple. amen.<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted X.</NOTE>
</P>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="5" TYPE="chapter"><PB REF="00000212.tif" N="146">
<HEAD>Capitulum 5<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>&THORN;e fyue&thorn;e defaute; &thorn;at &thorn;ei haunten<NOTE PLACE="foot">AA inserts is.</NOTE> strif &amp; plee &amp; gendren enuye &amp; hate among lewed men for ty&thorn;es, whanne &thorn;ei don not here office a&yogh;enward; for now &thorn;ei leuen prechynge of &thorn;e gospel &amp; crien faste aftir ty&thorn;es, &amp; somonen men to chapitre &amp; bi fors taken here goodis, &amp; ellis cursen hem seuene fote aboue &thorn;e er&thorn;e &amp; seuene foot wi&thorn;-inne &thorn;e her&thorn;e &amp; seuene fote on eche side; &amp; afterward drawen men to prison, as &thorn;ei weren kyngis &amp; emperours of mennus bodies &amp; catel, &amp; for&yogh;eten clenly &thorn;e mekenesse &amp; &thorn;e pacience of crist &amp; his apostlis, hou &thorn;ei curseden not for ty&thorn;es whanne men wolden nei&thorn;er &yogh;eue hem mete ne drynk ne herbwre. But crist blamyd his apostlis whanne &thorn;ei wolden axe suche vengaunce, as &thorn;e gospel of seynt luk teche&thorn;, &amp; seynt petir bidi&thorn; blisse<NOTE PLACE="marg">Luke ix. 55.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="marg">1 Peter iii. 9.</NOTE> o&thorn;ere men, &yogh;e here enemis, &amp; not haue wille to curse, &amp; poul<NOTE PLACE="marg">Rom. xii. 21.</NOTE> teche&thorn; &thorn;at we schulden not do euele for euyl, But ouer come an euyl dede bi good doynge a&yogh;en. Lord, hou louen &thorn;es curatis here sugetis soulis &thorn;at wolen for foure pens bitake hem bodi &amp; soule to &thorn;e fend, &yogh;e, whanne &thorn;ei may not paie for verray<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted X.</NOTE> pouert, &amp; whanne &thorn;ei don not here gostly office; &amp; &thorn;anne &thorn;e curatis ben more cursed of god for wi&thorn;drawynge of techynge in word, in<NOTE PLACE="foot">&amp; X.</NOTE> dede, in good en|saumple &thorn;anne &thorn;e sugetis wi&thorn;drawynge ti&thorn;es &amp; offryngis whanne &thorn;ei don wel here gostly office. &amp; wold god &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted AA.</NOTE> &thorn;e peple wolde axe as faste of &thorn;e curatis gostly office, &thorn;at &thorn;ei ben more holden to paie, as &thorn;e curatis axen dymes &amp; offryngis, &amp; &thorn;e curat loue&thorn; more his owene worldly good &thorn;an his sugetis soule<NOTE PLACE="foot">X inserts &amp;.</NOTE> &thorn;at wole brynge his parischen out of cherite &amp; pacience &amp; coste ten mark or twenti for a cause of &thorn;re pens or foure.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="6" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum 6<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>&THORN;e sixte defaute; &thorn;at &thorn;ei techen here parischens bi here dedis and lif; &thorn;at is a bok to here sugetis, to loue &amp; seke 
<PB REF="00000213.tif" N="147"> worldly glorye &amp; to recken nou&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted X.</NOTE> of heuenely &thorn;ingis; for &thorn;ei maken hem self bisy ni&yogh;t &amp; day to geten worldely avaunsementis &amp; here owene worschipe &amp; dignyte in &thorn;is world and<NOTE PLACE="foot">in X.</NOTE> pleden &amp; st[r]yuen &thorn;erfore, &amp; helden<NOTE PLACE="foot">horden X.</NOTE> it grete ri&yogh;twissnesse to holden for&thorn; &amp; meyntene a poynt of worldly priuylegie &amp; dignyte; but aboute gostly dignite &amp; hi&yogh;e degre of heuenly blisse &thorn;ei wolen not st[r]yue a&yogh;enst gostly ennemys; for &thorn;ei stryuen not who schal be most meke &amp; most wilful pore &amp; most bisi in opyn prechynge &amp; priuey counseilynge hou men schal conquere heuene, as dide crist &amp; his apostlis, but resten as mold-warpis in wrotynge of worldly worschipe &amp; er&thorn;ely goodis, as &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;ere were no lif but only in &thorn;is wrecchid world; &amp; &thorn;us where &thorn;ei schulden lede here parischenys to heuene bi trewe techynge &amp; holy ensaumple &amp; gret desir of heuenely &thorn;ynges, &thorn;ei leden hem to helle ward bi cursede ensaumple of pride, coueitise &amp; euyl techynge <MILESTONE N="126" UNIT="page">to sette here lykynge endeles in ioie &amp; worschipe of &thorn;is wrecchid world.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="7" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum 7<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>&THORN;e seuen&thorn;e errour; &thorn;at &thorn;ei techen synful men to bie helle ful dere &amp; not to come to heuene &thorn;at is profred hem for litel cost; for &thorn;ei techen cristen men to sufre moche cold, hungur &amp; &thorn;rist &amp; moche wakynge &amp; dispisynge &amp; betynge for to gete worldly honour &amp; a litel drit bi fals werrynge out of charite; &amp; &yogh;if &thorn;ei bryngen hem moche gold &thorn;ei assoilen hem li&yogh;tly &amp; maken hem siker bi here preieris &amp; graunten hem goddis blissynge, but &thorn;ei techen not hou here parischenys schulden dispose hem to resceyue &yogh;iftis of &thorn;e holy gost &amp; kepe condicions of charite, doynge trew&thorn;e &amp; good conscience to eche man bo&thorn;e pore &amp; riche; &amp; &yogh;if &thorn;ei ben pore bi aduen|ture of &thorn;e world or wilfully bi drede of synne, &thorn;ei dispisen hem &amp; setten hem at nou&yogh;t and seyn &thorn;ei ben cursed for &thorn;ei han not moche muk; &amp; &yogh;if &thorn;ei han mochel worldly catel 
<PB REF="00000214.tif" N="148"> geten wi&thorn; false o&thorn;is, false wei&yogh;tis, &amp; o&thorn;ere disceitis, &thorn;ei preisen hem &amp; b[l]issen hem &amp; seyn god is wi&thorn; hem <SUP>1</SUP>&amp; blisse&thorn; hem.<SUP>1</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot">1_1 omitted AA.</NOTE></P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="8" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum 8<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>&THORN;e ei&yogh;te defaute; &thorn;ei shitten &thorn;e kyngdom of heuene bi|fore men, &amp; nei&thorn;er gon in hem self ne suffren o&thorn;ere men to entren; for &thorn;ei shitten holy writt, as &thorn;e gospel &amp; com|aundementis<NOTE PLACE="marg">Matt. xxiii. 13.</NOTE> &amp; condic[i]ounes of charite &thorn;at ben clepid &thorn;e kyngdom of heuene, bi here false newe lawis &amp; euyl glosynge &amp; euyl techynge; for nei&thorn;er &thorn;ei wolen lerne hem self ne techen holy writt, ne suffre o&thorn;ere men to don it leste here owene synne &amp; ypocrisie be knowen &amp; here lustful lif wi&thorn;|drawen. &amp; &thorn;us &thorn;ei closen cristis lif &amp; his apostlis fro &thorn;e comune peple bi keies of anticristis iuridiccion &amp; censures, &amp; maken hem not so hardy to seye a treu&thorn;e of holi writt a&yogh;enst here cursed lif, for &thorn;at schal be holden detraccion &amp; enuye &amp; a&yogh;enst charite; &amp; &thorn;erfore &thorn;ei make &thorn;e peple to sue here techynge &amp; here statutis &amp; customes &amp; to leue goddis techynge, &amp; herbi leden hem blyndly in-to helle; &amp; &thorn;us closen &thorn;e kyngdom of heuene fro hem &amp; leden hem to helle bi here blynde ypocrisie &amp; coueityse, as crist sei&thorn; hym self.<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted X.</NOTE></P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="9" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum 9<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>&THORN;e ney[n]&thorn;e errour; &thorn;at &thorn;ei wasten pore mennus goode in ryche pellure &amp; costy clo&thorn;is &amp; worldly aray, as festis of ryche men &amp; glotonye &amp; dronkenesse &amp; lecherie sumtymes, for &thorn;ei passen grete men in here gaye pellure &amp; precious clo&thorn;is &amp; wast festis &amp; tatrid squeyeres &amp; o&thorn;ere meyne, &thorn;at semen ra&thorn;ere turmentours &thorn;an cristene men; &amp; he &thorn;at wast<NOTE PLACE="foot">waste&thorn; AA.</NOTE> most of pore mennus liflode is holden most wor&thorn;i &amp; most noble man of holy chirche. litel &thorn;enke &thorn;ei hou sore pore men traueilen &amp; spenden here flesch <MILESTONE N="127" UNIT="page">&amp; blood aboute &thorn;e goddis &thorn;at &thorn;ei wasten so nedeles; &amp; hou seynt 
<PB REF="00000215.tif" N="149"> bernard crie&thorn;: what euere &thorn;ing curatis holden of &thorn;e auterage ouer a sympule liflode &amp; clo&thorn;inge it nys not here but o&thorn;ere mennus, &amp; it is &thorn;efte &amp; raueyne &amp; sacrilegie; &amp; hou euyl it is to suffre pore men perische for hungire &amp; &thorn;riste &amp; cold, &amp; here curatis han fatte hors with gaye sadlis &amp; bridelis. hou resonable is &thorn;is poynt &thorn;at &thorn;e procuratour of pore men schal haue so riche pelure &amp; esy fare of body, bo&thorn; of mete &amp; drynk &amp; reste, &amp; pore men whos &thorn;es goddis ben schullen haue so moche peyne &amp; payn defaute.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="10" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum 10<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>&THORN;e ten&thorn;e defaute; &thorn;at &thorn;ei haunten lordis courtis &amp; ben occupied in worldly office &amp; don not here cure to here parischenys, &amp; &yogh;it &thorn;ei taken mo worldly goodis &thorn;erfore &thorn;an crist &amp; his apostlis. And certis &thorn;is is gret traitere, for what man druste vndertake to kepe men biseged in a feble castel wi&thorn; many stronge enemys, &amp; &thorn;anne fle in-to an hogherdis office &amp; lete enemys take &thorn;is castel &amp; distroie it?<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted X.</NOTE> were not &thorn;is opyn treson, and &thorn;is kepere gilty of &thorn;e castel lesynge &amp; alle men &thorn;er-inne? So it is of &thorn;es curatis &amp; cristene soulis of whiche &thorn;ei taken cure, &thorn;at ben bisegid wi&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">bi AA.</NOTE> fendis, whanne &thorn;ei leuen hem vnkept &amp; bisien hem in worldly office &amp; lordis courtis. whi ben not &thorn;es lordis &thorn;at &thorn;us holden curatis in here courtis &amp; worldly offices traitours to god almy&yogh;tty, si&thorn; &thorn;ei drawen awey his chef knyttis fro here gostly bataile whanne &amp; where &thorn;ei weren most nedful. for &thorn;is seruyce &thorn;at lordis han of curatis abouten worldly office cristene soulis ben vntau&yogh;t, &amp; woluys of helle stranglen hem &amp; encombren hem in endles dispeir.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="11" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum 11<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>&THORN;e eleuen&thorn;e errour; &thorn;at &thorn;ei chargen more wrongful maundementis of synful men &thorn;an &thorn;e most ri&yogh;tful comaunde|mentis of god; for &yogh;if &thorn;e pope or bischop sende a letter 
<PB REF="00000216.tif" N="150"> for to resceyue a pardoner to disceyue &thorn;e peple bi graunt of<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted X.</NOTE> many &thorn;ousand &yogh;eer to pardon, he schal be sped algatis; but &yogh;if<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted X.</NOTE> &thorn;er come ony trewe man to preche frely &amp; trewely &thorn;e gospel, he schal be lettid for wrongful comaunde|ment of a synful man. &amp; &thorn;us &thorn;ei dreden more synful men &thorn;an god almy&yogh;tty, si&thorn; &thorn;ei putten goddis comaundement &amp; his ri&yogh;tful wille bihynde &amp; putten a synful mannus wille &amp; wrong comaundement bifore. &amp; &thorn;us for here owene worldly profit &amp; bodely ayse &thorn;ei stoppen here parischenys fro herynge of goddis lawe, &thorn;at is fode of soule, &amp; leden hem blyndly to helle; &amp; &thorn;es ben euele fadris &thorn;at &thorn;us cruelly enfamynen here sugetis soulis &amp; dryuen hem to dampnacion for loue of worldly muk or bodily ayse, or for drede of wrecchid anticristis &thorn;at ben goddis traitours &amp; his peplis.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="12" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum 12<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>&THORN;e twel&thorn;e errour; &thorn;at &thorn;ei dispisen &thorn;e principal office comaundid of <MILESTONE N="128" UNIT="page">god to curatis, &amp; bisen hem aboute nouelries maad of synful men; for comunly &thorn;ei kunnen not preche &thorn;e gospel, &amp; &thorn;ei wolen lerne bisily mennus tradicions for worldly wynnynge, but not &thorn;e gospel &thorn;at crist god &amp; man tau&yogh;te &amp; comaundid curatis to techen &thorn;at to lif &amp; de&thorn;; &amp; certis as &thorn;ei louen to studie, kepe &amp; teche &thorn;e word<NOTE PLACE="foot">world X.</NOTE> of synful men bifore the word of god, so &thorn;ei louen synful men or pride or worldly drit &thorn;at come&thorn; of mennus lawe more &thorn;an almy&yogh;tty god &amp; &thorn;e blisse of heuene; &amp; certis herfore &thorn;ei ben traitours of god &amp; cheuenteynes in &thorn;e fendis hoost to lede men in|to helle.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="13" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum 13<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>&THORN;e &thorn;rittene errour; &thorn;ei cursen here gostly children more for loue of worldly catel &thorn;an for brekynge of goddis hestis. For &thorn;ou&yogh; a man breke opynly &thorn;e hestis of god, lyuynge in 
<PB REF="00000217.tif" N="151"> pride, in false swerynge,<NOTE PLACE="foot">werynge X.</NOTE> in opyn brekynge of &thorn;e holy day, he schal not be sompned ne ponysched ne cursed bi hem. But &yogh;if a man be bihynde of ti&thorn;es &amp; o&thorn;ere offryngis &amp; cust[u]mes maad of synful men, he schal be sompned, ponyschid &amp; cursed, &yogh;e &thorn;ou&yogh; he may not lyue out of o&thorn;ere mennus dette &amp; fynde his wif &amp; his children bi goddis comaundement; &amp; &thorn;us &thorn;ei seken more &thorn;ere<NOTE PLACE="foot">here AA.</NOTE> owene worschipe &amp; wynnynge &thorn;an &thorn;e worschipe of god &amp; sauynge of cristene soulis; &amp; &thorn;us &thorn;ei worschipen false goddis for here false coueitise. wonder it is &thorn;at &thorn;es curatis cursen so sore for here owene cause where &thorn;ei schulden be pacient as crist was <SUP>3</SUP>and hise apostlis<SUP>3</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot">3_3 omitted X.</NOTE>; &amp; so litel recken of dispit don to god where &thorn;ei schulden taken al resonable vengaunce.<NOTE PLACE="foot">In AA this last clause runs "and where &thorn;at &thorn;ei shulden take suche unresonable vengeaunce."</NOTE></P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="14" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum 14<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>&THORN;e fourten&thorn;e; &thorn;ei taken here worldly myr&thorn;e, haukynge &amp; huntynge &amp; o&thorn;ere vanytes doynge, &amp; suffren woluys of helle stranglen mennus soulis bi many cursed synnes. &thorn;ei schulden drawe men fro worldly vanytes &amp; techen hem &thorn;e perilis of &thorn;is lif &amp; to &thorn;enke on here de&thorn; day, &amp; be myrrour to hem to morne for here synnes &amp; o&thorn;ere mennus &amp; for longe tariynge of heueneley blisse, &amp; laste in holy preieris &amp; trewe techynge of &thorn;e gospel and aspiynge &thorn;e fendis cautelis, &amp; warne cristene men of hem. But now &thorn;e more &thorn;at a curat ha&thorn; of pore mennys goodis, &thorn;e more comunly he wasti&thorn; in costy fedynge of houndis &amp; haukis, &amp; suffre pore men haue grete defaute of mete &amp; drynk &amp; cloi&thorn;; but hou schullen &thorn;ei answere to crist at &thorn;e dredful day of dom, &thorn;at &thorn;us holden pore mennus liflode fro hem &amp; wasten it in such worldly vanyte? certis &thorn;ei schullen be dampnyd for mansleeris bo&thorn;e of body &amp; soule, &amp; for sleeris of crist wi&thorn; &thorn;e wickid iewis &thorn;at nayleden him on &thorn;e cros.</P>


</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="15" TYPE="chapter"><PB REF="00000218.tif" N="152">
<HEAD>Capitulum 15<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>&THORN;e feften&thorn;e; &thorn;at &thorn;ei haunten tauernes out of mesure &amp; stiren lewid men to dronkenesse, ydelnesse &amp; cursed swerynge and <MILESTONE N="129" UNIT="page">chydynge &amp; fi&yogh;ttynge; for &thorn;ei wolen not traueilen faste in here gostly office after crist &amp; his apostlis, <SUP>1</SUP>&thorn;at ful bisili ha&thorn; tau&yogh;t hem<SUP>1</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot">1_1 omitted X.</NOTE>; &thorn;erfore &thorn;ei fallen to nyse pleies, at tables, chees &amp; hasard, &amp; beten &thorn;e stretis, &amp; sitten at &thorn;e tauerne til &thorn;ei han lost here witt, &amp; &thorn;an chiden &amp; stryuen &amp; fi&yogh;ten sum|tyme, &amp; sumtyme nei&thorn;er han ei&yogh;e ne tonge ne hond ne foot to helpe hem self for dronkenesse, &amp; be &thorn;is ensaumple &thorn;e lewed peple wene&thorn; &thorn;at dronkenesse<NOTE PLACE="foot">added by a later hand in X.</NOTE> is no synne; but he &thorn;at wasti&thorn; most pore mennys goodis at tauernes, makynge hym self &amp; o&thorn;ere men dronken, is most preised of nobleie &amp; curtesie &amp; goodnesse &amp; largenesse &amp; wor&thorn;inesse <SUP>3</SUP>of &thorn;e world.<SUP>3</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot">3_3 These words, omitted in X, are added as a correction in AA.</NOTE> lord, hou wel ben &thorn;es dronken curatis disposid to serue god &amp; mynystre sacramentis, &amp; namely of confession in tyme of de&thorn;, to here sugetis.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="16" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum 16<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>&THORN;e sixten&thorn;e; &thorn;ei wolen not &yogh;eue &thorn;e sacramentis of &thorn;e auter, &thorn;at is cristis body, to here paryschenys, but &yogh;if &thorn;ei paied here ti&thorn;es &amp; offryngis, &amp; but &yogh;if &thorn;ei han paied money to a worldly prest to slee cristene men. &amp; &yogh;if men douten of &thorn;is, late hem enquere &thorn;e so&thorn;e hou it was whanne &thorn;e bischop of norwich went in-to flaundris, &amp; killed hem bi many &thorn;ousandis &amp; made hem oure enemys. litel recken &thorn;es curatis in what deuocion &amp; charite here parischenys resceyuen cristis body, whanne &thorn;ei openly taken hem vp fro goddis<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted AA.</NOTE> bord, &amp; stiren hem to vnpacience &amp; enuye &amp; hate for a litel muk &thorn;at &thorn;ei chalengen to hem self.</P>


</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="17" TYPE="chapter"><PB REF="00000219.tif" N="153">
<HEAD>Capitulum 17<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>&THORN;e seuenten&thorn;e; &thorn;e ben blynde lederis ledynge &thorn;e blynde<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted X.</NOTE> peple to synne bi here euyl ensaumple &amp; fals disceit in techynge, &amp; at &thorn;e laste in-to helle; for &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;ei kunnen not o poynt of &thorn;e gospel ne whiten what &thorn;ei reden, &yogh;it &thorn;ei wolen take a fat benefice wi&thorn; cure of mannus soule; &amp; nei&thorn;er kunnen reule here owene soule ne o&thorn;ere mennys, ne wolen spedly lerne ne suffre o&thorn;ere men to teche here parischenys trewly &amp; frely &thorn;e gospel &amp; goddis hestis. And &yogh;it &thorn;ei crien fast &thorn;at &thorn;e peple schal doo after hem, whenne &thorn;ei knowe not &thorn;e ri&yogh;tte weie to heuene; &amp; so &thorn;ei leden &thorn;e symple peple in errour &amp; synne whanne &thorn;e peple wene&thorn; for<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted X.</NOTE> to do wel, &amp; maken &thorn;e peple to demen good euyl &amp; euyl good, &amp; to wende &thorn;e weie to helle whanne &thorn;ei wenen to goo to heuene.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="18" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum 18<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>&THORN;e ei&yogh;ten&thorn;; &thorn;ei ben fals prophetis, techinge fals cronyclis &amp; fablis to colour here worldly lif &thorn;erby, &amp; leuen &thorn;e trewe gospel of ih&umacr; crist; for &thorn;ei louen welle to telle hou &thorn;is seynt <SUP>3</SUP>or &thorn;is<SUP>3</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot">3_3 omitted AA.</NOTE> lyuede in gay &amp; costy clo&thorn;is &amp; worldly aray, <SUP>4</SUP> &amp; &yogh;it is a grete seynt.<SUP>4</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot">4_4 X reads &amp; &yogh;it it is a grete synne.</NOTE> But &thorn;ei leuen to teche &thorn;e grete penaunce &amp; sorow &thorn;at &thorn;ei diden after ward, for which &thorn;ei<NOTE PLACE="foot">cut away from margin in X.</NOTE> pleseden god &amp; not for here worldly lif, &amp; &thorn;us &thorn;ei make &thorn;e peple to<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted X.</NOTE> wene &thorn;at worldly lif of prestis &amp; veyn cost of hem &amp; waste of pore mennus goodis plesi&thorn; god &amp; is<NOTE PLACE="foot">his X.</NOTE> vertuous lif, a&yogh;enst cristis lif &amp; his techynge &amp; his apostlis also; &amp; &thorn;ei techen also hou for curs of a synful man &thorn;e creature of god, as a loof, &thorn;at trespasid not, was mowlid &amp; fordon, &amp; make &thorn;e peple bileue <MILESTONE N="130" UNIT="page">&thorn;at &thorn;at a goode cristene man kepynge welle goddis hestis schal be dampnyd for a wrongful curs of a worldly prest, &thorn;at in caas is a dampnyd fend, &amp; &thorn;us &thorn;ei bryngen &thorn;e 
<PB REF="00000220.tif" N="154"> peple out of<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted X.</NOTE> cristene fei&thorn; bi here false cronyclis &amp; <SUP>2</SUP>here sotele<SUP>2</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot">2_2 omitted X.</NOTE> fablis. For crist sei&thorn; &thorn;at men schullen be blissed of god whanne men schullen curse hem &amp; pursue hem &amp; seie alle euyl a&yogh;enst hem falsly for &thorn;e loue of crist &amp; his trew&thorn;e. And &thorn;e peple bileue&thorn; &thorn;e contrarie of &thorn;is techynge of crist bi &thorn;is fablis &amp; seyntis dedis, or lesyngis putt on seyntis.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="19" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum 19<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>&THORN;e neynten&thorn;e; &thorn;ei assenten to pardoners disceyuynge &thorn;e peple in fei&thorn; &amp; charite &amp; worldly goodis for to haue part of here gederynge, &amp; letten prestis to preche &thorn;e gospel for drede laste here synne &amp; ypocrisie be knowen &amp; stoppid; for whanne &thorn;ere come&thorn; a pardoner wi&thorn; stollen bullis &amp; false relekis, grauntynge mo &yogh;eris of pardon &thorn;an comen bifore domes day for &yogh;euynge of worldly catel to riche placis where is no nede, he schal be sped &amp; resceyued of curatis for to haue part of &thorn;at he geti&thorn;; but a preste &thorn;at wole telle &thorn;e trew&thorn;e to alle men wi&thorn;-outen glosynge &amp; frely wi&thorn;-outen beggynge of &thorn;e pore peple, he schal be lettid bi sotil cauyllacions of mannus lawe, for drede last he touche &thorn;e sore of here conscience &amp; cursed lif. &amp; &thorn;is pardoner schalle telle of more power &thorn;an euere crist grauntid to petir or poul or ony apostle, to drawe &thorn;e almes fro pore bedrede nei&yogh;eboris &thorn;at ben knowen feble &amp; pore, &amp; to gete it to hem self &amp; wasten it <SUP>3</SUP>ful synfulli<SUP>3</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot">3_3 omitted X.</NOTE> in ydelnesse &amp; glotonye &amp; lecherie, &amp; senden gold out of oure lond to riche lordis &amp; housis where is no nede &amp; make oure lond pore by many sotile<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted X.</NOTE> weies; &amp; here bi &thorn;e peple is more bold to <SUP>5</SUP>lien stille<SUP>5</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot">5_5 lyue X.</NOTE> in her<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted X.</NOTE> synne, &amp; wene&thorn; not to haue as myche &thorn;ank &amp; reward of crist for to do<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted AA.</NOTE> here almes to pore feble men, as crist biddi&thorn; in &thorn;e gospel, as whanne &thorn;ei don here almes to riche housis aftir graunt of synful foolis; &amp; this is opyn errour a&yogh;enst cristene fei&thorn;.
</P>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="20" TYPE="chapter"><PB REF="00000221.tif" N="155">
<HEAD>Capitulum 20<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>&THORN;e twenti&thorn;e; &thorn;at a prest of good lif &amp; deuout &amp; trewe prechour of goddis lawe is dispised, hatid &amp; pursued of worldly curatis, &amp; a fals prest of worldly lif &amp; aray &thorn;at suffren men wexe roten in here cursed synne is louyd, preised &amp; cherischid among <SUP>1</SUP>such synful folis;<SUP>1</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot">1_1 hem X.</NOTE> for &thorn;ei seyn &thorn;at such a good prest is <SUP>2</SUP>an ydiot and<SUP>2</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot">2_2 omitted X.</NOTE> an ypocrite &amp; sclaundri&thorn; men of holy chirche &amp; letti&thorn; men to do here deuocion to holy chirche; &amp; bi here dom a prest &thorn;at liue&thorn; comyn worldly lif &amp; stiri&thorn; no men to wra&thorn; bi<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e X.</NOTE> reprouynge hem of here opyn synnes do&thorn; moche worschipe to holy chirche &amp; encresce&thorn; mennus deuocion; &amp; &thorn;us for here coueitise &amp; pride trewe prestis ben put abak &amp; dispised, &amp; ydel prestis &amp; worldly be preised &amp; cherischid, &amp; &thorn;is maki&thorn; many men slowe in good lif &amp; prechynge and manye <MILESTONE N="131" UNIT="page">to loue worldly lif &amp; ydelnesse <SUP>4</SUP>&amp; vanyte.<SUP>4</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot">4_4 omitted X.</NOTE></P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="21" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum 21<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>&THORN;e on and twente&thorn;e; &thorn;ei hiden &amp; meyntenen her synnes &amp; o&thorn;ere mennus bi proteccion &amp; helpe of lordis, &thorn;at here souereyns may not correcte hem ne compelle hem to resi|dence. for whanne &thorn;er is<NOTE PLACE="foot">his X.</NOTE> a vicious curat of lecherie or of<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted X.</NOTE> vnkunnynge he wole haue lettris of kyng &amp; lordis to dwelle in here courtis in worldly offices &amp; be absent fro his cure; &thorn;at his souereyn schal not dore correcte him for drede of his temperaltees &amp; wra&thorn;&thorn;e of lordis; &amp; &thorn;us lordis ben made schildis of synne for a litel money or worldly seruyce of wickid curatis, &thorn;at ri&yogh;twisnesse may not for&thorn; <SUP>7</SUP>in her vertuouse lyuynge.<SUP>7</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot">7_7 omitted X.</NOTE></P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="22" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum 22<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>&THORN;e two &amp; twen[ti]&thorn;e; &thorn;at many of hem vnder colour of lernynge of &thorn;e gospel lerne statutis maade of synful men &amp; 
<PB REF="00000222.tif" N="156"> worldly prestis, &amp; lyuen in ydelnesse, glotonye, dronkenesse &amp; lecherie, &amp; ben euere &thorn;e lengere &thorn;e more vnable. For whanne &thorn;ei han grete benefices, perauenture by symonye, &amp; connen not teche here sugetis to saue here soulis, &amp; doren not holden here lemmannys at home for clamour of men, &thorn;ei gon to scole &amp; faren wel of mete &amp; drenk &amp; reste &amp; studyen wi&thorn; &thorn;e cuppe &amp;<NOTE PLACE="foot">AA inserts here viciouse.</NOTE> strumpatis; where goode prestis traueilen faste to lerne goddis lawe, &thorn;ei gon for &thorn;e manere to cyuyle or canon, &amp; don litel good &thorn;er at <SUP>2</SUP>as trewe men &thorn;inken<SUP>2</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot">2_2 omitted X.</NOTE>; &amp; &thorn;us &thorn;ei wasten pore mennus liflode in hordom &amp; glotonye, &amp; lernen lorelschipe, &amp; to curse cristene men for here goodis, &amp; &yogh;euen to here sugettis ensaumple of pride &amp; coueitise &amp; glotonye &amp; lecherie &amp; ydelnesse.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="23" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum 23.<NOTE PLACE="foot">In X the heading of this chapter is omitted.</NOTE></HEAD>
<P>&THORN;e &thorn;re &amp; twenti&thorn;e; &thorn;e more kunnynge men of hem myspenden here witt &amp; kunnynge in meyntenaunce of synne, as of pride &amp; coueitise of clerkis &amp; oppressynge of pore parischenys bi wrong customes for drede of plee &amp; censuris, &amp; meyntenynge false causis in constories for gold; &amp; taken pensions of lecherous men &amp; wommen for<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted X.</NOTE> to helpe hem to ba&thorn;e hem in here synne as swyn in &thorn;e fen. &amp; herby he &thorn;at can cracke a litil latyn in constories of he&thorn;ene mennus lawe &amp; worldly prestis lawe &amp; can helpe to anoie a pore man bi knackis or chapitris, is holden a noble clerk &amp; redy &amp; wys, &thorn;ou&yogh; he kunne not rede wel a vers in his sauter ne vnder|stonden a comune auctorite of holy writt; &amp; siche knackeris ben as proude of here veyn kunnynge as lucifer, &amp; setten not bi pore mennus kunnynge in goddis lawe, but dispisen hem &amp; goddis lawe as &thorn;ou&yogh; it were no lawe, &amp; comenden here owene lawe &amp; hem self more &thorn;an holy writt &amp; ih&umacr; crist &amp; his apostlis <SUP>5</SUP>&thorn;at so blessidly lyueden<SUP>5</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot">5_5 omitted X.</NOTE>; &amp; &thorn;is maki&thorn; synne &amp; falsnesse to<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted X.</NOTE> regne, &amp; fei&thorn; &amp; treu&thorn;e &amp; charite be defoulid &amp; quenchid.</P>


</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="24" TYPE="chapter"><PB REF="00000223.tif" N="157">
<HEAD>Capitulum 24.<NOTE PLACE="foot">23 X.</NOTE></HEAD>
<P>&THORN;e foure &amp; twenti&thorn;e; &thorn;at &thorn;ei maken &thorn;e clene lawe of god vnder &thorn;e feet of anticrist &amp; his clerkis, &amp; treu&thorn;e of &thorn;e gospel be dampnyd for errour &amp; ignoraunce of worldly clerkis; for &thorn;es worldly clerkis &thorn;at lyuen in glotonye &amp; studien to drynke hei&yogh;e wynes<NOTE PLACE="foot">with wyues AA.</NOTE> <MILESTONE N="132" UNIT="page">&amp; base fisik wi&thorn; strumpetis presumen bi here pride to be domes men of sotil &amp; hei&yogh;e mysterijs<NOTE PLACE="foot">mynysters X.</NOTE> &amp; priue articlis of holy writt, &amp; blyndly dampnen treu&thorn;es of cristis gospel, for &thorn;ei ben a&yogh;enst here worldly lif &amp; fleschly lustis; &amp; &thorn;es blynde bosardis wolen dampnen trewe men &thorn;at techen trewely &amp; frely holy writt a&yogh;enst here synnes to be heretikis, For no man schulde here goddis lawe tauw&yogh;t bi suche trewe men, &amp; &thorn;ei hem self wole preche here owne tradicions &amp; not &thorn;e gospel; &amp; so holy writt schal be owtlawid or oppressid bi wronge statutis of synful mennys makynge; but certis alle cristene men schal crie out on &thorn;es deuelis blasphemyes &amp; cursed heresies of anticrist &amp; his worldly fonned clerkis.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="25" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum 25<SUP>m.</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot">24 X.</NOTE></HEAD>
<P>&THORN;e fyue &amp; twenti&thorn;e errour; &thorn;ei chesen newe lawis maad of synful men &amp; worldly &amp; coueytise prestis &amp; clerkis to reule &thorn;e peple bi hem as most nedful &amp; best lawis, &amp; forsaken &thorn;e perfiteste lawe of &thorn;e gospel &amp; pistlis of crist &amp; his apostlis, as not perfit ne fully ynou&yogh; ne trewe; for now he&thorn;ene mennus lawis and worldly clerkis statutis ben red in vnyuersitees, &amp; curatis lernen hem faste wi&thorn; grete desir, studie &amp; cost, but &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted X.</NOTE> lawe of god is litel studied, litel costid &thorn;er aboute, &amp; lesse kept &amp; tau&yogh;t; but &thorn;e olde testament for wynnyng of ty&thorn;es &amp; offryngis is sumwhat practised; &amp; &thorn;e gospel &thorn;at teche&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">techid X.</NOTE> cristis mekenesse &amp; wilful pouert &amp; bisi traueile&yogh; in prechynge to saue cristene soulis, for it constreyne&thorn; prestis to &thorn;is holy lif, is litel loued &amp; studied &amp; tau&yogh;t but ra&thorn;ere dispised &amp; hyndrid &amp; maade fals bi<NOTE PLACE="foot">AA inserts &thorn;e uiciouse.</NOTE> speche of anticristis clerkis. &amp; in &thorn;is &thorn;ei 
<PB REF="00000224.tif" N="158"> seyn &thorn;at crist is vnwytty, out of charite &amp; treu&thorn;e, si&thorn; he &yogh;af not a sufficient lawe &amp; &thorn;e beste for reuelynge of his peple, &amp; &thorn;at worldly fonned clerkis of sathanas &amp; anticrist ben wittiere, trewere &amp; in more charite &thorn;an ih&umacr; crist, si&thorn; here lawes ben betre &amp; more nedful for cristene men &thorn;an &thorn;o<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e X.</NOTE> lawis &thorn;at crist himsilf<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted X.</NOTE> made. But on this blasphemye heresie schullen alle cristene men crien out &amp; take fully &thorn;e gospel to here reule <SUP>3</SUP>&amp; hel&thorn;e,<SUP>3</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot">3_3 omitted X.</NOTE> &amp; not sette bi &thorn;es newe lawis <SUP>4</SUP>maad of synful wrecchis<SUP>4</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot">4_4 omitted X.</NOTE> but in also moche as &thorn;ei ben groundid in holy writt expresly or good reson &amp; trewe conscience &amp; charite; for as god bi seynt poul techi&thorn;, who euere teche&thorn; o&thorn;ere lawes he is cursed<NOTE PLACE="marg">Gal. i. 8.</NOTE> of god; &yogh;e, &thorn;ou&yogh; he were an angil of heuene; for god may not make o&thorn;ere lawis a&yogh;enst his gospel &amp; charite, whi schulde anticrist &amp; his clerkis?</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="26" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum 26<SUP>m.</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot">25 X.</NOTE></HEAD>
<P>&THORN;e sixe and twenti&thorn;e; &thorn;ei magnyfyen hem self abouen crist god &amp; man; for &thorn;ei comaunden here sugetis &thorn;at &thorn;ei owen not to iuge clerkis, ne here opyn werkis ne here techynge, But do aftir here techynge, be it trewe be it fals. But oure lord ih&umacr; crist comaundid his enemys to deme of hym a ri&yogh;tful dom &amp; not aftir &thorn;e face. Also oure lord ih&umacr; bad his enemys bileue<NOTE PLACE="marg">John vii. 24.</NOTE> to his werkis &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;ei wolden not bileue to him, &amp; bad &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="marg">John x. 38.</NOTE> <MILESTONE N="133" UNIT="page">men schulden not bileue to hym &yogh;if he dide not &thorn;e werkis of his fadir. &para; Also crist bad to his enemys &thorn;at &thorn;ei<NOTE PLACE="foot">he X.</NOTE> schulde bere<NOTE PLACE="marg">John xviii. 23.</NOTE> witnesse of euyl &yogh;if he had spoken euyle, &amp; seynt poul biddi&thorn; his hereris deme &thorn;at &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted X.</NOTE> he seide, where &thorn;es worldly foolis<NOTE PLACE="marg">1 Cor. x. 15.</NOTE> wolen be anticristis more maistris &thorn;an crist god &amp; man, Si&thorn; &thorn;ei wolen not be demyd &amp; amendid bi cristis<NOTE PLACE="foot">cristene AA.</NOTE> peple vnder hem of here opyn werkis a&yogh;enst goddis hestis ne of here fals lesyngis &thorn;at &thorn;ei techen in stede of cristis gospel. certis a more blasphemye ground castid neuere sathanas to norische synne of clerkis &amp; fals disceit in techynge, &amp; to lede blyndly cristene soulis to helle.</P>


</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="27" TYPE="chapter"><PB REF="00000225.tif" N="159">
<HEAD>Capitulum 27.<NOTE PLACE="foot">26 X.</NOTE></HEAD>
<P>&THORN;e seuene and twenti&thorn;e; &thorn;ei ben anticristis lettynge cristene men to kunne here bileue &amp; speken of holy writt; for &thorn;ei crien opynly &thorn;at seculer men schullen not entirmeten hem of &thorn;e gospel to rede it in heir<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted X.</NOTE> modir tonge, but heere<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted X.</NOTE> her gostly fadris preche &amp; do after hem in alle &thorn;ingis; but &thorn;is is ex|presly a&yogh;enst goddis techynge. For god comaundi&thorn; generaly to eche lewid man &thorn;at he schal haue goddis hestis bi-fore hym &amp; teche hem to his children <SUP>4</SUP>&amp; also to hise meyne,<SUP>4</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot">4_4 omitted X.</NOTE> &amp; &thorn;e wise<NOTE PLACE="marg">Deut. vi. 6.</NOTE> man biddi&thorn; euery cristene man &thorn;at alle his tellynge be in &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="marg">Ecclus. vi. 37.</NOTE> hestis of god altherhi&yogh;est,<NOTE PLACE="foot">alyerhi&yogh;est X.</NOTE> &amp; &thorn;at he haue euere more in mynde &thorn;e comaundementis of god. And seynt petir biddi&thorn; cristene<NOTE PLACE="marg">1 Peter iii. 15.</NOTE> men be redi to &yogh;eue reson of oure fei&thorn; &amp; ope to teche eche man &thorn;at axit it, &amp; god comaundid his prestis to preche &thorn;e gospel to eche man, &amp; &thorn;e skille is for alle men schulden kunne it and reule here lif &thorn;er aftir. lord, whi schulde worldly prestis forbede seculer men to speke of &thorn;e gospel &amp; goddis hestis, si&thorn; god &yogh;eue&thorn; hem gret witt of kynde &amp; gret desir to knowen god &amp; louen him. for &thorn;e more goodnesse &thorn;at &thorn;ei knowen of god &thorn;e more &thorn;ei schullen loue god. where worldly prestis schullen for here owene vnkunnyngnesse &amp; sleu&thorn;e &amp; ydelnesse &amp; pride<NOTE PLACE="foot">X inserts &amp;.</NOTE> stoppe cristene men to knowe god &amp; serue hym vp &thorn;e &yogh;iftis &thorn;at god &yogh;eue&thorn; hym. he&yogh;ere scole of anticrist to distroie cristene mennys bileue &amp; charite herde neuere creature fro makyng of &thorn;e world &thorn;an is &thorn;is blasphemye heresie, &thorn;at lewid men schulden not entirmeten hem of &thorn;e gospel.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="28" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum 28<SUP>m.</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot">27 X.</NOTE></HEAD>
<P>&THORN;e ei&yogh;te &amp; twenti&thorn;e; &thorn;ei disceyuen cristene men in doynge of verray penaunce; for &thorn;ei doren not telle &thorn;e so&thorn;e hou nedis &thorn;ei mosten forsake alle falsnesse in craftis, in o&thorn;is, &amp; alle synne vp here kunnynge &amp; power, &amp; for no good in er&thorn;e wityngly &amp; wilfully do a&yogh;enst goddis hestis, nei&thorn;er for lucre ne drede ne bodily de&thorn;, &amp; ellis it is not verrey <MILESTONE N="134" UNIT="page">contricion, &amp; 
<PB REF="00000226.tif" N="160"> ellis god wole not asoile hem for no confession of moue&thorn;, ne for assoilynge of prestis, ne bullis of pardon, ne lettris of fraternyte, ne massis, ne preieris of ony creatur<NOTE PLACE="foot">curature X.</NOTE> in er&thorn;e or in <SUP>2</SUP>&thorn;e blis of<SUP>2</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot">2_2 omitted X.</NOTE> heuene; but &thorn;ei speken mochil of ti&thorn;es &amp; offryngis in &thorn;is confession, &amp; litel of restitucion &amp; doynge of almes to pore bedrede<NOTE PLACE="foot">bedere X.</NOTE> men, But of masse pens &amp; chirche gaynesse. &amp; herby &thorn;e peple is brou&yogh;t out of bileue, tristynge &thorn;at here synne is for&yogh;oue for here prestis assoylynge, &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;ei don not verrey penaunce as god teche&thorn; hym self. And herby &thorn;ei magnyfien more here owene assoilynge &thorn;an assoilynge of god for verrey contricion, whanne god him self sei&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted X.</NOTE> in what kynne hour a synnere ha&thorn; inwardly<NOTE PLACE="foot">in worldly X.</NOTE> sorowe for his synnys he schal be saue, &thorn;ei wolen make &thorn;is word<NOTE PLACE="foot">lord AA.</NOTE> fals, seynge &thorn;at he schal not be saf be he neuere so contrit wi&thorn;outen schrifte of mou&thorn; maad to hem,<NOTE PLACE="foot">synful men AA.</NOTE> &thorn;at ben in cas &thorn;e fendis procuratours to disceyuen men in here soulis hel&thorn;e for here vnkunnynge &amp; pride &amp; coueitise.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="29" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum 29<SUP>m.</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot">28 X.</NOTE></HEAD>
<P>&THORN;e neyne &amp; twenti&thorn;e; &thorn;ei robben cristene peple of goodis of fortune, of goodis of kynde &amp; goodis of grace bi feyned censuris of here owen lawis; for &thorn;ei cursen so dispitusly &yogh;if men paie not monye at here lykynge, &thorn;at &thorn;ei chalengen bi synful mannus lawis &amp; newe customes &amp; deuocions &amp; not of goddis lawe, &thorn;at no man dar wi&thorn;-seie hem in here wrong for drede of curs, prisonynge, &amp; lesyngis of pacience &amp; charite; &amp; herbi &thorn;ei maken cristene men as bestis holde for&thorn; here wrong customes &amp; mannus lawe, &amp; not knowe goddis lawe &amp; &thorn;e ri&yogh;tte weie to heuene. certis it were lasse cruelte to sus|pende men fro bodily mete &amp; drynk &amp; make hem dede bodily &thorn;an to suspende hem fro herynge of &thorn;e gospel &amp; goddis hestis, &thorn;at is lif of &thorn;e soule. lord, hou cursed anticristis ben &thorn;es worldly prelatis &amp; curatis &thorn;at cursen trewe men for prechynge &amp; herynge of holy writt.</P>


</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="30" TYPE="chapter"><PB REF="00000227.tif" N="161">
<HEAD>Capitulum 30<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>&THORN;e &thorn;ritti&thorn;e; &thorn;ei taken not dymes &amp; offryngis bi forme of &thorn;e olde testament &amp; partyn hem in comyn to alle prestis &amp; mynystris nedful in &thorn;e chirche, ne bi forme of &thorn;e gospel takynge a symple liflode &yogh;ouen of free deuocion of &thorn;e peple wi&thorn;-outen constreynynge &amp; cursynge, as crist &amp; his apostlis diden. but bi &thorn;e newe lawe of synful men o prest chalengi&thorn; him self alle ti&thorn;es of a gret contre bi worldly plee &amp; newe censures; &amp; nei&thorn;er lyue&thorn; as a good prest, ne techi&thorn; as a curat, ne deli&thorn; &thorn;e residue to pore men as a good cristene man. <MILESTONE N="135" UNIT="page">But wasti&thorn; hem in pompe &amp; glotonye &amp; o&thorn;ere<NOTE PLACE="foot">AA. inserts synful.</NOTE> synnes, &amp; letti&thorn; trewe prestis to do &thorn;e office enyoyned to hem bi god almy&yogh;tty. certis it seme&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;es ben not prestis after goddis lawe but after synful mennus ordynaunce, to be maistris of god &amp; lordis of cristene peple, si&thorn; &thorn;ei holden neuer nei&thorn;er lawe of god in<NOTE PLACE="foot">&amp; X.</NOTE> dymes takynge, &amp; taken hem bi vyolence &amp; stronge curses a&yogh;enst mennus goode wille, &amp; maken &thorn;e peple out of pacience &amp; charite bi here pledynge, &amp; don not wel here gostly office.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="31" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum 31<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>&THORN;e on &amp; &thorn;ritti&thorn;e; &thorn;at at ensaumple of serpentis &thorn;ei seruen bisily to lordis in seculer offices for nou&yogh;t as who sei&thorn;, and in &thorn;e ende poisonen &thorn;e lordis wi&thorn; venym of symonye &thorn;at is worse &thorn;an ony bodily poison. &amp; whanne &thorn;ei han a benefice wi&thorn; cure of mennus soule &thorn;ei dwellen stille in worldly office of lordis, &amp; spenden pore mennus liflode in riot &amp; wombe ioie, &amp; suffren cristene men perische in body &amp; soule for defaute of techynge &amp; werkis of mercy. how cursed serpentis ben &thorn;is weiward curatis &thorn;at &thorn;us enuenymyn hem self, &thorn;e lordis &amp; comunes wi&thorn; venym of symonye, of pride &amp; glotonye &amp; alle manere of synne.</P>


</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="32" TYPE="chapter"><PB REF="00000228.tif" N="162">
<HEAD>Capitulum 32<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>&THORN;e two &amp; &thorn;ritti&thorn;e; &thorn;ei maken lordis &amp; comunes bi blynd deuocion &amp; ypocrisie to meyntenen worldly clerkis in pride, coueitise &amp; ydelnesse &amp; false techynge of anticristis errours vndir colour of fredom &amp; worschipynge of holy chirche &amp; goddis lawe. For &thorn;ei crien faste &thorn;at lordis &amp; comunes moten meyntenen goddis seruauntis in his seruyce &amp; &thorn;e lawis &amp; &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted AA.</NOTE> libertes of holy chirche, &amp; maken newe seruyce likynge to worldly mennus eris &amp; newe lawis &amp; customes for here owene wynnynge &amp; pride, &amp; leuen &thorn;at seruyce &amp; clene lawe &thorn;at god made to prestis for most profit on eche side. &amp; &thorn;us whanne lordis &amp; comyns wenen to meyntenen goddis prestis &amp; his lawe, &thorn;ei meyntenen anticristis prestis and<NOTE PLACE="foot">in X.</NOTE> here lawis &amp; wrong customes &amp; pride &amp; o&thorn;ere synnes in-stede of mekenesse &amp; o&thorn;ere vertues, &amp; magnifyenge of mennus lawis &amp; dispisynge of goddis lawis.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="33" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum 33<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>&THORN;e &thorn;re &amp; &thorn;ritti&thorn;e; &thorn;ei techen cristene men to blaspheme god &amp; holden werre a&yogh;enst hym; for &thorn;ei techen cristene men to meyntenen mennys lawis &amp; ordynaunces for betre &amp; more nedful &thorn;an &thorn;e clene lawe of crist &amp; his witty ordynaunce; &amp; crien faste, &yogh;if cristene men meyntenen &thorn;e multitude of worldly clerkis in here newe lawis &amp; customes &amp; libertes &thorn;ei schullen haue goddis blissynge &amp; prosperite &amp; pees &amp; reste, bi so many deuout prestis seculer &amp; religious preiynge, redynge &amp; syngynge ny&yogh;t &amp; day; &amp; &yogh;if &thorn;ei wolden brynge prestis out of &thorn;is glorious lif &amp; new song to mekenesse &amp; gostly pouert &amp; bisi traueile in lernynge &amp; prechynge of &thorn;e gospel, as crist &amp; his apostlis diden, &thorn;ei schullen be cursed &amp; haue werre &amp; myschif, bo&thorn;e in &thorn;is <MILESTONE N="136" UNIT="page">world &amp; &thorn;e to&thorn;er;<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at o&thorn;er AA.</NOTE> &amp; &thorn;is make&thorn; &thorn;e blynde peple to werre a&yogh;enst god &amp; his ordynaunce &amp; pursuen his techeris as<NOTE PLACE="foot">AA inserts he&thorn;en.</NOTE> heretikis. &para; O &yogh;e curatis, see&thorn; &thorn;es heresies &amp; 
<PB REF="00000229.tif" N="163"> blasphemyes &amp; many moo suynge of &yogh;oure wickid lif &amp; weiward techynge, &amp; forsake hem for drede of helle, &amp; turne to good lif &amp; trewe techynge of &thorn;e gospel &amp; ordynaunce of god, as crist &amp; his apostlis diden, for reward of heuenely blisse, &amp; in confessions &amp; o&thorn;ere spechis charge &yogh;e more brekenge of goddis hestis &thorn;an brekynge of foly bihestis of newe pylgrymagis &amp; offryngis; &amp; teche cristene men to turne suche fonnyd a-vowis in-to betre almes, as crist techi&thorn; in &thorn;e gospel. Almy&yogh;tty god brynge curatis in-to holy lif &amp; trewe techynge after crist &amp; his apostlis. Amen.</P>


</DIV2>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="8" TYPE="tract"><PB REF="00000230.tif" N="164">
<HEAD>VIII. THE ORDER OF PRIESTHOOD.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>OF this tract I can only say that it may be by Wyclif. If so it must be one of the earliest of his English tracts, written before his order of poor priests had been fully organized. It may be taken to express that strong sense of the faults prevalent among the clergy which led him to institute his order of preachers.</P><P>The writer was certainly a zealous lover of his University, as may be seen from his complaint (Chapter XXIII.) that the clergy stir rich men to support chaplains and chantry priests rather than poor scholars.</P><P>Chapter XXII. deserves notice for its attack on priests who excite the people to war by processions and public prayers. (Cf. p. 170, 1. 3.) Is this utterance due only to a personal horror of bloodshed, or does it point to the existence of a peace party?</P><P>Copied from the Corpus MS. X. and collated with the Dublin MS. AA.</P><P><TABLE>
<HEAD>SUMMARY.</HEAD>
<ROW>
<CELL>CHAP. I.</CELL>
<CELL>Priests commit simony in using influence and bribes to be ordained.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>II.</CELL>
<CELL>Priests sell their masses, and offer a share in the mass to those who pay them.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>III.</CELL>
<CELL>Priests are so ignorant that they cannot read the service properly.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>IV.</CELL>
<CELL>Priests live idle and luxurious lives, haunting taverns, etc.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>V.</CELL>
<CELL>Priests neglect their duties and take secular office with lords.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>VI.</CELL>
<CELL>Priests take money to say prayers and by evil life make their prayers vain.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>VII.</CELL>
<CELL>Priests care chiefly for new song, which sets people dancing, but hides the words of Holy Writ.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>VIII.</CELL>
<CELL>Priests care more to keep the Ordinal of Salisbury than God's com|mandments.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>IX.</CELL>
<CELL>Priests take rash vows of chastity and do not keep them.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>X.</CELL>
<CELL>Priests fear to reprove vice in their patrons.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>XI.</CELL>
<CELL>Priests who preach falsely are Satans transformed etc.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>XII.</CELL>
<CELL>Worldly priests seek their own gain more than the good of souls.</CELL>

<PB REF="00000231.tif" N="165">
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>CHAP. XIII.</CELL>
<CELL>Priests carry on business as maltsters and cattle-dealers.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>XIV.</CELL>
<CELL>They care more for forms of service than for following God's commands.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>XV.</CELL>
<CELL>Covetousness of worldly priests.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>XVI.</CELL>
<CELL>Too many men become priests, because the life is an easy one.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>XVII.</CELL>
<CELL>The excuses priests make for sin.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>XVIII.</CELL>
<CELL>Priests do not try to keep their patrons from sin.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>XIX.</CELL>
<CELL>Many priests poison their masters' minds against true teachers.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>XX.</CELL>
<CELL>Priests claim falsely the power of restricting and assigning the benefit of their prayers.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>XXI.</CELL>
<CELL>They teach men to give money to friars instead of doing good to their poor neighbours.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>XXII.</CELL>
<CELL>They excite the people to unjust wars.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>XXIII.</CELL>
<CELL>They get rich men to waste their gifts on mass-priests and law-students.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>XXIV.</CELL>
<CELL>They get men to found chantries for useless priests.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>XXV.</CELL>
<CELL>They lead men to trust to their prayers more than to good life.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>XXVI.</CELL>
<CELL>They persecute God's servants and slander his law.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>XXVII.</CELL>
<CELL>Priests break God's law from fear of the bishops.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>XXVIII.</CELL>
<CELL>They cease to obey God by preaching, etc., because the bishop suspends them.</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>XXIX.</CELL>
<CELL>Nobleness of priest's office and exhortation to priests and nobles.</CELL>
</ROW>
</TABLE></P></HEADNOTE>

<PB REF="00000232.tif" N="166">
<EPIGRAPH>
<Q>&THORN;is is for &thorn;e ordre of presthod.</Q>
</EPIGRAPH>
<DIV2 N="1" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum primum.</HEAD>
<P>For &thorn;e ordre of presthod is ordeyned of god bo&thorn;e in &thorn;e olde lawe &amp; &thorn;e newe, And many prestis kepen it ful euele, telle we summe errours of prestis to amende hem wi&thorn; goddis grace. First, comynly &thorn;ei comen to here ordris by symonye many weies, for &thorn;ei ben more maad prestis for worldly honour &amp; aisy lif &amp; welfare of body &thorn;an for deuocion to lyue in clennesse &amp; holynesse &amp; penaunce, &amp; gret gostly traueile in preieris &amp; studiynge &amp; techynge of goddis lawe, &amp; to suffre persecucion &amp; sclandre &amp; prisonynge &thorn;erfore; &amp; so &thorn;ei sillen in manere &thorn;e spiritual lif of cristis<NOTE PLACE="foot">crist X.</NOTE> apostilis &amp; disciplis for a litel drit &amp; wombe ioie, &amp; &thorn;is is cursed gostly symonye &amp; heresie bifore god. &amp; what lettris &amp; preieris &thorn;ei maken for to ben ordrid prestis whanne &thorn;ei ben vnable bo&thorn;e of lif &amp; kunnynge men may knowen opynly, &amp; &thorn;is is styngynge<NOTE PLACE="foot">stynkynge AA.</NOTE> heresie of symonye; &amp; &yogh;it &thorn;ei &yogh;euen a gret raunson to bischopis officers for lettris &amp; veyn customes or &thorn;ei may be ordrid &amp; do execucion of here office; &amp; &thorn;ou&yogh; prelatis &amp; here officeris ben grettere heretikis for sillynge of &thorn;es ordris &amp; &thorn;is extorcion doynge, ne&thorn;eles &thorn;es prestis ne be&thorn; not alle excused for &thorn;ei consenten &thorn;er-to ra&thorn;ere &thorn;an &thorn;ei wolen be harde examynyd &amp; lettid of here ordris. sumtyme holy men &amp; kunnynge is-scheweden<NOTE PLACE="foot">eschewen AA.</NOTE> to be prestis for hei&yogh;enesse of &thorn;e ordre. But now &yogh;onge childre vnable bo&thorn;e of lif &amp; kunnynge presen faste to be prestis in name &amp;<NOTE PLACE="foot">X inserts not in name &amp;.</NOTE> not in dede, &amp; aftirward wolen not bisien hem to lerne, But bete stretis vp &amp; doun &amp; synge &amp; pleie as mynystrelis, &amp; vse vanytees &amp; ydelnesse.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="2" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum 2<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>Also &thorn;ei lyuen comynly in symonye, sillynge here massis &amp; &thorn;e sacrament of cristis body for worldly muk &amp; wombe 
<PB REF="00000233.tif" N="167"> ioie; for comynly &thorn;ei wolen sille here masse for annuel salarie, &amp; ellis not dwellen wi&thorn; a man but where &thorn;ei may most wynne, &amp; seyn more &thorn;e masse for loue of &thorn;e peny &thorn;an for deuocion or charite to criste &amp; cristene soulis. <MILESTONE N="137" UNIT="page">for be &thorn;e masse seide in herynge of &thorn;e peple schortly &amp; vndewoutly, litel sauour of holynesse schal men fynden wi&thorn; hem, but nycete &amp; pleye &amp; goynge to &thorn;e tauerne &amp; o&thorn;ere vanytes. it seme&thorn; resonable &thorn;at a goode prest haue resonable liflode to serue god of wilful almes of &thorn;e peple, &amp; not bi lonynge &amp; bedynge as who wold selle a worldly &thorn;ing; for &thorn;e prest may not make his<NOTE PLACE="foot">is X.</NOTE> maister lord ne partyner of his masse, but only god for his goode lif &amp;<NOTE PLACE="foot">in AA.</NOTE> charite; but many prestis don &thorn;e masse more for money &amp; bodily welfare &thorn;an for deuocion &amp; worschipe of god, &amp; wollen not don &thorn;e masse but for hope of worldly wynnynge; &amp; certis alle &thorn;es sellen criste as iudas dide, &amp; worse, for he is nowe knowen for god &amp; glorified in his manhede, &amp; nowe ha&thorn; schewid mo benefices to mankynde &thorn;an he hadde do in iudas tymes, &amp; alle &thorn;es condicions aggregen &thorn;is cursed sillynge of cristis body.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="3" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum 3<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>Also &thorn;ei sclaundren &amp; defoulen &thorn;e holy ordre of presthod bi worldly lif &amp; ignoraunce <SUP>3</SUP>of holy writ<SUP>3</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot">3_3 &amp; holy X.</NOTE>; for sumtyme god seide bi his prophete in reprof of worldly prestis &thorn;at &thorn;e prest<NOTE PLACE="marg">Hosea iv. 9.</NOTE> is as &thorn;e peple. But nowe, as seynt bernard sei&thorn;, prestis ben more worldly &amp; vicious &thorn;an &thorn;e comune peple, &thorn;at bi hem &thorn;e peple taki&thorn; ensaumple &amp; boldnesse<NOTE PLACE="foot">blodnesse X.</NOTE> in synne; &amp; &thorn;ei ben so vnkunnynge &thorn;at men scornen hem in seynge of here seruyce, &amp;<NOTE PLACE="foot">in X.</NOTE> redynge of here pistil &amp; gospel. but god sei&thorn; to such a prest: &thorn;ou hast caste a weie kunnynge of my lawe &amp; I schal<NOTE PLACE="marg">Hosea iv. 6.</NOTE> caste &thorn;e aweie &thorn;at &thorn;ou be not sette in presthod to me. &amp; &yogh;it ignoraunce of good lif &amp; goddis hestis is werse &thorn;an ignoraunce of latyn or of ony o&thorn;er langage; &thorn;erfore prestis schulden don here bisynesse to lyue wel &amp; vnderstonde &amp; knowe goddis 
<PB REF="00000234.tif" N="168"> wille &amp; teche it in word &amp; dede, &amp; be<NOTE PLACE="foot">by AA.</NOTE> myrrour of holynesse to &thorn;e peple, &amp; goddis angelis, as god sei&thorn; bi &thorn;e prophete.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Mal. ii. 7.</NOTE></P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="4" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum 4<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>Prestis also sclaundren &thorn;e peple bi ensaumple of ydelnesse &amp; wauntounnesse; for comynly &thorn;ei chouchen<NOTE PLACE="foot">couchen AA.</NOTE> in softe beddis whanne o&thorn;ere men risen to here labour, &amp; blabren out matynys &amp; masse as hunteris wi&thorn;-outen deuocion &amp; contemplacion, &amp; hien faste to mete richely &amp; costly arayed of &thorn;e beste, &amp; &thorn;an to slepe; &amp; soone a-noon to tablis &amp; chees &amp; tauerne &amp; betynge of pauement, &amp; &thorn;an speken of lecherie, of de|prauynge of goode men, &thorn;at wolen<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted X.</NOTE> not sue here companye; &amp; &thorn;anne come&thorn; dronkennesse, chidynge &amp; fi&yogh;ttynge &amp; many tymes mansleynge, &amp; bi &thorn;es prestis &amp; here wantownesse moche peple is brou&yogh;t to lecherie, glotonye, ydelnesse &amp; &thorn;efte.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="5" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum 5<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>Also prestis occupien hem ouer moche in worldly occu|pacions &amp; seculer offices a&yogh;enst holy writt for plesynge of lordis &amp; hope of benefices; for comunly prestis ben stiwardis &amp; clerkis of kechene &amp; resceyuouris &amp; rente gedereris &amp; hunteris, &amp; leuen here gostly office vndon, &amp; han more <MILESTONE N="138" UNIT="page">wakynge &amp; rekenynge &amp; traueile for a litel worschipe &amp; muk &thorn;an haue many trewe seruauntis of god for alle here doynge, &amp; &thorn;e endis ben ful dyuerse. for &thorn;e first bisynesse &amp; care, but &yogh;if god helpe &thorn;e more, brynge&thorn; euerlastynge care &amp; peyne of helle; &amp; &thorn;e to&thorn;er<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at other AA.</NOTE> li&yogh;t traueile &amp; ioiful bryngi&thorn; euer|lastynge blisse of heuene in body &amp; soule.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="6" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum 6<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>Prestis also disceyuen cristen men bi here veyn preieris &amp; abhominable to god for here lecherie &amp; o&thorn;ere synnes; for &thorn;ei taken ful mochil hire for to seie here matynes &amp; masse &amp; 
<PB REF="00000235.tif" N="169"> o&thorn;ere deuocions, &amp; &thorn;er-wi&thorn; ben foul lecchouris,<NOTE PLACE="foot">lecherous X.</NOTE> ful of pride &amp; coueitise, glotonye &amp; ydelnesse; &amp; maken &thorn;e peple wene &thorn;at here preieris ben acceptable to god, &amp; &yogh;it god sei&thorn; bi his prophete &thorn;at he curse&thorn; suche wickid mennus blissyngis, and<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted X.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="marg">Mal. ii. 2.</NOTE> &thorn;at mannus preiere is abhominable &amp; cursed &thorn;at turne&thorn; a wey<NOTE PLACE="marg">Prov. xxviii. 9.</NOTE> his here &amp; heri&thorn; not goddis lawe; &amp; god sei&thorn; bi &thorn;e prophete ysaie to suche wickid men &thorn;at he wol not here hem whanne<NOTE PLACE="marg">Isaiah i. 18.</NOTE> &thorn;ei maken many preieris; for who lyue&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">leueth X.</NOTE> best preie&thorn; best, &amp; no man prei&thorn; wel but &yogh;if he leue wel, as austyn &amp; o&thorn;ere doctours techen pleynly, &thorn;anne is here a gret disceit of euyl prestis. For whan men purposen to fynde trewe seruauntis to god, &thorn;ei fynden his enemys &amp; traitours, &amp; here preieris cursed of god for here synful lif.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="7" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum 7<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>Also &thorn;ei magnyfien more newe songe founden of synful men &thorn;an &thorn;e gospel of ih&umacr; crist, &thorn;at is cristene mennus saluacion; for &thorn;ei bisien hem fastere to kunne &amp; do &amp; teche &thorn;is newe song &thorn;an to kunne &amp; kepe &amp; teche cristis gospel; &amp; &thorn;is is merueile, for &thorn;is song distracti&thorn; &thorn;e syngere fro deuocion &amp; letti&thorn; men fro consceiuynge of &thorn;e sentence; &amp;, as austyn &amp; gregory techen wel, preiere is betre herd of god bi compunccion &amp; wepyng &amp; stille devocion, as moyses &amp; ih&umacr; crist diden, &thorn;an bi gret criynge &amp; ioly chauntynge &thorn;at stire&thorn; men &amp; wommen to daunsynge &amp; letti&thorn; men fro &thorn;e sentence of holy writt, as Magnyficat, sanctus &amp; agnus dei, &thorn;at is so broken bi newe knackynge. it seme&thorn; &thorn;at god sei&thorn; bi &thorn;es newe singeris as he dide in &thorn;e gospel to pharisees, "&thorn;is peple<NOTE PLACE="marg">Matt. xv. 8.</NOTE> honoure&thorn; me wi&thorn; lippis but here herte is fer fro me, &thorn;ei worschipen me wi&thorn;-outen cause, techynge lore &amp; comaunde|mentis of men." moyses &amp; ih&umacr; crist &amp; his apostlis preiden bi ny&yogh;t stillely in hilles, wi&thorn; clennesse of lif &amp; gret desir of ri&yogh;twisnesse &amp; brennynge charite to frende &amp; enemys, &amp; here fore god herde hym graciously. but now newe men crien 
<PB REF="00000236.tif" N="170"> hi&yogh;e to mennus eris wi&thorn; stynckynge lecherie, pride, coueitise &amp; o&thorn;ere synnes, &amp; in wille to meyntene synful mennus ordynaunce contrarie to goddis ordynaunce, &amp; desiren cruel vengaunce on here enemys; &amp; herefore we axen oure owene dampnacion in &thorn;is preiere, &amp; &yogh;if god suffre vs haue oure desir, &thorn;at is vengaunce of god to haue oure wille to grettere peynes of <MILESTONE N="139" UNIT="page">helle, for god hati&thorn; vs.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="8" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum 8<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>&YOGH;it &thorn;ei chargen more &thorn;e ordynal of salusbury &thorn;an &thorn;e hestis of god; for &yogh;if a prest faile a poynt of his ordynal, &thorn;at is no poynt of cristene mennus fei&thorn;, he schal be reproued scharply &amp; openly anon &amp; of manye. But &thorn;ou&yogh; a prest faile opynly a&yogh;enst goddis hestis bi veyn swerynge, bi pride, bi coueitise &amp; vanyte &amp; ydelnesse noman almost chargi&thorn; &thorn;at, but lie&yogh;e&thorn; &amp; iapi&thorn; &amp; helpi&thorn; hym &thorn;er-to. ful vnable ben &thorn;es foolis to mynystre sacramentis &amp; to be mediatours bitwixe god &amp; synful man.<NOTE PLACE="foot">men AA.</NOTE></P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="9" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum 9<SUP>m.</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot">In AA the numbering of this chapter is omitted, so that all which follow it are numbered one less than they should be.</NOTE></HEAD>
<P>Also many prestis vnwisly taken a wow of chastite &amp; defoulen wyues, widewis &amp; maydens; For &thorn;ei taken presthod for to lyuen esely &amp; fare wel, &amp; take no reward to here hei&yogh;e hoot complexon, but norischen it in welfare of mete &amp; drynk of &thorn;e beste &amp; riche clo&thorn;is &amp; softe beddis, &amp; traueilen not, &amp; ben &yogh;onge &amp; idel &amp; li&yogh;t chered &amp; wordid &amp; han<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted X.</NOTE> daliaunce wi&thorn; nyce wommen; &amp; alle &thorn;is brynge&thorn; many brondis of lecherie; &amp; si&thorn; seynt poul chastised his flesch wi&thorn; so gret<NOTE PLACE="marg">1 Cor. ix. 27.</NOTE> traueile &amp; peyne &amp; abstynence, &amp; &yogh;it vnne&thorn;is my&yogh;te he ouercome lustis of lecherie, hou may &thorn;es &yogh;onge foolis clene be<NOTE PLACE="marg">2 Cor. xii. 7.</NOTE> kept fro &thorn;is synne wi&thorn; &thorn;is<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted X.</NOTE> lusty lif &amp; idel &amp; daliaunce of wommen.</P>


</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="10" TYPE="chapter"><PB REF="00000237.tif" N="171">
<HEAD>Capitulum 10<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>Also &thorn;ei doren not reproue men of here opyn synnes bi forme of &thorn;e gospel for displeisynge of here maistris &amp; leesynge of here salarie; for many of hem seyn &thorn;us: "I wole not displeise him of whom I haue my lyuynge." a, &yogh;e blynde foolis, drede &yogh;e more to lese a morsel of mete &thorn;an o poynt of charite? drede &yogh;e more to offende an er&thorn;ely wrecche &thorn;an god almy&yogh;tty? loue &yogh;e more wombe ioie &amp; worldly myr&thorn;e &thorn;an &thorn;ank of god &amp; ioye of heuene? sette &yogh;e more prise bi &yogh;oure stynkynge bely &thorn;an bi &yogh;oure lord? &yogh;e reueren god &amp; worschipen false goddis many weies &amp; ben hugely cursed of &thorn;e holy trinyte &amp; alle his aungelis. hou doren &yogh;e, cursed wrecchis, seie &yogh;oure masse in &thorn;is lif to &yogh;oure dampnacion,<NOTE PLACE="marg">1 Cor. xi. 29.</NOTE> as god sei&thorn; bi seynt poul, &amp; ofte &yogh;e reden it.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="11" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum 11<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>Also for gostly li&yogh;t of good ensaumple &amp; trewe techynge &thorn;ei hilden out foul derkenesse of many synnys; for si&thorn; god sei&thorn; bi his prophete &thorn;at a prest is aungel of god, &thorn;at is a<NOTE PLACE="marg">Mal. ii. 7.</NOTE> messager to telle goddis wille to &thorn;e peple, &amp; &thorn;ei leuen &thorn;is &amp; tellen lesyngis &amp; wrecchidnessis of synnys, &thorn;ei ben angeles of sathanas transfigurid into<NOTE PLACE="foot">&amp; to X.</NOTE> angelis of li&yogh;t; for &thorn;ei han name of holynesse &amp; of goddis trewe seruauntis &amp; ben not so in dede. &amp; si&thorn; crist sei&thorn; in &thorn;e gospel &thorn;at prestis owen to be<NOTE PLACE="marg">Matt. v. 13, 14.</NOTE> salt of &thorn;e er&thorn;e &amp; li&yogh;t of &thorn;e world, &thorn;at is myrrour &amp; ensaumple to make men bareyne fro synne &amp; bi li&yogh;t of trewe techynge brynge he&thorn;ene men to cristene fei&thorn;, hou ben &thorn;ei not traitours to god <MILESTONE N="140" UNIT="page">&amp; procuratouris of sathanas whanne &thorn;ei leuen &thorn;us gostly lif &amp; trewe prechynge of the gospel &amp; &yogh;euen ensaumple of synne &amp; boldnesse &thorn;er-inne?</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="12" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum 12<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>Also worldly prestis ben anticristis disciplis, sekynge here owene worldly honour<NOTE PLACE="foot">hous X.</NOTE> &amp; wynnynge more &thorn;an goddis, &amp; 
<PB REF="00000238.tif" N="172"> hel&thorn;e of mennys soulis; for &thorn;ei traueilen faste aboute here owene worldly honour and lucre &amp; ben wode &yogh;if ony man speke a&yogh;enst hem, but of goddis worschipe &amp; hel&thorn;e of cristene soulis chargen &thorn;ei ful litel; &amp; &thorn;at seme&thorn; wel bi here lif, studye &amp; spekynge, for it is aboute worldly goodis &amp; not aboute studie &amp; techynge of holy writt; &amp; ion &thorn;e euaungelist sei&thorn; &amp; seyn austyn declari&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;o men &thorn;at &thorn;us denyen ih&umacr;<NOTE PLACE="marg">1 John ii. 22.</NOTE> ben anticristis, &amp; setti&thorn; ensaumple of forsworen men, of lechouris &amp; coueitouse men &amp; vsureris<NOTE PLACE="foot">usuris X.</NOTE> &amp; many moo; &amp; seynt ysedore &amp; ierom accorden &thorn;er-to.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="13" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum 13<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>Prestis also ben machauntis,<NOTE PLACE="foot">marchauntis AA.</NOTE> as comunly as<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted X.</NOTE> worldly men &amp; more sotil &amp; falsere, &amp; leuen here gostly office; for &thorn;ei ben corseris &amp; makers of malt, &amp; bien schep &amp; neet &amp; sellen hem for wynnynge, &amp; beten marketis, &amp; entermeten hem of louedaies, holdynge wi&thorn; fors of armes, &thorn;at &thorn;ei ben myrrour of coueitise &amp; worldly lif &amp; pride &amp; of discencion amonge cristene peple, for of alle wicked men weiward prestis ben chiff whanne &thorn;ei turne to cursednesse, for &thorn;ei ben sotil &amp; han reste &amp; &thorn;e fend is more maistir in hem for brekynge of &thorn;e holy ordre.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="14" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum 14<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>Also &thorn;ei ben foule ypocritis, clensynge &thorn;e gnatte &amp; swolwynge &thorn;e g[r]ete camaile alhool; for &yogh;if &thorn;ei failen in manere of here song &amp; o&thorn;ere newe sygnes founden of synful men &thorn;ei chargen &thorn;at as a greuous synne for to be dampnyd in helle &thorn;erfore, but &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;ei failen foule in prechynge of cristis gospel &amp; holdynge of goddis hestis &thorn;ei chargen not a straw, but ra&thorn;ere letten, dispisen &amp; pursuen falsly &thorn;o prestis &thorn;at bisien hem to do &thorn;is grete poynt of charite; &amp; &yogh;it<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;it added in X by a later hand.</NOTE> &thorn;es ypocritis feynen hem ful holy in si&yogh;te of &thorn;e peple, &amp; knelynge 
<PB REF="00000239.tif" N="173"> &amp; knockynge on here brest &amp; o&thorn;ere signes, as &yogh;if &thorn;ei wolen flee to god al hool, &amp; &yogh;it ben his stronge enemys &amp; disceyueris of his peple.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="15" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum 15<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>&YOGH;it &thorn;es worldly prestis ben lik to helle, neuere ful of<NOTE PLACE="marg">Prov. xxvii. 20.</NOTE> coueitise in no degree; for &thorn;ei connen not be a-paied wi&thorn; a resonable liflode ne resonable clo&thorn;inge, but euere redy to take of alle men &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;ei han no nede, &amp; euele dispenden it &amp; quiten not a&yogh;en but stynkynge preiere bifore god, &amp; lyuen for&thorn; in ydelnesse &amp; pride &amp; o&thorn;ere vanytes; for here herte is ouermoche on worldly goodis &amp;<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted AA.</NOTE> veyn statis, what euere &thorn;e tonge sch[e]wi&thorn; wi&thorn;-outen for&thorn;. &amp; this is a venymous rote &thorn;at maki&thorn; here seruyce &amp; preieris not acceptable to god &amp; helpeful to cristene peple as &thorn;ei schulden be. <MILESTONE N="141" UNIT="page">&thorn;erfore &thorn;is coueitise schulde be fleed of alle prestis, as ground of alle synnes as poul sei&thorn;.<NOTE PLACE="marg">1 Tim. vi. 10.</NOTE></P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="16" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum 16<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>Also &thorn;ei ben &thorn;eues, robbynge pore men of here sustenaunce bi colour of holynesse; for &thorn;ei hi&yogh;en faste to be prestis mo &thorn;an ben nedful for &thorn;e peple, for to haue esy lif &amp; welfare &amp; han<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted X.</NOTE> &thorn;e almes &thorn;at god ordeyned to pore nedy men &thorn;at han not of here owene &amp; may not labore for sikenesse or<NOTE PLACE="foot">of X.</NOTE> elde; &amp; al is demyd holynesse for helpe of here preieris, &amp; &yogh;it &thorn;e beste of hem wot not what his preiere is wor&thorn;e &amp; where it turne to his owene dampnacion or saluacion. &amp; certis &thorn;at man &thorn;at loue&thorn; best god preie&thorn; best, not for o man only but for alle men &thorn;at ben able to haue part &thorn;er-of, be he schephe[r]de or ploughman.<NOTE PLACE="foot">plow&thorn;man X.</NOTE> &thorn;erfore prestis owen to lyuen wel &amp; wasten not pore mennus liflode in pride, glotonye &amp; o&thorn;ere vanytes.</P>


</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="17" TYPE="chapter"><PB REF="00000240.tif" N="174">
<HEAD>Capitulum 17<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>Prestis weiward of lif turnen vpsodoun cristis techynge bi lesyngis &amp; ypocrisie; for &thorn;ei colouren pride wi&thorn; honeste &amp; clennesse, wra&thorn;&thorn;e &amp; vengaunce bi manlynesse &amp; ri&yogh;twisnesse, enuye bi prudence &amp; wisdom, coueitise bi ri&yogh;t traueile &amp; wis kepynge of goodis to do almes in nede &amp; pursuynge of ri&yogh;t, sleu&thorn;e bi sauynge of mannes body &amp; wor&thorn;inesse, glotonye bi largenesse &amp; fedynge of pore men &amp; helpynge of viteleris &amp; o&thorn;ere men of craftis, dronkenesse bi good felaweschipe &amp; gendrynge of charite &amp; solasynge of mennus wittis, lecherie bi helpynge for&thorn; of &thorn;e world &amp; kyndely dede; &amp; &thorn;is &thorn;ei don to excuse here owene synne, &amp; norischen o&thorn;ere men &thorn;er-inne for &thorn;ank &amp; worldly wynnynge; but certis &thorn;es ben anticristis &amp; perilous heretikis.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="18" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum 18<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>Also &thorn;ei ben foule ypocritis &amp; setten more prise be an oxe, hors or asse &thorn;an bi &thorn;e soule of here maistir &thorn;at costi&thorn; mychil on hem; for &yogh;if &thorn;ei seen vnresonable bestis of here maistris or o&thorn;ere mennus fallen in a perilous lake &thorn;ei wolen traueile &amp; helpe &amp; crien to men aboute til &thorn;e vnresonable beste be out of perils; but &thorn;ou&yogh; here maistris<NOTE PLACE="foot">maistir X.</NOTE> soule be in &thorn;e foule lake of old custumable synne, &amp; body &amp; soule in poynt to be dampned wi&thorn;-oute ende, &thorn;ei schullen not helpe to brynge hem out of &thorn;is peril, nei&thorn;er bi trewe conseilynge ne trewe prechynge ne stirynge of gostly frendis to &thorn;is helpe; &amp; her-by &thorn;ei schewen &thorn;at here herte is seeit to loue his muk &amp; not is soule. but where ben falsere traitouris &thorn;an &thorn;es prestis &thorn;at wole not helpe here maistris<NOTE PLACE="foot">his maistre X.</NOTE> out of &thorn;is moste peril, but ra&thorn;ere norische hem &amp; conseile hem &thorn;er-inne for to haue here owene lustis &amp; welfare.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="19" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum 19<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>Many of hem poisonen<NOTE PLACE="foot">poisen X.</NOTE> gostily here maistris for &thorn;e benefices &thorn;at &thorn;ei receyuen of hem; for &thorn;ei conseilen here maistris faste 
<PB REF="00000241.tif" N="175"> &thorn;at &thorn;ei tristen not to pore prestis &amp; witty clerkis trewely techynge &thorn;e gospel &amp; comaundementis of god &amp; where men owe to do here almes, but lyuen for&thorn; after <MILESTONE N="142" UNIT="page">olde errouris &amp; lesyngis &amp; anticristis prechouris &thorn;at prechen for here wynnynge &amp; fablis &amp; newe soteltes for veyn name of clergie, &amp; bidde hem do as here fadris diden, &thorn;at many tyme lyuede in falsnesse to gete goodis of &thorn;is world and myspendeden<NOTE PLACE="foot">myspenden X.</NOTE> hem in pride &amp; glotonye, &amp; &thorn;ei witen neuere where &thorn;ei dieden out of charite &amp; ben dampned in helle; &amp; &thorn;us &thorn;ei conseilen here maistris to lyue for&thorn; in here cursede synne &amp; not to amende hem.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="20" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum 20<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>Also &thorn;ei disceyuen &thorn;e peple in fei&thorn; of cristendom; for &thorn;ei maken &thorn;e peple ween &thorn;at &thorn;ei schullen not haue part of here preieris, &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;ei ben in charite, but &yogh;if &thorn;ei paien moche money to a prest &thorn;at is ydel &amp; vicious. for &yogh;if men wisten &thorn;at &thorn;ei schulden haue part of alle goode preieris bi mercy of god as moche as is ri&yogh;tful, &thorn;ei wolden do here almes to here pore nei&yogh;eboris as crist biddi&thorn;, &amp; not fynde so many worldly prestis &thorn;at kunnen no goode &amp; non wolen lerne, ne teche o&thorn;ere men to lyue wel <SUP>2</SUP>ne lyue wel<SUP>2</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot">2_2 omitted X.</NOTE> hem self. but &thorn;us &thorn;ei maken hem maistris &amp; lordis of goode preieris &amp; sillen hem to men &thorn;at hem liki&thorn; for money, &amp; taken not reward to partynge of god, hou he is chief lord &amp; graunti&thorn; part of good preieris to euery goode man &thorn;at is in grace as moche as is ri&yogh;tful.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="21" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum 21<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>Wykede prestis also disceyuen cristene men in hope; for &thorn;ei techen &thorn;at men schullen haue more &thorn;ank of god to do here almes to riche freris &amp; false pardoneris &amp; to make grete waste housynge, &thorn;anne helpe here pore nei&yogh;eboris in clo&thorn;inge &amp; housynge &amp; out of dette &amp; prison, &amp; parische chirchis 
<PB REF="00000242.tif" N="176"> vplond; &amp; certis &thorn;is is anticristis techynge, for men ernen &amp; geten moche wra&thorn;&thorn;e of god in doynge syche nouelries for worldly name &amp; ignoraunce, &thorn;e whiche nouelries god biddi&thorn; not, &amp; in leuynge werkis of mercy where god comaundi&thorn; hem to be don, for bi &thorn;is techynge &thorn;ei wenen &thorn;at it is almes to myspenden<NOTE PLACE="foot">myspendynge X.</NOTE> here goodis &amp; leuen goddis comaundement vndo.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="22" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum 22<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>Also &thorn;ei disceyuen cristene men in charite; for &thorn;ei conforten hem to fi&yogh;tte a&yogh;enst cristene men in false werris for pride &amp; coueitise bi sikernesse of here veyn preieris &thorn;at ben cursed of god; &amp; hereto &thorn;ei wolen crie ora pro nobis abouten &thorn;e grete stretis &thorn;at god distroie here cristene bre&thorn;eren &amp; &yogh;eue hem schort lif, euyl sped &amp; wicked ende; &amp; here-bi &thorn;ei axen here owen dampnacion, as god sei&thorn; in &thorn;e pater noster &amp; o&thorn;ere placis of &thorn;e gospel. it were betre to crie faste &thorn;at &thorn;e peple amendid here lif, &amp; &thorn;at god helpe vs &amp; oure enemys a&yogh;enst &thorn;e fend &amp; make us frendis in crist.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="23" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum 23<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>&YOGH;it &thorn;es worldly prestis disceyuen riche men in here almes; for &thorn;ei wolen not stire riche men to fynde pore children able of witt &amp; lyuynge to scole for to lerne, but to fynde proude prestis at hom to crie faste in &thorn;e chirche in si&yogh;tte of <MILESTONE N="143" UNIT="page">&thorn;e world, &amp; helpe<NOTE PLACE="foot">hope X.</NOTE> to serue hem at &thorn;e mete &amp; o&thorn;ere worldly offices; &amp; &yogh;it &thorn;ei stiren hem to fynde summe prestis to lawe, &thorn;at maken false dyuorsis &amp; holden false causes &amp; dispisen o&thorn;ere symple prestis &thorn;at lyuen in mekenesse &amp; deuocion &amp; medlen not of syche pledynge, but &thorn;ei stiren not riche men to fynde a good deuout prest able of witt &amp; wille to lerne holy writt &amp; preche it freely to &thorn;e peple to saue here soulis; &amp; &thorn;is maki&thorn; moche &thorn;at holy writt is not knowen ne kept, ne tau&yogh;t trewely &amp; frely as it schulde be.</P>


</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="24" TYPE="chapter"><PB REF="00000243.tif" N="177">
<HEAD>Capitulum 24<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>Also &thorn;ei maken riche men &amp; tirauntis to holde werre a&yogh;enst god after here de&thorn; day; for whanne &thorn;es riche marchauntis &amp; tirauntis dien &amp; mowen no lengere meyntene synne in &thorn;is world bi here owen persone, &thorn;an &thorn;ei fynden many worldly &amp; synful prestis, bi goodis falsly geten &thorn;at schulden be restorid to pore men, not to lerne &amp; teche holy writt as crist comaundi&thorn; but dwelle at o place &amp; crie on hey wi&thorn; newe song &thorn;at letti&thorn; deuocion &amp; &thorn;e sentence to be vnderstonden; &amp; &thorn;es worldly prestis letten most o&thorn;ere prestis &thorn;at lyuen wel &amp; techen wel, last here synne be aspied &amp; here wynnynge &amp; bodily ayse ceese.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="25" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum 25<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>Also &thorn;ei disceyuen &thorn;e peple to holde for&thorn; here olde cursed lif &amp; synne; for &thorn;ei seyn &thorn;at &thorn;ei wolen preie for hem, &amp; &thorn;ei schullen ben excused to-fore god for &thorn;e almes &thorn;at &thorn;ei don in fyndynge hem to seie masse &amp; matynes &amp; euensong &amp; placebo &amp; dirige; &amp; herbi &thorn;e peple is bolder to dwelle in synne. but &thorn;es prestis schulden witnesse opynly &thorn;at alle &thorn;e seyntis in heuene may not brynge a man to heuene wi&thorn;-outen his owen goode lif, kepynge &thorn;e hestis of God, &amp; endynge in charite.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="26" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum 26<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>Also &thorn;es euele prestis pursuen crist in his membris &amp; nailen hym on &thorn;e croos of lesynges &amp; vnkyndenesse; for &thorn;ei sclaundren cristis seruauntis wi&thorn; lesynges &amp; haten hem, &amp; helpe to lette hem fro trewe prechynge bi suspendynge, symonynge<NOTE PLACE="foot">somenynge AA.</NOTE> &amp; cursynge &amp; mannus iurdiccioun, &amp; seyn &thorn;at it was god world be for &thorn;at prestis precheden &amp; si&thorn; ha&thorn; ben discencion &amp; werris &amp; pestilencis; &amp; alle &thorn;is is to lette goddis word &thorn;at it be not knowen &amp; kept &amp; opynly tau&yogh;t. &amp; &thorn;ei sclaundren goddis lawe wi&thorn; many errouris &amp; maken it vnsawory to worldly men, for as moche as &thorn;ei wolden &thorn;at it 
<PB REF="00000244.tif" N="178"> were not knowe[n] lesse<NOTE PLACE="foot">last AA.</NOTE> &thorn;ei were lettid of here<NOTE PLACE="foot">here not in X. through the margin being cut away.</NOTE> coueitise &amp; bodily welfaire &amp; aise, &amp; it is al on to pursue &thorn;us cristis seruauntis &amp; to pursue crist, as he sei&thorn; in &thorn;e gospel, &amp; to lie &thorn;us on his lawe &amp; to lien on him self as ion crisostom &amp; austyn &amp; ambrose witnessen.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="27" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum 27<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>Also &thorn;ei dreden more synful men &amp; in cas fendis of helle &thorn;an almy&yogh;tty god in trinyte; for &thorn;ou&yogh; god comaundid hem to preche<NOTE PLACE="foot">teche AA.</NOTE> goddis lawe in word &amp; ensaumple, &amp; fauoure trewe men &amp; helpe hem &amp; preche &thorn;e gospel, &thorn;is doren &thorn;ei not done ne<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted X.</NOTE> helpe o&thorn;ere &thorn;er-to for drede of a wrongful maundement <MILESTONE N="144" UNIT="page">of a bischop or his officeris; for &thorn;anne<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted X.</NOTE> &thorn;ei schulden be somoned &amp; traueiled &amp; dispised &amp; suspendid of here masse as &thorn;ei dreden, and alle &thorn;is were medful &yogh;if &thorn;ei wolden take it paciently. but &thorn;ei dreden ouere litel &thorn;e grete peyne of helle to whiche god schal sende hem for defaute of charite &amp;<NOTE PLACE="foot">in AA.</NOTE> doynge his wille bifore alle o&thorn;ere &thorn;ingis; &amp; &thorn;us &thorn;ei dreden more &thorn;e bischopis lettre &thorn;an &thorn;e gospel of crist, &amp; so &thorn;e bischop more &thorn;an oure lord god almy&yogh;tty, &amp; &thorn;is is foule blasphemye.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="28" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum 28<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>&YOGH;it &thorn;ei leuen seruyce of god vndon for a cursed sathanas &amp; anticrist biddi&thorn; hem ceesse; for whanne &thorn;e bischop or his mynystris somonen hem &amp; &thorn;ei comen not but ben betre occupied to serue god in deuocion &amp; clennesse of lif &amp; to helpe cristene soulis to heuene, a noon &thorn;ei schullen be suspendid fro seynge of masse &amp; prechynge of &thorn;e gospel; &amp; &thorn;us &thorn;ei leuen goddis seruyce &amp; comaundementis vndon for &thorn;e comaundement of anticrist &amp; sathanas; &amp; &thorn;us bischopis officeris &amp; curatis &amp; prestis fallen oute of bileue &amp; renne in|to blasphemye &amp; heresie &amp; drawen &thorn;e comyn peple after hem in-to errour.</P>


</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="29" TYPE="chapter"><PB REF="00000245.tif" N="179">
<HEAD>Capitulum 29<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>But goode prestis, &thorn;at lyuen wel in clennesse in &thorn;ou&yogh;t &amp;<NOTE PLACE="foot">in AA.</NOTE> speche &amp;<NOTE PLACE="foot">in AA.</NOTE> dede &amp; good ensaumple to &thorn;e peple, &amp; techen goddis lawe vp here kunnynge, &amp; traueile fast ny&yogh;t &amp; day to lerne betre &amp; teche opynly &amp; lastyngly, ben verrey prophetis of god &amp; holy aungelis of god &amp; gostly li&yogh;t of &thorn;e world, as god sey&thorn; bi his prophetis &amp; ih&umacr; crist in &thorn;e gospel, &amp; seyntis declaren it wel bi auctorite &amp; reson. &yogh;e prestis &thorn;enke on &thorn;is noble office &amp; wor&thorn;i, &amp; do&thorn; it wilfully vpon &yogh;oure kunnynge &amp; power. &thorn;enke,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;enke X.</NOTE> &yogh;e lordis &amp; my&yogh;tty men &thorn;at fynden prestis, hou dredeful it is to meyntene worldly prestis in here lustis, &thorn;at nei&thorn;er kunnen goode ne wolen lerne ne lyuen holiliche in &thorn;is noble ordre. for &yogh;e may li&yogh;tly amende hem wi&thorn;-outen coste or traueile, tellynge hem &thorn;at &yogh;e wolen not fynde hem but &yogh;if &thorn;ei don here besynesse to lyue wel &amp; lerne &amp; preche &thorn;e gospel, &amp; certis &thorn;an &thorn;ei wolden don it in dede. A, &thorn;enke &yogh;e, grete men, &thorn;at &thorn;is were a &thorn;ousand fold betre &thorn;an to conquere al &thorn;e world, &amp; her-by schulde be no more cost to &yogh;ou ne traueile ne deisese, but worschipe to god &amp; endeles good to &yogh;ouwre<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;ow AA.</NOTE> self, to prestis &amp; to alle cristendom. god for his endeles mercy &amp; charite brynge &thorn;is holy ende. Amen.</P>


</DIV2>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="9" TYPE="tract"><PB REF="00000246.tif" N="180">
<HEAD>IX. THREE THINGS DESTROY THIS WORLD.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>THERE is nothing in this tract which can give us any certainty as to authorship or date. It should be noticed that the false confessors are friars; and that the lawyers, who are charged with gross hypocrisy, are priests.</P><P>The complaints of packing and bribing juries are worth notice.</P><P>Copied from the Corpus MS. X. and collated with the Dublin MS. AA.</P><P><TABLE>
<HEAD>SUMMARY.</HEAD>
<ROW>
<CELL>False confessors are the chief cause of sin, since they excuse sins on condition of gifts to religious houses. They waste money in luxurious living, and get dis|pensation from their rule</CELL>
<CELL>p. 181</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>Wicked lawyers encourage quarrels, suborn perjury, pack juries, oppress the poor. They pretend to be religious</CELL>
<CELL>182</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>Ecclesiastical lawyers worst of all. They uphold the Civil Law above God's Law. They make divorces, and raise quarrels between man and wife</CELL>
<CELL>184</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>False merchants cheat, and teach their apprentices and servants to cheat. They are usurers</CELL>
<CELL>185</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>False confessors worst of all, since they encourage the rest</CELL>
<CELL>186</CELL>
</ROW>
</TABLE></P></HEADNOTE>

<PB REF="00000247.tif" N="181">
<EPIGRAPH>
<Q>&THORN;re &thorn;ingis distroien &thorn;is world, false confessoures, false men of lawe, &amp; false marchauntis.</Q>
</EPIGRAPH>
<P><MILESTONE N="160" UNIT="page">False confessouris ben cause of alle &thorn;e synne &thorn;at regne&thorn; among clerkis, among lordis, amonge comunes; for &thorn;ei taken &thorn;e charge to hele alle men of synne, &amp; don not here power &thorn;er-to, but meyntenen &amp; conforten hem &thorn;er-inne for worldly wynnynge, frendishipe &amp; worschipe. for &thorn;ei schulden teche hem here grete synnes &amp; peynes for hem, &amp; but &yogh;if men wolden leue here synnes &amp; taken goddis word in reuerence, &thorn;ei schulden leue here companye, &amp; go to o&thorn;ere to whom &thorn;ei my&yogh;ten profite more, as crist tau&yogh;te his apostlis. &amp; &thorn;at is<NOTE PLACE="marg">Luke x. 10.</NOTE> worse, &thorn;ei seyn<NOTE PLACE="foot">AA inserts for &thorn;ei sei.</NOTE> &thorn;at &thorn;ei wolen answere for men at domes day for to excuse hem &yogh;if &thorn;ei wolen &yogh;efe hem or here hous to make gaye wyndowis or veyn housynge &amp; nedles moche gold or siluer; &amp; so &thorn;at &thorn;at schulde be delid among most nedy men bi comaundement of god &thorn;ei wasten in veyn &amp; nedles houses, &amp; &thorn;at &thorn;ing &thorn;at schulde be restorid men, for it was taken of hem bi extorsion &amp; wronge menys, &thorn;ei taken to hemself to maken festis to riche men. <NOTE PLACE="foot">X inserts as.</NOTE>lordis &thorn;ei resceyuen to here housynge, &amp; letten osteleris of here offices &amp; wynnynge, &amp; maken iubilees &thorn;at we reden not<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted X.</NOTE> of, of<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted X.</NOTE> kyngis ne emperouris, to be &thorn;anne excused of risynge at mydny&yogh;t &amp; o&thorn;ere deuocions in whiche as &thorn;ei seyn stondi&thorn; perfeccion of here ordre. &amp; &thorn;us whanne &thorn;ei schulden be most perfit &thorn;ei leuen here perfeccion &amp; maken veyn cost &amp; gret,<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted X.</NOTE> not to <MILESTONE N="161" UNIT="page">fede pore men but lordis &thorn;at han no nede, to forsake &thorn;at &thorn;at sumtyme was perfeccion. &amp; &yogh;if &thorn;e potestatis of here ordre dispinsen wi&thorn; hem lawefully, &thorn;an &thorn;ei maken hem more perfit in lif &thorn;an &thorn;ei weren bifore, for ellis &thorn;ei don hem harm in soule &amp; peieren hem to godward, &thorn;at no creature may lesefully<NOTE PLACE="foot">leffully AA.</NOTE> do; &thorn;an it were more perfeccion to leue here singuler obedience &amp; obseruauncis, as &thorn;ei don now in most perfeccion, &amp; ellis &thorn;ei 
<PB REF="00000248.tif" N="182"> ben cursed alle &thorn;at approuen siche iubilees &amp; dispensacions. And si&thorn; &thorn;is dispensacion is wel don as &thorn;ei seyn, &thorn;an god approue&thorn; it for certeyn cause, but o&thorn;ere cause is &thorn;er noone but &thorn;at &thorn;is man schal betere serue god wi&thorn;-outen &thorn;es obseruaunces &thorn;an to holden hem for&thorn;; &thorn;anne what man frere or munk schal betere serue god wi&thorn;-outen siche obseruauncis of freris or munkis &thorn;an wi&thorn; hem, god approue&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;at frere or monk leue here obseruauncis &amp; turne to fredom of cristis gospel. But it seme&thorn; whanne lordis heren<NOTE PLACE="foot">hiren AA.</NOTE> a false confessour &thorn;ei hiren an anticrist to leden hem to helle. And &thorn;us false confessouris ben &thorn;e fendis norisses<NOTE PLACE="foot">norisses, a later hand in X.</NOTE> to norisse mennus soulis in synne &amp; to brynge hem to sathanas; &amp; &thorn;us in a maner &thorn;ei sillen soulis to sathanas for a litel stynkynge drit or wombe ioie or pride &amp; worldly worschipe, &amp; &thorn;us &thorn;ei ben traitouris to god almy&yogh;tty, to clerkis, lordis &amp; comeneris, &amp; dampnen hem self.</P>
<P>Also false men of lawe disceyuen moche &thorn;is world, for &thorn;ei tellen not sadly &amp; trewely hou &thorn;e lawe stondi&thorn;. But norischen pledynge &amp; debate among men for to haue a veyn name &amp; wynnen hem a litil worldly stynkynge muk wi&thorn; goddis curs, &amp; wittyngly meyntenen<NOTE PLACE="foot">in mayntenens AA.</NOTE> &thorn;e fals partie bi cauelacions, &amp; forbarien<NOTE PLACE="foot">forbarren AA.</NOTE> pore men of ri&yogh;t, &thorn;at &thorn;ou&yogh; a pore man han neuere so muche<NOTE PLACE="foot">opyn AA.</NOTE> ri&yogh;t &yogh;it &thorn;ei wole make many doseyns to forsweren hem on &thorn;e book to gete hem self &thorn;ank or wynnynge. but &thorn;es ben false procuratouris of sathanas to dryue mennus soulis to helle; for &yogh;if &thorn;er be a trewe man in a contre he schal not come on<NOTE PLACE="foot">to AA.</NOTE> his queste &yogh;if he may deuoyde hym, &amp; &yogh;if he seie &thorn;e so&thorn;e he schal haue his<NOTE PLACE="foot">is X.</NOTE> hate, sclaundrynge, loos of his catel or of his lif in &thorn;is<NOTE PLACE="foot">AA inserts wrecchid.</NOTE> world; &amp; &thorn;es laweieris &thorn;anken &amp; flateryn &amp; meyntenen false men &amp; helpen hem<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted X.</NOTE> what &thorn;ei may; &amp; &thorn;us &thorn;ei ben special procurators &amp; false kny&yogh;ttis or champions of &thorn;e deuyl to meyntenen falsenesse, &amp; distroien treu&thorn;e &amp; kny&yogh;ttis of treu&thorn;e, equyte &amp; charite; &amp; herby &thorn;ei geten <SUP>10</SUP>hem gold<SUP>10</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot">10_10 omitted X.</NOTE> &amp; purchasen rentis &amp; londis of lordis &amp; 
<PB REF="00000249.tif" N="183"> distroien verrey heieris, &amp; &thorn;is distroie&thorn; moche<NOTE PLACE="foot">AA inserts of.</NOTE> oure lond. for hou schulde ri&yogh;t be among suche men, &thorn;at &thorn;is day han but here penye &amp; anoon purchasen rentis &amp; londis to be peris wi&thorn; knyttis or barons. Certis falsnesse avaunse&thorn; hem, &amp; &thorn;erfore &thorn;ei maken sacrifice to &thorn;e fend. lord, hou schal god here hem in here moste nede, si&thorn; &thorn;ei wolen not here a pore man, haue <MILESTONE N="162" UNIT="page">he neuere so grete ri&yogh;t. certis si&thorn; men schullen be dampnyd for defaute of werkis of mercy, moche more &thorn;ei &thorn;at wolen not opene here mou&thorn; to speke o word for treu&thorn;e &amp; goddis loue; but moche more schullen &thorn;ei be dampnyd for extorcions &amp; false plees &thorn;at &thorn;ei meyntenen wittyngly, or whanne &thorn;ei owe to witte it, a&yogh;enst trewe partie; but most &thorn;ei schullen be depe dampnyd for here grete ypocrisie, for &thorn;ei maken it so holy bo&thorn;e in word &amp; signes, as knockynge on here brest, knelynge &amp; seiynge of matynes &amp; euensong, &amp; herynge of massis, &amp; many o&thorn;ere deuocions to coloure here falsnesse, &thorn;at symple men supposen no more ri&yogh;twisnesse in ony man &thorn;at leueth in her&thorn;e. but &yogh;it iurrouris in questis wolen forsweren hem wittyngly for here dyner &amp; a noble, &amp; &thorn;at so custumablice &thorn;at &thorn;ou&yogh; a man haue neuere so opyn ri&yogh;t to a lordischipe anemptis mannys lawe &amp; also goddis, &thorn;at many questis wolen wittyngly swere &thorn;at it is not his for a litel money; &amp; so &thorn;ei sillen crist &thorn;at is treu&thorn;e, as iudas dide, for a litel money, &amp; &thorn;ei ben so esely assoiled, but falsly of false confessouris for a litel part here wicked catel, &thorn;at &thorn;ei maken no conscience for &thorn;is cursed periurie but ben endurid or hardid &thorn;er-inne as fendis of helle. &amp; &thorn;us lordis &amp; o&thorn;ere men ben nedid for &thorn;is falsnesse to holden hem at fees &amp; o&thorn;ere grete costis, for ellis. wi&thorn; here wiles &amp; falnesse &thorn;ei wolen dryue lordis &amp; gentil men out of here housis, heritage &amp; alle here goodis; &amp; bi &thorn;is falsnesse a fewe pore wrecchis my&yogh;ten<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted X.</NOTE> conqueren in-to here owene hondis<NOTE PLACE="foot">housis AA.</NOTE> in schort tyme almost al &thorn;e lordischipe &thorn;at may be sold on ony<NOTE PLACE="foot">only X.</NOTE> resonable manere. &amp; &thorn;ou&yogh; it be bou&yogh;t opynly a&yogh;enst &thorn;e lawe, &yogh;it bi cauellacions &thorn;es lawieris holden it for&thorn;, &thorn;at &thorn;e ri&yogh;tful heir may as wel bien a straunge<NOTE PLACE="foot">stronge X.</NOTE> lordischipe as geten his 
<PB REF="00000250.tif" N="184"> owene. &para; Also falsse laweieris maken lordis &amp; o&thorn;ere men to meyntenen false causis &amp; do wrongis to here nei&yogh;eboris, whanne &thorn;e lordis wenen &thorn;at it is so&thorn;, &amp; so priuely maken lordis<NOTE PLACE="foot">Some pages are wanting here in AA. containing all the rest of the tract except six lines at the end.</NOTE> dampnable for here wrong meyntenynge.</P>
<P>But of laweiris of &thorn;e consistorie or chapitris is more synne &amp; ypocrisie to schewe. for &thorn;ei tarien men in here courtis &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;e ri&yogh;t neuere so pleyn, &thorn;at men ben ful [weary] of here peyneful lif so &thorn;ei ben hurlid abouten; for &yogh;if a trewe man be falsly sclaundride &amp; come among hem it is li&yogh;ttere to make a fyn for moche money &thorn;an to purge hym, be it neuere so opyn knowen; for ellis he schal be hurlid fro contre to contre, fro day to day, &thorn;at he schal be cotumax &amp; cursed, &amp; &thorn;anne stonde at here wille, or ellis for traueile &amp; cost be ful [weary] of his lif. &para; And &thorn;ou&yogh; a man be neuere so cursed, &yogh;if he wole paie an annuel rente to &thorn;es lawieris &amp; to <MILESTONE N="163" UNIT="page">&thorn;e cursed court or to bischopis almes, he schal ba&thorn;e hym in his synne as longe as he wole &thorn;us paie; &amp; &yogh;if &thorn;ere be ony good bischop &thorn;at wole chace &thorn;e fendis of lecherie or vsurie &amp; siche moo, anoon coueitous laweieris wi&thorn; here gnackis &amp; iapis, delaies, excusacions &amp; fals appelis, letten &thorn;e bischop to ponysche &thorn;is synne. &amp; cursed|nesse of &thorn;is synne regne&thorn; for&thorn; bi a &yogh;eer, hauynge &thorn;e apel in &thorn;e hei&yogh;ere court, &amp; sumtyme as long as &thorn;is cursed man lyue&thorn;; &amp; also whanne a trewe prest wolde bi goode conscience &amp; bi forme of &thorn;e gospel distroie synne, &thorn;an lawieris maken procees bi sotilte &amp; cauyllacions of lawe cyuyle, &thorn;at is moche he&thorn;ene mennus lawe, &amp; not accepten the forme of &thorn;e gospel, as &yogh;if &thorn;e gospel were not so good as paynymes lawe. &amp; &thorn;us &thorn;ei seyn &thorn;e gospel is not ynow&yogh; to reule holy chirche by, but synful mennus lawis ful of errour ben more nedful &thorn;an &thorn;e gospel &thorn;er-to. &amp; &thorn;us &thorn;ei seyn in dede &thorn;at crist was a fool &amp; out of charite; for si&thorn; he tau&yogh;te not &thorn;e beste lawe for to reule cristene mennys soulis bi, as &thorn;ei seyn, he was out of charite; for he my&yogh;tte &amp; coude &yogh;eue &thorn;e beste, &amp; si&thorn; he demyd &thorn;at &thorn;e gospel was &thorn;e beste, &amp; it is not &thorn;e beste as &thorn;ei seyn, 
<PB REF="00000251.tif" N="185"> &thorn;an &thorn;ei seyn &thorn;at crist was a fool. &amp; so &thorn;ei putten &thorn;e gospel bihynde &amp; dispisen it &amp; magnyfien paynymes lawes &amp; o&thorn;ere synful mennys lawes for &thorn;e beste, &amp; seyn in dede &thorn;at paynymes &amp; o&thorn;ere synful men, &thorn;at in caas be dampnyd deuelis, weren wisere &amp; betre &thorn;an ih&umacr; crist, si&thorn; &thorn;ei &yogh;euen betre lawes &amp; more nedful for holy chirche &thorn;an euere dide ih&umacr; crist; &amp; herefore &thorn;ei reulyn clerkis bi &thorn;es worldly wronge lawis, &amp; maken oure clerkis worldly &amp; to forsake holy writt, for it dampne&thorn; pride &amp; coueitise clerkis &amp; teche&thorn; mekenesse &amp; to flee coueitise &amp; o&thorn;ere synnes. But paynymes lawe &amp; worldly clerkis lawe meyntene pride, coueitise, extorcions &amp; o&thorn;ere synnes, &amp; &thorn;er-fore &thorn;ei ben studied of worldly clerkis, &amp; goddis owene wordis ben dispised. &para; Also &thorn;ei maken men to forsweren hem &amp; norischen hem &thorn;erinne, &amp; maken men to charge more &thorn;e peny &thorn;an &thorn;e trewe conscience &amp; maundementis of god, &amp; &thorn;er-to maken dyuors bi false witnesse &amp; o&thorn;ere cautelis, &amp; so reisen debatis &amp; enemytes bitwene weddid men &amp; here wiwes bi many priue menys of anticrist. &amp; &yogh;it &thorn;e fend teche&thorn; hem to make orible peynes of here owene wille for smale synnys, to make men for fere to paye moche money to hem; &amp; riche men &amp; my&yogh;tti ben not ponyschid bi here lawis, be here synne neuere so opyn, but pore men ben ponyschid, &yogh;e &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;ei ben trewe &amp; clene, but &yogh;if &thorn;ei paien to anticrist aftir his wille. &amp; &thorn;us <MILESTONE N="164" UNIT="page">&thorn;es courtis ben courtis of wrong &amp; falsnesse &amp; not cristis but &thorn;e fendis, to exile treu&thorn;e &amp; charite &amp; holy writt &amp; to meyntene falsnesse &amp; synne &amp; magnifien synful mennys lawis more &thorn;an &thorn;e gospel.</P>
<P>&para; Also false marchauntis bryngen vp &amp; susteynen moche synne to distroie &thorn;e world; for &thorn;ei lyuen comynly bi falsnesse as bi false swerynge, false mesure &amp; false weitis, &amp; techen &thorn;is falsnesse to &yogh;onge prentis, &amp; preisen hym most &thorn;at foulest rayme&thorn; alle &thorn;e membris of crist falsly, &amp; most sotilly can bigilen &thorn;e peple, &amp; &yogh;if ony seruaunt of here wole do treu&thorn;e &amp; drede synne he is holden but a fool &amp; vn&thorn;rifty &amp; schal neuere be man; &amp; &yogh;it &thorn;es false marchauntis bien gret chep &amp; sillen out of cours dere &amp; bringen fro he&thorn;ene men, &amp; o&thorn;ere 
<PB REF="00000252.tif" N="186"> cursed men &thorn;at han name of cristene men, many newe gises of pride &amp; worldly vanyte, &amp; magnyfien hem aboue &thorn;e cloudis; where-fore &thorn;e lordis &amp; o&thorn;ere men ben drawen fro &thorn;inkynge of god &amp; heuenely &thorn;ingis, &amp; setten here wittis &amp; likyngis in &thorn;es newe vanytees &amp; fantom of worldly glorie. &amp; &thorn;e moste of here wynnynge stondi&thorn; in fals vsure, so moche &thorn;at &thorn;ei han enuenymed almost alle clerkis, alle lordis, &amp; alle o&thorn;ere men wi&thorn; &thorn;is cursed vsure; summe bi doynge of vsure, summe bi consentynge &thorn;er-to &amp; for meyntenynge &thorn;er-of, &amp; so &thorn;ei bringen cursyngis to alle men comynly of oure lond. &amp; &yogh;it &thorn;ei lyuen in glotonye, dronkenesse &amp; lecherie as hoggis, &amp; in coueitise, ydelnesse, pride, enuye &amp; wra&thorn;&thorn;e as fendis; &amp; &thorn;is cursed lif &thorn;ei techen in word &amp; dede to o&thorn;ere pore men as sathanas procuratouris &amp; cursed heretikis. but &yogh;it false con|fessouris &thorn;at leden hem &amp; reulen hem in &thorn;is cursed lif, &amp; wolen not tellen hem &thorn;e so&thorn;e for drede of lesynge of here frendischipe &amp; worldly wynnynge but conforten hem in &thorn;is synful lif &amp; vndertaken for here synnes at domes day, don most cursed synne of alle. for &thorn;ei techen &thorn;es foolis to make gret cost of wast houses of freris or of o&thorn;ere veyn religion, or to holde proude &amp; worldly prestis, or to founde a college of worldly clerkis or religious a&yogh;enst goddis lawe, &amp; &thorn;er-bi to be sauyd &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;ei dwellen stille in here synne &amp; maken no restitucion to men &thorn;at &thorn;ei han disceyued, &amp; &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;ei don not here almes to pore men &amp; nedy &thorn;at ben bedered &amp; mowe not helpe hem self, but suffren hem to perische for myschief. &amp; &thorn;us lordis &amp; riche men hiren false confessouris wi&thorn; grete spensis &thorn;at leden hem faste to helle; &amp; &thorn;e comune peple is constreyned bi anticristis lawis to meyntene wi&thorn; ti&thorn;is &amp; offryngis false curatis &amp; confessouris, &thorn;at disceyuen hem in techynge of goddis lawe &amp; norischen hem in synne &amp; so leden hem to helle. And &thorn;us bi &thorn;es men<NOTE PLACE="foot">many X.</NOTE> falsnesse regne&thorn;, &amp; treu&thorn;e &amp; vertuous lif ben distroied, &amp; so &thorn;es &thorn;re fals men distroien &thorn;is world bo&thorn;e in soule &amp; in<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted X.</NOTE> worldly goodis.</P>


</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="10" TYPE="tract"><PB REF="00000253.tif" N="187">
<HEAD>X. OF FEIGNED CONTEMPLATIVE LIFE.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>I THINK this is an early work of Wyclif's. It is certainly higher in tone and better in style than many in this volume. Especially to be noticed is the passage on p. 193, where the author, after inveighing against the heavy burden of ritual ordinances laid upon priests, returns upon himself with the warning that men must not abuse the freedom to which he exhorts them by making it an excuse for sloth, for that is the devil's snare. So, too, the complaint (p.194) that priests lead a lower life than their conscience dictates, for fear of hurting the sick conscience of their brethren, is a touch finer than is common in these polemical papers. How often may Wyclif's impetuous exhortations to revolt have been parried by such considerations as these?</P><P>The scribe who wrote the Corpus MS. (X.) made a curious blunder with this tract, as has been pointed out by Mr. Arnold, S. E. W. III. 507. Owing most likely to the displacement of some leaves in the MS. from which he copied, he transferred the last part of this tract to the end of "A Petition to the King and Parliament," while bringing the last part of the Petition to the end of this. As is often the case with him, he passed over the junction in happy unconsciousness that he was writing nonsense.</P><P>Copied from the Corpus MS. X. and collated with the Dublin MS. AA.</P><P><TABLE>
<HEAD>SUMMARY.</HEAD>
<ROW>
<CELL>Contemplation (so called) is made an excuse for not preaching</CELL>
<CELL>p. 188</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>Contemplation to come in heaven after good life here</CELL>
<CELL>189</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>The devil prevents men from preaching by diverting their attention to singing in a tricky and artificial way</CELL>
<CELL>191</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>In a large choir a few sing and the rest stand dumb</CELL>
<CELL>192</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>The Ordinal of Salisbury interferes with preaching, for it burdens men with so many rites that they have no time for good works</CELL>
<CELL>192</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>Men who know better waste their time on services for fear of giving offence</CELL>
<CELL>194</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>Worldly business hinders preaching</CELL>
<CELL>194</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>Christ and his Apostles preached and did not administer alms</CELL>
<CELL>195</CELL>
</ROW>
</TABLE></P></HEADNOTE>

<PB REF="00000254.tif" N="188">
<EPIGRAPH>
<Q>Of feyned contemplatif lif, of song, of &thorn;e ordynal of salisbury, &amp; of bodely almes &amp; worldly bysynesse of prestis; hou bi &thorn;es foure &thorn;e fend letti&thorn; hem fro prechynge of &thorn;e gospel.</Q>
</EPIGRAPH>
<P><MILESTONE N="165" UNIT="page">First whanne trewe men techen bi goddis lawe wit &amp; reson &thorn;at eche prest owi&thorn; to do his my&yogh;t, his<NOTE PLACE="foot">and AA.</NOTE> wit &amp; his wille to preche cristis gospel, &thorn;e fend<NOTE PLACE="foot">fendis X.</NOTE> blyndi&thorn; ypocritis to excuse hem by feyned contemplatif lif, &amp; to seie &thorn;at si&thorn; it is &thorn;e beste &amp; &thorn;ei may not do bo&thorn;e to-gidre, &thorn;ei ben nedid for charite of god to leue &thorn;e prechynge of &thorn;e gospel &amp; lyuen in contempla|cion. See nowe &thorn;e ypocrisie of &thorn;is false seiynge; crist tau&yogh;t &amp; dide &thorn;e beste lif for prestis, as oure fei&thorn; techi&thorn;, si&thorn; he was god &amp; my&yogh;te not erre; but crist preched &thorn;e gospel &amp; charged alle his apostlis &amp; disciplis to goo &amp; preche &thorn;e gospel to alle men: &thorn;an<NOTE PLACE="marg">Luc ix. &amp; x.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="marg">Mark xvi. [15.]</NOTE> it is &thorn;e beste lif for prestis in &thorn;is world to preche <SUP>3</SUP>&amp; teche<SUP>3</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot">3_3 omitted X.</NOTE> &thorn;e gospel. &para; Also god in &thorn;e olde lawe techi&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;e office of a<NOTE PLACE="marg">Isaiah lviii. [1.]</NOTE> prophete is to schewe to &thorn;e peple here foule synnys; but eche<NOTE PLACE="marg">Ezekiel iii. 17 and xxxiii. 7.</NOTE> prest is a prophete bi his ordre, as gregory sey&thorn; vpon &thorn;e gospellis, &thorn;anne it is &thorn;e office of eche prest to preche &amp; telle &thorn;e synnys of &thorn;e peple, &amp; in &thorn;is manere schal eche prest be an aungel of god as holy writt sei&thorn;. &para; Also Crist &amp; ion baptist<NOTE PLACE="marg">Mal. ii. [7].</NOTE> leften desert &amp; precheden &thorn;e gospel to here de&thorn; &thorn;erfore, &amp; &thorn;is was most charite, for ellis &thorn;ei weren out of charite or peierid<NOTE PLACE="marg">Mat.iii.&amp;iv.&amp;v.</NOTE> in charite, &thorn;at my&yogh;te not be in hem bo&thorn;e, si&thorn; &thorn;e ton was god, &amp; no man after crist was holyere &thorn;an baptist &amp; he synned not for &thorn;is prechynge. &para; Also &thorn;e holy prophete Jeromye halwid in<NOTE PLACE="marg">Jer. i. [5.]</NOTE> his moder wombe my&yogh;tte not be excused fro prechynge bi his contemplacion, but chargid of god to preche &thorn;e synnes of &thorn;e peple &amp; suffre hard<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted X.</NOTE> peyne &thorn;erfore, &amp; so weren alle &thorn;e pro|phetis of god. &para; A lord, si&thorn; crist and ion baptist &amp; alle &thorn;e prophetis of god weren nedid bi charite to come out of desert 
<PB REF="00000255.tif" N="189"> to preche to &thorn;e peple &amp; leue here solitarie<NOTE PLACE="foot">solarie X.</NOTE> preiere, hou dore we fonnyd heretikys seie &thorn;at it is betre to be stille &amp; preie oure owen fonnyd ordynaunce &thorn;an to preche cristis gospel? Lord, what cursed spirit of lesyngis stiri&thorn; prestis to close hem in stonys or wallis for al here lif, si&thorn; crist comaundi&thorn; to alle his apostlis &amp; prestis to goo in-to alle &thorn;e world &amp; preche &thorn;e gospel. certis &thorn;ei ben opyn foolis &amp; don pleynly a&yogh;enst cristis gospel &amp;, &yogh;if &thorn;ei meyntenen &thorn;is errour, &thorn;ei ben cursed of god<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted X.</NOTE> &amp; ben perilous ypocritis &amp; heretikis also; &amp; si&thorn; men ben holden heretikis &thorn;at done a&yogh;enst &thorn;e popis lawe,<SUP>3</SUP> &amp; &thorn;e beste part of &thorn;e popis lawe<SUP>3</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot">3_3 omitted X.</NOTE> sei&thorn; pleynly &thorn;at eche &thorn;at come&thorn; to presthod taki&thorn; &thorn;e office of a bedele or criere to goo bifore domesday<MILESTONE N="166" UNIT="page"> to crie to &thorn;e peple here synnes &amp; vengaunce of god, whi ben not &thorn;o prestis heretikis &thorn;at leuen to preche cristis gospel, &amp; compelle o&thorn;ere treue men to leue prechynge of &thorn;e gospel, si&thorn; &thorn;is lawe is seynt gregoryes lawe, groundid opynly in goddis lawe &amp; reson &amp; charite, &amp; o&thorn;ere lawes of &thorn;e peple ben contrarie to holy writt &amp; reson &amp; charite for to meyntene pride &amp; coueitise of anticristis worldly clerkis. but ypocritis allegen &thorn;e gospel, &thorn;at magdaleyne chees to hereself &thorn;e beste part whanne she saat bisiden cristis feet &amp; herde his word; so&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">sei&thorn; AA.</NOTE> it is &thorn;at &thorn;is meke sittynge &amp; deuout herynge of cristis wordis was best to magdeleyne, for sche hadde not office of prechynge as prestis han, si&thorn; sche was a womman &thorn;at hadde not auctorite of goddis lawe to teche &amp; preche opynly. but what is &thorn;is dede to prestis &thorn;at han expresse &thorn;e comaundement of god &amp; men to preche &thorn;e gospel? where &thorn;ei wolen alle be wommen in ydelnesse, &amp; suen not ih&umacr; crist in lif &amp; prechynge &thorn;e gospel &thorn;at he comaundi&thorn; hym self bo&thorn;e in &thorn;o olde lawe and newe. &para; Also &thorn;is peisible<NOTE PLACE="foot">posible X.</NOTE> herynge of cristis word &amp; brennynge loue &thorn;at magdeleyne hadde was &thorn;e beste part, for it schal be ende in heuene of good lif in &thorn;is world; but in &thorn;is world<NOTE PLACE="foot">lif X.</NOTE> &thorn;e beste lif for prestis is holy lif in kepynge goddis hestis &amp; trewe prechynge of &thorn;e gospel, as crist dide &amp; 
<PB REF="00000256.tif" N="190"> chargid alle his prestis to do <SUP>1</SUP>&thorn;e same<SUP>1</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot">1_1 omitted X.</NOTE>; &amp; &thorn;es ypocritis wenen &thorn;at here dremys &amp; fantasies of hem-self ben contem|placion, &amp; &thorn;at prechynge of &thorn;e gospel be actif lif, &amp; so &thorn;ei menen &thorn;at crist tok &thorn;e worse lif for &thorn;is world, &amp; nedid alle prestis to leue &thorn;e betre &amp; take the worse lif; &amp; &thorn;us &thorn;es fonnyd ypocritis putten errour in ih&umacr; crist. But who ben more heretikis? &para; Also &thorn;es blynde ypocritis alleggen &thorn;at crist biddi&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="marg">Luke xxi. 36.</NOTE> vs preie euermore, &amp; poul biddi&thorn; &thorn;at we preie wi&thorn;-oute<NOTE PLACE="marg">1 Thess. v. 17.</NOTE> lettynge, &amp; &thorn;an we prestis may not preche as &thorn;ei feynen falsly. but here &thorn;es ypocritis schullen wite &thorn;at crist &amp; poul vnderstonden of preiere of holy lif, &thorn;at eche man do&thorn; as longe as he dwelli&thorn; in charite; &amp; not of babelynge of lippis &thorn;at no man may euere do wi&thorn;-outen cessynge, for ellis no man in &thorn;is world my&yogh;te fulfille &thorn;e comaundement of crist; &amp; &thorn;is techi&thorn; austyn &amp; o&thorn;ere seyntis. &amp; si&thorn; men &thorn;at fulfillen not goddis lawe &amp; ben out of charite ben not acceptid in here preiynge of lippis, for here preiere in lippis is abhomynable, as holy writt sei&thorn; bi salomon, &thorn;es prestis &thorn;at prechen not &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="marg">Prov. xxviii. 9.</NOTE> gospel as crist biddi&thorn; ben not able to preie god<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted X.</NOTE> for mercy, but disceyuen hemself &amp; &thorn;e peple &amp; dispisen god &amp; stiren hym to wra&thorn;&thorn;e &amp; vengaunce, as austyn &amp; gregory &amp; o&thorn;ere seyntis techen; &amp; principaly &thorn;es ypocritis &thorn;at han rentes &amp; worldly lordischipes &amp; parische chirchis approprid to hem, a&yogh;enst holy writt bo&thorn;e<MILESTONE N="167" UNIT="page"> old &amp; newe by symonye &amp; lesyngis on<NOTE PLACE="foot">&amp; X.</NOTE> crist &amp; his apostelis for stynkynge gronyngys &amp; a-bite of holynesse &amp; for<NOTE PLACE="foot">fro X.</NOTE> distroiynge of goddis ordynaunce &amp; for singuler profession maade to foolis &amp; in cas to fendis of helle. &thorn;es foolis schullen lerne what is actif lif &amp; contemplatif bi goddis lawe, &amp; &thorn;anne &thorn;ei my&yogh;tten wite &thorn;at &thorn;ei han nei&thorn;er &thorn;e ton ne &thorn;e toi&thorn;er, si&thorn; &thorn;ei chargen more veyn statutis of<NOTE PLACE="foot">&amp; X.</NOTE> synful men, &amp; in cas of<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted X.</NOTE> deuelys, &thorn;an &thorn;ei chargen &thorn;e heste of god &amp; werkis of mercy &amp; poyntis of charite. &amp; &thorn;e fende blyndi&thorn; hem so moche &thorn;at &thorn;ei seyn in-dede &thorn;at &thorn;ei moten 
<PB REF="00000257.tif" N="191"> neuere preie to plesynge<NOTE PLACE="foot">preisynge X.</NOTE> of god, si&thorn; &thorn;ei vnablen hem self to do &thorn;e office of prestis bi goddis lawe &amp; purposen to ende in here feyned deuocion &thorn;at is blasphemye to god.</P>
<P>&para; Also bi song &thorn;e fend letti&thorn; men to studie &amp; preche &thorn;e gospel; for si&thorn; mannys wittis ben of certeyn mesure &amp; my&yogh;t, &thorn;e more &thorn;at &thorn;ei ben occupied aboute siche mannus song &thorn;e lesse moten &thorn;ei be sette aboute goddis lawe; for &thorn;is stiri&thorn; men to pride &amp; iolite &amp; lecherie &amp; o&thorn;ere synnys, &amp; so vnable&thorn; hem many gatis to vnderstonde &amp; kepe holy writt &thorn;at teche&thorn; mekenesse, mornynge for oure synnys &amp; o&thorn;ere mennus, &amp; stable lif &amp; charite. &amp; &yogh;it god in all &thorn;e lawe of grace chargi&thorn; not siche song but deuocion in herte, trewe techynge &amp; holy spekynge in tonge, &amp; goode werkis &amp; holy lastynge in charite &amp; mekenesse; but mannus foly &amp; pride stie&thorn; vp euere more &amp; more in &thorn;is veyn nouelrie. First men ordeyned songe of mornynge whanne &thorn;ei weren in prison, for techynge of &thorn;e gospel, as ambrose &amp;<NOTE PLACE="foot">as AA.</NOTE> men seyn, to putte awey ydelnesse &amp; to be not vnoccupied in goode manere for &thorn;e tyme; &amp; &thorn;at songe &amp; oure<NOTE PLACE="foot">o&thorn;ere X.</NOTE> acordi&thorn; not, for oure stiri&thorn; to iolite &amp; pride, &amp; here stiri&thorn; to mornynge &amp; to dwelle lenger in wordis of goddis lawe. &THORN;an were matynys &amp; masse &amp; euen song, placebo &amp; dirige &amp; comendacion &amp; matynes of oure lady ordeyned of synful men, to be songen wi&thorn; hei&yogh;e criynge to lette men fro &thorn;e sentence &amp; vnderstondynge of &thorn;at &thorn;at was &thorn;us songen, &amp; to maken men wery &amp; vndisposid to studie goddis lawe for akyng of hedis: &amp; of<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted AA.</NOTE> schort tyme &thorn;anne weren<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted X.</NOTE> more veyn iapis founden; deschaunt, countre note &amp; orgon &amp; smale brekynge, &thorn;at stiri&thorn; veyn men to daunsynge more &thorn;an to<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted X.</NOTE> mornynge, &amp; here-fore ben many proude &amp; lecherous lorelis founden &amp; dowid wi&thorn; temperal &amp; worldly lordischipis &amp; gret cost. but &thorn;es foolis schulden drede &thorn;e scharpe wordis of austyn, &thorn;at sei&thorn;: as oft as &thorn;e song liki&thorn; me more &thorn;an do&thorn; &thorn;e sentence &thorn;at is songen, so oft I confesse &thorn;at I synne greuously. &para; And &yogh;if &thorn;es knackeris excusen hem bi song in &thorn;e olde lawe; seie &thorn;at crist, &thorn;at best kepte &thorn;e olde lawe as it schulde<MILESTONE N="168" UNIT="page"> be aftirward, tau&yogh;t not ne chargid vs wi&thorn; 
<PB REF="00000258.tif" N="192"> sich bodely song ne ony of his apostlis, but wi&thorn; deuocion in herte &amp; holy lif &amp; trewe prechynge, &amp; &thorn;at is ynow&thorn;&yogh; &amp; &thorn;e beste. but who schulde &thorn;anne charge vs wi&thorn; more ouere &thorn;e fredom and li&yogh;tnesse of cristis lawe? &amp; &yogh;if &thorn;ei seyn &thorn;at angelis heryen god bi song in heuene; seie &thorn;at we kunnen not &thorn;at song, but &thorn;ei ben in ful victorie of here enemys &amp; we ben in perilous bataile,<NOTE PLACE="foot">baitale X.</NOTE> &amp; in &thorn;e valeye of wepynge &amp; mornynge; &amp; oure song letti&thorn; vs fro betre occupacion &amp; stiri&thorn; vs to many grete synnes &amp; to for&yogh;ete vs self. but oure fleschly peple ha&thorn; more lykynge in here bodely eris in sich knackynge &amp; taterynge &thorn;an in herynge of goddis lawe, &amp; spekynge of &thorn;e blisse of heuene, for &thorn;ei wolen hire proude prestis &amp; o&thorn;ere lecherous lorelis &thorn;us to knacke notis for many markis &amp; poundis; but &thorn;ei wolen not &yogh;eue here almes to prestis &amp; children to lerne &amp; to<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted X.</NOTE> teche goddis lawe; &amp; &thorn;us bi &thorn;is nouelrie of song is goddis lawe vnstudied &amp; not kepte, &amp; pride &amp; o&thorn;ere grete synnys meyntenyd. &amp; &thorn;es fonnyd lordis &amp; peple gessen to haue more &thorn;ank of god &amp; to<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted X.</NOTE> worschipe hym more in haldynge vp of here owen nouelries wi&thorn; grete cost &thorn;an in lernynge &amp; techynge &amp; meyntenynge of his lawe &amp; his seruauntis &amp; his ordynaunce. but where is more disceit in fei&thorn;, hope &amp; charite? for whanne &thorn;er ben fourty or fyfty in a queer &thorn;re or foure proude &amp; lecherous lorellis schullen knacke &thorn;e most deuout seruyce &thorn;at noman schal here &thorn;e sentence, &amp; alle o&thorn;ere schullen be doumbe &amp; loken on hem as foolis. &amp; &thorn;anne strumpatis &amp; &thorn;euys preisen sire iacke or hobbe &amp; williem &thorn;e proude clerk, hou smale &thorn;ei knacken here notis; &amp; seyn &thorn;at &thorn;ei seruen wel god &amp; holy chirche, whanne &thorn;ei dispisen god in his face, &amp; letten o&thorn;ere cristene men of here deuocion &amp; compunccion, &amp; stiren hem to worldly vanyte; &amp; &thorn;us trewe seruyce of god is lettid &amp; &thorn;is veyn knackynge for oure iolite &amp; pride is preised abouen &thorn;e mone. &para; Also &thorn;e ordynalle of salisbury letti&thorn; moche prechynge of &thorn;e gospel; for folis chargen &thorn;at more &thorn;an &thorn;e maundementis of god &amp; to studie &amp; teche cristis gospel; for &yogh;if a man faile in 
<PB REF="00000259.tif" N="193"> his ordynale men holden &thorn;at grete synne &amp; reprouen hym &thorn;er|of faste, but &yogh;if a preste breke &thorn;e hestis of god men chargen &thorn;at litel or nou&yogh;t; &amp; so &yogh;if prestis seyn here matynes, masse &amp; euensong aftir salisbury vsse, &thorn;ei hem self &amp; o&thorn;ere men demen it is ynow&yogh;, &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;ei nei&thorn;er preche ne teche &thorn;e hestis of god &amp; &thorn;e gospel. &amp; &thorn;us &thorn;ei wenen &thorn;at it is ynow&yogh; to fulfille synful mennus ordynaunce &amp; to leue &thorn;e ri&yogh;tfulleste ordynaunce of god &thorn;at he chargid prestis to performe. but, lord, what was prestis office ordeyned bi god bifore &thorn;at salisbury vss was maad of proude prestis, coueitous, lecherous <MILESTONE N="169" UNIT="page">&amp; dronkelewe? where god &thorn;at dampne&thorn; alle ydelnesse chargid<NOTE PLACE="foot">chargen X.</NOTE> hem not at &thorn;e full wi&thorn; &thorn;e beste occupacion for hem self &amp; o&thorn;ere men? hou doren synful folis chargen cristis prestis wi&thorn; so moche nouelrie, &amp; euermore cloute more to, &thorn;at &thorn;ei may not frely do goddis ordynaunce? for &thorn;e iewis in &thorn;e olde lawe haden not so manye seremonyes of sacrifices ordeyned bi god as prestis han now ri&yogh;ttis &amp; reulis maade of synful men. And &yogh;it &thorn;e olde lawe in &thorn;es charious customes mosten nedes cesse for fredom of cristis gospel; but &thorn;is fredom is more don awei bi &thorn;is nouelrie &thorn;an bi customes of &thorn;e olde lawe; &amp; &thorn;us many grete axen where a prest may wi&thorn;-outen dedly synne seie his masse wi&thorn;-outen matynys; &amp; &thorn;ei demen it dedly synne, a prest to fulfille &thorn;e ordynaunce of god in his fredom wi&thorn;-oute nouelrie of synful men, &thorn;at letti&thorn; prestis fro &thorn;e betre occupacion, as &yogh;if &thorn;ei demen it dedly synne to leue &thorn;e worse &thorn;ing<NOTE PLACE="foot">teching AA.</NOTE> &amp; take &thorn;e betre whanne &thorn;ei may not do bo&thorn;e to-gidre. &amp; &thorn;us, lord, &thorn;in owen ordynaunce &thorn;at &thorn;ou madist for &thorn;i prestis is holden errour &amp; distroied for &thorn;e fonnyd nouelrie of synful foolis, &amp; in cas of fendis in helle. &para; But here men moste be war &thorn;at vnder colour of &thorn;is fredom &thorn;ei ben betre occupied in &thorn;e lawe of god to studie &amp; teche it, &amp; not slou&yogh; ne ydel in ouermoche sleep &amp; vanyte &amp; o&thorn;er synnes, for &thorn;at is &thorn;e fendis panter. &para; See now &thorn;e blyndnesse of &thorn;es foolis; &thorn;ei seyn &thorn;at a prest may be excused fro seiynge of masse &thorn;at god comaundid him self 
<PB REF="00000260.tif" N="194"> to &thorn;e substance &thorn;er-of, so &thorn;at he here on. But he schal not be excused but &yogh;if he seie matynes &amp; euensong him self &thorn;at synful men han ordeyned, &amp; &thorn;us &thorn;ei chargen more here owene fyndynge &thorn;an cristis comaundement. A lord, &yogh;if alle &thorn;e studie &amp; traueile &thorn;at men han now abowte salisbury vss wi&thorn; multitude of<NOTE PLACE="foot">&amp; X.</NOTE> newe costy portos, antifeners, graielis, &amp; alle o&thorn;ere bokis weren turned in-to makynge of biblis &amp; in studiynge &amp; techynge &thorn;er-of, hou moche schulde goddis lawe be for&thorn;ered &amp; knowen &amp; kept, &amp; now in so moche it is hyndrid, vnstudied &amp; vnkept. lord, hou schulden riche men ben excused &thorn;at costen so moche in grete schapellis &amp; costy bokis of mannus ordynaunce for fame &amp; nobleie of &thorn;e world, &amp; wolen not spende so moche aboute bokis of goddis lawe &amp; for to studie hem &amp; teche hem, si&thorn; &thorn;is were wi&thorn;-oute com|parison betre on alle siddis &amp; ly&yogh;ttere &amp; sykerere. but &yogh;it men &thorn;at knowen &thorn;e fredom of goddis ordynaunce for prestis to be &thorn;e beste wi&thorn; grete sorow of herte seyn here matynes, masse &amp; euensong, whanne &thorn;ei schulden ellis be betre occupied, last &thorn;ei sclaundren &thorn;e sike conscience of here bre&thorn;eren &thorn;at &yogh;it knowen not goddis lawe. god brynge &thorn;es prestis to &thorn;e fredom to studie holy writt, &amp; lyue &thorn;er-after, &amp; teche it o&thorn;er men frely, &amp; to preie as long and as moche as god meue&thorn; <MILESTONE N="170" UNIT="page">hem &thorn;er-to, &amp; ellis turne to o&thorn;ere medeful werkis, as crist &amp; his apostlis diden; &amp; &thorn;at &thorn;ei ben not constreyned to blabre alle day wi&thorn; tonge &amp; grete criynge, as pies &amp; iaies, &thorn;ing &thorn;at &thorn;ei knowen not &amp; to peiere here owen soule for defaute of wis deuocion &amp; charite.</P>
<P>Also bysynesse of worldly occupacion of prestis letti&thorn; prechynge of &thorn;e gospel, for &thorn;ei ben so besy &thorn;er<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted X.</NOTE> aboute &amp; namely in herte, &thorn;at &thorn;ei &thorn;enken litel on goddis lawe &amp; han no sauour &thorn;er-to. &para; And seyn &thorn;at &thorn;ei don &thorn;us for hospitalite &amp; to releue pore men wi&thorn; dedis of charite; but, hou euere men speken, it his for here owen coueitise, &amp; lustful lif in mete &amp; drynk &amp; precious clo&thorn;is, &amp; for name of &thorn;e world in fedynge of riche men, &amp; litel or nou&yogh;t come&thorn; frely 
<PB REF="00000261.tif" N="195"> to pore men &thorn;at han most nede. But &thorn;es prestis schulden sue crist in manere of lif &amp; trewe techynge; but crist lefte sich occupacion, and his apostlis also, &amp; weren betre occupied in<NOTE PLACE="marg">Acts vi. [2].</NOTE> holy preiere &amp; trewe techynge of &thorn;e gospel; &amp; &thorn;is determi|nacion &amp; ful sentence was &yogh;ouen of alle &thorn;e apostlis to-gidre whanne &thorn;ei hadden resceyued &thorn;e plenteuous &yogh;iftis of &thorn;e holy gost. Lord! where &thorn;es worldly prestis ben wisere &thorn;an ben alle &thorn;e apostlis of crist? it semeth &thorn;at &thorn;ei ben or ellis <SUP>1</SUP>&thorn;ei ben<SUP>1</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot">1_1 omitted X.</NOTE> fooles. also crist wolde not take &thorn;e kyngdom whan &thorn;e puple wolde haue maad him kyng, as iones gospel telle&thorn;; but if it<NOTE PLACE="marg">John vi. [15].</NOTE> haade be a prestis<NOTE PLACE="foot">apostlis AA.</NOTE> office to dele aboute &thorn;us bodily<NOTE PLACE="foot">bodi X.</NOTE> almes, Crist &thorn;at coude best haue do &thorn;is office wolde haue take &thorn;es temperal goodis to dele hem among poeuere men; but he wolde not do &thorn;us, but fley and took no man of &thorn;e aposteles wi&thorn; him, so faste he hiede. lord, where worldly prestis kunnen bettere don &thorn;is partinge of worldly goodis &thorn;an<NOTE PLACE="foot">of X.</NOTE> ih&umacr; crist? And &yogh;if &thorn;ei seyn &thorn;at crist fedde &thorn;e puple in desert with bodily almes manye &thorn;ousand, as &thorn;e gospel sai&thorn;; &thorn;at dide crist by miracle to shewe his godhede and to teche prestes hou&yogh; &thorn;ei schulden fede gostly cristene men by goddis word; for so dide cristis aposteles and hadde not where-of to do bodily almes, whan &thorn;ei mi&yogh;ten haue had tresour and iuelis y-nowe of kynggis &amp; lordis. Also peter sai&thorn; in dedis of<NOTE PLACE="marg">Acts iii. 6.</NOTE> apostlis to a pore man &thorn;at to him nei&thorn;er was gold ne siluer, and &yogh;it he performede wel &thorn;e office of a trewe prest; but oure prestis ben so bysye aboute worldly occupacioun &thorn;at &thorn;ei semen bettere bailyues or reues &thorn;an gostly prestis of ih&umacr; crist. For what man is so bysy aboute marchaundise and o&thorn;ere worldly doyngis as ben preostes, &thorn;at shulden ben ly&yogh;t of heuenly lif to alle men abouten hem? but certes &thorn;ei shulde be as bysy aboute studyinge of goddys lawe and holy preyer, not of famulorum but of holy desires and clene meditacioun of god, and trewe techinge of &thorn;e gospel, as ben laboreris aboute worldly labour for here sustenaunce; and muche more bysie 
<PB REF="00000262.tif" N="196"> &yogh;if &thorn;ei mi&yogh;ten, for &thorn;ey ben more holden for to lyue wel and &yogh;eue<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted X.</NOTE> ensaumple of holi lif to &thorn;e puple &amp; trewe techinge of holy writ &thorn;anne &thorn;e people is holden to &yogh;yue hem dymes or offringis or ony bodily almes; and &thorn;erfore prestis shulde not leue ensaumple of good lif &amp; studyinge of holi writ &amp; trewe techinge &thorn;er-of <SUP>2</SUP>for no<SUP>2</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot">2_2 ne X.</NOTE> bodily almes, ne for worldly goodis, ne for sauynge of here bodily lif. and as crist sauede &thorn;e world by writynge &amp; techinge of foure Euaungelistis, so &thorn;e fend caste&thorn; to dampne &thorn;e world and prestis for lettynge to preche &thorn;e gospel by &thorn;es foure; by feyned contemplacioun, by song, by salisbury vse, &amp; by worldly bysynes of prestis. God for his mercy styre &thorn;es prestis to preche &thorn;e gospel in word, in lif, and bewar of sathanas disceitis. Amen.</P>


</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="11" TYPE="tract"><PB REF="00000263.tif" N="197">
<HEAD>XI. THE PATERNOSTER.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>THIS tract should be compared with that printed by Mr. Arnold (S. E. W. III. 98), to which it has many points of likeness.</P><P>It is not improbable that Wyclif should have written more than one tract in explanation and praise of the Lord's Prayer, since he was never tired of opposing its excellence to the vanity of the church prayers of his day. There is nothing here which enables us to fix either date or author|ship with certainty, but I take the tract to be genuine from its close connexion with that which follows, as to which I have scarcely any doubt.</P><P>The tract is found only in X. from which it has been copied.</P><P><TABLE>
<HEAD>SUMMARY.</HEAD>
<ROW>
<CELL>The prayer is taken by petitions, each of which is explained, and to each is assigned some special virtue. Finally comes a praise of the prayer and of Christ's goodness in giving it to us.</CELL>
</ROW>
</TABLE></P></HEADNOTE>

<PB REF="00000264.tif" N="198">
<EPIGRAPH>
<Q>&THORN;is his &thorn;e pater noster.</Q>
</EPIGRAPH>
<P><MILESTONE N="172" UNIT="page"> Oure fadir &thorn;at art in heuenes, halwid be &thorn;i name. &thorn;i reume or kyngdom come to &thorn;e. be &thorn;i wille don in her&thorn;e as it is doun in heuene. &YOGH;eue to vs to-day oure eche dayes bred. &amp; for&yogh;eue to vs oure dettis, &thorn;at is oure synnys, as we for&yogh;euen to oure dettouris, &thorn;at is to men &thorn;at han synned in vs. &amp; lede vs not in-to temptacion, but delyuere vs from euyl. amen, so be it. Whanne we seyn, <B>oure fadir</B> &thorn;at <B>art</B> in <B>heuenes,</B> we ben tau&yogh;t to loue eche o&thorn;ere as bre&thorn;ren of o fadir &amp; o modir bodily, &amp; moche more, si&thorn; god is oure fadir &thorn;at made vs of nou&yogh;t; &amp; we ben tau&yogh;t to lyuen in mekenesse eche to o&thorn;er, &amp; to desire heuenly &thorn;ingis, as vertues &amp; holy lif, &amp; don alle oure dedis preuyly &amp; apert for &thorn;e honour of god &amp; &thorn;e blisse of heuene; &amp; so oure lif owi&thorn; to be in heuenys be holy desir &amp; lastynge. &amp; &thorn;us at &thorn;e bigynnynge we moten be meke &amp; in charite to alle men, bo&thorn;e cristene &amp; he&thorn;ene, &amp; frendis &amp; enemyes, &amp; ellis we ben not wor&thorn;i to preie &thorn;is pater noster. whanne we seyn, <B>halwid be &thorn;i name,</B> we preien &thorn;at we ben maad holy &amp; stable in vertues bi &thorn;e holy name of god &amp; his grace &amp; his vertue; &thorn;at we ben holy bi grace as oure fadir god is holy of hym self. in &thorn;is word we axen deuoutly sadnesse of fei&thorn;, wi&thorn;-oute whiche fei&thorn; we may not plese god; &amp; we preien &thorn;at alle manere of pride, bo&thorn;e in &thorn;ou&yogh;t &amp; spekynge &amp; dede &amp; alle manere berynge &amp; counte|naunce, be putt awey fro vs, for suche pride maki&thorn; men luciferis children; &amp; &thorn;at alle manere verrey mekenessis be grounded in vs a&yogh;enst &thorn;is pride, for verrey mekenesse maki&thorn; vs goddis children. &para; whanne we seyn <B>&thorn;i kyngdom or reume come to &thorn;e,</B> we preien &thorn;at alle men &amp; wommen lyuynge in &thorn;is world &thorn;at schullen be sauyd, &amp; alle &thorn;at ben departed come <MILESTONE N="173" UNIT="page">to &thorn;e Blisse of Heuene as soone as god wole, to see &thorn;ere oure blissed spouse ih&umacr; crist, &amp; haue endeles ioie wi&thorn; him &amp; his angelis &amp; seyntis. for alle angelis &amp; men &amp; wommen &thorn;at schullen be sauyd ben goddis kyngdom &amp; holy chirche; &amp; 
<PB REF="00000265.tif" N="199"> oure lord ih&umacr; is kyng of &thorn;is reume &amp; heed of &thorn;is holy chirche; &amp; alle &thorn;o &thorn;at schullen be dampnyd in helle ben deuelis chirche or synagoge, &amp; &thorn;e deuel is here false prince &amp; kyng, but ra&thorn;ere her tiraunt. &amp; here we axen trewe hope &amp; lastynge to haue &thorn;e blisse of heuene, be mercy of oure god &amp; bi oure goode lif &amp; endynge in perfit charite. in &thorn;is word we preien &thorn;at alle cursed enuye &amp; hate be putt awey from vs, &amp; &thorn;at alle brennynge charite to god &amp; oure euene cristene be so sadly rotyd in vs &thorn;at it faile neuere in &thorn;is lif for no &thorn;ing &thorn;at may be. &para; Whanne we seyn, <B>&thorn;ei wille be don</B> in <B>er&thorn;e ri&yogh;t as it is</B> in <B>heuene,</B> we preien &thorn;at we don &thorn;e wille of god wi&thorn;-outen any errour &amp; wi&thorn;-outen any cessynge, as blissed aungelis don euere in heuene, &amp; &thorn;at we don &thorn;is wille of god wi&thorn; ri&yogh;t fulle vnderstondynge, &amp; wi&thorn; grete desir &amp; ioie &amp; likynge, &amp; not wi&thorn; heuynesse &amp; grucchynge. &para; In &thorn;is word we axen &thorn;at in alle &thorn;ingis oure wille be confermed to goddis wille, &thorn;at no &thorn;ing may departe oure wille &amp; oure loue fro god, &thorn;at is endeles good &amp; ri&yogh;tful. &para; And here we preien algatis to geten &thorn;e he&yogh;e vertue of charite, with-outen whiche alle o&thorn;ere &thorn;ingis ben not wor&thorn;i to vs to brynge vs to heuene. &amp; here we preien &thorn;at god kepe vs fro wickid coueitise of worldly goodis, &thorn;at we offenden not goddis comaundementis ne good conscience, nei&thorn;er for wynnynge ne holdynge for&thorn; of worldly goodis; for he &thorn;at bi brekynge of goddis hestis, as bi false sweryngis, false mesures or wei&yogh;tis, or ony slei&yogh;tte, geti&thorn; or holdi&thorn; his nei&yogh;eboris goodis, do&thorn; not goddis wille, but is &thorn;ef &amp; traitour of god &amp; his nei&yogh;eboris bi goddis lawe. &para; Whanne we seyn, <B>&yogh;eue vs to-day oure eche dayes breed,</B> we preien for nedeful sustenaunce of oure body, &amp; for to haue vnderstondynge &amp; kepynge of goddis word, &amp; namely of his hestis &thorn;at ben gostly sustenaunce of oure soule, &amp; &thorn;at we han &thorn;is sustenaunce trewely geten, not by raueyne ne extorsion ne falsnesse, but &thorn;at it be spendid in seruyce of god &amp; his drede; &amp; &thorn;at we &thorn;anken mekely oure god for alle his grace &amp; &yogh;iftis &thorn;at he &yogh;eue&thorn; vs of his grete goodnesse. &para; In &thorn;is word we preien to haue &thorn;e vertue of prudence to knowe whiche 
<PB REF="00000266.tif" N="200"> sustenaunce is nedeful &amp; resonable to vs, &amp; what we owen to do &thorn;erfore to god, &amp; in what mesure we schullen take it, to putte awey alle manere glotonye &amp; dronkenesse &amp; coriouste &amp; wast of metis &amp; drynkis; for &thorn;is glotonye &amp; dronkenesse maki&thorn; men to loue more here bely &amp; here golet &thorn;an god almy&yogh;tty;<MILESTONE N="174" UNIT="page"> for &thorn;ei maken here wombe here false god, as seynt poul sei&thorn;. Whanne we seyn, &amp; <B>for-&yogh;eue vs oure dettis</B>, &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="marg">Phil. iii.19</NOTE> is oure synnes, <B>as we for&yogh;euen to</B> houre <B>dettouris</B>, &thorn;at is to men &thorn;at han trespassed a&yogh;enst vs, we<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. he.</NOTE> preien &thorn;at god haue mercy on vs as we han mercy on hem &thorn;at han wra&thorn;&thorn;id vs. certis &yogh;if we han no mercy on hem &thorn;at trespassen a&yogh;enst vs, we preien god a&yogh;enst oure owene heed &thorn;at he dampne vs for oure synnys. but here men moten for&yogh;eue &thorn;e rancour, hate &amp; euyl wille of here herte to here nei&yogh;eboris, but &thorn;ei may lawefully pursue worldly dette, so &thorn;at &thorn;ei do &thorn;is bi iuste menes, &amp; kepe pacience &amp; charite; &amp; &yogh;if men ben pore &amp; iust of lif &amp; wolden fayn paie, &amp; traueile bisily &thorn;erfore in treu&thorn;e, &amp; ben not wastouris of here litil good, &thorn;anne &thorn;is preiere wole &thorn;at siche<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. whiche.</NOTE> pore ben not prisonyd ne peyned, but bi pacience &amp; mercy suffer til &thorn;ei may paie. In &thorn;is word<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. world.</NOTE> we preien to haue &thorn;e vertue of ri&yogh;twisnesse to putten out vnresonable wra&thorn;&thorn;e &amp; vengaunce, &amp; holden vs sadde in verrey mercy &amp; pacience a&yogh;enst malencolie &amp; puttynge awey of reson, so &thorn;at reson &amp; mercy reule welle alle oure stiryngis of herte &amp; speche &amp; doynge. Whanne we seyn, <B>&amp; ne lede vs not in-to temptacion</B>, we preien &thorn;at god suffre vs not bi wi&thorn;drawynge of his grace &amp; helpe be ouercomen in tempta|tions of &thorn;e deuyl, of &thorn;e world, &amp; of &thorn;e fleschly lustis or foule delectacions. for it is profitable to be temptid &amp; wi&thorn;-stonde &thorn;e temptacions bi helpe of god &amp; his angelis, for &thorn;ere is oure mede &amp; ioie restorid; but it is euyl to ben ouercomen in &thorn;is temptacion, &amp; &thorn;at schal not be but be oure owene necligence &amp; slou&yogh;te &amp; fals likynge in synne. &thorn;erfore in &thorn;is word we preien to haue &thorn;e vertue of gostly streng&thorn;e, to be strong bi 
<PB REF="00000267.tif" N="201"> helpe of &thorn;e holy gost a&yogh;enst alle temptacions, &amp; &thorn;at we ben not hardid in synne, but &thorn;at we waken in holy preieris &amp; good occupacion, &amp; haue saad mynde of &thorn;e schortnesse of lykynge in synne, &amp; on &thorn;e bittre peynes of purgatorie &amp; helle; &amp; &yogh;if we wolen, bi &thorn;is mynde &amp; occupacion si&thorn; goddis grace &amp; helpe is redy, we schullen ouercomen alle oure temptacions &amp; gete oure corone in heuene wi&thorn;-outen ende. &para; Whanne we seyn, <B>but delyuere vs fro euyl,</B> we preien &thorn;at god delyuere vs from alle euyl of synne &amp; peyne bo&thorn;e of body &amp; soule in &thorn;is lif &amp; in purgatorie<NOTE PLACE="foot">Scored through in MS.</NOTE> &amp; namely fro peyne of helle, &amp; &thorn;at we falle not in-to dispeir of goddis mercy for olde rotynge &amp; custome in synne. In &thorn;is word we preien to haue &thorn;e vertue of temperaunce, to take so worldly goodis &amp; myr&thorn;e &thorn;at we for&yogh;eten not god in heuenly blisse, &amp; &thorn;at we tempere so &thorn;e stiryngis of oure fleisch &thorn;at we delen not fleischly wi&thorn; ony woman but &yogh;if it be in verrey &amp; laweful <MILESTONE N="175" UNIT="page">matrimonye; &amp; in drede of god, &amp; not as bestis wi&thorn;-outen reson, &thorn;at ben alle seit abouten here lustis &amp; for&yogh;eten god &amp; alle his werkis. for &thorn;e archangel raphael tau&yogh;te tobie &thorn;at &thorn;e deuyl ha&thorn; power<NOTE PLACE="marg">Tobit. vi. 17.</NOTE> ouer siche men &thorn;at &thorn;us defoulen &thorn;e ordre of matrimonye &amp; don al for here lustis &amp; for&yogh;eten god &amp; his drede &amp; don as bestis wi&thorn;-oute discrecion. &para; God delyuere vs from alle euyl of synne preuy &amp; apert, &amp; namely fro endurynge in synne &amp; dispeir of goddis mercy, &amp; fro bodely werris &amp; vengaunce &amp; peynes, bo&thorn;e in &thorn;is lif &amp; purgatorie &amp; helle; &amp; graunt vs bi ri&yogh;t fei&thorn; trewe &amp; perfit charite to gete heuenely blisse. so be it ih&umacr; for &thorn;i grete mercy. &para; Certis &thorn;is pater noster passi&thorn; alle o&thorn;ere preieris in auctorite, in sotilte &amp; profit bo&thorn;e of soule &amp; body. It is of most auctorite; for oure lord ih&umacr; crist, god &amp; man, made it &amp; comaundid cristene men to seie it; but o&thorn;ere preieris ben made bi men, &amp; enclosen noon o&thorn;er sentence &thorn;an do&thorn; &thorn;is pater noster, but &yogh;if it be errour. &thorn;erfore as ih&umacr; crist is more wor&thorn;i &thorn;an o&thorn;ere synful men, so &thorn;is pater noster is of more auctorite &thorn;an is preiere maad of o&thorn;ere men, &thorn;ou&yogh; here preiere be good. &thorn;is pater noster is more sotil &thorn;an 
<PB REF="00000268.tif" N="202"> o&thorn;ere preieris; for it is maad of endeles wisdom &amp; charite of crist, &amp; enclose&thorn; alle &thorn;inkyngis &thorn;at ben nedful bo&thorn;e for body &amp; soule in &thorn;is world &amp; &thorn;e to&thorn;er; &amp; oure lord ih&umacr; made it in schorte wordis &amp; moche witt, for men schulden not be heuy ne excusen hem fro kunnynge &amp; seiynge &thorn;er-of. it is of most profit, for &yogh;if a man seie it wel he ne schal faile no &thorn;ing &thorn;at is nedful &amp; profitable for bodily lif &amp; vertuous, to brynge men to heuene &amp; haue blisse in body &amp; soule wi&thorn;-outen ende. lord, hou moche ben &thorn;ei to blame &thorn;at bisien hem aboute preieris maade of synful men &amp; leuen &thorn;is pater noster &thorn;at is best &amp; most hesy of alle, &amp; comprehendi&thorn; alle goodis for body &amp; soule. blissed be &thorn;is endeles goode lord, &thorn;at of his endeles wisdom &amp; charite tau&yogh;te &thorn;is schorte preiere. Amen.</P>


