<DIV1 N="19" TYPE="tract"><PB REF="00000341.tif" N="275">
<HEAD>XIX. OF POOR PREACHING PRIESTS. </HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>I GIVE this title for want of a better, but the tract has no heading in the MS. It is a summary of the wishes of the writer as to reform in Church and State; the first thirteen points of the poor priests relating to the clergy, and the eighteen which follow (and which might almost be taken as a separate tract), having reference to the duties of secular rulers.</P><P>I am inclined to date it 1377. The first year of a new reign would be a suitable time for the issue of a programme such as this; and there is a stronger ground for the supposition in the correspondence of several 'points' with petitions of the Commons in Richard's first Parliament. The tract certainly belongs to the fourteenth century. The desire that no priest or religious should be prisoned without open doom (p. 279) marks a time when no Act of Parliament had sanctioned the burning of heretics, but when the bishops, alarmed at the spread of heresy, were taking the law into their own hands.</P><P>I can give no decided opinion as authorship, but all the points are within the scope of Wyclif's teaching.</P><P>The tract is to be found only in the Corpus MS. X.</P></HEADNOTE>

<PB REF="00000342.tif" N="276">
<HEAD>Of poor preaching Priests.</HEAD>
<P><MILESTONE N="234" UNIT="page">&THORN;e first general poynt of pore prestis &thorn;at prechen in engelond is &thorn;is; &thorn;at &thorn;e lawe of god be wel knowen, tau&yogh;t, meyntened, magnyfied. &para; &THORN;e secunde &thorn;at &thorn;e grete opyn synne &thorn;at regne&thorn; in diuerse statis be distroied, &amp; also heresie &amp; ypocrisie of anticristis &amp; his folweris. &para; &THORN;e &thorn;ridde &thorn;at verrey pees, pros|perite &amp; brennynge charite be encresed in cristendom, &amp; namely in &thorn;e rewme of engelond, for to brynge [men] redily to &thorn;e blisse of heuene. &para; &THORN;e first special poynt is &thorn;is, &thorn;at cristene men, &amp; namely clerkis of scole &amp; curatis, studie, kepe, teche, &amp; meyntene holy writt more &thorn;an newe statutis, cus|tomes &amp; s[er]ymonyes maad of synful men. &para; &THORN;e secunde, &thorn;at &thorn;e ordynaunce of ih&umacr; crist be stedfastly <MILESTONE N="235" UNIT="page">kept in alle degres, so &thorn;at alle clerkis lyue clenly on spiritualte, as crist &amp; his apostlis deden, &amp; &yogh;euynge ensaumple of mekenesse, pacience &amp; heuenly lif &amp; charite; &amp; &thorn;at alle seculer lordischipis turne clene to seculer lordis, as god biddi&thorn; in &thorn;e olde testament &amp; newe, &amp; &thorn;at &thorn;ei don ri&yogh;twisnesse, mercy &amp; pite, &amp; ri&yogh;tly gouerne &thorn;e comouns in reste, pees &amp; charite, iuste customes, [&amp;] resonable rentis to here lordis &amp; maistris; &amp; &thorn;at &thorn;e comyns wilfully, mekely &amp; trewely do here seruyce. &para; &THORN;e &thorn;ridde, &thorn;at &thorn;e ordre of presthod wi&thorn; clennest reulis of cristis gospel be holden [&amp;] meyntened bo&thorn;e perfiter &amp; esier &amp; sikerer &thorn;an ony newe [ordre]<NOTE PLACE="foot">Not in MS., but some such word is evidently wanted.</NOTE> or secte wi&thorn; bilawis, customes, obseruauncis founden of synful men, &thorn;at ofte erreden in &thorn;ou&yogh;t, worde &amp; dede. &para; &THORN;e fir&thorn;e, &thorn;at cursed heresie of symonye in &thorn;e clergie be distroied bo&thorn;e in benefices, ordris, sacramentis &amp; pardons. &para; &THORN;e fifte, &thorn;at &thorn;e raueyne &amp; extorcion of prelatis &amp; here officeris, &thorn;at &thorn;ei don vnder colour of iuridiccon &amp; almes in meyntenynge of synne for annuel rente, wisly &amp; trewely be stoppid, &amp; &thorn;at &thorn;ei be wel chastised for robbynge of &thorn;e kyngis lege men. &para; &THORN;e sixte, &thorn;at curatis ben not occupied in worldly 
<PB REF="00000343.tif" N="277"> office in lordis courtis, leuynge cristene soules vngouerned &amp; vntau&yogh;t, for bo&thorn;e &thorn;e lord &amp; &thorn;e clerk don gret traiterie to god &amp; his peple; &amp; &thorn;at fals confessoures &thorn;at norischen men in synne for worldly worschipe, worldly wynnynge, welfare &amp; ese, be hurled out of office &amp; courtis for drede of schedynge of worldly venyme. &para; &THORN;e seuen&thorn;e, &thorn;at clerkis be meke &amp; obeschaunt to worldly lordis, as crist &amp; his apostlis weren, &amp; be not norischid in grete synne by anticristis exempcion, leste cristene rewmes be distroied for suffraunce &amp; meyntenynge of cursed synnes. &para; &THORN;e ei&yogh;te&thorn;e, &thorn;at cristene men drede more &thorn;e ri&yogh;tful cursynge of god for brekynge of his hestis &thorn;en wrongful cursynge of synful men, &thorn;at cursen men for trewe prechynge of &thorn;e gospel &amp; fulfillynge of &thorn;e werkis of mercy; for god blisse&thorn; where &thorn;ei cursen. &para; &THORN;e nyn&thorn;e, &thorn;at pore men of &thorn;e rewme be not robbid for symonye of &thorn;e firste fruytis bi &thorn;e bischop of rome, ne bi &thorn;e bischepis at hom for halowynge of chirchis &amp; auteris, &amp; prouyng of testa|mentis &amp; aquitauncis. &para; &THORN;e ten&thorn;e, &thorn;at cristene men &yogh;eue more credence to cristis gospel &amp; his lif &thorn;an to ony bullis of synful bischopis of &thorn;is world, or ellis &thorn;ei forsaken crist and taken anticrist &amp; sathanas for here chief gouernour. &para; &THORN;e elleuen&thorn;e, &thorn;at &thorn;e sotil vsure of riche clerkis &amp; marchaundes be hurled out of lond, &amp; borwyng &amp; lynynge be frely don to pore men for goddis sake. &para; &THORN;e twelf&thorn;e, &thorn;at no lege man of oure kyng <MILESTONE N="236" UNIT="page">be prisoned for wrongful cursynge of prelat, &thorn;e while he is redy to be iustified bi holy writt &amp; trewely don his office. &para; &THORN;e &thorn;ritten&thorn;e, &thorn;at who euere do&thorn; most symonye &amp; meyntene&thorn; most synne be demed, knowen &amp; tretid most heretik, most aduersarie of ih&umacr; crist &amp; principal anticrist. &para; &YOGH;if ony man kan proue bi holy writt or reson &thorn;at &thorn;es poyntis ben false, pore prestis wolen mekely ben amendid, &amp; hertely preien alle goode men to helpe hem in here trewe cause for worschipe of god, hel&thorn;e of here soulis, &amp; saluacion of cristene rewmes.</P>
<P>&para; &THORN;es ben ei&yogh;tene poyntis to distroie grete wrongis &amp; synnes &amp; streng&thorn;e &thorn;e pees &amp; charite in oure lond, &yogh;if &thorn;e kyng, lordis &amp; comyns wolen practise hem wel.
<PB REF="00000344.tif" N="278"></P>
<P>&THORN;at &thorn;e grete blasphemye of goddis name in veyn &amp; fals swerynge &amp; vnlefully creaturis, as bi cristis woundes, nayles &amp; o&thorn;ere membris, be refreyned bi drede of peynes sett bi &thorn;e kyng, lordis &amp; comounte of cristene peple, lest god take grete vengaunce on oure peple, bo&thorn;e in &thorn;is wor[l]d &amp; in &thorn;e to&thorn;er. &para;&THORN;at falsse witnesse in assises &amp; o&thorn;ere causes, &thorn;at forsweren hem for coueitise, loue or drede or hate, &amp; alle &thorn;at procuren hem &thorn;er-to, ben opynly ponyschid in ensaumple of o&thorn;ere; for ellis schal no man meyntene his heritage, goodis or lif for multitude of false questis. &para;&THORN;at meyntenours of false causes bi streng&thorn;e or lordischipe or bi sotel cauillacions feyned on &thorn;e lawe be wisly refreyned &amp; scharply ponyschid in oure lond; for ellis no pore man schal ben hardy to chalenge his owene goodis, nei&thorn;er riche man but &yogh;if he wole make opyn debate or werre; or ellis treu&thorn;e, pees &amp; charite schullen be exilid, &amp; wrong &amp; mansleyng, &thorn;efte &amp; werre be hauntid, til oure lond be con|querid bi enemys or he&thorn;ene men, as it ha&thorn; ofte ben bi-fore &thorn;is tyme. &para;&THORN;at &thorn;e open &thorn;efte of mennus children &thorn;at feyned religious vsen vnder colour of holynesse be scharply ponyschid &amp; forbeden, for bi &thorn;is many children ben deppere dampned &thorn;an &thorn;ei schulden ellis; &amp; &thorn;ei may not worschipe here eldris as god biddi&thorn; ne vsen &thorn;e fredom of cristis gospel; for whanne &thorn;ei be&thorn; stolen awey fro here eldris, &yogh;e wi&thorn;-inne age of discrecion, &thorn;ei schul not forsake &thorn;e habit of freris for drede of prisonynge &amp; de&thorn;, &thorn;ou&yogh; it be agens here wille &amp; conscience; &amp; &thorn;ou&yogh; here frendis seke neuere so faste &thorn;ei schullen not fynde hem, so &thorn;ei schul be led fro place to place. &para;&THORN;at pore tenauntis of oure lond be not robbid bi &thorn;e gredy &amp; nedles beggeris of sotel ypocritis hauynge &thorn;e name of religiouse men, &amp; &thorn;at ih&utilde; crist be not sclaundred her by affermynge <MILESTONE N="237" UNIT="page">&thorn;at he beggede nedely fro hous to hous, as feyned religiouse vsen nowe; si&thorn; holy writt forbedi&thorn; siche beggynge, &thorn;ou&yogh; summe beggen my&yogh;te be suffrid in tyme of grete nede. &para;&THORN;at &thorn;e sotil amortasynge of seculer lordischipis &thorn;at is don bi menene hondis in fraude of 
<PB REF="00000345.tif" N="279"> &thorn;e kyngis statute be visely<NOTE PLACE="foot">?bisily; or, perhaps, for avisely=carefully.</NOTE> enquyred, &amp; &thorn;e goodis turned in helpe of &thorn;e rewme in sparynge of &thorn;e pore comons of taxes. &para; &THORN;at &thorn;e almes of lordis &yogh;ouen to prelatis &amp; religious, vp certeyn condicions to fede certeyn pore men &amp; o&thorn;er hospitalite &amp; certeyn noumber of good prestis, be wisly amendid bi &thorn;e kyng &amp; lordis whanne &thorn;es goodis be&thorn; turned in-to pompe, glotonye &amp; lecherie &amp; meyntenynge false purchases; for &thorn;e kyng &amp; lordis ben patrons &amp; meyntenours of many synnes to dis|truction of &thorn;e lond. &para; &THORN;at &thorn;e pore comons be not chargid wi&thorn; taxis, &thorn;e while clerkis, &amp; namely religiouse, han superfluyte of riches of gold &amp; siluer &amp; riche vesselis &amp; o&thorn;ere iewelis; si&thorn; alle &thorn;es goodis ben pore mennus goodis, &amp; clerkis ben not lordis of hem but proctours, to spende hem trewely in pore mennus nedis, as goddis lawe &amp; mannys witnessen. &para; &THORN;at &thorn;e wast tresour hanged on stockis &amp; stones be wisly spendid in defence of &thorn;e rewme, &amp; releuynge of &thorn;e pore comouns; &thorn;at &thorn;e peple of oure lond be not brou&yogh;t to maumetrie, ne &thorn;efte, ne lecherie meyntened vnder siche pilgrimage, ne almes drawen fro pore nedy men bou&yogh;t wi&thorn; cristis precious blood. &para; &THORN;at &thorn;e clergie of oure londe be refreyned fro pride, glorious array &amp; worldly occupacion, &amp; namely oure prelatis &amp; curatis; arn<NOTE PLACE="foot">?and</NOTE> chargid bi &thorn;e kyng &amp; lordis to teche wel here sugetis bi ensaumple of good lif &amp; opyn &amp; trewe prechynge of &thorn;e gospel, as bisily &amp; redily as &thorn;ei asken here ti&thorn;es. &para; &THORN;at non of &thorn;e clergie be lettid to kepe trewely &amp; frely &thorn;e gospel of ih&umacr; crist in good lyuynge &amp; trewe techynge, for no feyned priuelegie or tradicions founden vp of synful wrecchis. &para; &THORN;at no prest or religious in oure lond be prisoned wi&thorn;-oten opyn dom &amp; trewe cause, fully knowen to oure kyng or his trewe conseil; for ellis worldly prestis &amp; feyned religious may stoppe trewe men from prechynge of holy writt &amp; magnyfyng of &thorn;e kyngis regalie, &amp; mur&thorn;ere &thorn;e kyngis lege men wi&thorn;-outen answere. &para; &THORN;at &thorn;e obedience of children to fader &amp; to modir &amp; of seruauntis &amp; tenauntis to here lordis &amp; maistris, &thorn;e whiche 
<PB REF="00000346.tif" N="280"> obedience crist vsed &amp; tau&yogh;tte &amp; comaundid it<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. inserts to. Perhaps the sentence should be corrected by repeat|ing ".be magnyfied &amp; prechid."</NOTE> be magnyfied &amp; prechid more &thorn;an ony newe feyned obedience founden of synful men, &thorn;e whiche obedience nei&thorn;er crist ne his <MILESTONE N="238" UNIT="page">apostlis deden ne tau&yogh;ten ne comaunden ne conseileden opynly &thorn;er-to. &para; &THORN;at chepynge, &amp; namely feiris, be not vsed on &thorn;e halidaies, &amp; algatis on &thorn;e sunday &amp; in holy chirche, for &thorn;at is expresly a&yogh;enst goddis comaundement &amp; comone lawe of holy chirche. &para; &THORN;at open lecherie &amp; avoutrie be not suffrid in grete placis in oure rewme, ne meyntened for annual rente, for &thorn;at is vterly a&yogh;enst goddis biddynge. &para; &THORN;at &thorn;efte &amp; raueynen &amp; mansleyng &amp; robberie be not meyntened in seyntiwarye vnder colour of priuylegie; si&thorn; kyng &amp; cristene men ben sworen to meynten eche man in his ri&yogh;t &amp; distroie wrong &amp; falsenesse. &para; &THORN;at worldly clerkis &amp; feyned religious vsurpen not &thorn;e kyngis regalie, ne stelle fro hym his holy power graunted of god for no criynge or ypocrisie; si&thorn; &thorn;ei ben sworn to be trewe to &thorn;e kyng &amp; fur&thorn;ere his worschipe &amp; profit of his lond. &para; &THORN;at &thorn;e kyng &amp; lordis gouerne hem self in here astaat as god ordeyned it, in gret wisdom, my&yogh;t of men &amp; sufficient riches to a&yogh;en|stonde wrong &amp; mysdoeris, &amp; helpe pore men, fadirles &amp; modirles &amp; widewes &amp; aliens in here lordischipe &amp; worschipe, &amp; rewarde trewe men, to reule clerkis in mekenesse, wilful pouert &amp; bisynesse of gostly traueile for helpe of mannys soule, as crist &amp; his apostlis diden, and suffre hem not to haunten anticristis ypocrisie &amp; tirauntrie of &thorn;e comones bi feyned censures, iurisdiction &amp; power of prisonynge. &amp; &thorn;at &thorn;ei reule here seruauntis &amp; tenauntis in ri&yogh;t mercy, pees &amp; charite, &amp; suffre no man hardy to breke goddis hestis in here<NOTE PLACE="foot">herte MS.</NOTE> presence, ne ony man don wrong or dispit to o&thorn;ere, but in alle in worschipe of eche o&thorn;ere in vnyte, pees &amp; charite.</P>


</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="20" TYPE="tract"><PB REF="00000347.tif" N="281">
<HEAD>XX.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[This fly-sheet is merely a piece of translation, and is only printed for the sake of completeness. Copied from the Corpus MS. X.]</P></HEADNOTE>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Augustinus. Arguam te nescis.</HEAD>
<P>&THORN;e holy doctour seynt austyn spekyng in &thorn;e persone of crist vnto synful men sei&thorn; in &thorn;is wise: I schal reproue &thorn;e, &amp; in what manere &amp; whanne &thorn;ou wenest not I schal reproue &thorn;e. I holde me stille whanne &thorn;ou dost amys; but I wole not holde me stille wi&thorn; my iugement, I schal reproue &thorn;e. what schal I don vnto &thorn;e whanne &thorn;at I reproue &thorn;e? I schal sette &thorn;in self bifore &thorn;in owene face. &para; Now so&thorn;ly whanne &thorn;ou dost amys &thorn;ou wenest &thorn;at &thorn;ou art good, for &thorn;ou wilte not seen &thorn;i self. &THORN;ou reprouest o&thorn;er folk, &thorn;ou ne lookest not on &thorn;i self; &thorn;ou acusest o&thorn;er folk, but &thorn;ou ne &thorn;enkest not on &thorn;i self; &thorn;ou puttest o&thorn;er folk biforn &thorn;in eien, &thorn;ou puttest &thorn;i self bihinde &thorn;i bake. but whanne I reproue &thorn;e I do &thorn;e contrarie. I take &thorn;e fro &thorn;i bak, &amp; putte &thorn;e bi-for &thorn;in owene eien. &THORN;ou schalt loke vpon &thorn;i self &amp; &thorn;ou schalt bewayle &thorn;i self, &amp; &thorn;an schal &thorn;ere <MILESTONE N="239" UNIT="page">ben no manere hou &thorn;ou schalt amende &thorn;i self. &THORN;ou dispisest now &thorn;e tyme of mercy, &thorn;e tyme of iugement come&thorn;; for &thorn;ou hast songen to me in holy chirche &thorn;es wordes: Misericordiam et iudicium cantabo tibi domine etc. &para; Lord I schal synge to &thorn;e &thorn;i mercy, &amp; &thorn;i iugement out of oure mou&thorn; come&thorn;, &amp; cristis chirchis proclaymen euere where cristis mercy &amp; eke his iugement &amp;c. Now is &thorn;e tyme of mercy to amende vs. &YOGH;it is not come &thorn;e tyme of iugement. we han space, we han place, we don synne, eke amende we oure giltis.</P>


</DIV2>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="21" TYPE="tract"><PB REF="00000348.tif" N="282">
<HEAD>XXI. OF DOMINION.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>DR. SHIRLEY retains Bale's title of this tract, "De Dominio Divino," while saying "it is certainly erroneous." I have preferred to keep near to the old name, which after all is not very wrong. It is true that the chief subject of the tract is the wrongfulness of Church endowments, and of the clergy's exemption from secular jurisdiction, but the ground of the argument is that dominion (whether possession or jurisdiction) is set by God in the hand of lay rulers, who may not alienate it without his leave. We see here how the doctrine of dominion bore on that of the unlawful|ness of endowments.</P><P>I fancy that I see here signs of translation from the Latin. However this may be, I do not doubt that the tract is substantially Wyclif's. I can find no evidence as to date.</P><P>Copied from the Dublin MS. AA., where only it is found.</P><P><TABLE>
<HEAD>SUMMARY.</HEAD>
<ROW>
<CELL>CHAP. I.</CELL>
<CELL>It was ordained in the old law that priests should live of tithes and offerings. It is said that this law has passed away, and that lords would not be free if they might not give away their property in endowment</CELL>
<CELL>p. 284</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL></CELL>
<CELL>God is chief lord of all property, which therefore cannot be alienated without his leave, and he has forbidden in both testaments the endowment of the clergy</CELL>
<CELL>284</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL></CELL>
<CELL>This prohibition is moral, and has not been repealed, having as much sanction as the command to give tithes to the priesthood, which the clergy enforce</CELL>
<CELL>285</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL></CELL>
<CELL>Evils which follow the reversal of God's law. Lay lords are bound to amend these evils, and their confessors should urge them to do so</CELL>
<CELL>286</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>II.</CELL>
<CELL>The commands of Scripture clear. Examples set by Christ and his Apostles</CELL>
<CELL>286</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL></CELL>
<CELL>The advocates of endowments appeal to charters, which can have no weight against God's law</CELL>
<CELL>287</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL></CELL>
<CELL>The Pope's cursing not to be regarded. This thunder curseth the well that it comes from</CELL>
<CELL>288</CELL>

<PB REF="00000349.tif" N="283">
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL></CELL>
<CELL>Miracles and the example of saints are insufficient sanctions. Miracles may be the devil's work, and all are not saints that are called so</CELL>
<CELL>p. 288</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL></CELL>
<CELL>God's law is the only safe guide, and this forbids possession to the clergy, who should be near to Christ in poverty</CELL>
<CELL>289</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>CHAP. III.</CELL>
<CELL>Antichrist's clerks say that the clergy should be judged only by ecclesiastical judges; but every man must judge his neighbour, and the only judgment that God forbids is foolish judgment</CELL>
<CELL>289</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL></CELL>
<CELL>Judgment may be foolish, as ignorant, hasty, or founded on wrong principles</CELL>
<CELL>290</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL></CELL>
<CELL>God has given men their senses and their conscience to judge with, and if they do not use these they are no better than beasts; but the devil would like to make them judge blindfold, as the Jews did with Christ</CELL>
<CELL>291</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>IV.</CELL>
<CELL>The devil says that God forbids men to judge their brethren</CELL>
<CELL>291</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL></CELL>
<CELL>Christ bade the Jews judge him, which he would not have done if laymen might not judge clerks</CELL>
<CELL>291</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL></CELL>
<CELL>Prelates should be thankful to those that reprove them</CELL>
<CELL>292</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL></CELL>
<CELL>Duty of bearing God's chastisements</CELL>
<CELL>293</CELL>
</ROW>
</TABLE></P></HEADNOTE>

<PB REF="00000350.tif" N="284">
<EPIGRAPH>
<Q>[Of Dominion.]</Q>
</EPIGRAPH>
<DIV2 N="1" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum primum.</HEAD>
<P><MILESTONE N="188" UNIT="page">Si&thorn; many falce gloseris maken goddis lawe derk &amp; letten seculere men to susteyne it &amp; kepen it; of siche falce gloseris schulde ech man be war. it is seid ofte tyme, in &thorn;e oolde lawe, &thorn;at prestis &amp; clerkis schulde lyue on goddis part; &thorn;at is to seie, on dymes &amp; offeryngis, &amp; haue noon o&thorn;er heritage among here bri&thorn;eren. but aduersarie of goddis lawe sei&thorn; here bi his glose, &thorn;at &thorn;is schulde be kept in &thorn;e oolde testament, &amp; is no nede to be kept in &thorn;e tyme of grace, for partys of &thorn;e oolde lawe ben now passid; &amp; but &yogh;if lordis my&yogh;te &yogh;eue here heritage to clerkis, as bischoppis &amp; abbotis &amp; o&thorn;er holy housis, &thorn;ei were vnfree to helpe here soulis &amp; here fadris, &amp; so &thorn;ei weren no&yogh;t ful lordis of here owne goodis. But here we schal sup|pose as Cristen mennes bileue, &thorn;at god is cheef lord of eche &thorn;ing of &thorn;is world. And so, al &yogh;if kyngis &amp; o&thorn;ere han free lordschipe, ne&thorn;eles god is more free lord of &thorn;at same &thorn;ing, ne it is nou&yogh;t leeful to seculere lordis, to alyenen his lordschipe wi&thorn;outen leeue of god; as in mannes lordschipe a litil lord ha&thorn; no leeue to alienen his heritage but bi leue of &thorn;e cheif lord, &amp; &thorn;is lawe ha&thorn; more resoun in &thorn;e lordschipe of god. Here may we se, si&thorn; lordis of &thorn;is world hadde no&yogh;t leeue of god &thorn;us to dowe his clerkis, here fool &yogh;ifte schulde no&yogh;t stonde bi skile; si&thorn; god may no&yogh;t be contrarie to him silf. But god ofte tyme in his two testamentis forbedi&thorn; his clerkis to be &thorn;us dowid; &amp; so &thorn;is gile, &thorn;at cam bi cautel of &thorn;e fend, schulde be now broken for defaute of ground. ne grucche no&yogh;t herfore &thorn;at god is cheif lord, for it falli&thorn; to his godhed to be lord of eche &thorn;ing, &amp; more curteys lord may no man haue, ne more profitable lawis to lede a man by resoun. for &thorn;is lord suffri&thorn; &thorn;ee nou&yogh;t to leese good but bi resoun, <MILESTONE N="188b" UNIT="page">ne he axi&thorn; &thorn;ee no rente but for &thorn;in owne profite; &amp; &thorn;us &thorn;e streng&thorn;e of goddis lawe axe&thorn; a&yogh;en &thorn;is lordschipe, &amp; fillynge of goddis lawe &thorn;at sue&thorn; grace 
<PB REF="00000351.tif" N="285"> &amp; pees. and se &thorn;is lewidnesse of &thorn;is resoun, &thorn;at &thorn;es lawis han no streng&thorn;e for &thorn;ei ben of &thorn;e oolde lawe, &thorn;at myche is went awey. certis so ben &thorn;e ten comaundementis of &thorn;e oolde lawe, &thorn;at ech man mote kepe &yogh;if he wole be saued; and so sermonyalis of &thorn;e oolde lawe &amp; summe iudycialis bynden nou&yogh;t now, but moralis bynden euere, si&thorn; &thorn;ei stonden in vertues. And so forsakynge of worldly richessis scholde bi more skile be kept now &thorn;anne in &thorn;e oolde lawe. And herfore crist &amp; his apostlis kepten &thorn;is ful streytly, &amp; &thorn;ei telden beste how &thorn;e lawe schulde be kept. more-ouer men may se &thorn;at si&thorn;&thorn;e &thorn;es same lawis ben scharply holden in &thorn;ing &thorn;at touchi&thorn; wynnynge, as in dymes &amp; offryngis, by &thorn;e same skile &thorn;ei schulden be kept in lordschipe; or ellis we weren to myche chargid &amp; mut leeue seruese of crist, &thorn;at he ha&thorn; ordeyned vs to do. Also crist &amp; his apostlis techen vs to lyue beter &thorn;anne &thorn;es patrouns of &thorn;es newe ordris; &amp; &thorn;ei lyueden pore liif, &amp; fledde lordschipe as venym. lord, whi schulde not we do so aftir &thorn;ese holy patrouns? and whanne &thorn;ou seist &thorn;at goddis lawe maki&thorn; &thorn;es lordis vnfree to helpe hem wi&thorn; here owne goodis, bo&thorn;e in body &amp; soule, it is knowen &thorn;inge &thorn;at contrarie falli&thorn;, bi &thorn;at lordis reuersen &thorn;e ordeynaunce of crist, &amp; &thorn;us for lordis fooly fallen many harmes bo&thorn;e to lordis, clerkis &amp; comunes. lordis ben maked pore &amp; eke fewe in noumbre, &amp; ofte tymes &thorn;ei ben nedid to spoyle here tenauntis, &amp; bi grucching a&yogh;eyn &thorn;ei disturblyn &thorn;e pees; and &thorn;is nedid no&yogh;t to falle &yogh;if lordis of &thorn;is world hadden al &thorn;is lordschipe of &thorn;is world in here hond &amp; ordeyned wel &thorn;erfore. more riche clerkis passen lordis in hous<MILESTONE N="189" UNIT="page"> holde &amp; meyne, in glorie of &thorn;is world, in power &amp; richessis. And so it may falle &thorn;at &thorn;ei taken fro lordis werris &amp; powers a-proprid unto lordis, for one harme in goddis lawe bryngi&thorn; in o&thorn;ir. Also clerkis bi symonye envenemyn hem silf, &amp; &yogh;if &thorn;ei stode in pouert &thorn;ei fel no&yogh;t in &thorn;is perel. Also goodis of &thorn;is rewme ben yuel dispendid in hondis of &thorn;es clerkis &amp; &yogh;euen vnto false men, bo&thorn;e vnto alienes &amp; men of &thorn;is lond; &amp; so goodis of &thorn;is rewme ben yuel distryed. Also &thorn;es clerkis ben herbi vnabled to preie &amp; 
<PB REF="00000352.tif" N="286"> to serue god as he comaunde&thorn; hem; and &thorn;is is &thorn;e moste harme a&yogh;ens god &amp; man, for &thorn;is nedi&thorn; rewmes to lyuen in werres. for job sei&thorn; in his book, &amp; resoun approue&thorn;, &thorn;at no man<NOTE PLACE="marg">Job x. 4.</NOTE> reuersi&thorn; god but &yogh;if he haue vnpees; and so &thorn;is dowynge a&yogh;ens goddis lawe doi&thorn; harme to lordis &amp; clerkis &amp; comunys, bo&thorn;e bodily harme &amp; harme to here soulis, &amp; negligent of lordis in amendement here-of is a manere of consence &amp; greggi&thorn; here synne; &amp; it harme&thorn; here elderis &thorn;at bigan &thorn;is errour, ne good do&thorn; it noon; but moue&thorn; lordis to pride &thorn;at here kyn ha&thorn; &thorn;us foundid housis of religioun. and si&thorn; god in his lawe cursi&thorn; men &thorn;at breken it, it seme&thorn; &thorn;at bo&thorn;e ben cursid, lordis &amp; clerkis, and herfore confessouris &amp; alle &thorn;at ben on goddis half schulde moue &amp; maynteyne &thorn;is lawe of oure god. &amp; si&thorn;&thorn;e &thorn;e moste vnfredom is vnfredom of synne, for &thorn;at maki&thorn; a man seruaunt to nou&yogh;t &amp; seruaunt to &thorn;e fend, &amp; dampne&thorn; him in helle, coueytise of fredom schulde moue men her-to, and so synne bi his manere bryngi&thorn; his doere into &thorn;e same myre &thorn;at he eschewi&thorn;.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="2" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum 2<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>The seuene lawis of &thorn;e newe testament ben so open, &amp; &thorn;ere|to confermed wi&thorn; &thorn;e liif of crist &amp; of his apostlis, &thorn;at it is no nede to reuerse &thorn;es gloses &thorn;at feynen to &thorn;es lawis a falce vnderstondinge, &amp; techen clerkis to lyue on worldly manere. but &thorn;es religious <MILESTONE N="189b" UNIT="page">&amp; seculere prestis, &amp; so many clerkis, bi brekynge of &thorn;is lawe, ben cursid of god &amp; venemyn cristendome. for crist him silf teche&thorn; bi word of seynt poul &thorn;at he is cursid<NOTE PLACE="marg">1 Cor. xvi. 22.</NOTE> of god &thorn;at loue&thorn; no&yogh;t crist; but si&thorn; he onely loue&thorn; crist &thorn;at kepi&thorn; his wordis, who euere breki&thorn; cristis lawe is cursid of god, and he &thorn;at fauori&thorn; &thorn;is part or assenti&thorn; here-wi&thorn;; &amp; his cursynge is more &thorn;an cursynge of &thorn;e pope, or ony o&thorn;ere sensuris &thorn;at he kan feyne; &amp; so clerkis of &thorn;is lond semen<NOTE PLACE="foot">senen MS.</NOTE> irregulere, for &thorn;ei han so longe leyen in so gret cursinge. Also in &thorn;e tyme of grace crist for-bede his apostlis &thorn;at &thorn;ei<NOTE PLACE="marg">Matthew x. 10.</NOTE> 
<PB REF="00000353.tif" N="287"> schulde nou&yogh;t bere in &thorn;e weye &thorn;at wolde lette hem to preche; myche more clerkis schulde no&yogh;t take on hem such lordschipe, &thorn;at wolde lette more to preche &amp; to serue god; si&thorn; clerkis ben now more pore of &yogh;iftis of god &amp; more bisi aboute &thorn;e world, &thorn;anne to bere staues or kotis or hoosis or gretynge of folke &thorn;at crist forbeed his apostlis. Also we schulden haue mynde<NOTE PLACE="marg">Luke x. 4.</NOTE> on &thorn;e passioun of crist, hou dere he bou&yogh;te his lawe whanne he was deed herfore, for al &thorn;at he suffride &amp; kyndenesse &thorn;at he dide was to comende his lawe to men &thorn;at comen aftir him. O, how vnkynde ben &thorn;ei &thorn;at dispisen &thorn;is lawe, or for to breken it or to putte o&thorn;ere byfore it. certis &thorn;ei ben cursid, as &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="marg">Psalm cxix. 21.</NOTE> salme sei&thorn;, and suche ben vnable to preie or to &yogh;eue ony sacramentis. and &yogh;if &thorn;at heresie were wel knowen, &thorn;es clerkis were heretikis more &thorn;anne ony o&thorn;ere; for &thorn;ei defenden here part a&yogh;enes goddis lawe bi falce lawis &amp; cautels to here lyues ende. But &yogh;it antecristis clerkis prouen bi here resouns &thorn;at &thorn;e kyng &amp; &thorn;e rewme mote nede maynteynen hem, si&thorn;&thorn;e &thorn;ei ben sworen to &thorn;e grete charite.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Sic in MS. for chartir.</NOTE> But here we schal supposen as cristen mennes bileue, &thorn;at no mennes lawis ne chartirs maad of men han streng&thorn;e but in as myche as goddis lawe conferme&thorn; hem; for what is ony chartre or ony lawe wor&thorn;, But &yogh;if god conferme it by his <MILESTONE N="190" UNIT="page">lawe? &amp; so &thorn;is grete chartre wolde moue bi goddis wytt, &thorn;at kyngis &amp; here rewmes schulde maynteyne &thorn;e chirche by &thorn;e ordeynaunce of god, &amp; distroie &thorn;e contrarie. and &yogh;if we taken hede bo&thorn;e kyngis &amp; rewmes bi here opyn o&thorn;is schulden take awey &thorn;es rentis &thorn;at &thorn;e fend ha&thorn; dowid wi&thorn; clerkis a&yogh;ens cristis ordeynaunce. ffor no wise man wolde seie &thorn;at lordis by here o&thorn;is schulde maynteyne lawe of &thorn;e fend a&yogh;ens ihesu crist; and so to chalenge of &thorn;e kyng to maynteyne alle here chartres &amp; alle here newe lawis &thorn;at &thorn;ei han founden were to chalenge &thorn;e kyng as &thorn;e fendis seruaunt; and &thorn;ere were ouere myche dispit to here lyge lord. and &yogh;if &thorn;ou seie &thorn;at cursyngis purchased of &thorn;e pope and o&thorn;ere felle sensuris &thorn;ondured ouere til englond schulde fere ouere rewme to do siche &thorn;ingis; Here we schal suppose as 
<PB REF="00000354.tif" N="288"> oure bileue &thorn;at no mannes cursynge ha&thorn; ony streng&thorn;e but in as myche as god himsilf cursi&thorn;; and so ofte tyme cursi&thorn; &thorn;e fendis mynystris, &amp; god him silf blissi&thorn; and &thorn;e fend cursi&thorn;; &amp; &yogh;if &thorn;ou seie &thorn;at moo men stonden wi&thorn; siche cursynge &thorn;anne wi&thorn; blissynge of god, &amp; hem schulde we trowe; here oure bileue techi&thorn; vs &thorn;at goddis lawe is trewe &amp; mote stonde, al &yogh;if &thorn;ere be mo fendis &thorn;an trewe men, and triste to no man in &thorn;is mater but to goddis lawe; for &thorn;at sei&thorn; god himsilf, &thorn;at may neuere be false.<NOTE PLACE="foot">falle MS.</NOTE> O how hardy be we maad to werren on oure bri&thorn;eren, &amp; how foule cowardis to stonde in goddis cause, &amp; certis all &thorn;is is maad bi &thorn;e fendis craft. drede we nou&yogh;t &thorn;is &thorn;ondir, for it turne&thorn; a&yogh;en &amp; cursi&thorn; &thorn;e welle &thorn;at it come fro. ffor men stable in bileue ben a &thorn;ick walle to turnen a&yogh;en &thorn;is &thorn;ondir &thorn;at it<NOTE PLACE="foot">is MS.</NOTE> persi&thorn; no&yogh;t. But &yogh;it &thorn;ou seist &thorn;at oure rewme stood in myche ioye whanne &thorn;e chirche was putt &amp; mayntened in &thorn;is staat, &amp; so it were ful dredeful <MILESTONE N="190b" UNIT="page">to distrie &thorn;is staat. But certis &thorn;is is a fendis skile to maken vs drede in fei&thorn;; but we schal vndirstonde, as goddis lawe techi&thorn; us, &thorn;at ofte tymes fendis children passen here in wel&thorn;e &thorn;e children of god &thorn;at aftir schal haue blisse. &amp; so it is a feble skile: &yogh;if oure rewme hadde suche wel&thorn;e whanne &thorn;ei dide &amp; maynteyned suche staat to &thorn;e chirche, &thorn;anne &thorn;ei diden wel &amp; plesaunly to god. make goddis lawe &thorn;i iuge, for &thorn;at mote nedis be, &amp; &thorn;is iuge may no&yogh;t folde ne faile in ri&yogh;twisnesse; and as &thorn;e gospel sei&thorn; &thorn;is iuge is aduersarie to ech man in er&thorn;e &thorn;at holdi&thorn; no&yogh;t goddis lawe. But &thorn;ou seist &thorn;at myraclis &amp; lyues of holy men approuen &thorn;is dowynge of &thorn;e chirche, and god wi&thorn; his seyntis; who schulde be so hardy to breke siche an ordeynaunce? But here schulde we wyte &thorn;at many suche sygnes comen ofte of &thorn;e fend for mennes firste synne; so, as seynt poul sei&thorn;, &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="marg">2 Cor. xi. 14.</NOTE> fend ha&thorn; power for to figuren him in-til an aungel of li&yogh;t; &amp; so he is vntrewe man &thorn;at trowi&thorn; to siche signes as myche as he trowi&thorn; to &thorn;e fei&thorn; of goddis lawe. &amp; so it is no bileue &thorn;at alle &thorn;es men ben seyntis &thorn;at ben hirid of &thorn;e pope to ben holden siche; and fewe men woot how &thorn;es wondris comen &thorn;at we 
<PB REF="00000355.tif" N="289"> clepyn myraclis, whe&thorn;er of good or yuel; ffor well we wyten &thorn;at &thorn;e fend doi&thorn; ofte myche good. stonde we stable in oure bileue, for &thorn;at may neuere faile. But &thorn;e fend replye&thorn; a&yogh;enst &thorn;is tru&thorn;e, and sei&thorn;, &thorn;e king's graunt bi his owne chartre &amp; bullis of &thorn;e pope confermed &thorn;is dowynge, how schulde men denye &thorn;is or distroie it, But &yogh;if &thorn;ei reuersen al &thorn;e ordynaunce of &thorn;is rewme? Here I woot &thorn;at men of lawe ben moued bi siche resouns. But professouris of goddis lawe schulde stonde by here bileue, and putte abac mannes lawe, but &yogh;if goddis lawe ap<MILESTONE N="191" UNIT="page">proue it; &amp; so &yogh;if chartris of men ben contrarie to goddis lawe, &thorn;es chartres schulde be wayschen and goddis lawe schulde stonde; and so &yogh;if &thorn;es poscessioneris toke fre &thorn;is in here lond and allegede here chartris, and trewe men goddis lawe, &thorn;anne schulde men se whiche were goddis children &amp; whiche &thorn;e fendis children by maynteyn[yn]ge of &thorn;es lawis. and so &thorn;e fend can nou&yogh;t do but &yogh;if he ouere do, whanne he argue&thorn; &thorn;us, &thorn;at &yogh;if a rewme were purgid of errouris in goddis lawe, &thorn;anne were &thorn;is rewme distryed. wele I woot &thorn;at goddis lawe &yogh;eue&thorn; seculer lordschipis to seculer lordis &amp; forbedi&thorn; hem to clerkis. &thorn;e laboureris of cristis chirche han leffully rentis &amp; worldly possessiouns o&thorn;ere &thorn;an clerkis han, ffor &thorn;ei ben hi&yogh;ere in degree and neer to crist in pouerte; &amp; bo&thorn;e &thorn;es &thorn;ingis to|gidre may &thorn;ei nou&yogh;t haue.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="3" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum 3<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>But a&yogh;ens &thorn;is blaberen antecristis clerkis, and aleggen goddis lawe, but to false sentense, &thorn;at seculer men schulde no&yogh;t iuge of clerkis, how euere &thorn;ei don; for &thorn;ei han propre iuges, as popis &amp; bischopis &amp; o&thorn;ere iugis vndir hem; &amp; her-to &thorn;ei leggen but lewydly goddis lawe. Here schal we wite &thorn;at &thorn;ere ben many iugementis, as iugement bi goddis lawe and iugement by mannes lawe, &amp; in bo&thorn;e &thorn;es lawis ben many manere iugementis; and schal we trowe &thorn;at ech man of dis|crecioun schal iuge of his nei&yogh;bore, be he more or lesse, be he prest or clerk, lord or ellis pore man, and so to al &thorn;e speche &thorn;at is in goddis lawe aloonely fool iugement is &thorn;ere-inne for|fendid; 
<PB REF="00000356.tif" N="290"> &amp; man may iuge folily upon many maneris; as &yogh;if a man iuge of &thorn;ing &thorn;at he knowi&thorn; no&yogh;t, as many men presumen to iuge a man to heuene, or ellis iuge him to helle bi here feyned cursynge, &amp; so prelatis<MILESTONE N="191b" UNIT="page"> ofte tymes blasfemen in god, &amp; taken on hem iugement &amp; knowynge of god; and &thorn;is iuge|ment dampned poul, for prelatis schulde no&yogh;t iuge seruauntis<NOTE PLACE="marg">Rom. xiv. 4.</NOTE> of god in &thorn;at &thorn;ei knowe nou&yogh;t. &thorn;e secounde foly of iugement stondi&thorn; in &thorn;is, &thorn;at men iugen to li&yogh;tly &amp; bi litil euydence to good or to yuel, &thorn;at sue&thorn; no&yogh;t &thorn;er-of; as &yogh;if a man iuge for fame of his bro&thorn;er or for autorite of name, &thorn;at what euere he seye [is] so&thorn;e, and seki&thorn; no&yogh;t &thorn;e resoun of &thorn;ing &thorn;at he sei&thorn;; &amp; &thorn;us ben men disceyued in iugement of popis and of o&thorn;er prelatis &amp; of o&thorn;ere comyntes, &amp; ofte tymes on &thorn;is wise ben men disceyued of iugement of myraclis, &amp; many o&thorn;er signes, and &thorn;us mennes iugementis ben ofte ful of errouris whanne &thorn;ei iugen by mannes entent bi ouere<NOTE PLACE="foot">evere MS.</NOTE> li&yogh;t euydence. men schal euere suppose &thorn;e good, but &yogh;if open euydence teche &thorn;e con|trarie, of &thorn;ingis &thorn;at men &thorn;enken on. the &thorn;ridde manere of errour &thorn;at falli&thorn; in mannes iugement is falceheed of here prynciple &thorn;at &thorn;ei groundem hem on; as falce wytnesse &thorn;at gone on a quest gabben in here witnessis, &thorn;ei maken &thorn;e iuge erre and pupplische a sentence contrarie to trew&thorn;e. &amp; ri&yogh;t &thorn;us multitud of antecristis disciplis may moue men to leue cristis lore; but blessed be god, &thorn;at in euery chirche ha&thorn; ordeyned masse bookis to witnesse his gospel. And &thorn;us schulde kyngis bi worschipe of here staat, constreyne here lyge freris &amp; here o&thorn;ere clerkis, vp peyne of here leggeaunce, to telle trew&thorn;e of &thorn;es bullis &amp; of &thorn;es o&thorn;ere nouelries, whe&thorn;er &thorn;ei ben of bileue, &amp; grounde hem in resoun or in goddis lawe, &amp; examyne here proues whe&thorn;er &thorn;ei ben trewe men. and &thorn;us schulde &thorn;e rewme be reuled bi ri&yogh;t, and falce men distroyed &thorn;at venemen &thorn;e rewme; &amp; &thorn;us schulde men iuge &thorn;at ben goddis seruauntis, al &yogh;if &thorn;ei stirte no&yogh;t vp in pilatis chaier. and so ech iugement &thorn;at is<MILESTONE N="192" UNIT="page"> no&yogh;t groundid in god schulde be fleed of men as disceyt of &thorn;e fend. ffor god him silf is trewe&thorn;e, as &thorn;e 
<PB REF="00000357.tif" N="291"> gospel sei&thorn;, and &thorn;e fend is fadir of lesyngis. and so sum good iugement is of mennes out-wittis, as &thorn;ei iugen whiche mete is good &amp; whiche mete is yuel, &amp; sum men iugement is of mennes witt wi&thorn;inne, as men iugen how &thorn;ei schal do, by lawe of consience; as cristen men schal iuge to whom &thorn;ei don here almes, and &thorn;at &thorn;ei feden nou&yogh;t fendis children among here owne heed.<NOTE PLACE="foot">? herd.</NOTE> &amp; it were al on to reue fro worldly men &thorn;is iugement, &amp; to seie &thorn;at &thorn;ei ben bestis dampnable for here folye. And &thorn;us &thorn;e fend may hide mennes wittis &amp; bobbe hem in here resoun, as &thorn;e iewis diden wi&thorn; crist, &amp; leden hem to<NOTE PLACE="marg">Matt. xxvi. 68.</NOTE> helle as blynd avocatis of &thorn;e fend. &thorn;is blynde boffetynge schulde worldly men eschewe, ffor it helpi&thorn; nou&yogh;t to &thorn;is world ne to &thorn;e to&thorn;er world. And wite wel &thorn;es lordis &thorn;at god ha&thorn; &yogh;euen hem resoun for to seruen him, and loken here owne profi&yogh;t; ffor &thorn;is lord of his curtesye axe&thorn; no seruyse of man, but &yogh;if it turne to his profyt &amp; no&yogh;t to &thorn;e profyte of god. and &thorn;us it were al on antecrist to teche &thorn;at men schulde no&yogh;t iuge of dedis of his clerkis, &amp; to seie &thorn;at he is lorde aboue ihesu crist.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="4" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum 4<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>A&yogh;eyns &thorn;is &thorn;e fend grucchi&thorn; bi many blynde resouns, and sei&thorn; &thorn;at god forbeedi&thorn; his men to iuge of here bri&thorn;eren. But we schulde trowe to wordis &thorn;at god putti&thorn; in his lawe. ffor god biddi&thorn; &thorn;at a man schulde assaye him silf, and so ete of &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="marg">1 Cor. xi. 28.</NOTE> breed &thorn;at is &thorn;e sacrid oost. ffor he &thorn;at eti&thorn; unwor&thorn;ily eti&thorn; his owne jugement, ffor he iugi&thorn; no&yogh;t wisely &thorn;e wor&thorn;inesse of goddis body. &amp; &thorn;e holy salme sei&thorn;: "vnderstond, &yogh;e kyngis;<NOTE PLACE="marg">Psalm ii. 10.</NOTE> and schaak of &yogh;ou rudenesse, &yogh;e &thorn;at jugen londis." Sum tyme iugement god grauntid to kyngis, as davi&thorn; &amp; salamon &amp; many o&thorn;ere kyngis. &amp; &yogh;if &thorn;ou seie &thorn;at popis lawe speki&thorn; o&thorn;er wise of<MILESTONE N="192b" UNIT="page"> jugement, haue &thorn;e popis lawe more suspette; si&thorn; goddis<NOTE PLACE="marg">John vii. 24.</NOTE> lawe speke&thorn; &thorn;us, and &thorn;us crist biddi&thorn; &thorn;e iewis to iuge of him ri&yogh;t iugement. Lord, whe&thorn;er &thorn;es clerkis ben more hi&yogh;e ouere seculeris &thorn;an was our lord ihesu crist ouere &thorn;es falce iewis? ffor trewe men ben certeyn &thorn;at crist bad hem 
<PB REF="00000358.tif" N="292"> no&yogh;t juge of him but &yogh;if it were leeful to lewid men to iuge of clerkis; and so it were al on to denye siche iugement and denye regalye &thorn;at falli&thorn; to &thorn;e kyng. Lord, whe&thorn;er &thorn;e lawe of ynglond schal be now distried bi fablis of heretikis con|trarie to goddis lawe? Wel I woot &thorn;at men were wont bi iugement of ynglond to dampne prestis and clerkis for robberie &amp; &thorn;efte, and also for trayterie and o&thorn;er smale trespas; and &yogh;if &thorn;ei now denye &thorn;is &thorn;ei denye &thorn;e regalye. And &thorn;us seie to antecrist &thorn;at crist bad men iuge of him bo&thorn;e bi his godhede and eke by his manheed. Lord, whe&thorn;er antecristis clerkis ben more &thorn;anne was crist? Also seynt poul iugi&thorn; of petris<NOTE PLACE="marg">Gal. ii. [11.]</NOTE> synne, and a&yogh;en-stoode him for he was reprouable. Lord, whe&thorn;er prelatis now ben more confermed in grace &thorn;anne was seynt petir &thorn;anne aftir sonde of &thorn;e holy goost? Also ech man schulde bi &thorn;e lawe of &thorn;e gospel vndirnyme ech bro&thorn;er &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="marg">Matt. xviii. [15.]</NOTE> synne&thorn; a&yogh;ens him. But comunly &thorn;es prelatis synnen a&yogh;ens lewid men; &thorn;anne lewid men by here fei&thorn; schulde vndirnyme &thorn;es prelatis. And so it is al on to oute-take &thorn;es prelatis fro suche snybbinge of &thorn;e peple &amp; make hem more &thorn;an crist; ffor &yogh;if crist my&yogh;te haue synned he wolde &thorn;us haue be blamed. Also by &thorn;e lawe of charite ech man schulde loue ech o&thorn;ere; and si&thorn; god ha&thorn; &yogh;euen men witt to se &thorn;at prelatis don yuel, bi &thorn;e lawe of charite &thorn;ei schulde moue hem to good. &amp; so it were al on to take prelatis fro &thorn;is iugement and seie &thorn;at &thorn;ei ben fendis &thorn;at may nou&yogh;t be amendid. also bi goddis lawe a man schulde for charite drawe<MILESTONE N="193" UNIT="page"> his enemyes beste oute of &thorn;e lake; but god ha&thorn; more reward of men &thorn;anne of beestis, &thorn;anne myche more schulde a man helpe men oute of synne. also si&thorn; ech of vs schuld knowe him silf synful and be glaad of seuene goostly werkis of mercy, he schulde haue ioye &thorn;at men reproued him of his synne; and certis so wele ech man but &thorn;e quyk deuel; ffor he for his pride wele not be blamyd of god. And herfore seith &thorn;e wise man &thorn;at he &thorn;at hati&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="marg">Ecclus. [xxi. 7?]</NOTE> blamynge is sutere of &thorn;e fend, rebelle a&yogh;ens god. And salamon sei&thorn;: "he &thorn;at dispisi&thorn; his blamere schal be sodenly distried &amp;<NOTE PLACE="marg">Prov. xv. [10.]</NOTE> no&yogh;t helid of his synne." And herfore teche&thorn; seynt poul to<NOTE PLACE="marg">Titus 1. [13.]</NOTE> 
<PB REF="00000359.tif" N="293"> reprove siche ful harde. ffor &thorn;us dide crist oure al&thorn;ere maystir reprouynge &thorn;es pharisees, and so he dide to peple<NOTE PLACE="marg">Matt. xxiii.</NOTE> clepynge him sathanas, and so charite chacchi&thorn; men to &thorn;is iust jugement. ffor goddis lawe techi&thorn; vs to don to o&thorn;ere<NOTE PLACE="marg">Matt. vii. [12.]</NOTE> men as we schulden willen &thorn;at &thorn;ei diden to vs. But who led bi resoun putt in greet perel wolde no&yogh;t be glaad to haue helpe &thorn;ere of? But si&thorn;e ech man by synne is in an huge perel, he schulde be glaad of eche &thorn;ing &thorn;at warne&thorn; him of his perelle, &yogh;if it be neuere so lowe &amp; werse &thorn;an man in kynde. For ellis men<NOTE PLACE="foot">weren probably omitted.</NOTE> in obedient as &thorn;e firste apostata. Wel I rede in goddis lawe &thorn;at god was obedient unto voys of man as to his owne<NOTE PLACE="marg">Josh x. [12.]</NOTE> instrument. And so si&thorn;e ech creature &thorn;at telli&thorn; a man a treu&thorn;e is instrument of god to schewe him &thorn;is tru&thorn;e, it were oon to dispise &thorn;is instrument in &thorn;is and to dispise &thorn;e tru&thorn;e of &thorn;e lord &thorn;at he schewi&thorn;. But he were oute of resoun &thorn;at were smyten in feueris or ellis in a frenesye or ony o&thorn;er siknesse &thorn;at wolde no&yogh;t take his medicine or reule of ano&thorn;er man, al &yogh;if it were displesynge to him for a tyme. Thus meke men &amp; trewe men blamen no&yogh;t &thorn;e creature &thorn;at telli&thorn; hem a tru&thorn;e in name of god, si&thorn;e &thorn;e lord moeue&thorn; hem for profyt <MILESTONE N="193b" UNIT="page"> of men to tellen hem goddis wille, in him schulde &thorn;ei heren. and so &yogh;if we can se clerkis schulde wi&thorn; ioye suffre temporal lord|schipis be taken awey from hem. For wel we wyten &thorn;at &thorn;is were no&yogh;t a&yogh;ens goddis lawe ne hyndrid hem no&yogh;t to gete hi&yogh;e setis in heuene; but ra&thorn;ere disposide hem to come to myche blisse and &thorn;us schulde ech man willen as god him silf biddi&thorn; hem.</P>
<P>And so take heede what god biddi&thorn; &thorn;ee do &amp; do &thorn;at and noon o&thorn;er, for al o&thorn;ere is synne. &amp; loke to alle &thorn;ingis &thorn;at comen to &thorn;ee to suffre and suffre it mekely, si&thorn; god nedi&thorn; &thorn;ee &thorn;erto &amp; sendi&thorn; it for &thorn;e beste, al &yogh;if &thorn;ou kanst no&yogh;t se it; as a child is ofte betyn for his owne profyte and &yogh;it he grucchi&thorn; &thorn;er-a&yogh;ens, for he see&thorn; no&yogh;t &thorn;e resoun. and &thorn;is moue&thorn; many men mekely to suffre whateuere come&thorn; to hem, for so biddi&thorn; charite.</P>


</DIV2>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="22" TYPE="tract"><PB REF="00000360.tif" N="294">
<HEAD>XXII. TRACTATUS DE PSEUDO-FRERIS.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>I REGARD this tract as almost certainly Wyclif's, and in this I am sup|ported by Mr. Arnold's opinion, who omitted it only because he had printed so much invective against the Friars. It has an interest as showing that Wyclif felt it necessary to justify his attacks upon the Mendicants, though it must be owned that the apology takes the form of a renewal of the offence. But we must not disregard the 'pseudo' which forms part of the title, and is not forgotten in the text. What Wyclif inveighed against is the evil which followed from admitting and binding to an order men who did not live in the spirit of its founder. With a true follower of St. Francis Wyclif would have had much in common. Even as it was, he admits there were good men among them: as Paul and Nicodemus were among the Pharisees, to whom he delighted to liken them.</P><P>This higher temper may be noticed in his dealing with the practice of midnight prayers (p. 317). Such rising to pray he says may be good, or it may be a hindrance to a man whom God calls to some better occupation, and it is presumptuous to make a binding rule on the subject. So in his Latin sermons he says, "Non observant omnia que Christiana religio precipit et observat, cum non observant mensuram" (MS. Trin. Coll. Camb. fo. 195). Of his rougher humour there is a good specimen on p. 319, where he likens friars between whom there is ill-feeling to dogs in a sack.</P><P>Among the marks of authenticity we may note the incidental use of the doctrine of Dominion (p. 316) and of Wyclif's favourite point that it is impossible to tell of any man whether he will be saved or damned (p. 317). Another characteristic passage is that on p. 312: "We graunten mekeliche that . . . we faylen in the heyghnesse of charite." Wyclif knew that his besetting fault was intemperance in attack. In a passage quoted by Dr. Shirley (F. Z. xlv. note) he tells us that he was accused of vindictive|ness and spite; and in the tract De Sex Jugis (Lechler ii. 603) he says: "Omnes enim cogitamus superflue, quomodo vindicta caperetur de hostibus Christi atque ecclesi&aelig;, et potius cogitamus imprecando istam vindictam quam alia media misericordi&aelig;, qu&aelig; sic injuriantibus cederent ad salutem."</P><P>I must not omit to notice that this sharp attack on the Friars contains no mention of the Eucharist, but I cannot on that account disregard the weighty reasons in favour of its genuineness.</P><P>Copied from the only MS., Dublin, C. v. 6. [CC.].
<PB REF="00000361.tif" N="295"></P><P><TABLE>
<HEAD>SUMMARY.</HEAD>
<ROW>
<CELL>CHAP. I.</CELL>
<CELL>Many people cannot bear to hear friars spoken of as false, but we must do as God's law bids. We are bid to reprove sin; and as Christ reproved Pharisees we must reprove these new orders, which are Pharisees from Christians</CELL>
<CELL>p. 296</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL></CELL>
<CELL>We must not blame untruly, hastily, or on false principles; nor from envy, but from love</CELL>
<CELL>297</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL></CELL>
<CELL>Wrongfulness of trying to stop such language, since it is used by Paul</CELL>
<CELL>298</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>II.</CELL>
<CELL>There is good and evil in the orders. Some friars leave the convent and get better employment; yet they encourage the others who remain</CELL>
<CELL>298</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL></CELL>
<CELL>Their observances are superfluous. Christ's rebuke to Pharisees</CELL>
<CELL>299</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL></CELL>
<CELL>The New Testament forbids sects, but these orders make sects</CELL>
<CELL>299</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL></CELL>
<CELL>Covetousness of prelates and friars, who ought to take little and return much</CELL>
<CELL>300</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>III.</CELL>
<CELL>A sect is a new order, with a new patron and rule</CELL>
<CELL>301</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL></CELL>
<CELL>Christ's sect does not insist on clothes</CELL>
<CELL>301</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL></CELL>
<CELL>St. Peter's prophecies of the new sects and their evils</CELL>
<CELL>302</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL></CELL>
<CELL>How St. Paul speaks of them</CELL>
<CELL>303</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>IV.</CELL>
<CELL>See whether St. James spoke of these friars. He speaks of two religions: one pure, the other vain. The pure religion is that of Christ. Not kept by friars. Their various faults</CELL>
<CELL>304</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>V.</CELL>
<CELL>St. Jude prophesies of apostates and his warnings in their details correspond to the ways of friars</CELL>
<CELL>306</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>VI.</CELL>
<CELL>St. John's warnings against the friars</CELL>
<CELL>309</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL></CELL>
<CELL>His writings, like all other authors of the New Testament, teach us to reprove friars. They attribute ill-will to their reprovers, but God is the judge of intent</CELL>
<CELL>311</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>VII.</CELL>
<CELL>The fiend's clergy say that in reproving them we make ourselves equal with God, whereas we are sinful. We acknowledge our sins, but believe that we are Christ's servants, and that we speak as he bids us</CELL>
<CELL>312</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL></CELL>
<CELL>Christ's example. Need of reproof</CELL>
<CELL>313</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>VIII.</CELL>
<CELL>The fiend gives six reasons to love these orders&mdash;</CELL>
<CELL></CELL>
<TABLE>
<ROW>
<CELL>I.</CELL>
<CELL>Their dress. But it is wasteful</CELL>
<CELL>315</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>II.</CELL>
<CELL>Abstinence. Not true of all of them, and, if true, not necessarily good</CELL>
<CELL>316</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>III.</CELL>
<CELL>The excellence of their prayers. They do not know that they will be saved. Their selling prayers shows a bad conscience</CELL>
<CELL>317</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL></CELL>
<CELL>Their rules are presumptuous</CELL>
<CELL>318</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>IV.</CELL>
<CELL>The holiness of the society. They are not all holy, nor is their united prayer necessarily powerful</CELL>
<CELL>318</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL></CELL>
<CELL>Good life the best prayer, and the cloister is often not the best life</CELL>
<CELL>319</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>V.</CELL>
<CELL>Their special prayers. Their prayers are not so good as the Paternoster, or Christ would have taught them</CELL>
<CELL>320</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>VI.</CELL>
<CELL>Their handsome churches and appointments. These they ought to grieve for, since they are got by robbery, spoiling the poor, and injuring parish churches</CELL>
<CELL>321</CELL>
</ROW>
</TABLE>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL></CELL>
<CELL>Christ warns us against these sects. We are bound to withstand them</CELL>
<CELL>323</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL></CELL>
<CELL>If we are shown to err, we will turn to the truth</CELL>
<CELL>324</CELL>
</ROW>
</TABLE></P></HEADNOTE>

<PB REF="00000362.tif" N="296">
<EPIGRAPH>
<Q>Tractatus de Pseudo-freris.</Q>
</EPIGRAPH>
<DIV2 N="1" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum primum.</HEAD>
<P><MILESTONE N="81" UNIT="page">For many beren heuy &thorn;at freris ben clepid pseudo or ypocritis, antecristis or fendis, or ony siche name, it were to telle what goddis lawe sey&thorn; here, &amp; bi lore of goddis lawe men shulden stonde stifly. ffirst men taken of bileeue &thorn;at &thorn;ei shulden reproue synne; si&thorn; crist techi&thorn; &thorn;at &yogh;if &thorn;yn bro&thorn;er synne&thorn; in &thorn;ee, &thorn;ou shalt &thorn;ries reproue hym; &amp; fro &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="marg">Matt. xviii. [15.]</NOTE> bigynnyng of &thorn;e world til &thorn;is tyme was it vsid &thorn;at men shulden reproue synne for loue &amp; worship of god. for it were al oon to lette &thorn;is &amp; to lette men to be goddis children, and to forsake crist god &amp; take men fulliche to &thorn;e fend, &amp; so forsake cristis maundementis, &amp; bi-come &thorn;e fendis seruaunt. But for siche an heresye somme men shulden suffre martirdom, &amp; somme men make resouns, &amp; somme men vsen here worldliche streng&thorn;e; si&thorn; crist, heued of martris, deyede to destrie &thorn;is heresye, &amp; alle hise martris aftir deyeden in &thorn;e same cause; and hey&yogh; prestis of &thorn;e temple wi&thorn; pharisees &thorn;at crist reprouede weren more and betere groundid &thorn;en ben &thorn;e sectis of &thorn;ise freris. Aftirwa[r]d men supposen &thorn;at &thorn;ise freris may lytlyche erre; &amp; bi dedis &thorn;at fame telli&thorn;, &thorn;ei synnen &amp; harmen meche &thorn;e peple. Si&thorn; crist welle of religion here chees to hym tuelue apostlis, &amp; &yogh;it oon of hem was Sharioth, whom it was leueful to reproue &mdash; what vertu hauen &thorn;ise newe ordris, &thorn;at ben cropen in wi&thorn;-oute ground, &thorn;at men shal not reproue hem, harmen &thorn;ey neuere so myche &thorn;e chirche? hit were al oon to graunte &thorn;is, &amp; &yogh;iue it vp to &thorn;e fend, &amp; fy&yogh;te no more in goddis cause, but assent to &thorn;e fend what euere he do; &amp; it is al oon to reproue synne, &amp; to reproue persones &thorn;at synnen. lord, si&thorn; freris synnen ofte, why shulden not men reprouen hem, &amp; &yogh;if al &thorn;e secte assente&thorn;, speke we sharpliche a&yogh;en &thorn;e secte; &thorn;us spak crist sharpliche a&yogh;en &thorn;e secte of pharisees, as matheu telli&thorn; in eyhte woes &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="marg">Matt. xxiii. [13-33.]</NOTE> 
<PB REF="00000363.tif" N="297"> crist spak a&yogh;en hem, &amp; &yogh;it crist louede persones of hem, as weren poul and nychodeme. lorde, si&thorn; &thorn;ise newe ordris ben<NOTE PLACE="marg">John iii. [1.]</NOTE> pharisees fro cristen men, whi shulden not men by ensaumple of crist speke sharpliche a&yogh;en here synne? but in ilche werk god aski&thorn; ordre, &amp; so in blamyng of freris. <MILESTONE N="81b" UNIT="page">Two &thorn;ingis ben in &thorn;is ordre &thorn;at cristen men shulden holde; ffirst &thorn;at men &thorn;at blamen hem shulden holde treu&thorn;e &amp; not gabbe on hem; for al &yogh;if &thorn;ise ordris vsen &thorn;is craft, &yogh;it &thorn;ei don here amys, for craft of lyyng is not leueful, si&thorn; it is openliche a&yogh;en treu&thorn;e, &amp; so it is a&yogh;en crist, &thorn;e whiche is &thorn;e first treu&thorn;e. &amp; &thorn;us men may leuefulliche, but of hard, fy&yogh;te, plete &amp; scorne, but &thorn;e craft of lyyng is dampned generalliche, &amp; &thorn;us cristen men shulden be war to putte falsliche blame on freris; &amp; herfore many men speken g[e]neralliche of here synne, &amp; leuen to descende to persones lest &thorn;ei medlen fals wi&thorn; so&thorn;. &amp; &thorn;us &thorn;ei speken bi condicioun, or supposyng, or gessyng, &thorn;at &yogh;if freris don &thorn;us cristen men schulden be war wi&thorn; hem. neuer&thorn;elees we witen bi &thorn;e cours of goddis lawe &thorn;at &thorn;ise men &thorn;at ben disposid &amp; knowen defaute in certeyn persones shulden reproue hem in here beerd, but euere by mekenesse &amp; loue. &thorn;us baptist reprouede heroude of his open synne. &amp; officials and freris haunten ofte &thorn;is craft amys, when &thorn;ei louen more monee or ordris &thorn;en &thorn;ei don heel&thorn;e of here soulis, &amp; ofte &thorn;ei punysshen men bi peyne &thorn;at god approue&thorn; not. &THORN;e o&thorn;er condicioun of blamyng &thorn;at cristen men shulden holde is &thorn;at &thorn;ei shulden blame no men bi enuye or coueytyse, but algatis bi charite &thorn;at &thorn;ei hauen to god &amp; to his chirche; &yogh;he, to &thorn;o persones &thorn;at &thorn;ei snybben, al &yogh;if &thorn;ei shal be dampned aftir, &amp; &thorn;us noon man shulde curse an o&thorn;er but for loue &thorn;at he ha&thorn; to hym, as god dampneth neuer his servaunt but for mercy &amp; for loue. &amp; &thorn;us in speche a&yogh;en freris men casten to holde &thorn;ise two, and &yogh;if &thorn;ei faylen in ou&thorn;er of hem &thorn;ei cryen on god mercy &amp; help; for wo is vs &yogh;if we ben stille, &amp; speken not a&yogh;en here synnes, wenne we witen &thorn;at &thorn;ei synnen open|liche a&yogh;en bileue, &amp; leden many soulis aftir hem by wrong weye as fendis don. &amp; &thorn;us men supposen of freris &thorn;at somme 
<PB REF="00000364.tif" N="298"> of hem shal be dampned, &amp; &thorn;enne we witen bi &thorn;e gospel &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="marg">John vi. [70.]</NOTE> &thorn;ei ben quike fendis. lord, who shulde lette men to speke here as crist doi&thorn;? si&thorn; bi siche comune speche <MILESTONE N="82" UNIT="page">his lawe shulde be betere knowen, but as we witen not of &thorn;is frere whe&thorn;er he shal be dampned, so we kepen vs in oure speche &thorn;at we clepen not &thorn;is frere a fend. but a&yogh;en errours &thorn;at &thorn;ey sowen men shulden speke hertliche; &amp; bi siche reprouyngis god may turne &thorn;ise freris to goode, &amp; kepe sugetis in goddis weye, &thorn;at ellis wolden go the weye to helle. &amp; as anentis fals freris, resoun techi&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;ise ben fals, &amp; poul speki&thorn; &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="marg">[2] Cor. xi. [26.]</NOTE> perile is in fals freris. lord, whi shulden men be lettid to speke &thorn;us, si&thorn; goddis lawe sei&thorn; so? dampne &thorn;ou &thorn;is holi writ, &amp; lette &thorn;ou men to rede it, &amp; releese here oblishyng bi comune vse &thorn;at god approue&thorn;, &amp; &thorn;enne &thorn;er is som colour to blame men &thorn;at vsen &thorn;is word, but freris ben oblishid of god &amp; bi here rewele to seye &thorn;is word, &amp; as &thorn;ei seyen freris weren &thorn;enne &amp; longe bifore, &amp; somme false, what shulde lette &thorn;e holi goost to speke of fals freris bi poul.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="2" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum 2<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>&YOGH;it cristen men shulden be war in here speche a&yogh;en freris, &amp; for somme ben goode and somme euele, men shulden specifie &thorn;ise euele, &amp; not reproue good wi&thorn; euele lest &thorn;ei erreden in blamyng here bre&thorn;eren, &amp; herfore cristen men han declarid hou men shulden knowe a pseudo-frere &amp; what is good in here ordre &amp; what in here ordre is euel, as so myche of here ordre is good as is seid in goddis lawe, &amp; as myche of here ordre is euele as discordi&thorn; fro goddis lawe; but many &thorn;ingis may be wel don, &amp; &yogh;it &thorn;ei ben euele knytted to-gedre; as tyme &amp; o&thorn;er circumstaunce &thorn;at limiten peyne for a dede ben a&yogh;en &thorn;e fredom &thorn;at crist wole haue in hise lawe. &amp; &thorn;us &thorn;ise goode men of freris drawen hem fro here priuat rewelis &amp; fro here lyuyng in comune, lest it neede hem to breke goddis lawe; as somme freris procuren to be bisshopis, somme to be lystris and liue out of comunes, &amp; somme to be wi&thorn; lordis or laydis, 
<PB REF="00000365.tif" N="299"> &amp; somme freris to bi wi&thorn; bisshopis; but &thorn;at &thorn;at &thorn;ei seyn is best, as obedience to here souereyn &amp; risyng at myd-ny&yogh;t whi&thorn; kepyng of here priuat reulis &amp; sewyng of here chapitris, &thorn;ise ben warliche put abac wi&thorn; &thorn;e moost witty of freris. But &yogh;it &thorn;er ben ouer-many <MILESTONE N="82b" UNIT="page">cowordis &amp; foolis stondyng in &thorn;is fredom, si&thorn; &thorn;ey dar not reproue here comunes in kepyng of here obseruauncis, but dwellen in her naked habitis in tokene &thorn;at &thorn;ei wolen turne a&yogh;en. &amp; certis in &thorn;is is noon wisdom, but errour on many sydis; for siche kepyng of &thorn;ise habitis techi&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;ei lasten in &thorn;is synne, &amp; consenten to &thorn;e first errours, as ypocritis a&yogh;ens god. and &thorn;erfore many men wolden consele &thorn;at &thorn;ei casteden a-wey &thorn;ise habitis &amp; sich fool oblysshyng, and token fredom of cristis lawe; &amp; &thorn;us techi&thorn; ilche word of crist, &thorn;at reproue&thorn; &thorn;ise newe sectis, for here newe obseruauncis to whiche &thorn;ey oblishen hem so myche smacchen som weye ypocrisie, or ellis &thorn;ey ben superflue, and oblishen men wi&thorn;-oute chesoun a&yogh;en &thorn;e fredom of cristis lawe. &amp; herfore crist clepi&thorn; so ofte pharisees ypocritis, &amp; sey&thorn;: "ffle<NOTE PLACE="marg">Luke xii. [1.]</NOTE> &yogh;ee fro sourdou of pharisees, &thorn;at is ypocrisye, for &thorn;ei ben blaunchid wi&thorn;-oute as sepulcris, and wi&thorn;-inne ful of fyl&thorn;e. Wo be to &yogh;ou, pharisees," seyth crist, "&thorn;at ben hud monu|mentis; and men wandrynge on hem knowen not &thorn;e fil&thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="marg">Luke xi. [44.]</NOTE> wi&thorn;inne. oon of &thorn;e wyse men of lawe onsuerede to crist, and seyde &thorn;us: mayster, seyng &thorn;ise &thorn;ingis, &thorn;ou makest to vs greet strif. and crist seyde to &thorn;is man: &amp; wo to &yogh;ou, wise men of lawe, &thorn;at chargen men wi&thorn; bir&thorn;ins &thorn;at &thorn;ei may not bere, and &yogh;ee wi&thorn; &yogh;oure oon fynger touchen not &yogh;oure makid bir&thorn;ins." &amp; here men taken of cristis wordis &thorn;at men shulden not lette to speke for god, al &yogh;if &thorn;ei suffren harm for here speche; for crist tolde more sharpliche &thorn;is wo, when &thorn;is lawere hadde tolde &thorn;is perile. &amp; men may see of &thorn;e same word &thorn;at consenteris to siche ypocritis ben in &thorn;e same dampnacioun, si&thorn; crist sey&thorn;: "and to &yogh;ou be wo." Also bi &thorn;e newe lawe ben sectis ofte reproued, &amp; noon drede &thorn;ise newe ordris maken diuerse sectis, &amp; so bi oure bileue &thorn;ise ordris ben reproued. "I woot, sei&thorn; poul, &thorn;at aftir myn discess wolues of raueyn shal<NOTE PLACE="marg">Acts xx. [29.]</NOTE> 
<PB REF="00000366.tif" N="300"> come in to &thorn;e chirche, and &thorn;ei shal not spare &thorn;e floc. &amp; of &yogh;ou silf shal rise wicked men, spekynge peruerse &thorn;yngis, so &thorn;at &thorn;ei leden disciplis aftir hem. &amp; herfore wake &yogh;ee, &amp; &thorn;enke onne hou bi &thorn;re &yogh;eer ny&yogh;t &amp; day y ceessede not bi teris monestynge ilche of &yogh;ou; &amp; now y commende &yogh;ou to god and to word of <MILESTONE N="83" UNIT="page">his grace, whiche is my&yogh;ty to edifye &amp; &yogh;iue heritage in alle halewid. but siluer and gold or clo&thorn; of non of &yogh;ou coueytide I, as &yogh;ee &yogh;oure self witen, for to neede of &thorn;ingis &thorn;at i hauede and to hem &thorn;at weren wi&thorn; me ministreden &thorn;ise hondis, bi trauel &thorn;at i me self dide. alle &thorn;ise &thorn;ingis haue i shewid to &yogh;ou, for men &thorn;at trauelen &thorn;us moten take sike men &amp; helpe hem wi&thorn; siche goodis, &amp; haue mynde of &thorn;e word of &thorn;e lord ihesu, for he seyde &thorn;at it is more blissid more to &yogh;iue &thorn;en to take." &THORN;ise wordis of holi writt, si&thorn; &thorn;ei ben fey&thorn; of cristen men, ben more to preyse &thorn;en alle propre rewel of &thorn;ise newe ordris; for here autours weren lesse wor&thorn;, &amp; hauen neede &thorn;at &thorn;e pope conferme hem. for poul was betere &amp; myhtyere &thorn;en alle &thorn;e patrouns of &thorn;ise new ordris; &amp; non pope conferme&thorn; holi writt, si&thorn; it is first confermed of god. &amp; noo drede poul telli&thorn; here a rewele &thorn;at cristen men shulden holde, &amp; first men may see here hou poul prophecyede so&thorn; of comyng of &thorn;e newe sectis in-to &thorn;e chirche, bo&thorn;e oon &amp; o&thorn;er, &amp; hou &thorn;ei shal be wolues of raueyn &amp; not spare &thorn;e floc &thorn;at &thorn;ei ben inne; for what prelat or religiose spari&thorn; to pile &thorn;e comune peple, but coueyti&thorn; gold &amp; siluer &amp; clo&thorn;, fare &thorn;e peple neuere so euele. as freris when &thorn;ei beggen of men &thorn;enken not hou &thorn;ei ben rychere &thorn;en pore men &thorn;at &thorn;ei beggen of, &thorn;at hauen greet neede for hem &amp; heoris to &thorn;yng &thorn;at freris tillen of hem, and certis &thorn;is spoylyng is falsere &thorn;en open raueyn of dai &thorn;eues. But poul tau&yogh;te aftir hou he laborede, to &yogh;iue ensaumple to men aftir &thorn;at &thorn;ei shulden not bilde hem castels &amp; liue oon pore men bi beggerye. for it is bo&thorn;e needeful to men to &yogh;iue &amp; to take of here bretheren; but &thorn;e first condicioun is betere, &amp; &thorn;erfore crist &amp; poul useden it. and prelatis &thorn;at hauen cure of soulis loken hou scarsly &thorn;ei may liue, &amp; wi&thorn; hou lytil of siche almes 
<PB REF="00000367.tif" N="301"> &thorn;ei needen to charge &thorn;e peple, &amp; hou largeliche &thorn;ei &yogh;euen a&yogh;en lore and ensaumple of holynesse. &THORN;is rewle si&thorn; it is bileeue <MILESTONE N="83b" UNIT="page">shulde be studied of alle &thorn;ise sectis, &amp; not take an o&thorn;er lesse good but &yogh;if &thorn;at &thorn;is rewele faylede; &amp; herfore poul<NOTE PLACE="marg">1 Cor. i. [14] and iii.</NOTE> heriede god &thorn;at he brou&yogh;te not in siche sectis, but by clene lore &thorn;at crist tau&yogh;te poul liuede &amp; tau&yogh;te o&thorn;er. studie wyse men on &thorn;is word of poul, &amp; loke &thorn;ei ri&yogh;tliche whe&thorn;er &thorn;ise sectis ben euele &amp; wor&thorn;i to be left bi goddis lawe, &amp; to be spoken a&yogh;en sharpliche. &amp; &thorn;erfore sey&thorn; poul to conforte men, hou &thorn;ei shulden haue mynde of cristis word, &amp; hou crist shal &yogh;iue to men &thorn;at louen hym word &amp; grace to reproue hem, &amp; &thorn;is word moue&thorn; summe men to speke a&yogh;en &thorn;ise new ordris.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="3" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum 3<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>It were to wite ouer &thorn;is what goddis lawe mene&thorn; bi &thorn;ise sectis; &amp; it seme&thorn; to many men &thorn;at a secte is a newe ordre bi newe patroun &amp; newe lawe, as was &thorn;e secte of cristen men, and crist haue&thorn; ful autorite to make siche a blessid secte for hym &amp; hise &thorn;at comen aftir to &thorn;e ende of &thorn;e world. &yogh;if a cristen man haue a custom &thorn;at profiti&thorn; to hym for a tyme, but he haue&thorn; non patroun ne rewele but crist &amp; lore &thorn;at he ha&thorn; &yogh;iuen, he maki&thorn; not a newe secte o&thorn;er &thorn;en secte of cristen men. &amp; &yogh;if benet or dominic or fraunciss or bernard or angel of heuene make a newe secte upon cristis secte, he is herfore wor&thorn;i to be blamed; &amp; &thorn;is secte shulde be despisid &amp; cristis secte shulde be holde clene, as &thorn;e secte of macamethe taki&thorn; meche of cristis secte, but it varie&thorn; in som rewele &amp; in clo&thorn;is &amp; in patroun, &amp; so don sectis of oure newe ordris, &amp; of bo&thorn;e &thorn;ise prophecie&thorn; poul. Crist groundede not his secte in sich changyng of clo&thorn;is, but in rewle of vertues &thorn;at ben vnsensible to men, &amp; tolde nou&yogh;t bi siche abitis, but in as meche as &thorn;ei helpeden to vertues, &amp; &thorn;us men shulden not be weddid wi&thorn; hem, but change hem lest here loue erre. &amp; &thorn;us seyen summe &thorn;at these freris habitis to whiche freris ben &thorn;us oblishid, &thorn;at ben &thorn;us large &amp; variaunt as weren habitis of pharisees, <MILESTONE N="84" UNIT="page">seruen 
<PB REF="00000368.tif" N="302"> &thorn;e fend to putte in lesyngus &amp; to destrie pore mennus goodis. Cristis religion telli&thorn; lityl bi siche sensible habitis, but now taki&thorn; oon &amp; now an o&thorn;er, as dide crist on good fryday. for &thorn;ise habitis crien to &thorn;e folc holynesse &amp; stablenesse, &thorn;at god wole haue hid to hym, &amp; &thorn;us &thorn;ei ben ofte false signes &amp; garnementis of ypocritis, as crist clepi&thorn; ofte pharisees. And &thorn;us sei&thorn; petre in his book, &thorn;at is aboue alle &thorn;ise patrouns,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[2] Peter ii. [1.]</NOTE> So&thorn;eliche &thorn;er weren fals prophetis<NOTE PLACE="foot">propheris MS.</NOTE> in &thorn;e peple, as shal be in &yogh;ou mastris of lesyngis, &thorn;at shal brynge in sectis of loss, bo&thorn;e of religioun &amp; soul, as men mai openliche see now, &amp; &thorn;ei denyen &thorn;at lord &thorn;at ha&thorn; bou&yogh;t hem, ihesu crist. for when &thorn;ei leuen cristis secte, or louen it lasse for &thorn;ise newe sectis, &thorn;ei slaken in &thorn;is here loue to crist, &amp; &thorn;us &thorn;ei ben cursid of hym. &amp; iuge &thorn;e peple whe&thorn;er &thorn;ise sectis louen here patroun betere &thorn;en poul or o&thorn;ere seyntis, &thorn;at weren betere to-fore god &thorn;en &thorn;ise patrouns, &amp; louen lesse &thorn;e rewele of crist &amp; cristis ordynaunce for here ordris, &amp; here dedis wolen openliche shewe &thorn;at &thorn;ei don &thorn;us wi&thorn;-oute cause. whi shulden not &thorn;ise sectis be reproued? si&thorn; &thorn;ei ben &thorn;us sectis of lesyng; not of leesyng of worldliche worship ne worldliche vauntage, as we may see, but of lesyng of vertues &amp; of blisse for here vnkyndenesse. And herfore sei&thorn; petre aftir, &thorn;at &thorn;ise sectis leden vp-on hem hasty lesynge of vertues &amp; blisse bi here chargyng wi&thorn; newe ordris. who wolde seie &thorn;at he ne were a fool &thorn;at hauede a good ordre &thorn;at my&yogh;te not faile, &amp; &yogh;it bryngi&thorn; in a newe ordre &thorn;at is bo&thorn;e heuy &amp; vnperfi&yogh;t, &amp; letti&thorn; &thorn;e first parfyt ordre bo&thorn;e to be loued &amp; holden. Juge &thorn;e peple whe&thorn;er &thorn;ise freris bi here newenesse &thorn;at &thorn;ei han founden breken ofte cristis ordre, bo&thorn;e to hem &amp; to &thorn;e peple. And &thorn;us sei&thorn; petre aftir, &thorn;at many shal sewe her lecheryes,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[2 Peter ii. 2.]</NOTE> bi whom &thorn;e weye of treu&thorn;e shal be blasfemed. It is knowen &thorn;yng now &thorn;at many louen more &thorn;ise newe ordris &thorn;en &thorn;ei louen &thorn;e ordre of crist, &amp; don more worship to hem, &amp; &thorn;is is gostliche lecherie fro crist &thorn;e spouse of &thorn;e chirche, <MILESTONE N="84b" UNIT="page">&amp; &thorn;is 
<PB REF="00000369.tif" N="303"> is opone blasfemye si&thorn; roten ordinaunce of men is more worshipid &amp; more told bi &thorn;en &thorn;e ordinaunce of crist. Petre telli&thorn; aftir of &thorn;e frut &thorn;at come&thorn; of siche newe ordris: In<NOTE PLACE="marg">[2 Peter ii. 3.]</NOTE> coueytise wi&thorn; feyned wordis &thorn;ei shal chaffare of &yogh;ou. It is knowen hou &thorn;e pope wi&thorn; his court chaffari&thorn; wi&thorn; simple men in beneficis &amp; assoilyng, &amp; certis &thorn;is is a newe secte founden ouer &thorn;e secte of crist; &amp; &thorn;us chaffaren possessioners bi auarice wi&thorn; seculer men; &amp; &thorn;ise freris chaffaren now, &amp; sillen cuntrees to begge; &amp; in alle &thorn;ise wordis ben feyned of gostliche suffrage wi&thorn;-oute grounde. &thorn;us regneth chaffaryng of prestis and lewid men by auarice. But petre telli&thorn; aftir to what ende &thorn;ise sectis bryngyn men: "To &thorn;ise sectis ceessi&thorn; not &thorn;e iugement &thorn;at is now &amp; bifore tymes, &amp; here leesing nappi&thorn; not." Noo man dredi&thorn; &thorn;at haue&thorn; witt &thorn;at petre ne reprouede here &thorn;ise sectis. what cristen man shulde not speke a&yogh;en hem bi autorite of crist &amp; petre? &yogh;if petre prophecyede not &thorn;ise sectis, telle &thorn;ei what &thorn;e wordis of petre menen. And of &thorn;ise sectis speki&thorn; poul to his disciple tymothe: "&THORN;e holi gost sei&thorn; openliche &thorn;at in &thorn;e last tymes<NOTE PLACE="marg">[1] Tim. iv. [1.]</NOTE> summe shal depart fro bileeue, takynge hede to spiritis of errour &amp; to loris of fendis, &thorn;e wiche fendis speken lesyng in ypocrisie; hauynge here conscience brent wi&thorn; hoot yren of coueytise; &amp; forfenden to wedde, &amp; abstenen fro mete, &thorn;at god ha&thorn; ordeyned to trewe men to take wi&thorn; &thorn;ankyngis of god, &amp; to hem &thorn;at han knowe trew&thorn;e." Here ilche man on goddis half shulde trowe &thorn;ise wordis of poul, si&thorn; god sey&thorn; hem openliche to hym. &amp; &thorn;us it seme&thorn; &thorn;at poul wolde mene &thorn;at in tymes of &thorn;ise ordris men departen fro bileeue &thorn;at &thorn;ei shulden haue of cristis ordre, &amp; many taken ouer-meche hede to gostliche men of &thorn;ise ordris, &thorn;at erren as ypocritis &amp; magnifien here owen ordris. &amp; non drede siche seniours ben fendis &thorn;at speken lying in ypocrisie, &amp; &thorn;ei hauen here conscience brent wi&thorn; fier of coueytise, for al &thorn;at &thorn;ei may gete to here ordre, of men or of worldliche goodis, &thorn;ei &thorn;enken &thorn;ei geten newe to god, &thorn;at god is wel payed &thorn;erwi&thorn;, &amp; &thorn;us &thorn;ise ypocritis <MILESTONE N="85" UNIT="page">letten to wedde bo&thorn;e of prestis &amp; of nunnes, &amp; bi 
<PB REF="00000370.tif" N="304"> &thorn;is &thorn;ei fallen in foul leccherie, leuyng &thorn;at &thorn;at god ha&thorn; grauntid; &amp; &thorn;us &thorn;ise freris forberen fleshe &thorn;at crist vsede &amp; grauntede to ete. &amp; &thorn;us &thorn;es newe obseruauncis don harm to &thorn;e chirche many weyes. &amp; &thorn;is applie&thorn; poul to sectis &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="marg">[2] Tim. iii. [5.]</NOTE> hauen licnesse of pitee, but &thorn;ei denyen &thorn;e vertu &thorn;er-of; for &thorn;ei hauen non conscience to robbe pore men to magnifie here new ordris, &amp; to fordo cristis ordinaunce; but hou deneyen not &thorn;ise men &thorn;e vertu of pitee to god and man?</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="4" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum 4<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>See we what James sei&thorn; &thorn;at wroot to tuelue kynredis, &amp; so to alle cristen men, whe&thorn;er he speke ouht of freris. but &yogh;if god spake here of freris, certis &thorn;ei ben not wi&thorn; hym, &amp; crist sei&thorn;: "who &thorn;at is not wi&thorn; me, he mot neede be a&yogh;en me."<NOTE PLACE="marg">Matt. xii. [30.]</NOTE> Jamus telli&thorn; of two religions; &thorn;e first is clene wit-oute wem,<NOTE PLACE="marg">James i. [27.]</NOTE> &amp; &thorn;is mot nede be cristis religioun, bo&thorn;e for &thorn;e patroun &amp; &thorn;e rewele; &thorn;e secounde is veyn religioun, &amp; &thorn;at haue&thorn; o&thorn;er patroun and rewele. James sei&thorn; &thorn;at clene religioun &amp; wi&thorn;oute wem bifore god &amp; &thorn;e fader is &thorn;is, to visite moderlees children &amp; widewis in here tribulacion, &amp; kepe hym silf wi&thorn;|oute wem fro foulyng of &thorn;is world. James speki&thorn; not heere of &thorn;e ordris &thorn;at holden here castels or liuen as ankeris, but of &thorn;e religioun &thorn;at crist ha&thorn; ordeyned to fi&yogh;te wi&thorn; &thorn;e world &amp; profite to needi men, as crist dide wi&thorn; hise apostlis. And &yogh;if &thorn;ou seie &thorn;at freris visiten modirlees children &amp; widewis; so&thorn;eliche &thorn;e fend visiti&thorn; men, but to deceyue hem &amp; harme hem; &amp; &thorn;us &thorn;ise freris visiten men, but riche men in heere welfare. And cristis ordre biddi&thorn; men to kepe hem vnfoulid fro &thorn;e world, but freris seldem or neuere but when coueytise fouli&thorn; hem; for when &thorn;ei visiten pore men or widewis, &thorn;ei don to gete goodus of hem, as corn, monee, chese or som-what &thorn;at nedi&thorn; more hem &thorn;en &thorn;e freris; &amp; &thorn;us &thorn;ei helpen hem not in tribulacioun, but to deceyue here bodi &amp; soule. &amp; herfore<NOTE PLACE="marg">James iii. 15.</NOTE> sey&thorn; iames aftir, &thorn;at rewle or wisdom of &thorn;ise ordris is worldliche, beestliche, &amp; fendliche, &amp; &thorn;is is veyn religioun. 
<PB REF="00000371.tif" N="305"> &THORN;e rewele is first worldliche, <MILESTONE N="85b" UNIT="page">for &thorn;ei ben ouercomen of &thorn;e world, &amp; speche of men plesi&thorn; hem not but &yogh;if it turne hem to worldis vynnyng, &amp; sich a rewele mot neede ouercome &thorn;e flesh of siche freris, for &thorn;ei seken lust as bestis, &amp; coueyten likyngis of flesh. &amp; &thorn;is rewele is &thorn;e deuelis; as &thorn;e deuel is here patroun in &thorn;is, "&amp; &thorn;ere," sei&thorn; James, "is enuye &amp; strif where sich a veyn religion regne&thorn;." But &thorn;e rewele of clene religioun haue&thorn; ey&yogh;t condiciouns &thorn;at iames telli&thorn;. "ffirst it is<NOTE PLACE="marg">James iii. [17.]</NOTE> chast, pesible, temperat, tretable;<NOTE PLACE="foot">tretatable MS.</NOTE> assentyng to goode &thorn;ingis, &thorn;er-wi&thorn; ful of mercy, ful of goode fruytis, &amp; iugi&thorn; wi&thorn;-oute feynyng." Juge wise men whe&thorn;er &thorn;ise ey&yogh;te ben kept in &thorn;e ordris of freris. Bodiliche chastite is ofte broken, but oftere chastite of soule; ffreris fi&yogh;ten in mong hem silf, &amp; helpen to fi&yogh;te a&yogh;en reeaumus; ffreris hauen a newe maner in alle &thorn;e dedis &thorn;at &thorn;ei don heere, but &thorn;e old maner was ful good &thorn;at crist &yogh;af to hise disciplis. &THORN;e apostlis weren so tretable, &thorn;at &yogh;if men tau&yogh;ten hem a betere ordre or &thorn;at ou&yogh;t of here bileeue were fals, &thorn;ei wolden sone assente to treu&thorn;e; but &thorn;is &thorn;ing my&yogh;te not be, for stablenesse of here patroun. ffreris mai be pleynliche conuict bo&thorn;e of here ordre &amp; heere treu&thorn;e, &amp; &yogh;it heere pride letti&thorn; hem to assente<NOTE PLACE="foot">assento MS.</NOTE> to &thorn;is treu&thorn;e, bo&thorn;e of here ordris &amp; heere opiniouns; but &thorn;ei seken mannes help &amp; fals dilayes to lette knowyng of treu&thorn;e, &amp; &thorn;us &thorn;ei consenten not to good, but bi heere power striuen a&yogh;en it. And when &thorn;ei spoylen pore men, &thorn;ei ben not ful of mercy, but louen betere stones of heere housis &thorn;en pore men or o&thorn;ere freris. Hem wanti&thorn; good fruyt, when &thorn;ei pursewen trewe prestis bi gabbyngis &amp; bi gylis for &thorn;ei prechen freliche &thorn;e gospel. fflateryng &thorn;at &thorn;ise men vsen telli&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;ei iugen not wi&thorn;-outen feynyng. &THORN;is is &thorn;e veyn religioun &thorn;at James speki&thorn; of; "for who euere wene&thorn; &thorn;at he be religiose, &amp; refrene&thorn; not his tunge, but deceyue&thorn; his herte, &thorn;is mannes religion is veyn."<NOTE PLACE="marg">[James i. 26.]</NOTE> &THORN;ise freris ben doumbe in many placis when <MILESTONE N="86" UNIT="page">&thorn;ei shulde speke to heere bretheren of &thorn;e treu&thorn;e of goddis lawe &amp; o&thorn;ere weyes &thorn;at helpen to vertues; but when &thorn;ei comen out of &thorn;is prisoun 
<PB REF="00000372.tif" N="306"> &thorn;ei ben dilauy in heere tungis in gabbyngis &amp; other iapis &thorn;at sounen not to charite: Juge men whe&thorn;er ony freris ben siche &thorn;at hauen sich veyn religion. James telli&thorn; aftir bi cristis<NOTE PLACE="marg">[James ii. 9.]</NOTE> rewele &thorn;at men shulden not accepte persones; but men seyen &thorn;at freris don, bo&thorn;e of here bre&thorn;eren &amp; o&thorn;er men, for &yogh;if a frere be a maister or a riche frere in mong hise bre&thorn;eren, he shal be loutid &amp; worshipid more &thorn;en cristis lawe techi&thorn;; &amp; &thorn;us freris worshipen seculer lordis, to gete worldliche help of hem. &amp; &thorn;us freris speken bi goddis lawe, but &thorn;ei don euen &thorn;e reuers, as crist sei&thorn; of pharisees, &thorn;at &thorn;ei seyen but &thorn;ei don not. &THORN;us freris reden in goddis lawe, &thorn;at &thorn;ei shal not be makid maystris, &amp; &thorn;is &thorn;ei coueyten wi&thorn; &thorn;e synne, wherfore &thorn;is maystirship is forfendid. &amp; &thorn;us iames forbedi&thorn; cristen<NOTE PLACE="marg">James v. [1-3.]</NOTE> men to be riche here, for rust &amp; wormes destrien heere richesse, &amp; &thorn;at doi&thorn; harm to &thorn;e comunes; but &yogh;it &thorn;ise freris gederen monee &amp; o&thorn;er goodis to hem self, &amp; ben propre in heere hauyng a&yogh;en &thorn;e rewle of charite, &amp; but &yogh;if &thorn;ise wordis of iames don for &thorn;ise ordris, I am certeyn &thorn;at non word of iames approue&thorn; &thorn;ise newe religions.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="5" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum 5<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>Se we ouer &thorn;is what iude sei&thorn; of apostataes of &thorn;ise ordris, hou &thorn;ei weren first punyshid of god in tyme of &thorn;e old lawe. for cristis religioun lasti&thorn; euer, bo&thorn;e to &thorn;e dai of dom &amp; aftir, &amp; alle &thorn;ise newe religiouns moten haue ende &thorn;enne or bifore. Jude sei&thorn; &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="marg">Jude 12.</NOTE> &thorn;ise apostataas ben in heere metis fil&thorn;is, &thorn;at feeden men wi&thorn;-oute drede, feedynge hem self; &amp; &thorn;us freris, for heere metis &thorn;at &thorn;ei hauen of lordis &amp; bishopis, feeden heere soulis a&yogh;en bi fablis, &amp; ben a-boute to hyde heere synnes, but certis largenesse of heere abitis hydi&thorn; not synnes fro god. &THORN;ei mai blynde men for a tyme bi here feyned absolucions, but whenne men shal rekene bifore crist in day of his last iugement, &thorn;ere &thorn;ise habitis shal be a weye,<MILESTONE N="86b" UNIT="page"> &thorn;ise rewelis &amp; &thorn;ise religiouns, &amp; religion of cristis lawe shal shyne &thorn;en-ne for kepyng &thorn;er-of; for ypocritis shal be depperst dampned of alle &thorn;e fendis &thorn;at shal be in helle. Jude sey&thorn; 
<PB REF="00000373.tif" N="307"> aftir, &thorn;at &thorn;ise men ben cloudis wi&thorn;-oute watir, &thorn;at ben boren aboute wi&thorn; wyndis; &amp; &thorn;is a-cordi&thorn; to fals prestis, for philosophris seyn bi resoun &thorn;at it is eir of pestilence when it seme&thorn; to reyne &amp; reyne&thorn; not, as it falli&thorn; bi siche cloudis, for &thorn;ei letten &thorn;e li&yogh;t of heuene &amp; temperen not &thorn;e er&thorn;e bi reyn. &amp; &thorn;us it falli&thorn; gostliche bi men &thorn;at shulden preche goddis lawe, &amp; letten to teche &thorn;is lawe, &amp; occupien siche prelatis state bi gabbyng &amp; fagyngis, &amp; not bi reyn of goddis word; &amp; &thorn;is is a perilose tyme of pestilence of mannes soule. Jude sei&thorn; aftir &thorn;at &thorn;ise ben heruest trees wi&thorn;oute fruyt, twyes deed, &amp; &thorn;e rootis ben drawen up; &amp; &thorn;us &thorn;ei ben hydous trees. &THORN;is word shulde be dred of prelatis, si&thorn; &thorn;ei ben trees in &thorn;is world; &amp; &thorn;ei shulden bere gostliche fruyt as don o&thorn;er trees in heruest, but &thorn;ei ben wi&thorn;oute fruyt, as was &thorn;e fyge tree &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="marg">Mat. xxi. [19.]</NOTE> crist cursede, for ne&thorn;er in prechyng ne good lyf &thorn;ei profiten to &thorn;e peplis soule. And &thorn;us &thorn;ei ben twyes dede, deed body &amp; soule, deed in &thorn;is world &amp; in &thorn;e o&thorn;er, deed in heere owen persone, deed in profityng to o&thorn;er men. And heere rootis ben turned up; for here loue shulde be hid, &amp; bi growyng of &thorn;is roote &thorn;ei shulden profite to mennes soulis; but &yogh;if heere loue be ficchid on worldliche &thorn;ingis more &thorn;en on heuenliche &thorn;ingis, &thorn;e rote is turned up, &amp; &thorn;ei ben drye, wi&thorn;oute fruyt. Whe&thorn;er &thorn;at freris or o&thorn;ere men failen &thorn;us in heere office, iude prophecyde of hem, al &yogh;if &thorn;ey weren not in his tyme; for as petre sei&thorn;, "cristis apostlis haueden clere spirit to prophecie."<NOTE PLACE="marg">[2 Peter i. 19(?)]</NOTE> And &thorn;ise men ben boren aboute bi wyndis of vnstablenesse, &amp; heyhid to grete statis, now here &amp; now &thorn;ere, for hem wanti&thorn; &thorn;e rote of loue &thorn;at shulde be picchid in goddis lawe, &amp; &thorn;us wyndus mouen not &thorn;ise trees to growe stableliche in &thorn;e chirche. Jude sei&thorn; aftir, &thorn;at &thorn;ise ben flodis of &thorn;e wood see, &thorn;at fro&thorn;en heere owen confucions. <MILESTONE N="87" UNIT="page">It is knowen &thorn;at holi chirche is a ship in &thorn;e see, &amp; &thorn;ing &thorn;at moost noye&thorn; &thorn;is ship ben felle flodis of &thorn;is world; &amp; &yogh;if freris hauen &thorn;ise two, noo drede, god vndirstood hem here, &amp; &yogh;if &thorn;ei fro&thorn;en bi irose fisege a&yogh;en men &thorn;at tellen hem treu&thorn;e, noo drede &thorn;ei fro&thorn;en heere owen confusion, &amp; maken heere malice more knowen. &amp; but 
<PB REF="00000374.tif" N="308"> &yogh;if iude spak here of freris he spak in noo place of &thorn;ise sectis. Lord, si&thorn; crist &amp; hise apostlis spaken sharpliche a&yogh;ens mennes synnes, &amp; &thorn;ei bidden &thorn;at we shulden sewe hem, whi shulden we not so speke aftir? &YOGH;if a man be in despeyer of malice of &thorn;is wood see or &thorn;at men shal be helpid fro it, &thorn;enne is it noo boote hym to speke a&yogh;en; but men hopen bi goddis grace wi&thorn; sich sharp speche &amp; trewe, &thorn;at somme freris shal be amendid, &amp; &thorn;e peple shal knowe hem betere. And &thorn;us sei&thorn; Jude aftir, &thorn;at &thorn;ise men ben erryng sterris, to whom &thorn;e tempest of derkenesse is kept wi&thorn;outen ende. It is knowen bi philoso|phris &thorn;at &thorn;e sterre herid or beerdid erri&thorn; fro heuene in his mouyng, &amp; bitokene&thorn; pestilence, &amp; so it is of wickid prestis &thorn;at erren fro kepyng of goddis lawe. &amp; &thorn;us &yogh;if freris wolen excuse hem &thorn;at iude speki&thorn; not of hem, &thorn;ei moten excuse hem first &thorn;at &thorn;ei liuen not wickidliche, for euere men weren holden bi goddis lawe to speke a&yogh;en goddis aduersaries. And herfore sei&thorn; iude aftir, &thorn;at "enoc &thorn;e seuen&thorn;e persone fro adam prophecied of siche wickid men: lo, god come&thorn; in hise &thorn;ousynd seyntis to make iugement a&yogh;en alle wickid, &amp; to reproue alle wickid men of al &thorn;e werkis of heere wickidnesse in whiche &thorn;ei diden wickidliche; &amp; of alle hard &thorn;yngis bi whiche wickid men han spoken a&yogh;en god." Men moten o&thorn;er denye god, or seye &thorn;at fro &thorn;e bigynnyng of &thorn;e world it was leueful to reproue wickid men. Whi shulden not men reproue siche freris? si&thorn; god ha&thorn; ordeyned many &thorn;ousynd to mayn|tene his cause a&yogh;en &thorn;e fend. And herfore sey&thorn; iude aftir, hou men shal knowe siche pseudoes. "&THORN;ise ben gruccheris, ful of pleynt, wandringe oftir heere desyris, &amp; here mou&thorn; speki&thorn; pride, makinge <MILESTONE N="87b" UNIT="page">persones wondirful bi cause of here wynnyng." &YOGH;if freris ben not spoken of here &thorn;ei moten liue &thorn;us iustliche, &thorn;at &thorn;ei grucche not a&yogh;en here pouerte bi &thorn;e criyng of here beggyngis. And &yogh;if alle heere clo&thorn;is tellen to men &thorn;at &thorn;ei ben needi beggers, &amp; &thorn;ei wolen take of pore &amp; riche al maner of godis &thorn;at &thorn;ei mai gete, &thorn;enne &thorn;ei ben fals &amp; ful of playnt of &thorn;e pouerte &thorn;at &thorn;ei han chosen. And &yogh;if freris after &thorn;is feyned pouerte wandren in reumes aftir here 
<PB REF="00000375.tif" N="309"> lustis, &amp; chesen to ete wi&thorn; riche men where &thorn;ei may fare lustfulliche, &amp; haue heere daliaunce wi&thorn; wymmen for here leccherose lyues; who dredi&thorn; &thorn;at god ne spak here bi iude of &thorn;ise freris? And &yogh;if &thorn;ei speken proudliche to men of heere ordris &amp; of here persones; hou &thorn;ei passen o&thorn;ere ordris &amp; o&thorn;er persones bifore hem in holynesse &amp; in witt; &amp; &thorn;us glosen persones wondirful, bo&thorn;e of heere ordris &amp; wi&thorn;-oute, bi cause of heere wynnyng, who dredi&thorn; &thorn;at god ne spak here of siche freris &thorn;at don &thorn;us? And iude moue&thorn; cristen men aftir to be war &amp; reproue siche men: "But &yogh;ee, ful dere bre&thorn;eren, haue mynde of &thorn;e wordis &thorn;at weren seyd byfore of &thorn;e apostlis of oure lord ihesu crist, &thorn;at han seyd to &yogh;ou, &thorn;at in &thorn;e laste tymes shal come gilours wandring aftir heere desyris, not in good religion. &THORN;ise ben &thorn;ei &thorn;at departen hem silf bestial, &amp; hauen not &thorn;e holy goost." Juge men whe&thorn;er freris ben siche; &amp; certis &thorn;enne god spak here of hem, for god woot al &thorn;ing &thorn;at is to come, &amp; warne&thorn; his chirche of perilis of it. &YOGH;if &thorn;ise freris ben gylours bo&thorn;e of men &amp; of children, bi &thorn;e holynesse &thorn;at &thorn;ei biheeten to robbe men of heere goodis, &amp; wandren in cuntrees aftir heere desyris, to placis &amp; persones where &thorn;ei hopen to fare aftir lustis of heere flesh, &thorn;enne god spak heere of freris. And &yogh;if freris departen heere duellyng fro o&thorn;ere men, bo&thorn;e lerid &amp; lewid, &amp; wandren not as crist or hise apostlis, more to edifie &thorn;e peple &thorn;en for lust or worldliche wynnyng, &thorn;enne god spak here of hem. liue &thorn;e freris bi goddis lawe &amp; teche &thorn;ei men &thorn;at &thorn;ei ben not siche.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="6" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum 6<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P><MILESTONE N="88" UNIT="page">Jon euaungelist spak sharpliche of &thorn;is matere, bo&thorn;e in epistel of his wisdom &amp; in his book of priuetees; but for he speki&thorn; &thorn;ere mystiliche, &amp; fewe wolen &thorn;ere approue his sentence,<NOTE PLACE="foot">setence MS.</NOTE> &thorn;erfore leue we &thorn;is book, &amp; speke we a word of hise epistlis. Ion sei&thorn; in his book hou alle men shulden kepe charite, &amp; so men shulden 
<PB REF="00000376.tif" N="310"> loue &thorn;ingis aftir &thorn;at &thorn;ei ben goode. But here &thorn;enken somme &thorn;at freris failen openliche, for bi graunte of hem self o&thorn;ere ordris ben betere &thorn;en heeren, &amp; &yogh;it &thorn;ei louen more here owen &thorn;en &thorn;ei don &thorn;e betere ordris. as &yogh;if men askeden of &thorn;ise foure sectis whe&thorn;er alle &thorn;ise ordris ben euene goode, &thorn;ei wolen seye anon: "nay, but oon is betere &thorn;en an o&thorn;er;" &amp; &thorn;us bi here owen speche &thorn;ey tellen &thorn;at &thorn;ey leuen &thorn;e betere and louen persones of here ordre not euene aftir &thorn;at &thorn;ei ben goode, &amp; so &thorn;is diuision of freris bi &thorn;ise ordris &thorn;at ben not groundid maki&thorn; a priuee enuye and putti&thorn; out loue of god; but certis &thorn;enne &thorn;ei ben mansleers &amp; of &thorn;e fendis religion, for ion sei&thorn; &thorn;at ilche<NOTE PLACE="marg">[1] John iii. [15.]</NOTE> man &thorn;at hati&thorn; his bro&thorn;er is mansleer. &amp; &thorn;us it seme&thorn; of heere lyues, &thorn;at many of hem ben irreguler; &amp; &thorn;us in trauel of &thorn;ise freris, When &thorn;ei wandren aboute to preche, it seme&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;ei louen more worldliche goodis &thorn;en heel&thorn;e of soulis &thorn;at &thorn;ei visiten; &amp; who dredi&thorn; &thorn;at siche ordris ne ben brou&yogh;t in bi &thorn;e fend? &thorn;ei leuen to proue bi goddis lawe hey&yogh;nesse of &thorn;ingis &thorn;at &thorn;ei preysen so; but bi talis byne&thorn;e bileeue, &amp; bi bull of &thorn;e pope &thorn;ei prouen hey&yogh;nesse of heere patroun &amp; holynesse of here ordre. &amp; &thorn;us sei&thorn; ion so&thorn;eliche &thorn;at &thorn;er ben now many<NOTE PLACE="marg">[1] John ii. [18.]</NOTE> makid anticristis; for alle &thorn;ise men &thorn;at ben a&yogh;en crist in here loue, &thorn;ei louen not moost crist of alle &thorn;ingis &thorn;at ben. but &thorn;ise men louedon more crist, &yogh;if &thorn;ei haueden oonliche crist here patroun; for vnordynel love of here patroun departi&thorn; hem fro hool loue of crist; &amp; &thorn;us &thorn;ei hauen not god here fadir, but somme patroun byne&thorn;e god; &amp; &thorn;enne &thorn;ei ben anticristis and fendis children, as ion sey&thorn;. &amp; &thorn;us sei&thorn; ion,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[1 John iv. 3.]</NOTE> &thorn;at ilche spirit &thorn;at lousi&thorn; ihesu is not of god <MILESTONE N="88b" UNIT="page"> but antecrist, &amp; &thorn;us &thorn;er ben pseudo-prophetis now in &thorn;is laste hour brou&yogh;t in. Men may louse ihesu crist on many maneres a&yogh;ens god, as he &thorn;at trowi&thorn; not of crist &thorn;at he is bo&thorn;e god &amp; man, but trowi&thorn; &thorn;e oon not &thorn;e other, lousi&thorn; crist a&yogh;en bileue. and &thorn;ise men lousen crist &thorn;at maken hise membris heere special patrouns, &amp; leuen to haue crist oonliche heere patroun, werbi &thorn;ei louen lasse crist. &amp; &thorn;ise men lousen crist &thorn;at, bi heere prechyng or heere lif, maken &thorn;at crist is vnstableliche in mennes hertis 
<PB REF="00000377.tif" N="311"> where he was bifore. &amp; bo&thorn;e freris and o&thorn;er prestis lousen crist on many maneres, &amp; &thorn;us men hauen of holy writ &thorn;e names &thorn;at &thorn;ei putten oon freris. Ion telli&thorn; in his secunde epistle hou men shulden leue siche antecristis, &amp; not receyue hem in-to heere housis ne greete hem in &thorn;e weie; &amp; in mong alle &thorn;e remedies &thorn;at god spak a&yogh;en siche men, &thorn;is is a special remedie of god, to which ilche man is holdon. for ion sei&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="marg">2 John [11.]</NOTE> &thorn;at what man sei&thorn; heyl to siche antecristis shal haue part of heere werkis for assent &thorn;at he &yogh;iue&thorn;. &amp; meche more &yogh;if a man norisshe hem wi&thorn; hise goodis, or defende hem in worde &amp; dede, for &thorn;enne he defendi&thorn; cristis enmyes; &amp; certis bi lawe &thorn;at men vsen &thorn;enne he is traitour to crist; &amp; &thorn;is perile shulden men flee more &thorn;en perele of mannes lawe. &amp; herfore biddi&thorn; ion &thorn;at "men shulden assaye siche priuee men, whe&thorn;er<NOTE PLACE="marg">1 John iv. [1.]</NOTE> &thorn;ei ben on goddis side," for mony siche ben antecristis. &amp; bi certeyn rewele of ion, &yogh;if ony siche louse crist, he is &thorn;at ilke &thorn;at men shulden fle, bo&thorn;e in speche &amp; in lyf. &amp; &thorn;us &yogh;if it were wel studied ouer, mony of &thorn;ise newe ordris shulden be &thorn;us fled as antecristis for diuision &thorn;at &thorn;ei maken; &amp; &thorn;us bi alle &thorn;e autours &thorn;at ben in &thorn;e newe lawe men shulden speke &thorn;us a&yogh;en freris, when &thorn;ei don &thorn;us a&yogh;en crist. &amp; it were al oon to men to lette &thorn;is in word or dede &amp; to destrie bileeue &thorn;at god ha&thorn; &yogh;iuen in &thorn;e newe lawe. but as it is seyd bifore men shulden kepe hem in goddis boundis &amp; kepe treu&thorn;e &amp; good entent; &amp; &thorn;us for charite of &thorn;e chirche &amp; of freris speke &thorn;ise wordis; <MILESTONE N="89" UNIT="page"> &amp; certis &thorn;ise wordis ben so&thorn;e, &amp; ilche man shulde graunte hem. But oon errour is in &thorn;is matere when freris continuen in heere synne, &amp; iugen to what entent o&thorn;er men seien &thorn;ise treu&thorn;is to hem. But here &thorn;ise wordis ben suspect for many resouns of goddis lawe. It is propre to god to iuge entent &thorn;at man haue&thorn;; what fendis ben &thorn;ei &thorn;at taken on hem to what entent a man speki&thorn;. Certis alle &thorn;e fendis in helle kunnen not see a mannes entent, &amp; men shulden not in &thorn;is hye hem aboue fendis but &yogh;if god hadde beden hem &thorn;is. &amp; &thorn;us men shewen hem nakid of resoun; when &thorn;at noon of hem kan proue &thorn;at &thorn;is sentence &thorn;at men seyen is fals bi goddis 
<PB REF="00000378.tif" N="312"> lawe, but trewe &amp; sewynge of bileue, &thorn;ey shewen ferrere hou &thorn;ei ben disciplis of fals pharisees, &thorn;e whiche haueden &thorn;is maner when &thorn;ei my&yogh;ten not denye cristis dedis, &thorn;at &thorn;ei ne weren goode in hem self &amp; ful of myraclis &amp; grace of god, &thorn;ei depraueden &thorn;e maner of doyng, &amp; &thorn;us crist in hise dedis. &THORN;ei seyden som tyme &thorn;at crist was not on goddis syde, but wi&thorn; &thorn;e fend, for he kepte not his haliday in doyng of siche myraclis. Othere seyden &thorn;at crist dide &thorn;ise wondris in &thorn;e vertu of beelzebub. &amp; &thorn;us &thorn;ei casteden to depraue crist when &thorn;ei my&yogh;ten not forsake &thorn;e treu&thorn;e; &amp; &thorn;us &thorn;ei shewen hem luciferis children &thorn;at wolen not amende hem self, but studien hou &thorn;ei may depraue men &thorn;at tellen hem treu&thorn;e to here good.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="7" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum 7<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>Bvt here grucchen &thorn;e fendis clerkis &thorn;at &thorn;us accusen men, &amp; seyn &thorn;at &thorn;ei ben clene of &thorn;is. But we ben coupable in &thorn;is synne; for we maken vs euene wi&thorn; crist, &amp; trowen oure wordis as we weren god, &amp; forsaken &thorn;at we erren in entent as seyntis in heuene, but oure dedis &amp; oure lif shewen openliche &thorn;e con|trarie. Here we graunten mekeliche &thorn;at in &thorn;is &amp; al oure lif here we erren ofte &amp; faylen in &thorn;e hey&yogh;nesse of charite, &amp; her|fore we weylen here &thorn;at we synnen &thorn;us in &thorn;is lif. &amp; &thorn;us we wolen not be euene wi&thorn; crist, but trow &thorn;at <MILESTONE N="89b" UNIT="page">we ben hise synneful seruauntis, &amp; in vertu &amp; worschip of hym we seyen &thorn;e trew&thorn;e &thorn;at he ha&thorn; tau&yogh;t; &amp; ofte we erren in entent &amp; desyren veniaunce in rancour, but we ben war &thorn;at we seyn so&thorn; &amp; profitable to cristis chirche; &amp; when &thorn;at god &yogh;iue&thorn; vs grace we leuen errour of &thorn;is entent, &amp; witen &thorn;at we shulden not leue here for crepyng in of siche synnes, si&thorn; we shulden synne more leuynge to speke sharpliche &thorn;is. &amp; &thorn;us bi process of tyme we trowen &thorn;at god wole clenese oure entent, &amp; &thorn;us when we ben in quiete we don &thorn;is moost for goddis worship, &amp; also for profit of his chirche, &amp; for good &thorn;at freris mai haue. Wel we witen of oure bileeue &thorn;at we shulden sewe crist, but he reprouede men sharpliche &thorn;at diden &thorn;us a&yogh;en god; whi 
<PB REF="00000379.tif" N="313"> shulden not we do so, si&thorn; we graunten vs cristis disciplis? Petre &yogh;af consel to crist &thorn;at he shulde not &thorn;us suffre dee&thorn;, as<NOTE PLACE="marg">Mat. xvi. [22, 23.]</NOTE> crist tolde bifore &thorn;at he wolde; but crist seyde a&yogh;en to petre, for charite &thorn;at he hauede to hym: "Go bihynde me, Sathanas; for &thorn;ou sauerist not &thorn;e treu&thorn;e of god." Here may we see openliche hou crist lettede not for loue of petre to reproue hym sharpliche; whi may not men do so to freris, &yogh;if &thorn;ei trespassen more openliche &amp; to more harm of cristis chirche. Also we may see in &thorn;ise wordis hou we ben holden to sewe crist, &amp; to suffre peynes of oure body for more good of oure soule, &amp; herfore bad crist petre here: "go aftir me Sathanas." Men &thorn;at wolen aboue cristis lore not sewe hym but go bifore ben sathanas, as petre was, but crist reprouede &thorn;is in petre.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Matt. vii. [15.]</NOTE> also crist telli&thorn; &thorn;at "men shulden fle fro fals prophetis," &amp; telli&thorn; two condicions bi whiche men shulden knowe hem; ffirst "&thorn;ei comen in clo&thorn;is of sheep," for ypocritis bigilen men bi &thorn;is. Aftir "&thorn;ei ben wolues of raueyn," si&thorn; for worldliche goodis &thorn;ei feynen holynesse. &amp; crist sey&thorn; aftir hou men shal knowe hem bi &thorn;e fruytis &thorn;at comen of hem. &YOGH;if freris shewen bi here dedis &thorn;at &thorn;ei ben siche fals prophetis, <MILESTONE N="90" UNIT="page"> &amp; cristis chirche be harmed by hem, whi shulden not men teche here gylis? bo&thorn;e for loue of cristen men, &amp; for loue of &thorn;e freris; si&thorn; crist biddi&thorn;, &thorn;at "&yogh;if &thorn;in brother synne&thorn; in &thorn;ee, &thorn;ou shalt snybbe hym." Othere we moten forsake crist, or telle here sharpliche<NOTE PLACE="marg">Matt. xviii. [15.]</NOTE> as he ha&thorn; tau&yogh;t. &amp; &thorn;us we reden &thorn;at crist aftir &thorn;at he was risen fro deed reprouede sharpliche hise disciplis for here defaute in bileeue: "O foolis, &amp; slow to trowe in &thorn;ingis &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="marg">Luke xxiv. [25.]</NOTE> prophetis han seyd ofte." Lord, si&thorn; crist reprouede &thorn;us hise disciplis for loue of hem, and clepede hem foolis &amp; slow to trowe, why may not men bi lore of crist reproue more foolis for more perile? &amp; &thorn;is men shulden do sharpliche, for softe wordis mouen not &thorn;ise men. And marc telli&thorn; &thorn;at crist spak<NOTE PLACE="marg">Mark iii. [21.]</NOTE> so sharpliche &thorn;at somme of hise disciplis seyden &thorn;at crist bi hise dedis was turned in-to woodnesse, &amp; &thorn;us many men for sich slow&thorn;e of sharp reprouyng synnen meche, for sharp wordis byten ofte where soft speche shulde not moue; &amp; &thorn;us 
<PB REF="00000380.tif" N="314"> men seyen &thorn;at hely &thorn;e hey&yogh; prest was dampned, for he re|proued<NOTE PLACE="marg">1 Sam. iii. 13.</NOTE> hise sones but to softliche &amp; slowliche; &amp; in &thorn;is synnen mony men, &amp; herfore freris shulden loke whe&thorn;er &thorn;ei ben coupable in &thorn;is synne, &amp; amende hem sone &thorn;erof, &amp; iuge not by facis of men, for crist biddi&thorn;: "Ne wole &yogh;ee iuge<NOTE PLACE="marg">John vii. [24.]</NOTE> aftir &thorn;e face, but iuge &yogh;ee iust iugement of &thorn;ingis &thorn;at &yogh;ee knowen wel." &amp; herfore sei&thorn; ysaie: "Wo is me for I heelde<NOTE PLACE="marg">Isaiah vi. [5.]</NOTE> myn pees." and god sey&thorn; to ezechiel, "si&thorn; he ha&thorn; &yogh;iuen hym<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Ezekiel iii. 18.]</NOTE> offys &amp; wit, but &yogh;if he telle men peril &amp; synne he shal be dampned for &thorn;is synne." &amp; &thorn;is moue&thorn; somme men; si&thorn; god<NOTE PLACE="foot">ha&thorn; probably omitted.</NOTE> &yogh;iuen hem witt &amp; power, lest &thorn;ey disusen &yogh;ift of god, &thorn;ei vsen it when nede is; &amp; &thorn;us sei&thorn; poul: "Wo is me &yogh;if i preche<NOTE PLACE="marg">1 Cor. ix. [16.]</NOTE> not," &amp; telle &thorn;e peple heere synnes. &amp; herfore god biddi&thorn; his prophete to telle his peple heere foule synnes. &amp; &thorn;us sei&thorn; poul to tite, &thorn;e bisshop, "reproue &thorn;ou wi&thorn; al comaundement,"<NOTE PLACE="marg">Tytus 3<SUP>o</SUP>. [should be ii. 15.]</NOTE> &amp; poul biddi&thorn; tymothe to reproue, to preie &amp; to blame, <MILESTONE N="90b" UNIT="page">but<NOTE PLACE="marg">2 Tim. iv. [2.]</NOTE> couenabliche &amp; wi&thorn;oute ceesyng. poul biddi&thorn; hym reproue men, &amp; &thorn;us men shulden not blame herfore, but &yogh;if &thorn;ei fordiden goddis lawe, &amp; excuseden men at domes day of reprof &thorn;at god wole &yogh;iue; but &thorn;is blasfemye dar not freris seye; &amp; herfor men wolen trowe goddis lawe. Tuo sectis &thorn;er ben, &amp; &thorn;e oon reproue&thorn; synne hardliche, &amp; &thorn;is secte approue&thorn; crist in word &amp; dede; &thorn;e o&thorn;ere secte hidi&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">biddeth MS.</NOTE> synne as antecrist &amp; hise clerkis. &amp; noo drede &thorn;e firste secte is cristis lore, &amp; &thorn;e o&thorn;er &thorn;e fendis; &amp; for &thorn;e firste secte deyede crist &amp; bi hym alle hise apostlis, &amp; &thorn;is &thorn;ey tau&yogh;ten in worde, as we han told ofte bifore. &THORN;e secounde secte &thorn;at hydi&thorn; synne was in tyme of bo&thorn;e goddis lawis, but now it is late renewelid in &thorn;e tyme of &thorn;ise newe ordris; but noo man shulde trowe hem here, as noo man shulde be frere but &yogh;if bi impossible god tolde man &thorn;at he shulde make hym a frere; &amp; &thorn;is hidyng is clepid pees &thorn;at crist com not to sende in er&thorn;e, but to depart worldliche frendis for more loue &thorn;at men shulden haue to god. &amp; &thorn;us &yogh;if men shulden leue to reproue til &thorn;ei weren clene wi&thorn;-oute 
<PB REF="00000381.tif" N="315"> synne, &thorn;ey shulden neuer reproue here, si&thorn; apostlis weren not wi&thorn;-outen synne; but goddis lawe dampne&thorn; &thorn;is, &thorn;at men shulden reproue a synne &amp; wi&thorn; &thorn;is synne more in &thorn;e synne &thorn;at &thorn;ei reprouen. &amp; &thorn;us kepe we vs fro greete synnes; &amp; speke we wyseliche a&yogh;en open synne; &amp; who &thorn;at sey&thorn; a&yogh;en &thorn;is, he is on &thorn;e fendis syde. hou sharpliche &thorn;at men shulden speke a&yogh;en synne, &amp; bi what ordre, god mo teche, for hid synne &thorn;at man is inne letti&thorn; hym ofte to kunne &thorn;is lore. Wel I woot &thorn;at crist &amp; baptist reproueden men for here synne &amp; clepeden hem kyndlyngis of eddris; &amp; god woot whe&thorn;er men ben now worse. lyue we wel, &amp; triste we to god &thorn;at he wole &yogh;iue vs concel in &thorn;is, &amp; haue we euere oure hertis to hym, and comune entent to plese hym!</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="8" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum 8<SUP>m.</SUP></HEAD>
<P>It were to wite ouer &thorn;e falshede of euidencis &thorn;at &thorn;e fend ha&thorn; brouht in to loue hise newe ordris. al &yogh;if loue be good &yogh;if it be clene in crist, &yogh;it vnordinel loue groundid in falshed is noyose <MILESTONE N="91" UNIT="page">to men for many enchesouns. &para; Sixe euidencis maky&thorn; &thorn;e fend to loue &thorn;us hise ordris. ffirst for heere habitis; &thorn;at &thorn;ei ben passyngliche holy, here gurdlis &amp; al here atier &thorn;at falli&thorn; to hem, &amp; ilche man loue&thorn; kyndeliche holy|nesse of his bro&thorn;er. But here shulden men wite &thorn;at holynesse is in &thorn;e soule &amp; in noon bodiliche &thorn;ing but &yogh;if hit springe fro &thorn;at, &amp; &yogh;it it is lytil or nou&yogh;t but &yogh;if it be groundid in treu&thorn;e. But men han told ofte &thorn;e cause whi &thorn;at siche atieris my&yogh;ten profite. Bo&thorn;e colours &amp; figuris ben shapen to deceyue &thorn;e folc, to suppose &thorn;at &thorn;ei ben holy &thorn;at hauen siche signes wi&thorn;|oute; but crist biddi&thorn; &thorn;at mennus holynesse be hid fro siche signes. &amp; so &thorn;e offys of hem, who so vndirstondi&thorn; hem wel, is to shewe heere ypocrisie &amp; to hyde heere synnes wi&thorn;-inne for&thorn;. &amp; herfore sei&thorn; crist of pharisees &thorn;at "&thorn;ei ben<NOTE PLACE="marg">Matt. xxiii. [27.]</NOTE> blaunchid sepulcris." lord, what helpi&thorn; wydnesse of habitis of &thorn;ise ordris? it seme&thorn; &thorn;at to &thorn;ise tuo bi cast of &thorn;e fend; ffirst to make hem more hidliche to breede hem grete balyes, 
<PB REF="00000382.tif" N="316"> for many of siche ordris hauen heere balyes for heere god. &THORN;e secunde cause of &thorn;is wydnesse is wastyng of goddis good; for alle goodis of &thorn;is world ben goodis of god &thorn;e cheef lord, &amp; he &yogh;iue&thorn; hem to hise pore men &thorn;at seruen hym treweliche. &amp; so ilche &thorn;reed of siche clo&thorn;is &thorn;at ben tuo wast &amp; too costliche beri&thorn; wi&thorn; hym a wrong bo&thorn;e to god &amp; man, &amp; specialliche when &thorn;ise clo&thorn;is ben too riche &amp; costliche. &YOGH;if &thorn;ise clo&thorn;is ben gurde &amp; more large in widnesse, &thorn;ei beren on hem more synne, for more ypocrisie in hem. And knottis &thorn;at bitokenen penaunce hongynge bifore fro &thorn;e bodi ben signes of ypocrisie &amp; noon o&thorn;er holynesse; &amp; &thorn;us widnesse of siche clo&thorn;is is an hord to hyde synnes, as gabbyngis &amp; ypocrisie, &yogh;if it be not superflue. &amp; trowyng of holynesse of hem bryngi&thorn; in many heresies, &thorn;at &thorn;ise clo&thorn;is ben more hooly &thorn;en weren &thorn;e clo&thorn;is of crist. Si&thorn; pilat my&yogh;te haue be dampned al &yogh;if he hadde dyed in cristis clo&thorn;is. &amp; &thorn;us &thorn;ise habitis of &thorn;e newe ordris bleren &thorn;e eyen of &thorn;e peple &amp; <MILESTONE N="91b" UNIT="page">hyden heere priuey robberye, &amp; o&thorn;er good don &thorn;ei but lytel; but &yogh;if &thorn;ei verifyen iudis wordis, &thorn;at siche ben trees turned vpsodoun, for roote &amp; inward of hem ben shewid wi&thorn;-oute to &thorn;e world, and falsnesse of here entent is hid fro men bi &thorn;is turnyng. it shulde be knowen to cristen men &thorn;at alle siche sensible signes ben not signes of hoolynesse, but &yogh;if &thorn;ei maken hooly|nesse in men. &para; &THORN;e secunde deceyte of &thorn;e fend bi whiche he bigyli&thorn; simple men stondi&thorn; in &thorn;is; &thorn;at siche ordris lyuen scars fro good mete, &amp; so scarsnesse of heere foode telli&thorn; to men &thorn;at &thorn;ei ben hooly. But here men seyen to &thorn;e fend &thorn;at &thorn;ise signes ben ofte false, for many of &thorn;ise newe ordris liuen lustfulliche in heere foode &amp; &thorn;at men mai see wel bi growyng &amp; colour of here body. but &thorn;is may falle ofte tymes &thorn;at summe bre&thorn;eren of &thorn;ise ordris faylen ouer-meche in mete &amp; drynk, &amp; summe ben too wel fed bi vneuene partyng of here goodis; &amp; so &thorn;is poynt of siche ordris stondi&thorn; in &thorn;ise two &thorn;ingis, &thorn;at where rewele of apostlis was to haue alle &thorn;ingis in comune &amp; be partid to ilche as he hauede nede, &thorn;ise ordris don &thorn;e contrarie; &amp; so si&thorn; apostlis rewele was good, spring|ynge 
<PB REF="00000383.tif" N="317"> of gooddis wille, &thorn;is rewele mot nede be euel &amp; come of lawe of lucifer. &THORN;e secunde fruyt of &thorn;is delyng stondi&thorn; in &thorn;is poynt, &thorn;at siche etyng is priuee &amp; hid fro o&thorn;ere bre&thorn;eren, &amp; so it aski&thorn; priuee housis &amp; priuee seruice to performe it. &amp; &thorn;us when holynesse shulde be hid, &amp; lustliche foode shulde be exilid, &thorn;is delyng doi&thorn; &thorn;e contrarie &amp; come&thorn; of &thorn;e fend heere patroun. &amp; &thorn;us &thorn;ei don not oonliche in &thorn;is partyng wrong to heere owen bre&thorn;eren, but to pore men wi&thorn;oute &thorn;ise ordris whom &thorn;ei spoylen of heere goodis. &amp; se, when crist biddit hise disciplis to ete &amp; dryngke &thorn;e metis &thorn;at ben in<NOTE PLACE="marg">Luke x. [7.]</NOTE> folc &thorn;at thei comen to, &thorn;ise ordeynen &thorn;e contrarie, &thorn;at &thorn;ei haue propre foode for heere mou&thorn; &thorn;at passi&thorn; ofte &thorn;e <MILESTONE N="92" UNIT="page">boundis of resoun. &amp; &thorn;us when siche ordris han forsake propertee &amp; take al in comune, &thorn;ei a&yogh;en heere owne ordre hauen heere properte in lust, &amp; comunete in simple foode is forbeden bi here ordre, &amp; poul mene&thorn; to tymothe &thorn;at sich is blasfeme<NOTE PLACE="marg">[1 Tim. iv. 3.]</NOTE> abstinence. &para; &THORN;e &thorn;ridde deceyt of &thorn;ise ordris is &thorn;at &thorn;ei passen o&thorn;ere in preyeris, bo&thorn;e for tyme &thorn;ei preyen &amp; for multitude of hem. Who shulde not bye dere siche preyeris? si&thorn; &thorn;ei bryngen men swiftliche to heuene; &amp; o&thorn;er men when &thorn;ei slepen on ny&yogh;tis hauen of hem preyeris at mydny&yogh;t, &thorn;at crien devowteliche on god bi clere voys, stif &amp; clene. Here men seyen &thorn;at in &thorn;is poynt many seculers ben deceyued, for &thorn;ise ordris witen not whe&thorn;er &thorn;at &thorn;ei shal come to heuene, &amp; so whe&thorn;er &thorn;at heere preyeris profiten to hem or any o&thorn;er man. hou is heere conscience brent, &thorn;at &thorn;ei dar &thorn;us sille siche preyeris; &amp; algatis si&thorn; it is proprid to god to parte meritis as hym liki&thorn;, &amp; noon man may approue hise meritis but as god iugi&thorn; &thorn;at it is wor&thorn;i; &amp; &thorn;us &thorn;is preyere of &thorn;ise ordris is of a nest of blasfemye &amp; chaffaryng of fendis preyere bi &thorn;e craft of symonye. &amp; where &thorn;ei maken hem a rewele to ryse reweleliche at mydny&yogh;t, &thorn;ei passen crist &amp; david &amp; &thorn;e ordy|naunce of &thorn;e godhede<NOTE PLACE="foot">goghede MS.</NOTE>; for god vndisposi&thorn; ofte tymes men to ryse &thorn;us at mydny&yogh;t, &amp; aski&thorn; of hem a betere lif, &thorn;at &thorn;ei 
<PB REF="00000384.tif" N="318"> putten of bi heere statute. Crist duelled in preyere al &thorn;e ny&yogh;t, but bi hym silf wi&thorn;oute siche couentis; &amp; so &thorn;ise ordris holden not cristis rewele ne&thorn;er in tyme ne in stide, for crist preyede wi&thorn;oute siche criynge, lyk to &thorn;e state of innocence, bi hym self vndir &thorn;e cope of heuene. Siche risyng may som tyme do good &amp; ofte it doi&thorn; yuel; &amp; &thorn;us to &yogh;iue rewele wi&thorn;oute god were presumpcion of a fend, &amp; to make a rewele &thorn;us to crie on god were a signe of blasfeme folye; as who seyde bi &thorn;e prophetis word: "crye &yogh;ee fast,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[1] Kings xviii. [27.]</NOTE> for &yogh;oure god slepi&thorn;, or ellis he is in som priuee place, or ellis ocupied wi&thorn; o&thorn;ere men." <MILESTONE N="92b" UNIT="page">We graunten &thorn;at criyng profiti&thorn; som tyme, but not to make &thorn;us rewele &thorn;er-of. hit is knowen to men of resoon &thorn;at many signes ben nakid to moue men &thorn;at preyeris of &thorn;ise ordris ben betere &thorn;en o&thorn;er comune lyues; for fastyng come&thorn; ofte in robberis, bo&thorn;e in watir &amp; in lond, meche more &thorn;en ordris taken, but biddyng of god fayli&thorn; hem bo&thorn;e; &amp; wakyng at mydny&yogh;t falli&thorn; to &thorn;eues &thorn;at robben men; &amp; &yogh;if &thorn;ise outlawis passen &thorn;is rewele, it is for &thorn;ei robben men priueliche, &amp; herfore &thorn;ey feynen o&thorn;ere causis wherby heere preyere is so good. &para; &THORN;e four&thorn;e cause in ordre is holynesse of here compaynye; &amp; as many men drawen a ship or don an o&thorn;er dede of streng&thorn;e where fewere shulden not do &thorn;is dede, so it is in craft of preyng; many men when &thorn;ey ben gederid preyen more plesingliche to god &thorn;en wen &thorn;ei ben scaterid in twynny, or fewe to preye god herfore. &amp; &thorn;is &thorn;ei prouen bi mannes custom; when a peple wole preye a lord, &thorn;ei gederen hem hool to|gidere, &amp; preyen<NOTE PLACE="foot">preyem MS.</NOTE> mekeliche &amp; wi&thorn; knelyng. &amp; &thorn;us men shapen for many massis to brynge a soule anoon to heuene<NOTE PLACE="foot">heuenene MS.</NOTE>; who wolde not procure siche helperis to preye god &amp; shende &thorn;e fend. But<NOTE PLACE="foot">Bub MS.</NOTE> here cristen men &thorn;enken &thorn;at &thorn;ise wordis smacchen ofte falshede &amp; blasfemye a&yogh;en god, but hou sulden &thorn;ei conferme preyere? It is seyd ofte hou &thorn;at &thorn;e couent of cristis apostlis passede alle o&thorn;ere couentis bo&thorn;e in 
<PB REF="00000385.tif" N="319"> patroun &amp; in rewele, &amp; &yogh;it oon of hem was scarioth; hou many scariothis ben in &thorn;ise couentis? &amp; felowship of siche pseudoes letti&thorn; o&thorn;er men to preye, for hou shulde &thorn;at man preye wel &thorn;at ha&thorn; enuye to his bro&thorn;er &amp; stondi&thorn; in queer wi&thorn; hym, o&thorn;er next hym or a syde? si&thorn; siche daliaunce wole gregge his ire, &amp; vnable hym to haue ou&yogh;t of god. &amp; &thorn;us &thorn;ei faren ofte as don doggis in a poke; oon drawi&thorn; for&thorn; an-o&thorn;er a&yogh;en; but hou shulde sich drawyng helpe to drawe &thorn;e ship of holy chirche bi fisshis &thorn;at ben &thorn;us deepe in watir? many of hem wolden drawe betere &yogh;if &thorn;ei stooden hem self al one. &amp; &thorn;is blasfeme lickenesse, <MILESTONE N="93" UNIT="page">&thorn;at comunes preyen &thorn;us to lordis, telli&thorn; openliche &thorn;is heresye &thorn;at &thorn;ise newe ordris hauen here; for god for his grettnesse is in ilche place of &thorn;is world, &amp; redy to helpe men soonere in what place &thorn;at &thorn;ei lyuen betere. &amp; &thorn;us as freris lyues techen, it were good to many men &thorn;at ben closid in &thorn;ise ordris &thorn;at &thorn;ei disporteden hem in &thorn;e world. for siche auentyng many times fordoi&thorn; enuye, ire &amp; lust, &amp; &thorn;ise &thorn;re synnes ofte tymes letten &thorn;ise men to preye deuoteliche; &amp; &thorn;us it is open heresie too trowe &thorn;at &thorn;ristyng of ordris in oon cloystre or in oon hous helpi&thorn; &thorn;at god heeri&thorn; hem betere, al &yogh;if &thorn;ei liuen worse or ellis not betere to goddis pay. for al &thorn;ing is present to god, &amp; sich &thorn;ristyng helpi&thorn; not to hym, but &yogh;if it make men worse, for the synne of oon persone bi siche &thorn;ristyng fouli&thorn; more hise bro&thorn;ere. Lord, si&thorn; disciplis of crist aftir &thorn;at he was went to heuene weren scaterid in mony cuntres, &amp; weren not &thorn;rungen in siche couentis, what wit shulde moue &thorn;ise ordris aftir to gedere hem &thorn;us a&yogh;en skile? certis a fool may wel see &thorn;at &thorn;is resoun faili&thorn; fouliche, &amp; crist gederede tuelue apostlis, &thorn;erfore antecrist shal gedre moo; god reyne&thorn; in &thorn;is ordre, &thorn;erfore antecrist shulde &yogh;ette in wallis. god wole &thorn;at men quiken &thorn;is er&thorn;e, &amp; ben spred aboute in vertu of god, &amp; &thorn;is tau&yogh;ten cristis apostlis fro &thorn;at &thorn;ei weren quikid of crist heere maistre;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[2 Tim. iii. 7.]</NOTE> but &thorn;ise ordris wolen euere be disciplis &amp; neuere come to knowyng of treu&thorn;e. &amp; &thorn;us &thorn;ei moten neede be euer pun|yshid as disciplis of antecrist, but &yogh;if &thorn;ei lernen som tyme 
<PB REF="00000386.tif" N="320"> to go out of &thorn;ise newe ordris, si&thorn; &thorn;ei letten cristis lawe to rennue &amp; double profyt of hooly chirche. &para; &THORN;e fif&thorn;e deceyt of &thorn;ise pseudoes stondi&thorn; falsliche in &thorn;is feynyng, &thorn;at &thorn;ei maken a newe craft to preye &amp; to loue god, &amp; so &thorn;is newe craft is betere &thorn;en al &thorn;e ordre &thorn;at crist ha&thorn; makyd; &amp; &thorn;us &thorn;ei hauen special preyeris makid of newe bi &thorn;e pope &thorn;at ben betere &thorn;en &thorn;e pater noster, for more pardoun falli&thorn; to hem. &thorn;ise wordis may moue men &thorn;at wolen <MILESTONE N="93b" UNIT="page">folyliche trowe to hem, but ion biddi&thorn; men to assaye spiritis, whe&thorn;ere &thorn;ei ben on goddis<NOTE PLACE="marg">[1] John iv. [1.]</NOTE> syde. &amp; &thorn;us men ben not wi&thorn; god, &thorn;at holden wi&thorn; man more &thorn;en wi&thorn; crist. Oure bileue techi&thorn; us &thorn;at crist is bo&thorn;e god &amp; man, &amp; so he is al my&yogh;ty, al witty, &amp; al ful of good wille. &amp; &thorn;us noon pope ne o&thorn;er prelat haue&thorn; witt ne power but of crist, in as meche as he sewi&thorn; crist bifore o&thorn;ere of hise felowis; &amp; so it is a feyned power, a feyned wit, &amp; feyned good, al &thorn;at is not shewid in dede, in trewe sewyng of crist. &amp; &thorn;us what man &thorn;at euere sei&thorn; &thorn;at he maki&thorn; betere preyere &thorn;en crist, &amp; ordeyne&thorn; &thorn;er-to more pardoun, blasfeme&thorn; as antecrist; &amp; &thorn;us &thorn;e old maner was betere to preye &amp; to plese god &thorn;en ony newe preyer mai be, hou euere antecrist speke here. Shewe men bi goddis lawe or resoun &thorn;e good|nesse of siche preyeris, &amp; &thorn;at &thorn;ei plesen so meche to god as &thorn;ei ben feyned of &thorn;is nouelrie; &amp; ellis men shulden not trowe to hem, but have hem suspect bi maner of lif. Wel I wott &thorn;e fend may feyne sich goodnesse of hise preyeris &amp; hey&yogh;nesse of his power, for men mai not see it; &amp; herfore he mai pursewe men but &yogh;if &thorn;ey graunten &thorn;is excellence, but noon man shulde trowe &thorn;is but if God taw&yogh;te it as bileeue. And here is weye to antecrist, to pursewe cristen men for &thorn;ei holden hem in &thorn;e boundis &thorn;at crist ha&thorn; &yogh;iuen to bileeue. Cristen men trowen &thorn;is, &thorn;at &yogh;if &thorn;ise preyeris weren so goode, crist wolde haue shewid hem bifore, when hise vikeris &amp; his peple weren betere, &amp; &thorn;us &thorn;ei ben foolis &thorn;at trowen &thorn;is goodnesse of &thorn;ise newe preyeris; for &thorn;e pater noster is &thorn;e best preyere &thorn;at ony pope or man kon ordeyne. for who shulde autorise &thorn;at god shulde more be payed of ony preyere? 
<PB REF="00000387.tif" N="321"> &amp; it is al oon to seye &thorn;at a preyere is betere, &amp; &thorn;at it plesi&thorn; god more; but who mai do &thorn;is but god? for god oonliche mai &yogh;iue grace &amp; more accepte men to mede; &amp; &thorn;us trowe we not in &thorn;ise preyeris, si&thorn; hem wanti&thorn; ground. &amp; &thorn;us &yogh;if lif <MILESTONE N="94" UNIT="page">of &thorn;ise newe ordris be more medeful &thorn;en mannes lif was woned, it mot neede be grauntid of god, for newe ordinaunce is but fantym here; &amp; &thorn;us si&thorn; good lif of men &thorn;at ben wandrynge in &thorn;is weye is betere preyere to god, &yogh;if it plese more to god. What lif &thorn;at plesi&thorn; more to god is betere preiere to god; as lif of a trewe plow man or ellis of a trewe heerde is betere preyere to god &thorn;en preyere of any ordre &thorn;at god loue&thorn; lesse, blabere &thorn;ei neuere so meche wi&thorn; lippis. as it is likeliche &thorn;at baptist preyede betere bi hym silf in desert &thorn;en ony persone of &thorn;ise newe ordris, for hise lippis ben lesse wor&thorn;; &amp; &thorn;us betere lif helpi&thorn; more to soulis &thorn;en massis or &thorn;ise newe preyeris. &THORN;e sixte deceyte of ypocritis, &thorn;at bigyli&thorn; men in &thorn;is matere, is &thorn;at &thorn;ei liuen honestliche in chirche, in hous, &amp; in gardyn, &amp; in alle ornamentis &thorn;at fallen to worship of god; who shulde not loue sich a sect, bo&thorn;e bi kynde &amp; bi resoun? Here men &thorn;enken &thorn;at &thorn;e fend vsi&thorn; hise ypocrisie, &amp; contrarieliche to crist moue&thorn; men bi sensible signes. it is good &amp; resonable men to haue chirchis in mesure, &amp; in numbre, &amp; in weyhte, aftir &thorn;e hooly trinitee; but &thorn;enne it is nedeful &thorn;at &thorn;ei be makyd bi iust dispensis, &amp; to profit of &thorn;e lond in which &thorn;ei ben makid inne, &amp; not do wrong to old chirchis bi weye of heere newe fyndyng; &amp; so alle housis &amp; placis shulden be shapen bi lore of crist. But somme men &thorn;enken &thorn;at freris bildyng faili&thorn; in alle &thorn;ise &thorn;re poyntis. It is comuneliche makid bi slyh robbyngis of &thorn;e fend, so &thorn;at it is al oon to see bildyngis of &thorn;ise newe ordris, &amp; to see a fendis holde, makid of robberye of pore men; &amp; so when men loken on heere castelis &thorn;ei hauen matere to wepe, bo&thorn;e &thorn;ise ordris &amp; seculeris, but specialliche &thorn;e pore peple. for &yogh;if we loken to cristis lif, he forsok sich bildyng,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Luke xix. [41.]</NOTE> &amp; lokyng on &thorn;e citee, &thorn;at he seyde was a&yogh;en &thorn;e apostlis, he wepte &thorn;er upon for greet synne &thorn;at it hoordede. &amp; when 
<PB REF="00000388.tif" N="322"> crist wente out of &thorn;e temple <MILESTONE N="94b" UNIT="page">&amp; sat in &thorn;e mount a&yogh;en it, hise disciplis for wondryng &thorn;er-of &amp; to see his wit &thorn;er-of askeden<NOTE PLACE="marg">Matt. xxiv. [2.]</NOTE> whe&thorn;er he sau alle &thorn;ise wondirful byldyngis. &amp; crist an|suerede to hise apostlis, &amp; tolde hem hou hym likede herof: "So&thorn;eliche i seye to &yogh;ou, tyme shal come soone heraftir &thorn;at noon stoon shal be left here on an-o&thorn;er, &thorn;at it ne shal be destryed;" and so it fel soone aftir, when ierusalem was destryed. &THORN;re &thorn;yngis shulden moue men to be glad of sich byldyng: On, for it turne&thorn; a-wey fro &thorn;e state of innocence; &amp; herfore crist &amp; baptist &amp; o&thorn;ere seyntis makeden noon siche. &THORN;e secunde cause &thorn;at shulde moue to be glad of siche byld|yng is, &thorn;at god sey&thorn; bi poul: "we hauen not here a<NOTE PLACE="marg">Heb. xiii. [14.]</NOTE> duellynge citee, but we seken heuen to come." &amp; non drede siche housyng maki&thorn; many to loue &thorn;is world, &amp; to duelle in lustis &thorn;er-of, &amp; leue loue of &thorn;e o&thorn;ere worlde. &THORN;e &thorn;ridde cause &thorn;at men shulden haue to loke on siche byldyng is &thorn;at &thorn;ei shulden &thorn;enke on &thorn;e pore peple; hou ofte &thorn;at &thorn;ei ben spoylid bi suttil fraudis of &thorn;e fend bifore &thorn;at siche housis weren bildid, &thorn;at ben but an heep of wrongis. &THORN;ise &thorn;re causis shulden not &yogh;iue matere of ioye to men of resoun, but ra&thorn;ere matere of sorowe to telle hasty destriyng of hem. men may see ouer whe&thorn;er &thorn;ise patrouns vseden &thorn;ise housis in sich mesure, &amp; leften in heere rewlis aftir &thorn;at heere disciplis shulden bilde &thorn;us; &amp; si&thorn; &thorn;e contrarie is so&thorn;, to whiche &thorn;ise ordris ben streytliche sworen, it seme&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;e fend shapi&thorn; a disport to hise clerkis to serue hym inne. &amp; so &yogh;if men chargen mesure, &thorn;ise placis &amp; bildyng of hem passen mesure &thorn;at god ha&thorn; tau&yogh;t, &amp; so &thorn;ei ben agen goddis power. &amp; &yogh;if we taken heede to &thorn;e noumbre of siche castel of &thorn;e fend, &thorn;ey ben a&yogh;en wisdom of crist, si&thorn; he approuede not siche housis. for si&thorn; in tyme of more wisdom &thorn;er weren chirchis &amp; housis ynowe, what wisdom <MILESTONE N="95" UNIT="page">is it to multiplie &thorn;ise, &amp; destrye hoolyere old placis? certis iniuries ben don to parisshe chirchis bi siche newe chirchis of ordris; &amp; &yogh;if &thorn;us wrongis of a place shulden lette men to herye god &thorn;ere, siche placis of newe ordris shulden be fled as fendis holetis. And &yogh;if we 
<PB REF="00000389.tif" N="323"> weyn aryht dispensis bi lore of &thorn;e hooly goost, &thorn;er is ney&thorn;er stoon ne tree in alle siche newe ordris placis &thorn;at it ne is groundid bi wrong, &amp; temporid bi robbyng of pore men. &amp; &thorn;us siche bildyngis makyn pride, &amp; not comfort of goddis prisounneris, for &thorn;ei ben not fed bi &thorn;is, but robbid of goodis &thorn;at &thorn;ei shulden haue; &amp; &thorn;is is not lore of &thorn;e hooli goost, but techyng of &thorn;e kyng of pride. &amp; &thorn;us ornamentis &thorn;at &thorn;ise freris ordris vsen ben toolis to bigyle &thorn;e peple, &amp; to feede heere bodiliche eye, &amp; robbe &thorn;e eye of heere soule, as somme of &thorn;ise newe ordris hauen costy encenseris to encense beddis of men &amp; of wymmen &amp; to spoyle hem. &THORN;us &thorn;ei assoylen men &thorn;at weren longe deed byfore; &amp; soulis of siche men ben in helle as somme men supposen; &amp; &thorn;ise blynde men &thorn;at assoylen &thorn;us kunnen not teche &thorn;e contrarie of &thorn;is. &amp; &thorn;us &thorn;ey doon &thorn;is for monee, &amp; not for deuocioun, but &yogh;if siche blynde blasfemyes be clepid deuocioun of freris. &THORN;us ornamentis of ypocritis harmen &thorn;e peple &thorn;at &thorn;ei duellen wi&thorn;, &amp; al heere lif doi&thorn; harm to men bo&thorn;e to body &amp; to soule. &amp; &thorn;us fendis children bygilen men bi &thorn;ing &thorn;at hem seme&thorn; good, &amp; maken hem trow &thorn;at it profiti&thorn;, but &yogh;it it doi&thorn; meche harm. &amp; si&thorn; alle lyues of siche men ben ful of &thorn;e fendis deceytis, men sufficen not to telle heere gylis, but bi &thorn;is men may knowe somme. And here ben somme men moued to trowe &thorn;at crist speki&thorn; in his lawe of sich maner of ypocritis, to teche his peple to fle hem. for si&thorn; crist is veree god,<NOTE PLACE="foot">good MS.</NOTE> &amp; knowi&thorn; <MILESTONE N="95b" UNIT="page">clereliche al &thorn;ing to come, alle &thorn;ise deceytis ben present to hym; what shulde lette hym to telle hem? Certis charite of Crist shulde neede hym to warne men here. &amp; &thorn;us resoun moue&thorn; men to suppose &thorn;at crist telli&thorn; of gilis of &thorn;e pope,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Matt. xxiv.</NOTE> &amp; aftir of gilis of &thorn;ise new sectis, for alle &thorn;ise ben lemes of antecrist. whi shulde not crist telle here of hem? and &thorn;us &thorn;enken somme &thorn;at it were a medeful dede &amp; good preyere to god to a&yogh;enstonde &thorn;ise new sectis, &amp; clenese cristis ordi|naunce fro sich errours &thorn;at ben brou&yogh;t inne. Lordis, clerkis 
<PB REF="00000390.tif" N="324"> &amp; comunes shulden helpe here for mede of crist, &amp; oldnesse of &thorn;ise errours shulde not moue to leue hem, si&thorn; god is my&yogh;ty ynou to helpe &amp; destrye hem alle. &THORN;is entent hauen meke men bi grace &amp; bileeue of crist, &thorn;at his ordinaunce was and is best, and o&thorn;er contrarie ordinaunce is euel; &amp; bileeue techi&thorn; &thorn;at [he] mai not fayle to helpe men &thorn;at trauelen wel here. Examine &thorn;ou wel &thorn;e grounde an &thorn;e resoun of newe men, &thorn;at seyen &thorn;ey holden &thorn;e lawe and &thorn;e ordinaunce of crist, &amp; we trauelen to destrye hem. for certis &yogh;if we erreden here in wit or wille bi fals lore, we wolden mekeliche a-noon turne to treu&thorn;e when it were tau&yogh;t. Amen.</P>
<TRAILER>Explicit tractatus de pseudo freris.</TRAILER>


