<DIV1 N="23" TYPE="tract"><PB REF="00000391.tif" N="325">
<HEAD>XXIII. OF CONFESSION.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>DR. SHIRLEY says that this tract is the same as the Latin De Eucharistia et P&oelig;nitentia. The latter is found only at Vienna, and I have not been able to compare the two. I have, however, no doubt that this is genuine. Its presence in the Ashburnham MS. tells much in its favour, while the evidence of style seems to me to mark it as decidedly Wyclif's. His predestinarian doctrines are incidentally referred to on p. 329: "who is he &thorn;at letti&thorn; god to saue men as he ha&thorn; ordeyned . . . before &thorn;e world was made?"</P><P>There are curious notices on pp. 333 and 335 of the prevalent fashion of keeping private confessors and of the influence which such men wielded.</P><P>The attack on transubstantiation at the end of the tract shows it to be late.</P><P>Copied from the Dublin MS. CC, and collated with the Ashburnham MS. MM.</P><P><TABLE>
<HEAD>SUMMARY.</HEAD>
<ROW>
<CELL>Two virtues are in man's soul: holiness and knowledge. Holiness is the more important. To holiness confession is needful. Definition of confession. Con|fession of sin is made to God or to man. The latter may be either open or private, but must be voluntary</CELL>
<CELL>p. 327</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>Private confession is unnecessary, unauthorized by Christ or by the practice of the early Church. It is a device to increase the power of the Pope</CELL>
<CELL>328</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>It is limiting God's power to say a man cannot be saved without shrift. Private confession gives occasion to sin</CELL>
<CELL>329</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>Possible abuses from the law of regular confession. The proper priest may be unfit. Confession hinders preaching</CELL>
<CELL>330</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>The methods of absolution vary. Some seem to claim fellowship with God for the priest. Arbitrary assignment of penance. Leads to buying sin for money</CELL>
<CELL>332</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>The devil wishes all men to believe that priests only have power to absolve, and the four orders of friars unite to maintain this. Evil of private confessors</CELL>
<CELL>334</CELL>

<PB REF="00000392.tif" N="326">
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>It would be well to have two priests to hear penance, as it would prevent mischief and increase wholesome shame. Some confessions would be better divulged</CELL>
<CELL>p. 335</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>Confession has done much good and much harm. It should not be obligatory. None of the confessors are equal to the task they undertake. General and open confession sufficient</CELL>
<CELL>336</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>All sin is offence against God</CELL>
<CELL>337</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>Need of sorrow for sin. God's free grace a reason for avoiding sin</CELL>
<CELL>338</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>Antichrist argues that without the outward sign of shrift the sacrament of penance is destroyed</CELL>
<CELL>339</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>God's courtesy does not in all cases require audible confession, and all good deeds may be called sacraments</CELL>
<CELL>340</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>The keys given to St. Peter are knowledge and power, which were given also to the other apostles. The knowledge is knowledge of God's law, the power is that of preaching and teaching</CELL>
<CELL>341</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>Antichrist cites the ten lepers that Christ bid show themselves to the priest</CELL>
<CELL>342</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>It was Christ that healed them; and we should follow the Samaritan's example and thank Christ for forgiveness</CELL>
<CELL>343</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>Arguments of Antichrist from James v. 16; from the raising of Lazarus; and from John's baptism, shown not to bear on private confession to priests</CELL>
<CELL>343</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>Exhortation to priests to attend to preaching and to avoid claiming to perform miracles in the transubstantiation of the Host</CELL>
<CELL>345</CELL>
</ROW>
</TABLE></P></HEADNOTE>

<PB REF="00000393.tif" N="327">
<HEAD>Nota de Confessione.</HEAD>
<P><MILESTONE N="127b" UNIT="page">Two virtues ben in mannes soule by whyche a man shuld be rewled;<NOTE PLACE="foot">CC inserts in.</NOTE> hoolynesse in mannes wille, &amp; good kunnyng in his witt. hoolynesse shuld put out synne, &amp; good<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;is MM.</NOTE> kunnyng shuld put out foly; but as wille ha&thorn; principalite to-fore witt of mannes soule, so hoolynesse is more wor&thorn;e &thorn;enne is kunnynge of synful man. for wuckud aungels han myche kunnyng, but &thorn;ei han nou&yogh;t of hoolynesse. And ellis iche man were hoolier aftur &thorn;at he is more kunnynge; but poule sei&thorn; &thorn;at mannes kunnyng bolni&thorn; hym bi pride. but in oure<NOTE PLACE="marg">[1] Cor. viii. [1.]</NOTE> lord ihesu crist was kunnynge &amp; hoolynesse euen, for he was ful &amp; heierst in kunnyng &amp; heierst hooly, bo&thorn;e god &amp; man. and &thorn;us he seith in Iones gospel: "who of &yogh;ou shal reproue me of synne," <SUP>3</SUP>as &yogh;if crist wolde seye to hem "y may<NOTE PLACE="marg">John viii. [46.]</NOTE> not synne<SUP>3</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot">3_3 omitted CC.</NOTE> si&thorn; I am god; and &thorn;us nou&yogh;t may reproue me of synne." but crist sei&thorn; next aftur &thorn;at sith he sei&thorn; treu&thorn;e; whi <SUP>4</SUP>trowen &thorn;ei<SUP>4</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot">4_4 trowe &yogh;e CC.</NOTE> not to hym? In &thorn;ise two wordis &thorn;at crist ha&thorn; seid, may we see hoolynesse &amp; kunnynge. and hou hoolynes go&thorn;e before &amp; kunnyng sue&thorn; in wor&thorn;inesse; for lyue a man hooly lyf, and kunnynge I-now wil folow aftur. To make hoolynesse in men is confession nedful; and &thorn;erfor shuld hooly churche witt sumwhat of confession. Confession gene|raly is knowlechynge made wi&thorn; wille; and sum confession is made wi&thorn;-oute synne, and sum is knowlechynge of synne; &amp; bo&thorn;e &thorn;ise two ben goode in man, but &thorn;e first is more wor&thorn;e in crist. Mathew telli&thorn; hou crist confessed to his fadur, <SUP>5</SUP>lord of &thorn;is world,<SUP>5</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot">5_5 omitted CC.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="marg">Mt. 2<SUP>o</SUP>. [should be Matt. xi. 25.]</NOTE> &amp; &yogh;itt crist my&yogh;t not synne, and &thorn;is confessioun my&yogh;t not be veyne. Confessioun &thorn;at man maki&thorn; of synne is made of man in two maners. Summe is mad oonly to god truly by herte or mou&thorn;e. And sum confessioun is made to man, and &thorn;at may be on many maneres; ou&thorn;er opynly &amp;<NOTE PLACE="foot">or CC.</NOTE> generaly, as men 
<PB REF="00000394.tif" N="328"> confesseden in &thorn;e oolde lawe; Or priuely &amp; rownyngly, as men confessen nowe-a-daies. whenne a man is constreyned by bodily<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted MM.</NOTE> peyne to telle his gilte, <MILESTONE N="128" UNIT="page">he confesse&thorn; not; but<NOTE PLACE="foot">for MM.</NOTE> confession mut be wilful, or ellis it is not medeful to man.</P>
<P>It were to wite ouer in &thorn;is mater,<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted CC.</NOTE> whe&thorn;er priue confession<NOTE PLACE="marg">C<SUP>m</SUP> 2<SUP>m</SUP> MM.</NOTE> made to prestis be nedeful to<NOTE PLACE="foot">CC inserts &thorn;e.</NOTE> synful men, &amp; wher &thorn;is confessioun is groundid. and it seme&thorn; &thorn;at it is not nedful, but brou&yogh;t in late be &thorn;e fend; for crist alwitty vsed it not, ne noon of hise apostles aftur. And if it were nedful to man, crist wolde have vsed it or tau&yogh;t it. Whenne crist for&yogh;aue marie magde|leyne hir synnes, he vsed not siche rownynge; and whenne he for&yogh;aue petir hise synnes, &amp; poule his, &amp; o&thorn;er men heren &thorn;at he clensid, he vsid not sich rownyng in ere, ne siche asoylyng as prestis vsen nowe; and &thorn;us whenne crist clensed &thorn;e a|woutrer, &thorn;at &thorn;e Iewes alegeden shulde be stoned, crist vsed not &thorn;is confession to hir, but bad hir go and wilne to synne<NOTE PLACE="marg">John viii. [11.]</NOTE> no more. and si&thorn; &thorn;at crist my&yogh;t not faile in ordynaunce to hise chirche, &amp; he left &thorn;is confessioun, it semyth &thorn;at it is not nedeful; for if it were, &thorn;enne crist faylid in leuynge it; and also petre &amp; alle o&thorn;er apostles, and also alle o&thorn;er popis faileden &thorn;at weren til Innocens cam, whenne &thorn;e fende was loused, and &yogh;itt men weren clensed of her synne &thorn;icker &amp; bettur &thorn;enne &thorn;ei weren aftur, for I rede in &thorn;e boke &thorn;at luk wroto of apostles dedis, hou &thorn;re &thorn;ousand turned in oon daye fro Iewes fables to cristis lawe, &amp; noon of hem was &thorn;us confessid<NOTE PLACE="marg">Acts ii. [41.]</NOTE> to prestis. as &thorn;e story telli&thorn;,<NOTE PLACE="foot">shewi&thorn; MM.</NOTE> petir bade hem generaly haue sorowe &amp; be baptized ychoon; but god telli&thorn; not here of shrifte, but &thorn;at &thorn;ei token &thorn;e hooly goost; and &thorn;us here synnes weren for&yogh;yuen of god wi&thorn;-outen siche confessioun as we nowe vsen. and &thorn;us it semi&thorn; to many men &thorn;at cristen men my&yogh;ten wele be saued wi&thorn;-outen sich confessioun; as &thorn;ei were be-fore pope Innocent, and &thorn;us it seme&thorn; presump|cioun of &thorn;is pope to make &thorn;is lawe; for hooly churche shuld 
<PB REF="00000395.tif" N="329"> not &thorn;us be charged wi&thorn; newe lawes, <MILESTONE N="128b" UNIT="page">whenne oolde sufficeden; and &thorn;us men seyne &thorn;at &thorn;e fend kest this for wynnyng &amp; hi&yogh;nes of preestis: and in token of &thorn;is defaute makers of &thorn;is lawe weren so marrid &thorn;at her lawe bynde&thorn; noo persone but only suche &thorn;at ben bo&thorn;e men &amp; wymmen. &thorn;is semi&thorn; a feendis presumpcion to him &thorn;at knowe&thorn; not kynd of lawe to ordeyne lawe in siche a maner,<NOTE PLACE="foot">mater MM.</NOTE> of whiche noo siche shulde be made. and &thorn;us it seme&thorn; to many men &thorn;at antecrist ha&thorn; cast &thorn;is cast to make alle men soget to the pope; &amp; lede hem aftur &thorn;at hym liki&thorn;. lord, where is fredom of crist whenne men ben costen<NOTE PLACE="foot">castun MM.</NOTE> in siche bondage? Crist made hise seruauntes free, but antecrist ha&thorn; made hem bonde a&yogh;eyne. And certis &thorn;er is noo autorite &thorn;at gaue him leue to make men &thorn;us &thorn;rallis.</P>
<P>&YOGH;itt it were to wite &thorn;e reson of goddis lawe whi men<NOTE PLACE="marg">C<SUP>m</SUP> 3<SUP>m</SUP> MM.</NOTE> shulden hoolde hem in here bondes, &amp; not make lawe fro cristis ordre. It is oft seid in goddis lawe &thorn;at men shulden<NOTE PLACE="marg">Deut. iv. [2.]</NOTE> not adde &thorn;erto ne take &thorn;erfro, lest &thorn;ei failen, si&thorn; it is made at poynt deuyse; and &thorn;us it seme&thorn; a feendis presumpcioun, &thorn;at hi&yogh;e&thorn; himsilf a-bouen god, to make &thorn;us a newe lawe wi&thorn;|outen leeue of &thorn;e furst treu&thorn;e. Also &thorn;is lawe of confessioun &thorn;at iche man mut nedis shryuen oonys in &thorn;e &yogh;er priuely to his propur prest, it seme&thorn; opun a&yogh;ens reson. for a man may be baptized in tyme &thorn;at he<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted CC.</NOTE> ha&thorn; discrecioun, &amp;<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted CC.</NOTE> anon aftur be ded wi&thorn;-outen doynge of dedly<NOTE PLACE="foot">dely CC.</NOTE> synne. lord, whi shuld &thorn;is man be dampned al if he shriue him not &thorn;us <SUP>6</SUP>in &thorn;e &yogh;eer<SUP>6</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot">6_6 omitted CC.</NOTE>? Ion baptist shroof hym neuer &thorn;us, ne any apostle of crist; and &yogh;itt bileue nedi&thorn; vs to graunte &thorn;at &thorn;ei ben seyntes in heuen. and &thorn;us it may fallen of many martyres, &amp; of men &thorn;at han no propur prest. who is he &thorn;at letti&thorn; god to saue men as he ha&thorn; ordeyned before &thorn;e pope &amp; his lawe camen inne, &amp; before &thorn;e world was made? Also god gyue&thorn; frely his grace, not-wi&thorn;|stondynge mannes lawe. whi may not <MILESTONE N="129" UNIT="page">god do grace to hise 
<PB REF="00000396.tif" N="330"> treue seruauntes &thorn;at seruen him wele, al if &thorn;er were noo siche prest nor pope? as sumtyme was non. hou-euer antecrist glauer, he lette&thorn; not god to do his wille; for he may disseyue<NOTE PLACE="foot">distroy&yogh;e CC.</NOTE> foolis, but not god, hou-euer he speke. also beleeue techi&thorn; men &thorn;at if a man be contrite, god &thorn;enne for&yogh;yue&thorn; him his synne; but who may lette god fro &thorn;is? David speke&thorn; to god &thorn;us: "I seide, i shulde shryue my synnes a&yogh;ens me<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Psalm xxxii.15.]</NOTE> to &thorn;ee, lord; &amp; &thorn;ou for&yogh;auest me my synnes." lord, wher god be not as merciful as he was in &thorn;e olde<NOTE PLACE="foot">wolde CC.</NOTE> lawe? No &thorn;ing shuld lett &thorn;er-to, but &thorn;at he becam man for mercy; &amp; &thorn;us it seeme&thorn; a blasfeme heresie to seie &thorn;at man<NOTE PLACE="foot">he CC.</NOTE> may not ellis come to heuen, but if he fulfille &thorn;is roten lawe &thorn;at was &thorn;us late made of antecrist. Also god may not &yogh;yue occasioun to two persones for to synne, for &thorn;enne he were auctor of synne &amp; contrarie to himsilf; but bi &thorn;is priueye shrift a frere &amp; nunne may synne to-gidre; and close hemsilf in a chaumbre bi lok in-sted of feyned assoylynge; for I suppose as knowen &thorn;ing, &thorn;at whenne a lawe is feyned wi&thorn;outen god, &amp; of &thorn;is lawe come&thorn; myche synne, &thorn;is lawe &yogh;yue&thorn; occasion to al &thorn;at synne; <SUP>4</SUP>but &thorn;is lawe &yogh;yue&thorn; occasioun to do so as it falli&thorn; ofte.<SUP>4</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot">4_4 omitted CC.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="marg">[Job xxxi. 1.]</NOTE> lord, whe&thorn;ir god, &thorn;at sei&thorn; bi Iob &thorn;at a man shuld make couenaunt wi&thorn; hise wittis to &thorn;enke not on<NOTE PLACE="foot">wi&thorn; CC.</NOTE> a virgyne, ordeyned sich a lawe to men, &thorn;at prestis &amp; wymmen shulde turne her faces to-gider, &amp; speke of lustful<NOTE PLACE="foot">synful CC.</NOTE> &thorn;outes &amp; dedis, which my&yogh;t do harme to hem bo&thorn;e; but &thorn;is lawe &yogh;yue&thorn; occasioun to do synne as it falli&thorn; oft. Also &thorn;us may lordus &amp; laidis be nedid to trowe sich men, &amp; lettid to holde goddis lawe, and to stonde for ri&yogh;t on cristis syde. lord, if iche lord of ynglond &amp; his wiif haden two schariotis to lede hem &amp; her meyne and her werkis to &thorn;e puple, hou li&yogh;tly my&yogh;t antecrist conqwere &thorn;e churche and distruy&yogh;e cristis rewme?</P>
<P><MILESTONE N="129b" UNIT="page">And &yogh;it men maken moo resons to meue &thorn;e chirche to<NOTE PLACE="marg">C<SUP>m</SUP> 4<SUP>m</SUP> MM.</NOTE> knowe &thorn;e treu&thorn;e &amp; fredam of goddis lawe, so &thorn;at &thorn;e churche 
<PB REF="00000397.tif" N="331"> be not made bonde bi noo disceitis of antecrist, but stonde in &thorn;e same fredam &thorn;at crist ha&thorn; &yogh;ouen. God &yogh;yue&thorn; non occasion to antecrist for to synne; but bi &thorn;is feyned assoylyng he ha&thorn; occasion to synne in &thorn;e churche, and &thorn;us &thorn;is power is not of crist, wherby &thorn;is assoylyng is feyned; and &thorn;us &thorn;e fend mut nedis gabb whenne his prestis assoilen &thorn;us. for &thorn;us &thorn;e pope my&yogh;t kepe to hym to name whom euer he wolde propur prestis, and make couenaunt wi&thorn; &thorn;is prest &thorn;at he assoyle&thorn; no man but if he &yogh;yue so myche mone; or ellis behey&yogh;t to holde on his syde, and &thorn;us antecrist my&yogh;t soone conqwere lordshipes &amp; eke rewmes to hym. and &thorn;us curatis &amp; parishe prestis my&yogh;ten spuyle &thorn;e puple as freres done; and &thorn;us it were a benyfice to purchace of &thorn;e pope to be a propur preste &thorn;us. and it falle&thorn; oft &thorn;at sich propur prestus ben vn-able to here shriftis; and &thorn;e maker of &thorn;is lawe may not make alle siche propre prestis able, and so he constreyne&thorn; men in cas to shryue hem to an vnable prest. but who shuld preise &thorn;is lawe &thorn;erfore? si&thorn; yuel frute witnessi&thorn; yuel rote. As<NOTE PLACE="foot">al CC.</NOTE> if a pope make a lawe &thorn;at who euer he lymyti&thorn; to here confessioun of &thorn;is man or confession of &thorn;is comu[n]atee, he shal here &thorn;ise mennes shrift, &amp; he<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted CC.</NOTE> is founden vnable aftur, &thorn;enne &thorn;is popis lawe wi&thorn; treu&thorn;e in-dede may li&yogh;tly &yogh;yue occasioun of syne. and if &thorn;ou seist &thorn;at siche bullis of &thorn;e pope vndurstonden euer a condicioun; &thorn;at if &thorn;is persone bi goddis lawe shal profi&yogh;t in<NOTE PLACE="foot">into CC.</NOTE> fulfillyng of &thorn;ise popes bulles, &thorn;enne &thorn;e popes bullis shulen haue streng&thorn;e, &amp; elles &thorn;ei shulen not stonde in stede: Certis if &thorn;ise popis bulles shulen be undurstonden wi&thorn; sich a label, &thorn;en-ne &thorn;ei weren not profitable to &thorn;e purchasour ne to &thorn;e churche; <MILESTONE N="130" UNIT="page">for who <SUP>4</SUP>shuld take ony benyfiss of &thorn;e puple<SUP>4</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot">4_4 who shuld not take eny benyfice of &thorn;e pope CC.</NOTE> wi&thorn; sich bullis, if his ablete shulde be proued in werk be-fore he were acceptid? so&thorn;e it is &thorn;e more able man to god shuld qwenche &thorn;is ablete of &thorn;is man; and &thorn;is skil moued hooly men to stryue not for suche ablete. but crist &yogh;af reule 
<PB REF="00000398.tif" N="332"> to &thorn;e Iewes to iuge hym able bi hise werkis, but wele men witen &thorn;at ne&thorn;er popis bullis ne traueile for hem by coueitise maki&thorn; &thorn;is man but more vnable<NOTE PLACE="foot">vnable&thorn; hym CC.</NOTE> to gete ou&yogh;t by suche bullis. Also &thorn;is lawe is full suspecte, for it lette&thorn; bettur occupying, &amp; aske&thorn; werse occupyinge, &thorn;at is not grounded in goddis lawe. &thorn;at prelate &thorn;at shriue&thorn; shuld preche &thorn;e puple, and he &thorn;at is shriuen shuld here goddis worde; but bi &thorn;is shriften ben bo&thorn;e &thorn;ise lettid. and noo drede &thorn;ei weren bettre, si&thorn; crist vsed hem &amp; not &thorn;is shrift, &amp; bad hem be vsed, &amp; not &thorn;is. So it seme&thorn; &thorn;at antecrist bi &thorn;is putti&thorn; cristis ordynaunce abake; and we taken here as opynly knowen, &thorn;at whenne eny harm come&thorn; of a lawe, &amp; &thorn;at lawe is not groundid in skyl, it &yogh;yue&thorn; occasioun of &thorn;is harme; for reson excuse&thorn; not &thorn;is lawe, &thorn;at ne it make&thorn; blamefuly &thorn;is harme. and if it were reson in &thorn;is popis tyme to make &thorn;is lawe to &thorn;e churchis profite, it were as myche resoun &thorn;at &thorn;is lawe had ben vsed bi-fore &thorn;is popis tyme; but &thorn;enne weren crist &amp; petre &amp; o&thorn;er popes to blame &thorn;at leften it &thorn;us. lord, what meued &thorn;is late popes to make furst &thorn;is lawe, whenne &thorn;e fend was vnbounden, and god meued not crist ne hise vikers to sue it, whenne it semed as myche skil. wher &thorn;is pope was god of heuen, so &thorn;at men<NOTE PLACE="foot">god CC.</NOTE> may not know his<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;is CC.</NOTE> reson.</P>
<P>But &yogh;itt &thorn;er come&thorn; more harme of &thorn;is lawe of confessioun,<NOTE PLACE="marg">C<SUP>m</SUP> 5<SUP>m</SUP> MM.</NOTE> ffor confessours varien in wordis of assoylyng, as &thorn;ei done in wordis of her cursyng, &amp; gabben commynly wi&thorn; blasfeme wordis a&yogh;ens beleeue; and it is licly to many men si&thorn; &thorn;e pope kan not teche &thorn;ise wordis &thorn;at prestis shulden seie <MILESTONE N="130b" UNIT="page">bi goddis lawe, he can not grounde &thorn;is lawe in reson. Summe prestis seyne symply "I assoyle &thorn;e of &thorn;i synnes;" &amp; leyne her hondes on her hedes, or ellis touchen hem wi&thorn; a &yogh;erde. Summe prestis seyne a more raunge; &thorn;ei preyen furst &thorn;at god assoyle hym, &amp; afftur &thorn;ei assoylen hym bi autorite &yogh;ouen to hem.<NOTE PLACE="foot">hym CC.</NOTE> &thorn;e &thorn;ridde maner &amp; leste yuel, &thorn;at men seyn &thorn;at greks han, is &thorn;at &thorn;e prest preye&thorn; &thorn;at god 
<PB REF="00000399.tif" N="333"> assoyle hym &amp; leuyng worde of assoylyng; and &thorn;us he my&yogh;t assoyle at home hym &thorn;at were a &thorn;ousand myle fro hym. and lewed men &thorn;at weren bettur my&yogh;ten &thorn;us assoyle bettur &thorn;enne wickid prestis. ffor it is licly &thorn;at a prest ordeyned to be dampned assoyle&thorn; not &thorn;us; but what prest or man con|fessid wot wher &thorn;is prest shal be dampned. and &thorn;is shrift &thorn;us brou&yogh;t inne seme&thorn; to marre &thorn;e churche in bileeue, as &thorn;e prest made hym goddis felow, as god and he shulden assoile to|gidre; or ellis &thorn;at god mut nedis assoile whenne &thorn;e prest maki&thorn; his sygne. Suche many blassefemys a&yogh;eynes &thorn;e beleue ben sowen of antecrist in &thorn;is mater, ffor god, &thorn;at &yogh;yue&thorn; grace &amp; is in &thorn;e soule, assoyleth &amp; do&thorn; a-wey synne, and &thorn;is may not &thorn;e prest do, si&thorn; it is propur to god, and, si&thorn; no man shuld li&yogh;e a lytle lesyng to saue &thorn;e worlde, a prest shuld not seye, "y assoyle," whenne he not neuer whe&thorn;ir god assoyle. ffor he knowe&thorn; nei&thorn;er wher &thorn;is man confessid seye treu&thorn;e vpon conscyence, or wher &thorn;at he be contrite, as he knowe&thorn; not hym-self; and I suppose he wite &thorn;e so&thorn;e, &yogh;itte he knowi&thorn; not &thorn;e quantite of peyne &thorn;at god wole &thorn;at &thorn;is man haue for hise trespase a&yogh;eynes god, for penaunce is arbitrarie, now more &amp; nowe lesse, aftur &thorn;at &thorn;e prest wole lymyte, be he neuer so grete a fool. And here spryngen many errours a&yogh;ens beleue on bo&thorn;e sydis; for &thorn;e prest gedre&thorn; hym ofte<NOTE PLACE="foot">of CC.</NOTE> moneye or money wor&thorn;e by suche penaunce, and so bi priuey symony he harme&thorn; hem bo&thorn;e &amp; &thorn;e churche. and &thorn;us a frere or a prest ha&thorn; as<NOTE PLACE="foot">CC inserts myche.</NOTE> leue to be seurerly a confessour of a lord or of a<MILESTONE N="131" UNIT="page"> lady as <SUP>3</SUP>to be<SUP>3</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot">3_3 omitted CC.</NOTE> a simple bischop; for bi &thorn;is office he taki&thorn; his worship &amp; his wynnyng, as if he were pope. and it were hard to telle &thorn;e harme &thorn;at come&thorn; be many of &thorn;ise confessours, for &thorn;e pope &amp; &thorn;e emperour my&yogh;te priuely be poysened bi suche fadres, and rewmes my&yogh;ten li&yogh;tly be destruy&yogh;ed by counseilis &thorn;at &thorn;ei &yogh;yuen to lordis, for no drede &thorn;ei ben cause of mennes synne confessid to hem. anentis &thorn;e persone &thorn;at is confessid fallen many errours a&yogh;ens bileeue, as &thorn;at he &thorn;at is 
<PB REF="00000400.tif" N="334"> confessid trowe as bileeue &thorn;at al his synne is for&yogh;yuen be-for god, as &thorn;e confessour telle&thorn; hym. and &yogh;itt it may falle &thorn;at bo&thorn;e &thorn;ise shulen ben dampned for her foly; for ofte &thorn;e confessid is not contrite &amp; turne&thorn; a&yogh;eyne to his synne; and siche treting<NOTE PLACE="foot">tretee MM.</NOTE> &yogh;yue&thorn; occasioun &thorn;at &thorn;ei bo&thorn;e ben disceyued; and &thorn;e man &thorn;at is confessed wene&thorn; &thorn;at god doi&thorn; him wrong if he haue euer more peyne for his synne &thorn;enne &thorn;e prest enioyne&thorn;. and &thorn;us synne my&yogh;t be bou&yogh;t for money, as who by&yogh;e an ox or a kowe; and so riche men haden occasioun to drede not for to synne, whenne &thorn;ei my&yogh;ten for a lytle moneye be &thorn;us assoyled of alle her synnes; and pore men my&yogh;ten dispeire, for &thorn;ei haden not to by&yogh;e &thorn;us synne. Such many errours fallen &amp; fewe men speken a&yogh;eynes hem.</P>
<P>But &yogh;itt &thorn;e feend feyne&thorn; here a lesynge to excuse prestis<NOTE PLACE="marg">C<SUP>m</SUP> 6<SUP>m</SUP> MM.</NOTE> hise seruauntis; he sei&thorn; &thorn;at alle men shulden beleue &thorn;at what man &thorn;at his prest assoyle&thorn;, what ever penaunce he enioyne&thorn;, he is assoiled be-fore god; and &thorn;us popes &amp; prelates kepen to hem silf assoylyng, in which ly&thorn;e wynnyng; and &thorn;us who|euer a&yogh;eyne seye &thorn;is is pursued as an heretike, &amp; &thorn;us by hise olde<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted CC.</NOTE> wiles he knytti&thorn; to-gidre men to helpe popis &amp; cardinales, bischopes &amp; freres to crie &thorn;is as bileeue; &amp; freris mouen lordis &amp; ladies to defend &thorn;is lawe by streng&thorn;e, and bi &thorn;is gile &thorn;ei leden lordis as a man ledi&thorn; a prisoner; &amp; cristis secte is made pore, &amp; &thorn;ise foure ben enhaunsed hi&yogh;e; so &thorn;at, but if crist helpe his secte, &thorn;e foure new wolen brynge <MILESTONE N="131b" UNIT="page">it a-down; and &thorn;ei foure ben knyttid to-gidre in &thorn;is confessioun &thorn;at her maister ha&thorn; tau&yogh;t, as if oon seid to ano&thorn;ur, "helpe me here, &amp; I shul helpe &thorn;ee." a &thorn;us a frere &thorn;at is a confessour to kyng or to a duke is ympe or pere to a bishop, by &thorn;e feyning of &thorn;is confessioun, for &thorn;ei seien he ledi&thorn; his soule eeuen to heuen by goddis lawe. and qwenes, duchesses, and o&thorn;er ladies han confessours of grete name, for as &thorn;ise ladies ben felowes to lordis, so her confessours ben felowis to o&thorn;ur. and &thorn;us &thorn;ise lordis &thorn;at shulden be free, ben oft made &thorn;ral bi ygnoraunce 
<PB REF="00000401.tif" N="335"> <SUP>1</SUP>of suche confessours<SUP>1</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot">1_1 omitted MM.</NOTE>; for assoylinge of suche confessours ha&thorn; lytel vertu or non; but assoilyng of god aftur &thorn;at a mannes liif is wor&thorn;i fordo&thorn;e synne, &amp; punyse&thorn; it til &thorn;at it be fully for|&yogh;yuen. it is seide communly, &thorn;at coupabilnesse of synne is for-&yogh;yuen, and &yogh;it &thorn;at synne dwelli&thorn; to be punyshid, but not for to be dampned in helle. &amp; al &thorn;is &thorn;ing is priuey to god, bo&thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">but CC.</NOTE> to know it &amp; to do it; as an er&thorn;ly lord &yogh;yue&thorn; not to his seruaunt power to for&yogh;yue his trespasse, but &thorn;at he doi&thorn; in his owne wille, &amp; make&thorn; his seruaunt to telle it. miche more god of heuen for&yogh;yue&thorn; synne, when he knowe&thorn; man &thorn;at he is wor&thorn;i for sorowe of herte &amp; for treue seruyce &thorn;at he doi&thorn; aftur. and &thorn;us it is a blasfemy &thorn;at confessours seyn in &thorn;is mater, &thorn;at &thorn;ei for&yogh;yuen synne don a&yogh;ens god, &amp; treten peyne aftur her lykyng. Al &thorn;is is propur to god, but whi shulde he make hem here his felowis? and it shal be shewed aftur, &thorn;at &thorn;is beleue may not be grounded; but &thorn;e feende is about to turne falsehed in-to treu&thorn;e, and turne hope in-to bileue, &amp; dedis of hate in-to charite; &amp; &thorn;us fredam, &thorn;at crist gaf to hise children, he wole turne falsely in-to &thorn;raldam. for now it is a lordly &thorn;ing to have sich a proper confessour, and god wot, but &thorn;e lord wot not, wher he be a feend of helle; and algatis if he feyne hym power to assoyle more &thorn;enne he ha&thorn;; for by <MILESTONE N="132" UNIT="page">sich ypocrisie may he drawe hem bo&thorn;e to helle, and do harme to &thorn;e churche &thorn;us more &thorn;enne he do&thorn;e on &thorn;e to&thorn;ur syde.</P>
<P>And &yogh;itt it semi&thorn; &thorn;at suche prestis &thorn;at heren confessiouns oblischen hem folily to here &thorn;us confessions; and so non were discrete prest &thorn;us shryuyng, as &thorn;e popes lawe biddi&thorn;. and &yogh;itt &thorn;e pope biddi&thorn; in his lawe &thorn;at confessours be discrete, &amp; &thorn;ei here aloon mennes synnes; but it seme&thorn; vndiscretly spoken, for it were better ioyne two prestis to be witnesse of mannes shrifte. for two witnessis ben bettre &thorn;enne oon, &amp; more acordyng to goddis lawe; for bo&thorn;e in &thorn;e oolde lawe, &amp; in &thorn;e newe, men tolden commynly her synne; as &thorn;at &thorn;eef 
<PB REF="00000402.tif" N="336"> tolde in &thorn;e crosse to crist hise fordone synne; he shroue hym more medefully, &thorn;enne don <SUP>1</SUP>men now<SUP>1</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot">1_1 omitted CC.</NOTE> rownyng with prestis, for crist telli&thorn; <I>in</I> &thorn;e gospel &thorn;at he behy&yogh;t hym &thorn;at he shulde be wi&thorn; hym in paradise &thorn;at same daye; &amp; sich absolucion &yogh;aue no pope aftur &thorn;is lawe. &amp; if &thorn;ou seist &thorn;at no man wolde shriue hym at oonys to many prestis, &amp; so shulde mannes synne be hidde, &amp; many dampned &thorn;at now ben saued. Certis si&thorn;en &thorn;ei shulde haue shame to telle her synnes &thorn;us to oo prest, &amp; &thorn;is shame is &thorn;e moost part of penaunce, and make&thorn; penaunce more<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted MM.</NOTE> medeful,<NOTE PLACE="foot">nedeful CC.</NOTE> It seme&thorn; it were more medeful<NOTE PLACE="foot">nedeful CC.</NOTE> to shriue togidre to twey prestis. hou oft &yogh;auen men glorie to god shriuyng to mo men &thorn;enne to two; as whenne tweyn prestis seien ny&yogh;e masse, many shryuen hem to bo&thorn;e to-gidre. And but &yogh;if &thorn;is shrift were medeful, &thorn;e churche vsed it wi&thorn;-outen cause. and &thorn;us as men hiden here synnes to shriue hem to|gidre to many prestis, so many men hiden here synnes to shriue hem to oo preest alone. And si&thorn;en prestis han not &thorn;e craft to enioyne a iust penaunce, it seme&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;ei ben foolis to take so grete a charge vpon hem; and if a man &thorn;at slou&yogh; a lord shulde be hanged for<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;is dede MM.</NOTE> his de&thorn;e,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;is dede MM.</NOTE> more shulde &thorn;at leche &thorn;at slou&yogh; a mannes soule be hanged of god for his foly. see we what penaunce was <MILESTONE N="132b" UNIT="page">sumtyme enioyned to men &thorn;at synneden greuously, and see we penaunce nowe enioyned; &amp; &thorn;ise two a-corde ful litil, and as lawers moten graunt &thorn;at &thorn;is penaunce writen was goode; so &thorn;ei moten graunt &thorn;at synners lyuen as longe as summe of hem diden, and it were as myche nede to leye now as myche penaunce to summe, as was &thorn;enne nede to many of hem; and &thorn;us noo prest &thorn;at lyue&thorn; nowe ha&thorn; &thorn;is craft to leye euen &thorn;is penaunce. what wisedam were &thorn;enne to make &thorn;is lawe, or prestis to take &thorn;is craft on hem? and specialy si&thorn; prestis ben bounden on grete peyne to hele &thorn;is synne; and hit my&yogh;t fellen in many caice &thorn;at it were bo&thorn;e almes &amp; nede to shewe mennes synne &thorn;at ben shriuen, but 
<PB REF="00000403.tif" N="337"> whi shulden prestis ben punyshed herfore? Men han<NOTE PLACE="foot">MM inserts seen.</NOTE> writen in latyn many resouns ageyne &thorn;is shrift.</P>
<P>Men dreden here to seie &thorn;e treu&thorn;e, but summen &thorn;enken &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="marg">C<SUP>m</SUP> 8<SUP>m</SUP> MM.</NOTE> it standes in &thorn;is; &thorn;at confession made to god, wi&thorn; wor&thorn;i penaunce ioyned &thorn;erwi&thorn;, is better &thorn;an &thorn;is<NOTE PLACE="foot">any CC.</NOTE> confessioun made to any prest or pope. but I wot &thorn;at &thorn;ise newe confessiouns han don myche good in &thorn;e churche, &amp; &thorn;erwi&thorn; myche harme; and god woot whe&thorn;er was more of hem. and it is certeyne &thorn;at &thorn;is newe shrifte be-gan by ordynaunce of &thorn;e pope, for no man can telle ellis hou &amp; whenne &thorn;is shrifte beganne, and &thorn;is witnessi&thorn; her propur doctour of &thorn;e popes lawe opynly; and so it seme&thorn; to many men &thorn;at &thorn;is lawe shuld not be holden as goddis lawe ne euer more, but in &thorn;at tyme whenne reson of god shulde moue mennes consciens &thorn;at &thorn;is confessioun wold don hem good. and if any man aske more, he axi&thorn; more &thorn;enne god wole axe, for god ordeyne&thorn; neuer a lawe ne men to perfourme it but if &thorn;is lawe were grounded in resoun, and men shulden perfourme it wi&thorn; wille; for ellis it were noo meede<NOTE PLACE="foot">nede CC.</NOTE> to do it, but if it were wilful sumtyme; and &thorn;us &thorn;is <MILESTONE N="134" UNIT="page">lawers han nede to grounde &thorn;is lawe vpon reson, &amp; to teche wheche ben able prestis to here &thorn;us mennes confessioun; for ellis shuld no man bi resoun telle &thorn;us his schrift to any prest. and &thorn;us men of conscience wolen not telle here &thorn;us her synne to prestis; for &thorn;ei seyne &thorn;at no prest is able, but oonly crist, to here &thorn;us shriftes; and if eny diffame hem or pursue hem by &thorn;is lawe, &thorn;ei baden shewe hem an able prest to here &thorn;us synnes of hem, and &thorn;ei wolen ble&thorn;ely shryue hem &thorn;us, and ellis not, as &thorn;is lawe techi&thorn;. but what prest &thorn;at it be, &thorn;at is synful &amp; couetouse, &amp; proferi&thorn; him &thorn;us to here mennes schrifte, shewi&thorn; himself vnable &thorn;erby? for if he had not couetise of worldly goodis &amp; subiectioun of folk, he shuld preche to &thorn;e puple, &amp; leue al siche rownyng &thorn;at is un|grundid; for sich preching by cristis lawe made many men to leue her synne, but I rede not in goddis lawe &thorn;at &thorn;is rownyng made euer man iust; and if it dide, it was becase, 
<PB REF="00000404.tif" N="338"> as a wronge may sumtyme make ri&yogh;t; and algatis synful men &thorn;at han prestis suspect of couetyse &amp; of vnkunnyng in &thorn;is craft shuld kepe &thorn;is shrift fro sech prestis. but begynne we at &thorn;e pope, &amp; aske him of dedly synne, &amp; hou men shulden know contricion, &amp; whi siche penaunce shal be enioyned; and it seme&thorn; to many men &thorn;at alle &thorn;e popes &amp; &thorn;ere clerkis kunnen not telle on of &thorn;ise &thorn;re; and &thorn;erfore &thorn;ei wolen shryue hem to god. general schrifte &amp; opyn to man wole &thorn;ei make, &amp; &thorn;at is I-now&yogh;, so &thorn;at it come of contricion &amp; treue penaunce &thorn;at men speken of.</P>
<P>For it were not to &yogh;yue occasion to horde synne &amp; to holde<NOTE PLACE="marg">C<SUP>m</SUP> 9<SUP>m</SUP> MM.</NOTE> it, &thorn;erfor men shulden by goddis lawe moue men to forsake synne, and &thorn;us shulden prestis do be prechyng; but antecrist ha&thorn; suspendid hit now. man shuld have sorowe of his synne, for gretnesse of &thorn;e kynd lord, &amp; harm of leesing of his grace, &amp; for oblishyng to grete peyne. No man synne&thorn; as we speken here but if he synne <MILESTONE N="134b" UNIT="page">a&yogh;en god, for who euer synne&thorn; not a&yogh;ens hym, be his trespas neuer so myche punyshed here, he may not be dampned in helle &thorn;erfore, and ellis it were no synne of man. &amp; &thorn;us men punyshen ofte men here in mennes courte ful greuously for dedis &thorn;at men callen tres|passes, &amp; &yogh;itt god is not wro&thorn;e for<NOTE PLACE="foot">wi&thorn; CC.</NOTE> hem; but it may falle oft &thorn;at men erren, &amp; punyshen not &thorn;e trespasses of god, ne for &thorn;at it is don a&yogh;ens god, but for mennes wynnyng; or for &thorn;at it misse-liki&thorn; hem. and &thorn;enke we hou a man wole meke him to a worldly lord for trespasse don to hym; &amp; bi oure fei&thorn; god is more lord wi&thorn;outen mesure &thorn;enne any er&thorn;ly kynge; herfore we shulden be meke to god for trespasses &thorn;at we han don to hym, and specialy for his kyndenesse &thorn;at he made vs first of nou&yogh;t, &amp; si&thorn;en bou&yogh;t vs fro &thorn;e fendes prisoun, &amp; giue&thorn; vs aye grace in alle oure goodis; and he is redy to &yogh;yue vs blisse, if we seruen him perfi&yogh;tly. and &thorn;us bo&thorn;e &thorn;e gretnesse of &thorn;is lord &amp; his kyndenesse shuld meue us to sorow for oure synnes. a man ha&thorn; a myche for&thorn;inkyng for leesyng of loue &amp; of an er&thorn;ely lorde; what witt or treu&thorn;e is in &thorn;at man 
<PB REF="00000405.tif" N="339"> &thorn;at sorowe&thorn; not for losse of goddis grace? we han sorowe for losse of two goodis, of worldly goodis, &amp; goodis of kynde; and &yogh;itt we sorowen to lytil for lesyng of goodis of grace; &amp; &yogh;itt &thorn;ei ben &thorn;e moost goodis of &thorn;ise &thorn;re goodis &thorn;at a man ha&thorn;e. and si&thorn;en beleeue techi&thorn; vs &thorn;at men &thorn;at breken goddis hestis, &amp; maken not a-see&thorn;e &thorn;erfore, moten nedis be dampned in helle, Drede of &thorn;is grete peyny shuld moue men to sorowe for synne. &amp; &thorn;us ambrose &amp; gregory seyne &thorn;at &thorn;enne a man ha&thorn; fully sorowe, whenne hym displesi&thorn; fordon synne, &amp; not eft wil synne ageyne; an &thorn;us is &thorn;at man contrite of synne, &thorn;at he vngodeli to god ha&thorn; don, &thorn;at he ha&thorn; perfit wille to leue it, and for no &thorn;ing wil synne a&yogh;eyne. &thorn;ise men &thorn;at han<MILESTONE N="135" UNIT="page"> a litil displesyng &amp; ben ful ny&yogh; to synne a&yogh;eyne han no penaunce of her synne, be &thorn;ei neuer so oft I-shriuen; and &thorn;us &thorn;e shrift &thorn;at is &thorn;us made make&thorn; men hardy to synne a&yogh;eyne, for contricioun mut be groundid in sad loue of ihesu crist, so &thorn;at contricioun seye sad sorowe for synne &thorn;at is don, and sadde loue to synne not a&yogh;eyne, as myche or more as was likyng to synne. and &thorn;is kunne not we knowe ful certeyne, but han glymeryng &amp; supposyng, &amp; &thorn;us we moten lyue here in beleue &amp; in hope to crist, &thorn;at ri&yogh;t entent &amp; goode werkis grounde vs in hope, &thorn;at crist wole saue vs. and he &thorn;at trusti&thorn; to popis bulles or assoylinge fro peyne &amp; synne, or o&thorn;ur wordis of confessours, &thorn;at &thorn;ei feynen<NOTE PLACE="foot">eynen CC.</NOTE> bisyde goddis lawe, is folily disceyued in hise bileue &amp; in hope, &amp; &thorn;us he dispeyre&thorn;; but we shulden beleue &thorn;at grace of god is so gret &amp; plentyuouse, &thorn;at if a man synne neuer so miche ne so longe in his lyue, if he wole aske of god mercye &amp; be contrite for his synne, god wole for&yogh;yue him his synne wi&thorn;outen siche iapes feyned of prestis. but be men war of &thorn;is perile, &thorn;at continuaunce of mannes synne wi&thorn;outen sorowe &amp; displesaunce wole make his synne harde, &amp; bereue him power to sorowe &thorn;erfore, &amp; to gete mercy, and &thorn;us men shulden euer drede synne, &amp; flee to knytt on to a-no&thorn;er; for whenne a man synkis in &thorn;e myre, at &thorn;e laste he may not helpe hym self.
<PB REF="00000406.tif" N="340"></P>
<P>It were to witt to assoyle skils &thorn;at antecrist maki&thorn; a&yogh;ens<NOTE PLACE="marg">C<SUP>m</SUP> 10<SUP>m</SUP> MM.</NOTE> &thorn;is waye. ffurst he sei&thorn; &thorn;at heretikes wolun distruy&yogh;e &thorn;e seuen sacramentis; for &thorn;at stondi&thorn; in confessioun of mou&thorn;, &amp; sorow of hert, &amp; a-seet makyng, and herfor sei&thorn; david in<NOTE PLACE="marg">Psalm 1 xxi. 22.</NOTE> his boke: "&thorn;ou god &thorn;at art my god, I shal synge to &thorn;e in an harpe." an harpe ha&thorn;e &thorn;re partis of hym; &thorn;e ouermost in which ben stringis wrastid, &thorn;e secounde is &thorn;e holow part of &thorn;e harpe, &thorn;e &thorn;ridde knytte&thorn; &thorn;ise two to-gidre. Ri&yogh;t so in<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted CC.</NOTE> &thorn;is sacrament mut be contricioun for &thorn;e furst part, &amp; aftur a man mut <MILESTONE N="135b" UNIT="page">synge to god in voice for &thorn;e secound part, and &thorn;e &thorn;ridde tyme he must make a-see&thorn; &amp; knytt &thorn;ise two partes to-gidre. what herityke or fool is he &thorn;at wold distru&yogh;e &thorn;is gostly harpe? here men seyen &thorn;at trewe entent shuld be to declare ri&yogh;t beleue, hou men shulden harpe here to god, as david did &amp; o&thorn;er seyntis; for many kunne not<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted CC.</NOTE> wrast &thorn;is harpe, &amp; o&thorn;ur kunne not harpe whenne it is di&yogh;t. Suche wittis gyuen to goddis worde ben goode whenne &thorn;ei ben wele taken; and &thorn;is witt &thorn;at here is seid telli&thorn; &thorn;at a man shulde shriue hym to god, &amp; maki&thorn; no mynde of rownynge shrift, &thorn;at is late brou&yogh;t inne bi &thorn;e pope. and iche man &thorn;at holdi&thorn; beleeue grante&thorn; &thorn;at a man shuld shriue him to god, &yogh;e, &amp; to man, bi voice of mou&thorn;e, and haue sorow for his synne, &amp; &thorn;erfor make to god a-see&thorn; for synne; but &thorn;is is<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted CC.</NOTE> don apertly to prestis, when &thorn;ei ben good &amp; louen more &thorn;e heele of mennes soules &thorn;enne her goodis by coueytise. but here men shulden vndurstonde &thorn;at &thorn;e curtesie of god aski&thorn; not of iche man to shriue him &thorn;us by voice of mou&thorn;e; for as many synnen greuously wi&thorn;-inne in herte, as did &thorn;e fend, so many men maken asee&thorn; bi sorow of herte, &thorn;at may not speke or wante&thorn; oportunytee to shryue hym to man bi voice; and ri&yogh;t so as a man may synne, so he may here make asee&thorn;e; for god is as redy to &yogh;yue mercy as he is redy to take veniaunce. triste wele to god &amp; holde his lawe, &amp; &thorn;enne &thorn;ou shriuest &thorn;e wele to him; &amp; synge to him wi&thorn; ten stringis, &thorn;at ben kepinge of &thorn;e ten hestis; and sorowe of trespasse a&yogh;eyns hem 
<PB REF="00000407.tif" N="341"> ten shal wraste &thorn;is harpe to a-corde welle. and many men failen in &thorn;is wrastyng &amp; in goostly syngyng aftur; and so &thorn;is priuey sorowe of herte is no sacrament of &thorn;e churche, ne priuey rownyng late brou&yogh;t inne, for sacramentis ben open &amp; knowen. but whenne a man wi&thorn; contrite herte shriue&thorn; him opynly to god or man, &thorn;enne his voice, &thorn;at is token of his hooly sorowe of herte, may be cal<MILESTONE N="136" UNIT="page">led a sacrament, as men knowen &thorn;at discriuen it. &amp; &thorn;us we largen in sacramentis, for iche good sensible dede &thorn;at we don, or &thorn;at springi&thorn; of mannes charite, may be callid a sacrament; and &thorn;us &thorn;re reisyngis of dede bodies &thorn;at crist dide, as &thorn;e gospel telli&thorn;, may be called &thorn;re sacramentis, for &thorn;re turnyngis of man to god. Summe men turnen to god wi&thorn;-inne, &amp; summe aftur &thorn;at &thorn;ei han synned wi&thorn;-outward, and summe fro <SUP>1</SUP>&thorn;at &thorn;ei han<SUP>1</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot">1_1 &thorn;at &thorn;at CC.</NOTE> synned in custom; and &thorn;us &thorn;e rysyng of &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted MM.</NOTE> lasar was a grete sacrament, as men reden in &thorn;e churche. and antecrist may bigyle foolis bi sich lewde resouns as he maki&thorn;, but goddis lawe telli&thorn; wele &thorn;e falshed of suche resouns.</P>
<P>And &yogh;itt grucche&thorn; antecrist, and sei&thorn; &thorn;at crist telli&thorn; in &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="marg">C<SUP>m</SUP> 11<SUP>m</SUP> MM.</NOTE> gospel how crist specified to petre to &yogh;yue hym &thorn;e keyes of heuen; and so petre mut haue a viker &thorn;at shuld specialy bere &thorn;e keyes, and &thorn;ise keyes shulden opyn &amp; bynde to for-&yogh;yue synnes, and opyn men heuen, &amp; to curse o&thorn;ur men &thorn;at don a&yogh;en goddis lawe.</P>
<P>Here we seyne be goddis techyng &thorn;at mich errour is in &thorn;is poynt. Summe ben so ny&yogh; beestis, &thorn;at &thorn;ei vndurstonden bodily key&yogh;es, by whiche heuen &yogh;ates shulden be openid and stokune,<NOTE PLACE="foot">sperid MM.</NOTE> &amp; petur is porter in &thorn;is office. &thorn;e secounde errour in &thorn;is poynt is more perelouse in &thorn;e churche, for pharesees alargen her browes &amp; gogelen fer<NOTE PLACE="foot">foule MM.</NOTE> fro goddis lawe; &thorn;ei seyn &thorn;at &thorn;ise keyes ben goostly wittis &amp; power, &yogh;yuen to hem to bynde &amp; assoile men aftur &thorn;e witt approprid to hem; and herby<NOTE PLACE="foot">herfor CC.</NOTE> &thorn;e fend feyne&thorn; oft bi his viker antecrist many errours in &thorn;e churche, &amp; do&thorn;e myche harme to foolis.</P>
<P>The &thorn;ride weye of bileeue sei&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;er ben many key&yogh;es; 
<PB REF="00000408.tif" N="342"> si&thorn; crist, &thorn;at may not synne, calle&thorn; bo&thorn;e &thorn;e keyes of heuenes &amp; &thorn;e &yogh;ates of helle; and no doute to grete witt &thorn;e keyes of heuen ben vndurstonden witt &amp; power, &thorn;at prestis han to telle men &thorn;e wille of god, &amp; to wurche aftur &thorn;is witt; and so god &yogh;aue to petre &thorn;es two keies for him &amp; hise; and af<MILESTONE N="136b" UNIT="page">turward god &yogh;aue to &thorn;e apostles &thorn;es two key&yogh;es for hem &amp; hers. and &thorn;us antecrist au&yogh;te to shame to chalenge oonly petres key&yogh;es, but he had passyngly witt &amp; lijf aftur petur; for if he reuerse him in &thorn;ise two, he is porter of helle &yogh;ates. and &thorn;is witt &thorn;at crist speki&thorn; of stonde&thorn; not in mannes lawe, ne in o&thorn;ur curiouse lawes, as matematik,<NOTE PLACE="foot">makamete CC.</NOTE> or lawes of kynde, but it stonde&thorn; in goddis lawe to holde men in mesur &thorn;erof, &amp; to teche cristen men hou &thorn;ei shulden lyue to god &amp; man, &amp; come to heuen. and I dar not seie for drede of god, &thorn;at &thorn;is power stonde&thorn; in assoilyng &amp; cursyng as men practisen to|daye; for petre forfendid to curse, &amp; vsed not &thorn;is assoilynge; but by autorite of god to preche &amp; to teche cristis weie, &amp; to repreue wickud men bo&thorn;e in word &amp; in dede; &thorn;at seme&thorn; to be &thorn;e power &thorn;at god &yogh;aue petur &amp; his felowes. and it seme&thorn; to many men &thorn;at if a prest presume for pride &thorn;at he ha&thorn; passyngly &thorn;is power, in &thorn;at he<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted CC.</NOTE> shewi&thorn; &thorn;at he wanti&thorn; it; but it seme&thorn; &thorn;at iche prest &thorn;at telli&thorn; trewly &thorn;e lawe<NOTE PLACE="foot">wille MM.</NOTE> of god ha&thorn; &thorn;is power, more or lesse, aftur &thorn;at god wole &yogh;yue him, &amp; mennes rules or mennes chesing<NOTE PLACE="foot">clensyng CC.</NOTE> ben not gospel in &thorn;is poynt, ne any beleue &thorn;at &thorn;ei ben so&thorn;e, if &thorn;e gospel grounde hem not; and &thorn;erfore kepe wele goddis<NOTE PLACE="foot">cristis MM.</NOTE> lawe, &amp; lyue &thorn;ou in bileue of crist. and &thorn;us sumwhat bi &thorn;ise wordis may antecristis resoun be asoyled. But we sufficen not to shewe now &thorn;e errours &thorn;at ben grounded in &thorn;is mater.</P>
<P>But &yogh;itt argue&thorn; antecrist &thorn;at &thorn;is sentence is heresie, for<NOTE PLACE="marg">C<SUP>m</SUP> 12<SUP>m</SUP> MM.</NOTE> crist bad ten leprouse men go &amp; shewe hem to &thorn;e prestis; and bi &thorn;is he tau&yogh;t opynly &thorn;at it nedi&thorn; to be shriuen at prestis, and to &thorn;is crist gaue prestis power, but wherto but to assoyle? Here men seyne aftur austyn, &thorn;at no witt of holi 
<PB REF="00000409.tif" N="343"> writt, but if[it] be literal witt, proue&thorn; ou&yogh;t by autorite of it; but &thorn;e literal witt is &thorn;is: crist bad ten leprouse men go &amp; shewe hem to prestis, as it was boden in &thorn;e <MILESTONE N="137" UNIT="page">olde lawe, but &thorn;ise prestis in &thorn;e oolde lawe assoileden not rownyngly, as we don nowe, but bi signes of goddis lawe &thorn;ei sheweden wheche men weren leprouse, &amp; which weren not leprouse, and to her iugement shulden men stonde. but crist tau&yogh;t in &thorn;is gospel &thorn;at he cam not to destru&yogh;e &thorn;e lawe, but to fulfille it, as he telli&thorn; be-fore bi mathewe; and to &thorn;is entente crist bad &thorn;e mesels<NOTE PLACE="marg">Matt. v. 17.</NOTE> go and shewe hem to prestis. and &thorn;us freris my&yogh;ten telle &thorn;e puple &thorn;at holy writt ha&thorn; mystily<NOTE PLACE="foot">iustly CC.</NOTE> &thorn;is witt what euer &thorn;ei wolen seye; and &thorn;us men tellen &thorn;at freris tellen &thorn;at what treu&thorn;e &thorn;at &thorn;ei seyne, if it be noteful to &thorn;e puple, &thorn;enne &thorn;at trew&thorn;e is &thorn;e gospel; and &thorn;us alle synnes &thorn;at &thorn;e freris don, or any trew&thorn;e &thorn;at [&thorn;ei] may teche men is &thorn;e gospel of crist. but god forbede &thorn;at it were so; for no drede &thorn;ise mennes defautis ben so&thorn;e, &amp; it is profitable &thorn;at &thorn;ei ben knowen to &thorn;e puple, lest &thorn;at &thorn;ei disceyue hem. &thorn;us men vndurstonden not &thorn;e gospelle of ihesu crist but &thorn;ei taken &thorn;e lettir &thorn;er-off, &amp; aftur vndurstonden it vp &thorn;e grammer, and seyntes han tau&yogh;t &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">&amp; CC.</NOTE> &thorn;at furst witt is &thorn;e gospel. and gyue we to aduersaries here &thorn;at men shulden goo &amp; shewe hem to prestis, for so men diden bifore tyme bo&thorn;e in &thorn;e oolde lawe &amp; in &thorn;e newe, but hou shulde men take of &thorn;is to roune wi&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">wist CC.</NOTE> prestis &amp; &thorn;us to be assoiled? and marke we wele &thorn;is gospels witt, &amp; it seme&thorn; opyn &thorn;erby &thorn;at &thorn;ise ten cammen not to &thorn;e prestis; for crist he-ledde hem by &thorn;e weye, and so &thorn;is gospel techi&thorn; vs hou crist him self clensi&thorn; of synne; &amp; to him is &thorn;is thanke propur, &amp; ney&thorn;ur to pope ne confessour; for crist take&thorn; a-wei &thorn;e synne, &amp; &thorn;ei not, but disceyuen men; &amp; &thorn;us men shulden be aliens, as was &thorn;is samaritan, and turne a&yogh;en &amp; &thorn;anke crist, &amp; not gyue money to &thorn;ise prestis; for crist wole assoyle men wele, al if &thorn;ei gon not &thorn;us to rome. for crist bi his godhed is in iche place of &thorn;e worlde, and bi &thorn;at he take&thorn; away 
<PB REF="00000410.tif" N="344"> synne whenne he maki&thorn; men able &thorn;er-to; &amp; pilgrimage wi&thorn; siche offrynge vnabli&thorn; men oft to be assoyled of god.</P>
<P><MILESTONE N="137b" UNIT="page">But &yogh;itt argue&thorn; antecrist &thorn;at Iames biddi&thorn; men shriue<NOTE PLACE="marg">C<SUP>m</SUP> 13<SUP>m</SUP> MM.</NOTE> her synnes; and no drede god biddi&thorn; bi Iames &thorn;at iche synful man do so; &amp; &thorn;at prestis shuld assoyle men techi&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="marg">James v. 16.</NOTE> crist in &thorn;e risynge of lazar, for crist bad to hise apostlis &thorn;at &thorn;ei shulden vnknytt his bondis. and &thorn;us men shriuen in cristis tyme, whenne Ion baptist washed hem. why shuld not &yogh;itt men do so, bi &thorn;e fourme of holy churche?</P>
<P>Here men seyne &thorn;at it were good to holde &thorn;e fourme of hooly churche, as men diden before &thorn;at tyme &thorn;at &thorn;e fend was vnbounden &amp; &thorn;is lawe made. for &thorn;enne crist assoiled &thorn;icker men &thorn;enne he dide aftur &thorn;e tyme of &thorn;is lawe. and to &thorn;e first autorite &thorn;at is aleggid of Iames epistle; men shulden merke hou Iames biddi&thorn; &thorn;at men shulden shriue iche to o&thorn;ur &thorn;e synnes &thorn;at &thorn;ei fellen inne, &amp; &thorn;us &thorn;ei shulden knowleche mekeli &thorn;e freelte &thorn;at &thorn;ei weren inne, and not oon feyne as an ypocrite &thorn;at he were more hooly before a-no&thorn;ur, &amp; had vertu to for&yogh;yue synne. &amp; &thorn;is worde &thorn;at Iames speki&thorn; maki&thorn; not for &thorn;e emperour prelatis; for bi &thorn;is word &thorn;at Iames speki&thorn; iche man shulde shriue him to his bro&thorn;ur, and knowleche mekely &thorn;e freelte &thorn;at he is inne. si&thorn; crist sei&thorn; &thorn;at iche man &thorn;at hi&yogh;e&thorn; himsilf shal be lowid, hou shuld not &thorn;ise emperour prelatis be lowid bi &thorn;e sentence of crist, si&thorn; &thorn;ei hi&yogh;en hemsilf wi&thorn;-outen skil of &thorn;ing &thorn;at is approprid to crist? and &thorn;us &thorn;ise emperour prelatis synnen a&yogh;en &thorn;is worde &thorn;at Iames biddi&thorn;. And as a-nentis &thorn;e secound worde &thorn;at crist bad to hise apostlis whenne he had qwickened lazar, he brou&yogh;t him out of his sepulcre al knyttid in hise bondis, &amp; bad hem to vnbynde him. &THORN;is mysty witt of &thorn;ise dedis telli&thorn; vnto true men &thorn;at crist appropri&thorn; to himsilf to qwiken dede men gostly, &amp; to make hem stonde in grace. but &yogh;itt crist leue&thorn; bondis of synnes, &thorn;at ben yuel costoms to falle in synnes, and crist <MILESTONE N="138" UNIT="page">biddi&thorn; apostlis &amp; prestis to vnknytt &thorn;ise bondis bi trewe preching. but &thorn;is office is dispised<NOTE PLACE="foot">suspended MM.</NOTE> &amp; cristes owne 
<PB REF="00000411.tif" N="345"> office is misse-taken; for now prestis prechen not to &thorn;ise men &thorn;at ben conuertid bi grace of crist, but &thorn;ei seyn &thorn;ei fordon synne and &thorn;at is more &thorn;enne any prechynge, and &thorn;us &thorn;ei gon bifore crist, &amp; leuen &thorn;e maundement &thorn;at he biddi&thorn;, and antecrist can-not dispreue &thorn;is witt bi resoun ne godis lawe. And as a-nentis &thorn;e &thorn;ridd worde, &thorn;at men &thorn;at weren baptized of Ione confesseden here synnes, &amp; so shulde we; I graunt &thorn;is word &thorn;at is seid, but &thorn;e gospel sei&thorn; ne&thorn;ir &thorn;at &thorn;ei shrouen her synnes to Ion, ne bi &thorn;is rounynge to prestis. but it is lickly &thorn;at ychone of hem shryuen mekely his synne to o&thorn;ur, and so her baptym was medeful.<NOTE PLACE="foot">nedeful CC.</NOTE> &amp; so what man shryue&thorn; him mekely to god or to man, no drede god for&yogh;yue&thorn; him his synne, &amp; &yogh;yue&thorn; him grace; but &thorn;is falle&thorn; not euer more whenne a man shriue&thorn; him to &thorn;e emperour clerk; &yogh;e, if he shriue him to &thorn;e pope. &amp; &thorn;us alle autorites &thorn;at ben founden in goddis lawe, &thorn;at <SUP>2</SUP>techen &thorn;at<SUP>2</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot">2_2 omitted CC.</NOTE> men shulden shriue hem, ben to graunt to &thorn;is witt; &thorn;at men shulden shriue hem to god, and in case to her bro&thorn;ur, whenne it profiti&thorn; to hem. but antecrist shulde shame here &thorn;at if men shulden &thorn;us shriue hem, &thorn;enne &thorn;ei shulden telle &thorn;e emperour clerkis in her eeris alle her synnes, &amp; do what &thorn;ei bidden hem do, for ellis god wole not assoile hem. if &thorn;ou be a prest of cristis secte, holde &thorn;e payde of his lawe to teche his puple cristis gospel, al if &thorn;ou feyne &thorn;ee no<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted CC.</NOTE> more power; for crist ha&thorn; &yogh;yue power I-nowe to his prestis to teche his churche; &amp; enioyned hem siche office &thorn;at &yogh;yue&thorn; hem not occasioun to synne. &amp; &thorn;us power &thorn;at prestis han stande&thorn; not in trans|substansinge of &thorn;e oste, ne in makyng of accidentis for to stonde bi hemsilf; for &thorn;is power graunted not god to crist ne to any apostle, and so crist ha&thorn; speciali power to do awey mennes synne; &amp; &thorn;ise miracles &thorn;at ben feyned &thorn;at no man may see ne knowe, as &thorn;ei waxen<NOTE PLACE="foot">weren MM.</NOTE> without profit, so &thorn;ei han no grounde in god.<NOTE PLACE="foot">5_5 only in MM.</NOTE></P>
<TRAILER>Explicit tractatus <SUP>5</SUP>de confessione &amp; penitencia.<SUP>5</SUP></TRAILER>


</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="24" TYPE="tract"><PB REF="00000412.tif" N="346">
<HEAD>XXIV. OF FAITH, HOPE AND CHARITY.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>MR. ARNOLD thought this tract not improbably the work of Wyclif, but did not print it, because he "found it to be a remarkably dull composition and to contain not a single new idea." He may not be alone in this severe judgment; but after several fiercely polemical tracts, it is almost a relief to come upon a specimen of Wyclif's simple evangelical teaching. Even here his foes are not forgotten, and his attack on the friars, and on their teaching as to the Eucharist, marks the tract as a late one. I have very little doubt that it is authentic.</P><P>There is a curious reference in Chapter IV. to Antinomian opinions, which we should not have expected to be prevalent among Wyclif's hearers.</P><P>Copied from the MS. at New College, Oxford (Q), and collated with the Dublin MS. CC.</P><P><TABLE>
