<DIV1 N="25" TYPE="tract"><PB REF="00000422.tif" N="356">
<HEAD>XXV. DE SACRAMENTO ALTARIS.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>IN this little tract Wyclif sums up the difference between his teaching on the Eucharist and that of the friars. It is curious to see him taking up the position of a loyal son of the Church, and complaining that his adversaries accuse the Pope and the Court of Rome of heresy. As the tract is evidently a fragment, it may be that in the larger piece from which it was taken he had alleged some utterance of the Roman see in his favour; perhaps the oath of Berengarius, to which he often appealed, although his opponents might have cited it on their side with at least equal confidence.</P><P>Copied from the Bodleian MS. (A), and collated with the Dublin MS. (AA).</P><P><TABLE>
<HEAD>SUMMARY.</HEAD>
<ROW>
<CELL>The friars say that the bread which Christ broke is neither bread nor his body</CELL>
<CELL>p. 357</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>They accuse the Church of sharing their heresy</CELL>
<CELL>357</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>The true faith is that the Host is both bread and Christ's body</CELL>
<CELL>357</CELL>
</ROW>
</TABLE></P></HEADNOTE>

<PB REF="00000423.tif" N="357">
<EPIGRAPH>
<Q>De sacramento altaris corpus domini.</Q>
</EPIGRAPH>
<P><MILESTONE N="96" UNIT="page">Of<SUP>1</SUP>al &thorn;e<SUP>1</SUP><NOTE PLACE="foot">1_1 omitted AA.</NOTE> fei&thorn; of &thorn;e gospel gederen trewe men, wi&thorn; opyne confescioun of &thorn;es newe ordris, &thorn;at men shulden rette hem eretikis, &amp; so not comyne wi&thorn; hem. for &thorn;ei denyen &thorn;e gospel &amp; comyn bileeue, &thorn;at &thorn;at breed &thorn;at crist took in hise hondis &amp; blesside it &amp; brac it &amp; &yogh;af it to hise disciplis for to ete, was his owne bodi bi vertu of his wordis. &amp; &thorn;us &thorn;ei denyen &thorn;at &thorn;e oost sacrid, whijt &amp; round, &thorn;at bifore was breed, is maad goddis bodi bi uertu of hise wordis. but &thorn;ei seien &thorn;at &thorn;ere is goddis bodi, &amp; &thorn;at is not goddis bodi, but it is nou&yogh;t or accident worse &thorn;an ony breed; &amp; &thorn;us &thorn;ei accusen &thorn;e court of rome, bishops &amp; prelatis, &amp; seien &thorn;at &thorn;ei shulden seie so bi cristen mennys bileeue. &amp; no wondir is, si&thorn; &thorn;es freris accuseden &thorn;er bre&thorn;eren &amp; &thorn;ei<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted AA.</NOTE> bigan first at crist; &amp; seiden &thorn;at he was as<NOTE PLACE="foot">omitted AA.</NOTE> an eretyk, &amp; oure king wi&thorn; his rewme, but hem shamede to seie &thorn;is openli, but &thorn;ei seiden &thorn;is priuyli. &amp; si&thorn; &thorn;ei han lastid so longe in &thorn;is errour <MILESTONE N="97" UNIT="page">cristen men shulden flee hem as he&thorn;en men out of &thorn;e fei&thorn;. &amp; if &thorn;ei somene symple men for &thorn;is accusing, symple men seien &thorn;at &thorn;ei supposen freris siche, but &thorn;ei affermen not hem sich; but euydence &thorn;ei han of &thorn;is errour in bileue, &amp; many o&thorn;ere &thorn;at freris seien, and if &thorn;is be not so&thorn;, late &thorn;es freris purgen hem, for we han herd ofte-tymes many freris techen &thorn;us.<NOTE PLACE="foot">AA. breaks off here.</NOTE> Crist &amp; his apostlis &amp; &thorn;e olde seintis &thorn;at weren til &thorn;at &thorn;e fend was vnboundun, &amp; &thorn;e courte of rome bi open witnesse of her lawe' techen &thorn;is bileue; &thorn;at &thorn;e sacrid oost whijt &amp; round &thorn;at men seen in &thorn;e preestis hondes is veri goddis bodi in forme of breed. but freris, si&thorn; &thorn;e fend fader of lesyngis was vnboundun, seien &thorn;at it is an accident wi&thorn;-outen suget or nou&yogh;t, &amp; mai in 
<PB REF="00000424.tif" N="358"> noo wise be goddis bodi; &amp; so &thorn;ei glosen &thorn;e wordis of holi writt euen to &thorn;e contrarie, &amp; &thorn;ei leuen &thorn;e wordis of holi writt, &amp; chesen hem newe founden termes of hem-silf, &amp; seien &thorn;at &thorn;ei ben so&thorn;, but &thorn;e wordis of holi writt ben false &amp; ful of eresie; and so &thorn;ei seien priuyli &thorn;at crist &amp; hise apostlis &amp; &thorn;es oolde seintis &amp; &thorn;e court of rome weren opyn eretikes.</P>


</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="26" TYPE="tract"><PB REF="00000425.tif" N="359">
<HEAD>XXVI. THE CLERGY MAY NOT HOLD PROPERTY.<LB>WITH AN APPENDIX ON THE WRONGFULNESS OF THEIR UNDERTAKING SECULAR WORK.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>No external evidence authorizes us to attribute this tract to Wyclif. It does not even derive credit from being bound up with other works believed to be his, since it fills the little volume in which only it is found.</P><P>Dr. Shirley admitted it to his catalogue on the ground of style, and it is only on that ground, and for its general consonance with Wyclif's habits of thought, that it can be ascribed to him. I find it very difficult to arrive at a decided opinion. On the one hand, it is more orderly and less vivacious than most of Wyclif's pamphlets; with scarcely any of his characteristic outbursts of lament over abuses or invectives against those who practise them. It relies more, too, on citations of authorities than is his custom. On the other hand, there are passages that look like his work, such as (p. 368) the story of the bishop who looked forward to the time when the gentry should be the hired soldiers of the Church, and the warning (p. 372) that when the clergy have once got power, "the secular party may go pipe with an ivy-leaf," (otherwise whistle for) the return of any part of it.</P><P>In substance the tract is purely Wyclifite, but it has no trace of his latest developments. If it is by the master, it must be one of the earliest compositions in this volume, as it has much more likeness to his writings of 1365-1375 than to those of his latest years. The difference will be strongly felt if it is compared with the Supplementum Trialogi, which deals with the same subject.</P><P>Copied from the Lambeth MS. (LL).
<PB REF="00000426.tif" N="360"></P><P><TABLE>
<HEAD>SUMMARY.</HEAD>
<ROW>
<CELL>CHAP. I.</CELL>
<CELL>To the three persons of the Trinity answer the three states in Christ's Church</CELL>
<CELL>p. 362</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL></CELL>
<CELL>Secular lords to the Father</CELL>
<CELL>362</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL></CELL>
<CELL>Priests to the Son</CELL>
<CELL>362</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL></CELL>
<CELL>Commons to the Holy Ghost</CELL>
<CELL>363</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL></CELL>
<CELL>Each has its own duties, and may not infringe on the province of another</CELL>
<CELL>364</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>II.</CELL>
<CELL>Christ in the old law gave no possessions to the clergy, but ordered them to live on tithes and other offerings</CELL>
<CELL>364</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL></CELL>
<CELL>This law is still binding, since it was confirmed by Christ</CELL>
<CELL>366</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL></CELL>
<CELL>It ought then to be kept more strictly now than under the old law</CELL>
<CELL>367</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>III.</CELL>
<CELL>The lordship of priests is against the commands and the example of Christ</CELL>
<CELL>368</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL></CELL>
<CELL>The priests aim at getting all property into their hands</CELL>
<CELL>369</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL></CELL>
<CELL>They try to stop the mouth of those who would preach the truth</CELL>
<CELL>369</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL></CELL>
<CELL>The secular power of priests is a cause of confusion</CELL>
<CELL>370</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL></CELL>
<CELL>Lords must amend the evil, or they will be guilty of consenting to it</CELL>
<CELL>370</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>IV.</CELL>
<CELL>The evil is great and increasing</CELL>
<CELL>372</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL></CELL>
<CELL>The clergy say they are upholding the rights of Holy Church</CELL>
<CELL>373</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL></CELL>
<CELL>But the chief lord of all property, God, has forbidden them to possess property</CELL>
<CELL>373</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL></CELL>
<CELL>Scriptural and patristic authorities</CELL>
<CELL>374</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>V.</CELL>
<CELL>Silvester committed a great sin in accepting lordship, and was guilty of simony</CELL>
<CELL>377</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL></CELL>
<CELL>Contrast of his behaviour with that of Elisha to Naaman, and with that of Christ</CELL>
<CELL>377</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>VI.</CELL>
<CELL>The deed of Silvester being wrong, the endowment of the clergy, which is founded upon it, must be wrong</CELL>
<CELL>379</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL></CELL>
<CELL>We may blame what Silvester did without blasphemy</CELL>
<CELL>380</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL></CELL>
<CELL>We must follow the saints only so far as they follow Christ</CELL>
<CELL>381</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>VII.</CELL>
<CELL>Covetous clerks allege the example of Hugh and other saints</CELL>
<CELL>382</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL></CELL>
<CELL>It is not safe to take any creature as a pattern</CELL>
<CELL>382</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL></CELL>
<CELL>The clergy bargain and even fight for property</CELL>
<CELL>383</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL></CELL>
<CELL>St. Peter behaved far otherwise</CELL>
<CELL>383</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>VIII.</CELL>
<CELL>The clergy and religious say that they hold their property in common, as did the first Christians</CELL>
<CELL>384</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL></CELL>
<CELL>They say, too, that they hold it not by secular dominion, but as perpetual alms</CELL>
<CELL>384</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL></CELL>
<CELL>They quarrel like lords for rights of jurisdiction and of gallows</CELL>
<CELL>385</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL></CELL>
<CELL>It is not alms to take from secular lords and give to the clergy</CELL>
<CELL>386</CELL>

<PB REF="00000427.tif" N="361">
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>CHAP. IX.</CELL>
<CELL>God provided for all states that he ordained, and he commanded the priests to act as proctors for the poor, and be content with food and raiment</CELL>
<CELL>p. 386</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL></CELL>
<CELL>It is presumptuous to add to a provision made by God and secured by Christ's promise</CELL>
<CELL>388</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL></CELL>
<CELL>Endowment is not alms, and should be taken away from the priest|hood</CELL>
<CELL>388</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL></CELL>
<CELL>Oaths sworn to maintain it are not binding, since it is sinful</CELL>
<CELL>389</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>X.</CELL>
<CELL>It is thought wrong to alienate entailed land from those to whom it is entailed</CELL>
<CELL>390</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL></CELL>
<CELL>God, the chief lord, has given to lay lords in perpetuity all secular lordship</CELL>
<CELL>391</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL></CELL>
<CELL>It is wrong to divert it to the clergy; yet the clergy have laid hands on it, under pretence of holiness</CELL>
<CELL>392</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL></CELL>
<CELL>Laymen should follow the rule of ecclesiastical corporations, which forbid all alienation of property</CELL>
<CELL>392</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL></CELL>
<CELL>The clergy have enough with tithes, offerings and fees</CELL>
<CELL>392</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL>APPENDIX.</CELL>
<CELL>The clergy ought not to take secular office</CELL>
<CELL>393</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL></CELL>
<CELL>Lay lords should not induce them to do so</CELL>
<CELL>394</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL></CELL>
<CELL>Bishops should show lords the peril of thus withdrawing the clergy from their duty</CELL>
<CELL>395</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL></CELL>
<CELL>Lords should look that they do not set up prelates who neglect their duty as watchmen</CELL>
<CELL>395</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL></CELL>
<CELL>Authorities (in Latin) against the secular lordship of priests</CELL>
<CELL>396</CELL>
</ROW>
<ROW>
<CELL></CELL>
<CELL>Authorities against the secular office of priests</CELL>
<CELL>402</CELL>
</ROW>
</TABLE></P></HEADNOTE>

<PB REF="00000428.tif" N="362">
<EPIGRAPH>
<Q><MILESTONE N="2" UNIT="page">Fundamentum aliud nemo potest ponere preter id quod positum est quod est cristus Jhesus.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[1 Cor. iii. 11.]</NOTE></Q>
</EPIGRAPH>
<DIV2 N="1" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>[Capitulum i.]</HEAD>
<P>Almy&yogh;ty god &thorn;e trinyte, fadir, sonne and holy gooste, bo&thorn;e in &thorn;e olde lawe and &thorn;e newe ha&thorn; fowndid his chirche up-on &thorn;re statis, awnswerynge or acordynge to &thorn;es &thorn;re persones and her propirtes. So &thorn;at to &thorn;e fadir in trinyte, to whom is apropred power, awnsweri&thorn; &thorn;e state of seculer lordis, fro &thorn;e hi&yogh;est kny&yogh;te, &thorn;at is, or schuld be, &thorn;e emperoure, to &thorn;e lowest sqwyer &thorn;at by wai of office of his state beri&thorn; &thorn;e swerde. For &thorn;is state in holy chirche saynt poule calli&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="marg">Rom. xiii. [4.]</NOTE> powers, and sai&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;is power beri&thorn; &thorn;e swerde not wi&thorn;-owte cause, but to avenge &thorn;e wra&thorn; of god in-to hym &thorn;at misdoi&thorn;, <MILESTONE N="2b" UNIT="page">and to supporte and mayntene hym &thorn;at wel do&thorn;e. &thorn;is is &thorn;e sentence of poule &thorn;ere. And &thorn;is state or power is &thorn;e vicar of &thorn;e god-heede, as it may be growndid here. And as saynt Austyn sai&thorn; in &thorn;e booke of qwestyons of &thorn;e olde lawe and &thorn;e newe, and in o&thorn;er dyuers placis. And so as it bylongi&thorn; to &thorn;e godheed of criste to avenge hym on his ennemys and to rewarde his trewe saruandis, as god hymsijlfe sai&thorn;, as &thorn;e apostle rehersi&thorn;: "To me," sai&thorn; god,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Rom. xii. 19.]</NOTE> "it longi&thorn; to do vengance and I schal rewarde." And also &thorn;e prophete sei&thorn; &thorn;at "god shal rewarde euery man aftir his werkis." So it by-longi&thorn; here up-on er&thorn;e to &thorn;e state of seculere lordis, as vicars of &thorn;e godhede, to do in ponyschynge and rewardynge to <MILESTONE N="3" UNIT="page">&thorn;e ennemyes and seruandis of god.</P>
<P>To &thorn;e secunde persone in trinyte, to whom is apropred wisdam or kunnynge, awnsweri&thorn; &thorn;e state of &thorn;e clergy or of presthode; &thorn;e whiche by bissy study and contemplacyon schulde gete hem heuenly kunnynge, wherby &thorn;ai schulde teche &thorn;e peple &thorn;e way to heuen and lede hem &thorn;er-inne. 
<PB REF="00000429.tif" N="363"> And herfor sai&thorn; god by his prophete Malachie: "Labia<NOTE PLACE="marg">Mal. ii. [7.]</NOTE> sacerdotis custodiunt scienciam, et legem exquirunt ex ore ejus, quia angelus domini exercituum est"&mdash;"&thorn;e lippis of &thorn;e prest kepyn kunnynge, and the pepille schul seke &thorn;e lawe of his mou&thorn;e, for he is &thorn;e awngell of god." And herfor criste, supposynge &thorn;at &thorn;is heuenly kunnynge schuld be in the state of presthode, commaundid hem alle in his ascencyon in &thorn;o wordis &thorn;at he saide to <MILESTONE N="3b" UNIT="page">his apostles, and in hem to alle o&thorn;er prestis, as saynt awstyn sai&thorn; in a sermon &thorn;at bigynne&thorn; &thorn;us: "Si diligenter attendites etcetera," &thorn;at &thorn;ai schulden teche and preche &thorn;e gospelle to his peple, &thorn;e whiche gospel is heuenly kunnynge. For &thorn;is state in &thorn;e chirche is &thorn;e vicar of &thorn;e manhede of criste, as saynt austyn sai&thorn; in a booke &thorn;at is alegyd to-fore. And so as criste cam in his manhede to teche and preche &thorn;e gospelle and to suffre meekly persecucion &thorn;erfore, so schulde &thorn;e state of prestis, &thorn;at ben vicaris of his manhede, do as he commaundit hem in his ascencyon and oft-times byfore.</P>
<P>To &thorn;e &thorn;ridde persone in trinyte, to whom is apropryd true loue or goode wille to &thorn;e fadir &amp; sonne, <MILESTONE N="4" UNIT="page">awnsweri&thorn; &thorn;e state of &thorn;e comonte, &thorn;e whiche owi&thorn; true loue &amp; obedyente wille to &thorn;e statis of lordis &amp; prestis, as saynt poule teche&thorn;, saynge: "Serui obedite dominis vestris carnalibus cum omni<NOTE PLACE="marg">Eph. vi. [5.]</NOTE> timore et tremore," &thorn;at is: "Seruandis obeyi&thorn; to &yogh;our temporalle lordis wi&thorn; alle drede and tremblynge." Also saynt poule sai&thorn; &thorn;us: "Obedite prepositis vestris; ipsi enim<NOTE PLACE="marg">Heb. xiii. [17.]</NOTE> vigilant tanquam reddituri racionem pro animabus vestris:" &thorn;at is: "obei&thorn; to &yogh;oure souereyns; forso&thorn;e &thorn;ai waken as for to &yogh;eue acowntis for &yogh;oure soulis." By &thorn;es souereyns is undir|stonde &thorn;e state of presthode; &thorn;e whiche schulde bisyly wake in studiynge and prechynge of goddis lawe to alle cristen peple, and to &yogh;eue goode ensaumple in her lyuynge. And in &thorn;is euery man <MILESTONE N="4b" UNIT="page">is bonden to obey to her doctrine. And &thorn;erfore poule sai&thorn;: "Be &yogh;e fylowers of me as I am of criste."<NOTE PLACE="marg">[1 Cor. xi. 1.]</NOTE> And efte he sai&thorn;; "&thorn;ou&yogh; we or an awngelle of heuen preche<NOTE PLACE="marg">Gal. i. [8.]</NOTE> to &yogh;ou bysidis &thorn;at &thorn;at we han prechid, be he acursid." And 
<PB REF="00000430.tif" N="364"> so bi &thorn;is sentence prestis schulden not haue worldly lorde|schippis; si&thorn; criste and his apostles han uttirly forfendid hem, bo&thorn;e in her lyuynge and techynge, as it sui&thorn; playnly her-aftir. For it was neuer cristis lore to make prestis riche and kny&yogh;tis pore. And so &thorn;es &thorn;re statis ben, or schulde be, sufficient in goddis chirche; or ellis men mosten say &thorn;at god is and was fawty in ordenance of bo&thorn;e his lawis. And in full euydence and open tooknynge &thorn;at god taki&thorn; &thorn;is or|denance in his chirche <MILESTONE N="5" UNIT="page">as full sufficient, and in no wise fawtye in scarste or excesse &thorn;er-of, criste, &thorn;e wisdam of &thorn;e trinyte, by whiche wisdome &thorn;e chirche is ordend and fowndid up-on &thorn;es &thorn;re statis, techi&thorn; us in all his lawe to kepe &amp; to mayntene &thorn;is ordenance with-owten addynge &thorn;er-to or abregynge &thorn;er-fro. wherfor poule sai&thorn;: "no man may putt an o&thorn;er grounde bysidis &thorn;at &thorn;at is putt, &thorn;e whiche is criste ihesu."</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="2" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum ij.</HEAD>
<P>hEre it schal be schewid how god hati&thorn; worldly lordeschip in &thorn;e state of his clergye, &thorn;at schulde performe the perfeccyon of &thorn;e gospell. For in &thorn;e olde lawe, wher god made an ordynance how &amp; wher-wi&thorn; &thorn;ai schulde lyue in every state, he assigned &thorn;e worldly possescyons to &thorn;e<MILESTONE N="5b" UNIT="page">seculer party, and bad &thorn;at prestis schulde by no way haue eny possescions wi&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="marg">Num. xviii. [20.]</NOTE> &thorn;at o&thorn;er partye of &thorn;e peple. Saue &thorn;e people was chargid of god to ordeyn &thorn;e prestis and deeknys housis, not to be lordis of hem but to dwelle in hem. And on &thorn;e same wise &thorn;ai hadden subarbis to fede &thorn;er &thorn;e beestis &thorn;at schuld be offred sacrifice to god in &thorn;e temple. And god saide he wolde be &thorn;e parte of &thorn;e prestis and deknys; &thorn;at is to mene, &thorn;at &thorn;o &thorn;ingis &thorn;at I schal assigne to hem, &thorn;e whiche &thorn;ingis ben offred to me, schal be her parte and her lyuynge. And so god assignyd to &thorn;e prestis and deknys &thorn;e first fruytis and ti&thorn;is and o&thorn;er certeyn deuocyons of &thorn;e peple, &thorn;e whiche was lijflode I|now&yogh;e 
<PB REF="00000431.tif" N="365"> <MILESTONE N="6" UNIT="page">for hem wi&thorn; alle her seruandis and o&thorn;er meyn&yogh;e. And he chargid sore and harde &thorn;e peple to &thorn;enke on his clergi, and &thorn;at &thorn;ai defraude not hem of &thorn;e parte &thorn;at god ha&thorn; assignyd to hem. For &thorn;ai hadden noone o&thorn;er possesyon amonge &thorn;e o&thorn;er peple, ne eny schuld haue. So &thorn;at goddis parte was &thorn;us assignyd to &thorn;e trybe or kynrede of leuy; of &thorn;e whiche kynrede wern goddis prestis in &thorn;e old lawe, and of noone o&thorn;ere. And &thorn;is ordynance of god as tochynge &thorn;e liflode of prestis was kept ful streytly, so fer for&thorn;e &thorn;at &thorn;o &thorn;ingis &thorn;at wer offrid to god in &thorn;e temple by deuocyon of &thorn;e peple, &thorn;e whiche wer not by &thorn;e lawe of god expresly assigned to the kynrede of leuy, weren kept <MILESTONE N="6b" UNIT="page">fro &thorn;e use of &thorn;at kynrede to &thorn;e comon profete of alle &thorn;e peple; as to &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="marg">4 Kings xii. [4-15] and xxii. [4-7.]</NOTE> repaire of &thorn;e temple, and to rawnson &thorn;e kynge and &thorn;e rewme at nede, as scripture beri&thorn; witnesse in the tyme of goode kyngis Joas &amp; Josias. For si&thorn; god had assigned lyflode to &thorn;e kynrede of leuy aftir his owne witte, and he may not be fawty in his worchinge or ordenance, it had ben a dampnable presumpcion for to haue ordend more lijflode to hem. And not-wi&thorn;stondinge &thorn;at kynge dauyd, purposynge to encrese &thorn;e worschip of god in his peple, ordend syngers and players in dyuers musical instrumentis to serue byfore god in &thorn;e temple; &yogh;it presumyd he not to take eny &thorn;inge &thorn;at god had assigned to &thorn;e temporall parte of his peple, and endowe wi&thorn; siche goodis &thorn;es <MILESTONE N="7" UNIT="page">mynystres of &thorn;e temple; but he chese &thorn;es men of &thorn;e tribe or kynrede of leuy and lett hem lyue on her owne parte, and so kept &thorn;e temporalte hoole wi&thorn;-owte eny peyr|ynge &thorn;erof. And salamon his sonne, the wisest kynge &thorn;at euer was, dide &thorn;e same. And si&thorn; kynge dauid, &thorn;e chosen of god aftir his owne herte &amp; full of &thorn;e spirite of prophecye, and salamon his wise sonne also, durste not chawnge &thorn;e ordenance of &thorn;e goodis mouable and vnmouable, &thorn;e whiche god had by|take to her gouernance, and make prestis ryche, as &thorn;ou&yogh; god had not sufficiently ordend for hem in his lawe. And wi&thorn; &thorn;is, not-wi&thorn;stondynge &thorn;at kynge dauyd was so fulle of vertuous and kyngly condycions &thorn;at he is sett in scripture as 
<PB REF="00000432.tif" N="366"> a patrone &amp; ensaumple <MILESTONE N="7b" UNIT="page">of alle goode kyngis, how dar oure kyngis, &thorn;at han not &thorn;es &yogh;iftis of god, so expresly a&yogh;ens goddis lawe, &thorn;e olde and &thorn;e newe, presume to ouerturne all the gloriouse ordinance of god a-bowte siche temporaltes, and make the state of presthode lordis a&yogh;ens &thorn;e lyfe and &thorn;e lore of criste and his apostles, and a&yogh;ens &thorn;e proces of &thorn;e olde lawe in &thorn;is poynte, confermyd bi &thorn;e newe? In whiche he ha&thorn; so openly, in worde, dede, and in ensaumple, tau&yogh;te and commaundit hem &thorn;at &thorn;ai schuld not be lordis so. And understonde &thorn;u here, &thorn;at whan &thorn;er is eny &thorn;inge dampned of god in &thorn;e olde lawe, if &thorn;e same be dampnyd in &thorn;e newe, alle &thorn;e euydence &thorn;at ben a&yogh;en syche a defawte in &thorn;e olde lawe ben euen a&yogh;ens &thorn;e same <MILESTONE N="8" UNIT="page">in &thorn;e newe. And so all &thorn;e lawis &thorn;at god &yogh;aue by moyses a&yogh;ens &thorn;e worldly lordeschip of prestis of &thorn;e olde lawe be euen a&yogh;ens &thorn;is, &thorn;at prestis schulde be lordis so in &thorn;e newe lawe. Si&thorn; &thorn;at moyses lawe is moralle in &thorn;is poynte, &thorn;at longe&thorn; to &thorn;e perfeccyon of presthode, criste my&yogh;te not distroy &thorn;es lawis nei&thorn;er dispens wi&thorn; hem, &thorn;at prestis schulden not now be bunden to &thorn;es lawis. And si&thorn; criste and his colage my&yogh;t not be dispensid wi&thorn; ne be exempte fro &thorn;e bondis of &thorn;e olde lawe in &thorn;is mater, I merueyle wher &thorn;e pryuelegis commen alonde wherby owre colagis of monkis, chanons or eny o&thorn;er endowid prestis &thorn;at dwellen in siche conventycles claymen to be exempt fro &thorn;is bonde of &thorn;e olde lawe <MILESTONE N="8b" UNIT="page">in this poynte, &thorn;at in so many placis so opynly forfendi&thorn; hem siche lordeschip; for &thorn;us it is writen: "Dixit<NOTE PLACE="marg">Num. xviii. [20.]</NOTE> dominus ad aaron In terra eorum nichil possidebitis nec habebitis partem inter eos Ego pars et hereditas tua in medio filiorum israel. filiis autem leui dedi omnes decimas israel in possessionem pro ministerio quo seruiunt mihi in tabernaculo. Nichil aliud possidebunt decimarum oblacione contenti, quas in usus eorum et necessaria separaui"&mdash;"&thorn;e lorde sayde to aaron, and in hym to alle &thorn;e tribe or kynred of leuy, of &thorn;e whiche kynred wer &thorn;e prestis &amp; deeknys: &yogh;e schal haue no possescyon in &thorn;e londe of &thorn;e childern of israelle. I am &thorn;ine part &amp; &thorn;ine erytage in &thorn;e myddis of &thorn;e sonnys of israelle. And I have 
<PB REF="00000433.tif" N="367"> &yogh;oue to the sonnys of leuy alle &thorn;e ti&thorn;is of <MILESTONE N="9" UNIT="page">israel in-to possescion, for &thorn;e seruyce &thorn;e whiche &thorn;ai done to me in &thorn;e tabernacle. &thorn;ai schal haue noone o&thorn;er possessyon, &thorn;ai schal be payde wi&thorn; offrynge and ti&thorn;is &thorn;e whiche I haue departid in-to her vsis and nedis." Also in &thorn;e booke of Deutronomy<NOTE PLACE="marg">Deut. xviii. [1.]</NOTE> god saide thus: "Non habebunt sacerdotes, et omnes qui de eadem tribu sunt, partem et hereditatem cum reliquo populo israelle; et sacrificia domini et oblaciones commedent, et nichil aliud accipient de possescione fratrum suorum"&mdash;"&thorn;e prestis and deeknys, and alle &thorn;o &thorn;at ben of &thorn;e same tribe, schal not have part and heritage wi&thorn; &thorn;at o&thorn;er peple of israel; for &thorn;ai schal ete &thorn;e sacrifyce and &thorn;e offryngis of &thorn;e lorde, and &thorn;ai schal taake no &thorn;inge ellis of &thorn;e possessyon of <MILESTONE N="9b" UNIT="page">her bre&thorn;ern." Also it is writen &thorn;us: "Tribui autem leui non dedit posses|cionem:<NOTE PLACE="marg">Josue xiii. [33.]</NOTE> quoniam dominus deus israel ipse est possescio eorum, ut locutus est illi,"&mdash;&thorn;at is, whan moyses assignyd &thorn;e possescyon of &thorn;e londe of israel amonge &thorn;e peple, he &yogh;aue no possescion to &thorn;e tribe of leuy. For whi, &thorn;e lorde god of israel is &thorn;e possescion of &thorn;at tribe, as he ha&thorn; spoken to hym. Also &thorn;es lawis, &yogh;ouen of god by moyses, &thorn;e holy prophetis tau&yogh;ten. As amonge o&thorn;er we may rede of Ezechiel, &thorn;at taw&yogh;te how &thorn;e prestis &amp; deeknys schuld haue hem-sijlfe to godwarde in lyuynge and sacrifice doynge; for he sai&thorn; &thorn;us: "Non est<NOTE PLACE="marg">Ezec. xliii. [28.]</NOTE> autem eis hereditas, ego autem hereditas eorum: et posses|cionem non dabitis eis in israel, ego enim <MILESTONE N="10" UNIT="page">possessio eorum." "Forso&thorn;e &thorn;er schal be noone heritage to hem; forso&thorn;e I am &thorn;e heritage of hem; and &yogh;e schal &yogh;eue no possescion to hem in israel, for I am &thorn;e possessyon of hem." And saynt Jerom sai&thorn; acordynge her-to: "Clericus nichil preter dominum possidere debet, scilicet, non aurum, non argentum, nec<NOTE PLACE="marg">Ep. xxxiiij.</NOTE> possessiones; quia cum huiusmodi non vult dominus esse pars." "A clerke schal haue no possession but god; &thorn;at is to say, ne&thorn;er gold, ne siluer, or possessions, for wi&thorn; siche god wille not be parte, &thorn;at han more &thorn;an is necessary to performe her office wi&thorn;. Of &thorn;is processe be-fore we may se how expresly god forfendi&thorn; lordeschip to his prestis in &thorn;e olde lawe; and 
<PB REF="00000434.tif" N="368"> &thorn;ai cowde not schake away &thorn;is bonde by a contrari glose, lijke <MILESTONE N="10b" UNIT="page">as oure prestis kan nowe. And bi &thorn;e same bonde oure prestis ben bonden to kepe &thorn;es lawis, as tochynge &thorn;e auoyd|ynge of worldly lordeschipis. And ouer &thorn;at &thorn;ai ben bonden to &thorn;e same by a more perfyte lawe &thorn;an wer &thorn;e prestis of &thorn;e olde testament; &thorn;erfore &thorn;ai schulde be &thorn;e more wi&thorn;drawe fro seculer lordeschip &thorn;an prestis of &thorn;e olde lawe; namely, si&thorn; &thorn;e olde lawe byhoti&thorn; for &thorn;e kepynge &thorn;erof prosperite of &thorn;is lyfe, and &thorn;e gospelle bihoti&thorn; &thorn;e kyngdome of heuen. And so no man may putte an o&thorn;er grounde bisyde &thorn;at &thorn;at is putte &thorn;e whiche is criste ihesu.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="3" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum iij.</HEAD>
<P>MOre ouer we may se how euen a&yogh;ens cristis wordis in &thorn;e gospelle prestis ben &thorn;us lordis, wher criste sai&thorn; &thorn;us:</P>
<P>"Reges gencium dominantur eorum, vos autem <MILESTONE N="11" UNIT="page">non sic"&mdash; "&thorn;e kyngys of he&thorn;en han lordeschip on hem, but &yogh;e not so."<NOTE PLACE="marg">Luke xxii. [25.]</NOTE> And also a&yogh;ens his ensaumple &thorn;ai ben lordis; for whan he was sow&yogh;te to be made a kynge, &amp; so to take in hym worldly lordeschip, he fledde in-to &thorn;e hille and prayde, in toknynge &thorn;at siche lordeschip was contrarie to &thorn;e state of &thorn;e clergi, &thorn;at schuld lyue in contemplacyon. But clerkis nowe lyuen not oonly contrariously to &thorn;is techynge and ensaumple of criste, but also &thorn;ai maken stronge lawis reuersynge bo&thorn;e his wordis and dedis, and letten, in alle &thorn;at &thorn;ai may, hem &thorn;at wolde teche &thorn;e trou&thorn;e of criste. And, by &thorn;is lawe &thorn;at &thorn;ai han made, sum of hem han saide &thorn;at &thorn;ai schuld gete owte of &thorn;e seculer hondis alle <MILESTONE N="11b" UNIT="page">the temporal lordeschip &thorn;at &thorn;ai may, and in no caase delyuer noone a&yogh;en. And &thorn;erfore a gentilman axid a greete bischop of &thorn;is londe: "In caase &thorn;at &thorn;e clergy hadde alle &thorn;e temporal possescyons, as &thorn;ai han now &thorn;e more parte, how schal &thorn;e seculer lordis &amp; knyghtis lyue, &amp; wher-wi&thorn;? si&thorn; god ha&thorn; in bo&thorn;e his lawis alowid her staate and her lijflode." And &thorn;en he awnswerid &amp; sayde &thorn;at "&thorn;ai schuld be clerkis soudyoures, and lyue by her wagis." And certis 
<PB REF="00000435.tif" N="369"> &thorn;is lawe of getynge in of &thorn;es temporaltes and &thorn;es o&thorn;er wordis of &thorn;is bischop ou&yogh;te to be taken hede to. For si&thorn; &thorn;ai han now &thorn;e more part of &thorn;e temporal lordeschips, and wi&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;e spiritualtees and &thorn;e greete <MILESTONE N="12" UNIT="page">mouable tresouris of &thorn;e rewme, &thorn;ai may lightly make a conquest up-on &thorn;at othir party; namely, si&thorn; &thorn;e temporal lordis ben not in noumbre and in ryches lyke as &thorn;ai wer sum tyme; for &thorn;ai ben sotilly spolid of her lordeschipis, in distroyng of her staate and power &thorn;at god sett hem in, and &thorn;e party of &thorn;e clergy in alle &thorn;es poyntis ben encresyd, and so couetously &thorn;ai ben sette up-on &thorn;es goodis &thorn;at &thorn;ai welden now, &amp; mo &thorn;at &thorn;ai hopen to haue, &thorn;at &thorn;ai will not suffre her couetise to be enpugnyd openly ne priuely, als ferr as &thorn;ai may lett it. For &thorn;e gospel of Jon sai&thorn; &thorn;at bischopis and pharises sayden<NOTE PLACE="marg">John xi. [47.]</NOTE> of criste: "If we leuen hym &thorn;us alle men schul byleue in hym, <MILESTONE N="12b" UNIT="page">and romayns schulen comme &amp; take oure place and oure folke." For &thorn;ai dredden hem of criste, &yogh;if his wordis wenten for&thorn;e, &thorn;at romayns schulden comme and fordo prestis and phariseis. As if bischoppis and abbotis spaken to-day to-gedre: "hyde we goddis lawe, lest &thorn;es seculer lordis comme and take oure lordeschippis and fordo oure statis." "And fro &thorn;at day," &thorn;e gospel sai&thorn;, "&thorn;ai &thorn;ou&yogh;ten to sle criste." So now by more malyce &thorn;ai killen hem &thorn;at techen &thorn;e trou&thorn;e of cristis gospelle. and in &thorn;at &thorn;ai suffre not criste to be alyue in &thorn;e sowlis of his peple bi qwike faythe, whiche commi&thorn; by knouleche of his lawe, &thorn;at &thorn;ai so cruely hyden fro &thorn;e peple; &amp; &thorn;is is more cruel killynge of criste &thorn;an to kille hym bodely in his owne persone, <MILESTONE N="13" UNIT="page">for &thorn;er-of came &thorn;e mooste goode to mankynde, &thorn;at is, saluacion of &thorn;o &thorn;at ben chosen to blisse. But of &thorn;at o&thorn;er maner of killynge of criste by hidynge of his lawe may no goode comme; for it is a&yogh;ens &thorn;e plesance of criste, &amp; mooste lykynge to &thorn;e fende and lesynge of soulis. And &thorn;erfore saynt poule sai&thorn;: "Si<NOTE PLACE="marg">[2 Cor. iv. 3.]</NOTE> opertum est euaungelium nostrum: hiis qui pereunt est opertum: in quibus deus huius seculi excecauit mentes in|fidelium" (2 cor. 4)&mdash;"&yogh;if &thorn;e gospel is hid, it is hid to hem 
<PB REF="00000436.tif" N="370"> &thorn;at perschen, in &thorn;e whiche god of &thorn;is worlde ha&thorn; blyndid &thorn;e mynde of unfei&thorn;ful men." And &thorn;us whoso bi&thorn;enki&thorn; hym what maner malyce was practisid a&yogh;ens criste by bischopis and scribis and religious in tyme of his bodily presence here, &thorn;e same malice in kynde <MILESTONE N="13b" UNIT="page">he schal fynde, &yogh;he uphepid, in oure byschopis and religious. And as &thorn;e peple of israel wern werste gouernyd undir her prestis, whan &thorn;e gouernance was commen holy in-to her hondis, and undir &thorn;at gouernance come in her mooste confusion &amp; losten &thorn;e holy londe for euer; so ben now cristen rewmys foule confoundid by worldly gouernaunce and lordeschip &thorn;at prestis han take up-on hem. And alwey as &thorn;ai getyn more &amp; more of &thorn;is, so to more confusion drawen cristen rewmys. And for crist wolde not &thorn;at prestis schulde haue syche worldly gouernance, he sai&thorn; to alle men: "Reddite que sunt cesaris cesari, &amp; que sunt dei deo"&mdash;"&yogh;eldi&thorn; to cesar &thorn;o &thorn;ingis &thorn;at ben of cesar,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Luke xx. [25.]</NOTE> and to god &thorn;o <MILESTONE N="14" UNIT="page">&thorn;ingis &thorn;at ben of god"; confermynge to &thorn;e seculer party of the chirche &thorn;e material swerde wi&thorn; his purtenance in &thorn;e persone of cesar, in whom &thorn;at tyme was chefly &thorn;is swerde, wi&thorn; alle &thorn;e temporaltes &thorn;at longen &thorn;erto. And certis I drede not but &thorn;at &thorn;e seculer party of &thorn;e chirche, &amp; namely &thorn;e lordis, han als myche or more coloure of &thorn;e firste party of &thorn;is texte to chalenge oonly to hem &thorn;e tem|poral swerde, wi&thorn; his purtenances &thorn;at longe&thorn; &thorn;erto, as seculer lordeschipis wi&thorn; seculer iugement &amp; seculer offyce, as oure prestis han euydence of &thorn;e secunde party of &thorn;is tixte to chalenge &thorn;e ti&thorn;is of &thorn;e peple, as &thorn;ingis oonly longynge to hem. And if &thorn;ai wer indifferent, as &thorn;ai demen &thorn;at it is wronge and <MILESTONE N="14b" UNIT="page">dampnable a seculer man to take up-on hym a prestis office, in prechynge or minystrynge of sacramentis, and in disposynge of ti&thorn;is, &thorn;at weren lymyted to &thorn;e state of &thorn;e clergy, so &thorn;ai schulden deme it fulle dampnable a prest to ocupie &thorn;e temporal swerde, wi&thorn; &thorn;e purtenance &thorn;at longi&thorn; &thorn;er-to specified to-fore. And in full witnes &thorn;at &thorn;is lordeschip is dampnable in &thorn;e state of presthode, crist, in whom is full ensaumple and lore of perfeccyon of presthode, fled alle &thorn;es 
<PB REF="00000437.tif" N="371"> &thorn;ingis; for he auoidid &thorn;is swerde in seculer office, and tau&yogh;te his apostles, and in hem alle o&thorn;er prestis, to do &thorn;e same whan he fled fro &thorn;e peple &thorn;at wolde han sett hym in &thorn;e office of a kynge. And whan he was requirid to &yogh;eue iugement bitwene two bre&thorn;ern <MILESTONE N="15" UNIT="page">stryuynge for heritage, he wolde not &yogh;eue &thorn;at seculer iugement, but saide: "Homo, quis me<NOTE PLACE="marg">Luc. xii. [14.]</NOTE> constituit iudicem aut diuisorem super vos?"&mdash;"Man, who made me a iuge or a departer up-on &yogh;ou?" And so he auoidid &thorn;is swerde, and left it to &thorn;e temporal party of his chirche wi&thorn; all &thorn;e purtenances. And &thorn;is same lesson tau&yogh;te &thorn;e apostle: for saynt poule assigne&thorn; &thorn;is swerde to &thorn;e seculer lordis, as it is saide bifore, and techi&thorn; men to pray firste for<NOTE PLACE="marg">[1] Tim. ii. [2.]</NOTE> suche men; &thorn;at &thorn;e peple mai lede a pesable lyfe undir hem. And he techi&thorn; cristen men to obey to hem whedir &thorn;ai ben<NOTE PLACE="marg">Eph. vi. [5.]</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="marg">Titus iii. [1.]</NOTE> cristen or he&thorn;en; &yogh;e, all-&thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;ai ben tirawntes. And saynt<NOTE PLACE="marg">1 Peter ii. [13.]</NOTE> petir techi&thorn; &thorn;e same lesson, and biddid &thorn;e peple to obey to &thorn;e kynge, as to hym &thorn;at is passynge <MILESTONE N="15b" UNIT="page">o&thorn;er, &amp; to duykys as to &thorn;o &thorn;at ben sent of &thorn;e kynge, in-to &thorn;e vengance of schrewis &amp; preysynge of goode men. And as touchynge &thorn;is seculer lordeschip, saynt petir techi&thorn; how &thorn;er schulde be no lordis in<NOTE PLACE="marg">[1] Peter v. [3.]</NOTE> &thorn;e clergy; and &thorn;is worde most nedis be vndirstonden of seculer lordeschip, &thorn;e which criste his maistir bifore forfendid to alle his clergi. Si&thorn; &thorn;an &thorn;at &thorn;is lordeschip of &thorn;e clerkis is so openli a&yogh;ens &thorn;e wille of god, schewid in bo&thorn;e his lawis, and so &thorn;ai offenden god deedly, &amp; euer schulen while it duri&thorn; in hem, it wer tyme &thorn;at cristis chirche toke hede to cristis wordis, &thorn;e whiche he spak to petir figurynge &thorn;is chirche, and saide: "turne &thorn;e swerde in-to his place"; as &thorn;ou&yogh; crist <MILESTONE N="16" UNIT="page">wolde say &thorn;us: "&thorn;ou my chirche, figurid bi petir, se how &thorn;e material swerde wi&thorn; his purtenances is owte of his place; &thorn;erfor do as I commaundid &thorn;e, and turne &thorn;is swerde in-to his place wi&thorn; his purtenancis, as secular lordeschipis, seculer office &amp; seculer iugement, in-to &thorn;e seculer arme of my chirche, as I haue ordeyned." And certis, but if &thorn;e chirche here effectualy &thorn;is worde of criste, schal it neuer stonde in redy rule, ne aftir &thorn;e plesance of god; and &thorn;erfore lordis schulden take hede fulle tendirly to 
<PB REF="00000438.tif" N="372"> &thorn;is voyce of criste &thorn;at sai&thorn;: "turne &thorn;is swerde a&yogh;eyne in-to his place;" for whi &thorn;is apostasie of &thorn;e clergie will not oonly be cause of dampnacion of hem sijlfe, but also of alle <MILESTONE N="16b" UNIT="page">&thorn;o &thorn;at mai<NOTE PLACE="marg">Rom. i. [32.]</NOTE> amende &thorn;is &amp; done not. For saynt poule sai&thorn; he is not oonly wor&thorn;i de&thorn; &thorn;at do&thorn;e yuel &thorn;ingis, but also he &thorn;at consenti&thorn; to &thorn;e doer. Forso&thorn;e alle &thorn;o consenten &thorn;at done not her power to amende syche defawtis. And &thorn;erfore no man may putt an o&thorn;er grounde bisidis &thorn;at &thorn;at is putt, &thorn;e whiche is criste ihesu.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="4" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum iiij.</HEAD>
<P>nE&thorn;elesse of o &thorn;inge I pray &yogh;ou here, &thorn;at &yogh;e greue &yogh;ou not, all-&thorn;ou&yogh; I for&yogh;ete not li&yogh;tly &thorn;e materialle swerde wi&thorn; his purtenances, and &thorn;at I desire hertly &thorn;at it wer turnyd a&yogh;en in-to his kyndely place, wher god hym sijlf had putt it. For whan crist was in &thorn;e hondis of his enmyes, wher co<MILESTONE N="17" UNIT="page">munly men for&yogh;eten hem sijlfe &amp; all &thorn;at &thorn;ai han to do, &yogh;it he by&thorn;ou&yogh;te hym on &thorn;is swerde, and saide to petir, &amp; in hym to all his clergye: "turne &thorn;e swerde in-to his place." And it wer nede &thorn;at cristis chirche toke tente to &thorn;is word by-tymys; for &thorn;is swerde wi&thorn; his purtenance may be drawe so fer owte of his place &thorn;at it wille be vnpossible to brynge it a&yogh;en. For &thorn;us it stondi&thorn; of &thorn;is swerde in fulle many londis, wher clerkis han fully &thorn;e seculer lordeschipis in her power; &amp; it is ful like for to stonde in &thorn;e same wise wi&thorn;-in a few &yogh;eris in ynglonde, but if &thorn;e kny&yogh;thode of &thorn;is rewme sett &thorn;e sonner honde upon &thorn;is swerde to brynge it in-to his kyndely place. For well my&yogh;te we se<MILESTONE N="17b" UNIT="page">uer &thorn;at slepe of litergi &thorn;at is fallen up-on vs, &thorn;at &thorn;e clergi ha&thorn; fro day to day more &amp; more honde vp-on &thorn;is swerde wi&thorn; his purtenance. And so &thorn;ai ben likly durynge &thorn;is slepe in &thorn;e seculer partye to pull &thorn;is swerde owte of &thorn;e seculer honde sodenly, and so to haue fulle power &thorn;erof, as clerkis in o&thorn;er diuers londis han. And wete lordis well &thorn;at, if &thorn;e clergi gete &thorn;is swerde oonys fully in her power, &thorn;e seculer party may go pipe wi&thorn; an yuy lefe for eny lordeschipis &thorn;at &thorn;e clerkis wille &yogh;eue hem a&yogh;en; for it wer a&yogh;ens &thorn;e lawe &thorn;at &thorn;ai 
<PB REF="00000439.tif" N="373"> han made as touchynge siche lordeschipis; bi &thorn;e whiche lawe &thorn;ai ben bonden to gete in-to &thorn;e clergie als myche of &thorn;e possescions as &thorn;ai may, and in no caas to &yogh;eue eny siche <MILESTONE N="18" UNIT="page">lordeschipis a&yogh;en in-to &thorn;e seculer honde. And &thorn;is lawe, as experience techi&thorn; vs, is streytly ynou&yogh; kepte amonge hem. For alle day it is seen &thorn;at seculer men &yogh;euen her temporall possessions to &thorn;e clergi; but cowde I neuer seen ne here &thorn;at eny siche lordeschipis wern &yogh;euen a&yogh;en to &thorn;e seculer party. Ne&thorn;eles I wote welle &thorn;at &thorn;e clergi will sai here, &thorn;at all her bissynes &thorn;at &thorn;ai han in &thorn;is worlde a-bowte siche lordeschipe, as in stryuynge, pletynge, chydynge, and fi&yogh;tynge, is for the ry&yogh;te of holy chirche. But certis it is merueyl how &amp; by whos autorite &thorn;is ri&yogh;te cam a place. For welle I wote &thorn;at god is fulle lorde of alle &thorn;is worlde aboue and also of the erthe bine&thorn;e, as &thorn;e prophete dauyd sai&thorn;: "Domini est terra &amp;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Psalm xxiv. 1.]</NOTE> plenitudo <MILESTONE N="18b" UNIT="page">eius"&mdash;"&thorn;e er&thorn;e and &thorn;e plente &thorn;erof is &thorn;e lordis." And welle I wote &thorn;at &thorn;er is no lorde here of &thorn;e er&thorn;e, but if he hold of hym as chefe lorde, &amp; haue his lordeschip &amp; hold it by autorite of &thorn;is lorde god. And wel I wote for&thorn;ermore &thorn;at &thorn;is chefe lorde ha&thorn; &yogh;eue a decre vp-on his clergi, bo&thorn;e in &thorn;e olde lawe &amp; in &thorn;e newe, &thorn;e whiche may not be reuokid ri&yogh;tfully; &thorn;at none of &thorn;e clergye, &thorn;e whiche is ybonden by his astate &amp; office to sue criste in &thorn;e perfeccion of &thorn;e gospelle, schulde eny siche lorde be; as it is schewid openli before by autorite of bo&thorn;e &thorn;e lawis and by &thorn;e lijfe of criste and his apostles. And &thorn;erfore &thorn;e holy doctoure origene writi&thorn; &thorn;us of<NOTE PLACE="marg">hom. xvi.</NOTE> goode prestis &amp; yuelle: "wolt &thorn;u wite what difference is bitwix &thorn;e prestis <MILESTONE N="19" UNIT="page">of god &amp; &thorn;e prestis of pharao? pharao grawnti&thorn; londis to his prestis; forso&thorn;e god graunti&thorn; none partye in &thorn;e er&thorn;e to his prestis, but sai&thorn;, 'I am &yogh;oure parte.' &thorn;erfore alle &yogh;e prestis of &thorn;e lorde &thorn;at reden &thorn;es &thorn;ingis, take hede &amp; se what is &thorn;e difference of prestis; lest &thorn;ai &thorn;at han parte in &thorn;e er&thorn;e &amp; taken tente to bissinessis and til&thorn;is of &thorn;e er&thorn;e be not seyn to be prestis of &thorn;e lorde but of pharao; for he wille &thorn;at his prestis haue possessions, &amp; hawnte &thorn;e tylynge of &thorn;e felde &amp; not of &thorn;e soule; he wol &thorn;at &thorn;ai &yogh;eue bissynes to &thorn;e londe, 
<PB REF="00000440.tif" N="374"> &amp; not to &thorn;e lawe. But what criste commaundi&thorn;, here &yogh;e: 'He<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Luke xiv. 33.]</NOTE> &thorn;at forsaki&thorn; not alle &thorn;ingis &thorn;at he ha&thorn; in possession may not be my disciple.' Crist denye&thorn; him to be his disciple &thorn;at ha&thorn; <MILESTONE N="19b" UNIT="page">any &thorn;inge in possess[i]on, and him &thorn;at forsaki&thorn; not alle &thorn;ingis &thorn;at he ha&thorn;; &amp; what do we? how rede we &thorn;es &thorn;ingis oure sijlfe, o&thorn;er how expowne we &thorn;es &thorn;ingis to &thorn;e peple? &thorn;e whiche renounce not &thorn;es &thorn;ingis &thorn;at we han, but we willen gete to vs &thorn;o &thorn;inges &thorn;at we hadden neuer bifore we cam to criste. That is to forsake pouert and bodely trauelle for to haue riches and ese. But certis &thorn;is is contrarie to &thorn;e apostles lijfe, as saynt petir witnessi&thorn;, saynge to criste: what schal be to vs &thorn;at han<NOTE PLACE="marg">Matt. xix. [27.]</NOTE> forsaken alle &thorn;ingis &amp; swen &thorn;e? so petir axed not lordeschip &amp; ese of &thorn;is lijfe to rewarde for his seruyce." And &thorn;erfor &thorn;e holy doctoure Odo in a sermon sai&thorn;, &thorn;at bigynne&thorn; &thorn;us, <MILESTONE N="20" UNIT="page">Ecce, nos reliquimus omnia: "Abel is dede; &thorn;e bissynes of schipard and spiritual mornynge or weylynge is slayne; but cayme, &thorn;at is possession, is kept, &yogh;ee and caym &thorn;e er&thorn;e-tyllere, is made &thorn;e hirde or gouernor<NOTE PLACE="foot">gouer MS.</NOTE> of sowlis. For it is not axyd in &thorn;e chirche if he kan welle teche, or if he kan wepe &amp; weyle for synys, but &yogh;ef he be caym, &thorn;at is an er&thorn;e-tilyere &thorn;at kan welle tille &thorn;e londe. And it is no wondir &thorn;ou&yogh; possession sle ful many, si&thorn; it is venym. For &thorn;e same day &thorn;at the chirche was endowid bi constantyne, &thorn;er was herde a voyce in &thorn;e eyre: 'to-day is venym sched in-to &thorn;e chirche.' for the chirche was made more in dignite but lesse in religion. And if it be axid of siche oone: <MILESTONE N="20b" UNIT="page">'where is &thorn;e schepe &thorn;at was bytaken to &thorn;e?' he awnsweri&thorn; 'whe&thorn;er I am kepar of my bro&thorn;er?' as &thorn;ou&yogh; he sayde, 'what charge is to me of &thorn;e sowlis, so &thorn;at I haue welle ordenyd for &thorn;e temporalle goodis.' Syche ben acursid, as cayme was, &thorn;at led owte &thorn;e schepe abel &amp; brynge hym not a&yogh;en, but disseyuen hym; of whiche god sai&thorn; by &thorn;e prophete Ezechiel, her schipardis han disseyuyd hem." Alle &thorn;is sai&thorn; &thorn;e goode doctour Odo. To siche holy sentence of scripture &amp; doctouris schulden lordis take hede; for saynt ysydre sai&thorn;, 
<PB REF="00000441.tif" N="375"> and it is putt in &thorn;e lawe: "Seculer lordis, pryncis of &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="marg">Ysydori senten|ciarum 1. iii. c. xxi.</NOTE> worlde, schulden well wite &amp; knowe &thorn;at &thorn;ai schal &yogh;elde herd rekenynge &amp; acowntis to god for <MILESTONE N="21" UNIT="page">holy chirche, &thorn;at &thorn;ai han take of criste to kepe &amp; to defende. For as sai&thorn; the law; &thorn;er whe&thorn;er so euer &thorn;at seculer lordis rule holy chirche wel or yuelle, criste schal ax reknynge of hem. For undir seculer lordis power crist ha&thorn; sett &thorn;e rulynge and gouernynge of his chirche." And &thorn;erfore saynt Austyn, in &thorn;e boke of questyons of &thorn;e olde lawe and &thorn;e newe, &amp; in o&thorn;er dyuers placis, sai&thorn; &thorn;at kyngis and lordis ben vicaris of &thorn;e godhede. And saynte poule sai&thorn;: "Not wi&thorn;-oute cause kny&yogh;tis beren swerde, but<NOTE PLACE="marg">Rom. xiii. [4.]</NOTE> to avenge &thorn;e wra&thorn;e of god in-to hym &thorn;at mysdo&thorn;e, &amp; to supporte &amp; mayntene hem &thorn;at done wel."<NOTE PLACE="foot">yuel MS. (This clause is not in the passage referred to.)</NOTE> And for wor&thorn;ines of &thorn;is astate saynt poule techi&thorn; to pray first of alle for kyngis<NOTE PLACE="marg">[1] Tim. ii. [2.]</NOTE> &amp; kny&yogh;tis, &thorn;at god &yogh;eue hem grace to gouern <MILESTONE N="21b" UNIT="page">hem selfe &amp; her peple, &thorn;at &thorn;ai han in gouernance to &thorn;e plesance of god &amp; to hel&thorn;e of her owne sowlis. And herfor saynt petir biddi&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[1] Peter ii. [17.]</NOTE> &thorn;e peple to obey to kyngis, as to hem &thorn;at ben passynge o&thorn;er, &amp; to dukys as to &thorn;o &thorn;at ben<NOTE PLACE="foot">bent MS.</NOTE> sent of kyngis in-to &thorn;e vengance of mysdoers &amp; to &thorn;e praysynge of goode men. And not|wi&thorn;stondynge alle &thorn;es autorites, &thorn;at ben rehersid afore a&yogh;en &thorn;e lordeschipis &thorn;at &thorn;e clerkis occupien expresly a&yogh;ens goddis lawe, as it schal be pleynly proued her-aftir wi&thorn; goddis help, &yogh;it &thorn;ai sayen &thorn;at criste forfendi&thorn; hem not siche worldly lordeschip, saaf &thorn;at &thorn;ai schuld not be lordis aftir &thorn;e pompe &amp; pride of &thorn;is worlde. But &thorn;is fleschly glose &amp; many siche o&thorn;er &thorn;at &thorn;ai han is no &thorn;inge to pur<MILESTONE N="22" UNIT="page"> pose. For god ha&thorn; forfendit pompe and pride to all maner of men, and mysuse of his goodis; for he &yogh;aue neuer man leue to do synne. But vp hap &thorn;u art a clerke or a religious man endowid wi&thorn; many worldly lordeschipis, and art wo &thorn;at euer crist was so yuel avised to say, or &thorn;e euaungelist to write, &thorn;es wordis; &thorn;e kyngis of he&thorn;en han lordeschip upon hem, but &yogh;e not so; and woldist li&yogh;tly, and it wer in &thorn;ine power, do &thorn;is worde &amp; siche 
<PB REF="00000442.tif" N="376"> o&thorn;er owte of &thorn;e gospelle for euer; as waiwerd clerkis wolden in seynt Austyns time haue done owte, &amp; &thorn;ai wisten how, &thorn;is worde of &thorn;e gospelle: "super cathedram moyses sederunt &amp;c."<NOTE PLACE="marg">Matt. xxiii. [2.]</NOTE> "Vpon moyses chayer han siten scribis &amp; pharyseis: alle &thorn;at &thorn;ai schal say to <MILESTONE N="22b" UNIT="page">&yogh;ou kepe &amp; do &yogh;e, but do &yogh;e not aftir her werkis." &thorn;us sai&thorn; Austyn, de uerbis domini, super isto textu. And for als myche as &thorn;u maist not undo for euer suche textis, ne &yogh;it &thorn;u wilt do aftir &thorn;e letter of siche textis; &thorn;erfore &thorn;u saist &thorn;u most haue a glose. wel &thorn;an for goddis loue, If &thorn;u wilt glose &thorn;e textis of &thorn;e gospelle &thorn;at ben so euen a&yogh;ens &thorn;i lordeschip, glose hem as criste did and commaundid &thorn;e to &yogh;eue fulle credence to his glose, whan he saide: "&yogh;if &yogh;e leue not<NOTE PLACE="marg">John x. [38], xiv. [11.]</NOTE> me for my wordis, leue &yogh;e &thorn;e dedis." And if &thorn;u bileue effectualy &thorn;is glose, &thorn;u schalt not oonly forsake &thorn;e lordeschip &thorn;at &thorn;u occupiest, but also, ra&thorn;er &thorn;an &thorn;u schuldist be ocupied &thorn;erwi&thorn;, &thorn;u schalt renne awai &thorn;er-fro &amp; hyde &thorn;e, as cristis<NOTE PLACE="marg">John vi. [15.]</NOTE> glose sai&thorn; &thorn;at he did. and if &thorn;u wilt not bileue ef <MILESTONE N="23" UNIT="page">fectualy cristis wordis ne&thorn;er his glose, &thorn;an &thorn;u wilfully &amp; obstynatly forsakist crist vttirly; and so &thorn;u bycummyst a lymme of anticriste, for no man may putt an o&thorn;er grounde bysidis &thorn;at &thorn;at is put, &thorn;e whiche is criste ihesu.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="5" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum v.</HEAD>
<P>hEre we may se &thorn;at a clerk may not be a lorde, or vir|tuosly occupi so seculer lordeschip. And &yogh;if &thorn;u wilt wete whi, me semi&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;is is a cause sufficient y-nowe. &thorn;at criste ha&thorn; forbodun hem &thorn;is lordeschip in playne wordis, as it is writen ofte to-fore, &amp; glosid &thorn;o wordis wi&thorn; his dedis; for whan he was sou&yogh;te to his passion, he profred hym silfe, but whan he was sou&yogh;te to be a kynge &amp; to haue taake up-on hym &thorn;e material swerde wi&thorn; his purtenances, he fled and <MILESTONE N="23b" UNIT="page">hidde hym self and left &thorn;is swerde hooly in his place; techynge his prestis by &thorn;is ensample to do &thorn;e same. And it is no doute but &thorn;at &thorn;is ensaumple was a commaundement to 
<PB REF="00000443.tif" N="377"> cristis prestis to fle vttirli &thorn;is lordeschip. For as seynt gregory sai&thorn;: "Dominus ihesus cristus aliud nos sermonibus,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Gregorius omelia xvii.</NOTE> aliud vero operibus ammonet. Ipsa enim facta eius precepta sunt, quia dum aliud tacitus facit, quid agere debeamus innotescit." Cristis dedis or ensaumples ben commaunde|mentis what we schulden do. And &thorn;at criste fled &thorn;is temptacion of &thorn;e peple &amp; hidde hymself schuld teche prestis to fle, not oonly &thorn;is synfull &amp; dampnable lordeschip in &thorn;e state of presthode, but also &thorn;at<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. inserts 'but.'</NOTE> &thorn;ai fle &thorn;e occasion or the temptaci[on] <MILESTONE N="24" UNIT="page">&thorn;er-of. And &thorn;is ensaumpled criste in his fleynge and hydynge. And not oonly &thorn;is, but also crist in his doynge dampnyd symony, &thorn;e whiche is takynge, or an unruely wille to take or to &yogh;eue, worldly goode for grace, or bi occasion of grace of god mynystred to eny creature. For whan criste had graciously &amp; by myracle fed &thorn;e peple, &thorn;orow occasion of &thorn;at grace, &thorn;is peple was moued to take hym &amp; make hym a lorde; but criste, a clere ensaumple of clennesse of prestis, by whom as goddis instrumentis grace is &yogh;ouen to &thorn;e peple as &thorn;is grace was by &thorn;e preste criste, fled &thorn;is &yogh;ifte. And in &thorn;is fleynge of criste fro &thorn;is lordeschip aftir &thorn;e myracle &amp; grace &thorn;at god &thorn;e fadir had ministrid by hym, he dampned <MILESTONE N="24b" UNIT="page">&thorn;e ressauyng of &thorn;e lordeschip &thorn;e whiche siluestre toke of constantyne. And criste commendid &amp; confermyd &thorn;e dede of &thorn;e blessid prophete hely&yogh;e, &thorn;at refusid &thorn;e &yogh;iftis proferid to hym of Naaman after &thorn;e miracle &amp; grace<NOTE PLACE="marg">4 Kings v. [16.]</NOTE> &thorn;at god had done by hym to Naaman. Ne&thorn;elesse for &thorn;e more open knowleche of &thorn;at &thorn;at I moue here, &thorn;u schalt undirstonde &thorn;at &thorn;e casis &thorn;at bitydden bytwene constantyne &amp; siluestre &amp; naaman &amp; heli&yogh;e ben wondir like; for bo&thorn;e &thorn;es seculer men wer grete lordis &amp; mesels, and bo&thorn;e weren helid bi myracle of god, &amp; bi grace mynystred to hem bi &thorn;es two prestis. For Naaman was helid of god bi grace ministred to<NOTE PLACE="marg">4 Kings v.</NOTE> hym bi heli&yogh;e. And constantyne was he[lid] <MILESTONE N="25" UNIT="page">of god by grace ministred to hym bi siluestre, as his storie telli&thorn;. and bo&thorn; 
<PB REF="00000444.tif" N="378"> &thorn;ai wer helid in oon wise, for in water schewid of god to &thorn;es two prestis, and bi &thorn;es two prestis schewid to &thorn;es<NOTE PLACE="foot">to &thorn;es to &thorn;e MS.</NOTE> two sike men. And aftir &thorn;es gracis &thorn;us minystred by &thorn;es two prestis, Naaman proferid to heli&yogh;e wondir grete &yogh;iftis of mouable goodis, and constantyne proferid to siluestre bo&thorn;e mouable &amp; vnmouable goodis in wondir grete plente and excesse. But not-wi&thorn;stondynge &thorn;at naaman prayed fulle hertly heli&yogh;e, &amp; enforsid hym &thorn;at he schuld haue take &thorn;o &yogh;iftis, vttirly he forsoke hem; but siluestre in &thorn;e same case toke &thorn;at &thorn;e emperoure proferid hym, bo&thorn;e &thorn;e grete worldly <MILESTONE N="25b" UNIT="page">aray &amp; &thorn;e wondir grete lordeschipis. And oo grete cause whi heli&yogh;e wold not assent to Naaman to take eny &yogh;iftis of hym in &thorn;is case was for &thorn;an heli&yogh;e had been a symonient, si&thorn; his man giezi, &thorn;at ran aftir naaman and toke &yogh;iftis of hym &thorn;orow occasion of &thorn;at grace so minystred, was a symonyent, not|wi&thorn;stondynge &thorn;at &thorn;at grace was not &yogh;eue by hym in eny wise to Naaman, but &thorn;at he toke &thorn;o &yogh;iftis bi occasion of &thorn;at grace. how myche ra&thorn;er his maister heli&yogh;e, &thorn;at had more kunnynge &amp; was bounden to more perfeccion, schuld haue be a symonyent &yogh;if he had ressauyd &thorn;at goode, si&thorn; &thorn;at grace was ministred to Naaman by hym. And no dowte &thorn;ou&yogh; siluestre had in &thorn;is case ressauyd but mouable goodis, he <MILESTONE N="26" UNIT="page">schulde haue synned more greuously &thorn;an giezi did, or heli&yogh;e schulde &yogh;if he had ressauyd &thorn;at naaman proferid to hym; for siluestir trespassid a&yogh;ens a more perfite lawe. And what bi giezi &amp; balam, what by Judas &amp; symon magus, &thorn;at wer symony|entis acursid of god &amp; ysmyten wi&thorn; goddis vengance, &amp; what bi many faire euydencis of scripture &amp; reson &thorn;at siche a man ow&yogh;t to haue had, he had many grete warnyngis of hydousnes &amp; perille of &thorn;is synne ouer &thorn;at his predecessouris hadden; and alle &thorn;is agregeden hys syn. Here it may be knowen &thorn;at siluestre did not aftir &thorn;e ensaumple of criste, &thorn;at fled whan he schuld haue be made a kynge &amp; hidde hym self and so wi&thorn;-stode it, but he proferid hymself to his 
<PB REF="00000445.tif" N="379"> passion. But <MILESTONE N="26b" UNIT="page">siluestir did on &thorn;e contrari wise; for whan he was sow&yogh;te to passion, he hidde hym sijlfe, as &thorn;e storie of<NOTE PLACE="marg">John xviii. [4.]</NOTE> hym telli&thorn;. And whan he was callid to &thorn;e state of &thorn;e emperoure or worldly dignite, he in a maner proferid hym self; in als myche as he manly wi&thorn;stode not &thorn;e hidous &amp; synfulle purpose of &thorn;e emperoure, but cowerdly consentid to his foly. And certis I drede not &thorn;at he had neuer better cause of martirdome &thorn;an to haue wi&thorn;stonde &thorn;is foli of &thorn;e emperour, in case &thorn;at he wolde by violence haue enforsid hym to &thorn;is lordeschip. For as a man may conceyue, in partye of &thorn;at &thorn;at is saide before, &amp; of euydence &thorn;at wi&thorn; goddis help schal sue her-aftir, &thorn;is wickid dede was peruertynge of cristis ordenances in <MILESTONE N="27" UNIT="page">his chirche, &amp; harmfulle &amp; destruction to euery state &thorn;erof, &amp; will be fynal confusion &thorn;erof but &yogh;if it be remedied. And so &thorn;is man had neuer so grete cause to fle &amp; to hide hym self as whan he was callid to &thorn;is rialte; and &thorn;at he my&yogh;te haue lernyd of criste, &thorn;at schulde haue be his maister, &thorn;at in &thorn;e same case fled &amp; hidde hymself. And &thorn;ou&yogh; vnkunnyngnes my&yogh;te sumdele excuse &thorn;e emperour; &yogh;it &thorn;at my&yogh;t not excuse &thorn;is preste, &thorn;at ow&yogh;te to knowe, as a &thorn;inge chefly bilongyng to his perfeccion, &thorn;at he schulde not be a lorde on &thorn;at wise. For no man may putt an o&thorn;ir grounde biside &thorn;at [&thorn;at] is putt whiche is criste ihesu.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="6" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum vj.</HEAD>
<P>aNd so who so loki&thorn; wel &thorn;e dede of siluestir, it was <MILESTONE N="27b" UNIT="page">ex|presly a&yogh;ens &thorn;e lyuynge &amp; &thorn;e techynge of ihesu criste, as it is openli taw&yogh;t bifore. And si&thorn; &thorn;e endowynge of &thorn;e clergi is groundid vp-on &thorn;is dede, we may se by &thorn;is processe how &thorn;e clergi is wondirfulle enfect wi&thorn; symonye &amp; heresie. For &thorn;is sinne in hem may not be vndo till &thorn;e temporalle lordeschip in hem be distried, whiche ha&thorn; envenemyd alle &thorn;e clergi. &amp; &yogh;if we taake hede to &thorn;is processe, we schal not myche wondir, all|&thorn;ou&yogh; 
<PB REF="00000446.tif" N="380"> &thorn;e awngelle of god, aperynge in &thorn;e eyre in &thorn;e tyme of doynge of &thorn;is wickid dede, saide &thorn;es wordis: "&thorn;is day is venym sched or helt in &thorn;e chirche of god;" as gorram sai&thorn; up|on &thorn;e xij chapitre of &thorn;e apocalips. And &thorn;erfor sai&thorn; <MILESTONE N="28" UNIT="page">saynt Jerom, in vitis patrum: "Si&thorn; &thorn;e chirche encresid in posses|syouns, it ha&thorn; decresid in vertues." And herfore criste &thorn;at was in lyke case wi&thorn; &thorn;es two prestis, heli&yogh;e &amp; siluestre, in dampnynge of &thorn;is wickid dede &thorn;at ha&thorn; so myche harmyd &amp; envenymyd his chirche, left &thorn;e way of siluestre, &thorn;at toke &thorn;is worldly lordeschip, and chese &thorn;e way of heli&yogh;e &thorn;e prophete, &thorn;at forsoke &thorn;o &yogh;iftis &thorn;at naaman proferid hym, and fled bo&thorn; symony &amp; heresy. And so, as heliye left &thorn;e grete richesse &thorn;at naaman wold haue &yogh;yue hym &amp; tooke wor&thorn;ili &thorn;e pore ordenance &amp; fyndynge &thorn;at a goode man &amp; his wyfe proferid<NOTE PLACE="marg">4 Kings iv. [8.]</NOTE> to hym; &thorn;at is to say, a lytille soler, a bedde, a borde, a chaire, &amp; a kandilstek, &thorn;e whiche <MILESTONE N="28b" UNIT="page">ben acordynge to a studier or a contemplatyfe man; So criste forsoke seculer lordeschipis, &amp; held hym payde wi&thorn; &thorn;e pore liflode &thorn;at deuoute peple ministred to hym to his nedeful sustenance in his labours. And &thorn;us didden also alle &thorn;e apostles, as a man may conceyue of &thorn;e gospelle &amp; in many o&thorn;er placis of her lijfis. For aftir<NOTE PLACE="marg">Luke viii. [3.]</NOTE> tyme &thorn;at god &thorn;e fadir had wrou&yogh;te &thorn;is grete miracle bi criste his preste, in releuynge of fyve &thorn;ousande &amp; mo &thorn;at wern in mysese of hunger, he avoydid siche worldly rewarde &thorn;at schulde haue be &yogh;oue to hym by occasion of minystrynge of &thorn;is grace. Si&thorn; &thorn;an &thorn;at criste &amp; heli&yogh;e acorden to-gydre in &thorn;is case, &amp; siluestre reuersi&thorn; hem bo&thorn;e here; <MILESTONE N="29" UNIT="page">and siche contrarius dedis in casis &thorn;at ben so lijke mow not be glosid to-gedre, &thorn;an we most nedis, &yogh;if we will go a sure way, magnifie in worde &amp; dede &thorn;e doynge of heli&yogh;e &amp; of criste in &thorn;is case; si&thorn; &thorn;at heli&yogh;es dede is commendid in scripture, and crist is tru&thorn;e and autor of scripture. &thorn;an we moten dampne &thorn;e doynge of gyezi &amp; of siluestre, &thorn;us ferr strayynge away fro heli&yogh;e &amp; criste &amp; his gospelle. And in &thorn;is writynge I blasfeme no more siluestre, &amp; &thorn;es holy men and sayntis &thorn;at han ben si&thorn; &thorn;is endowynge 
<PB REF="00000447.tif" N="381"> of &thorn;e chirche cam in, all-&thorn;ou&yogh; [I] rehers &amp; blame her synne, &thorn;an I do petir &amp; his felowis whan I say &thorn;at &thorn;ai synfully forsoken criste, or poule whan <MILESTONE N="29b" UNIT="page">i say &thorn;at he wickidly pursuyd cristis chirche. for I blame of no &thorn;inge wher-of &thorn;ai schuld be sayntis, no more &thorn;an I do &thorn;es apostles; alle-&thorn;ou&yogh; I blame her synnys, &thorn;e whiche &thorn;ai hem self dampnyd, &amp; wer sori &thorn;at euer &thorn;ai synned so. For petir wept sore for his<NOTE PLACE="marg">Matt. xxvi. [75.]</NOTE> synne, as &thorn;e gospelle sai&thorn;. and saynt poule, mekely knowlech|ynge his synne, saide &thorn;at he was not wor&thorn;i to be callid<NOTE PLACE="marg">[1] Cor. xv. [9.]</NOTE> apostle of criste, and &thorn;at bi-cause &thorn;at he pursuyd cristis chirche. And on &thorn;e same wise siluestre and &thorn;es sayntis diden, or ellis schuld haue do for her synne. For whan we will preyse sayntis, we schul loke wherin &thorn;ai suyd criste and his lawe in worde, dede, or maners, and so ferr &thorn;ai ben wor&thorn;i<NOTE PLACE="marg">Matt. xi.</NOTE> preysynge <MILESTONE N="30" UNIT="page">and no fer&thorn;er; for crist is &thorn;e mesure of vertuous lyuynge &amp; worchynge; and herfore he calli&thorn; alle men to sue<NOTE PLACE="marg">Matt.xxviii.[20.]</NOTE> hym &amp; to lerne of hym, &amp; namely prestis to teche &thorn;at &thorn;at he taw&yogh;te, and &thorn;an we may not erre. And herfore saynt poule<NOTE PLACE="marg">Eph. v. [1.]</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="marg">[should be 1 Cor. xi. 1.]</NOTE> tau&yogh;te cristen peple to sue hym, but no ferrer &thorn;an he sue&thorn; ihesu criste. And saynt petir remitti&thorn; &thorn;e pepille to criste, for to take of hym ensaumple; saiynge &thorn;us: "Crist ha&thorn; suffred for<NOTE PLACE="marg">1 Peter ii. [21.]</NOTE> vs, leuynge &yogh;ou ensaumple &thorn;at &yogh;e filow &thorn;e steppis of hym &thorn;at did no synne, ne&thorn;ir was eny gyle founden in his mou&thorn;e." And so a man may euer saafly sue his lyuynge and techynge wi&thorn;-owte eny errynge; but &amp; we sue in alle &thorn;ingis ei&thorn;er petir, poule, or siluestre, or eny <MILESTONE N="30b" UNIT="page">o&thorn;er synfulle man, we must nedis erre in many &thorn;ingis, as &thorn;ai diden. Loke &thorn;an if siluestre suyd criste whan he forsoke &thorn;e pouert of &thorn;e gospelle &amp; by-cam a lorde vpon &thorn;e west empire of &thorn;e worlde. And if he so did, &thorn;an preyse hym in &thorn;at doynge, &amp; ellis not. for whi no man may putt an o&thorn;er grounde bisidis &thorn;at &thorn;at is putt, &thorn;e whiche is criste ihesu.</P>


</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="7" TYPE="chapter"><PB REF="00000448.tif" N="382">
<HEAD>Capitulum vij.</HEAD>
<P>bI &thorn;is processe bifore saide men mow lerne to awnswere to &thorn;e comon argumentis &thorn;at couetous clerkis maken in &thorn;is mater to mayntene wi&thorn; her synne. In &thorn;e whiche argumen|tis &thorn;ai aleggen for hem &thorn;e sinnes of her predecessoris, saynge &thorn;us, "seynt hue, seynt thomas and seynt swy&thorn;une <MILESTONE N="31" UNIT="page">wer &thorn;us lordis, &amp; &thorn;ai wer holy men here &amp; now ben seyntis in heuen; &thorn;an may we, be &thorn;e same skile, medefulli taake up-on vs &thorn;is temporall lordeschip, and sue hem in &thorn;is." But &yogh;e schal undirstonde &thorn;at &thorn;is maner of arguynge holdi&thorn; welle whan we argue of god; for it suy&thorn; well, "criste did &thorn;us, saide &thorn;us, or wolde &thorn;us, &thorn;erfor &thorn;is was wel done, saide, or willid; &amp; so in &thorn;is dede, worde, or wille, it is holsum, spedy &amp; plesaunt to god &thorn;at we sue hym." But whan we argue of an creature &thorn;is argument is to schorte; for it sue&thorn; not, "Petir saide &thorn;us or did &thorn;us, &thorn;erfore he did or saide welle, and in &thorn;es wordis &amp; dedis it is holsum to sue hym;" for &thorn;is maner <MILESTONE N="31b" UNIT="page">of arguynge is vnpreuyd in &thorn;at &thorn;at petir forsoke criste, &amp; in &thorn;at &thorn;at he smote of malcus ere; so &thorn;at &thorn;is maner of arguynge of a creature is to schorte. And &thorn;erfor &yogh;e most argue &thorn;us: "Petir saide or did &thorn;us, and in &thorn;is saiynge or doynge he suyd &thorn;e life &amp; &thorn;e lore of ihesu criste; &thorn;erfor petir in &thorn;is did or sayde welle, and in &thorn;is it is holsum to sue petir." And so musten oure clerkis argue whan &thorn;ai aleggen for her lordeschip &thorn;e lyuynge of her patrons &amp; sayntis, &amp; sayen &thorn;us: "Seynt thomas &amp; seynt hwe &amp; seynt Swi&thorn;une wer &thorn;us lordis, &amp; in &thorn;is &thorn;ai suyd cristis lyuynge &amp; his lore; &thorn;erfor we may lefulli be &thorn;us lordis." And I wote wel &thorn;at gabriel schal blow his horne or &thorn;ai han preuyd &thorn;e mynor; <MILESTONE N="32" UNIT="page">&thorn;at is, &thorn;at &thorn;es seyntes or patrons in &thorn;is suyden &thorn;e lore or &thorn;e life of ihesu criste. And of &thorn;is &yogh;e may se &thorn;at siche nakid argumentis, &thorn;at ben not clo&thorn;id wi&thorn; cristis lyuynge or his techynge, ben ri&yogh;t nou&yogh;t wor&thorn;e, alle-&thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;e clerkis ablynden wi&thorn; hem myche folke in &thorn;is worlde. But here haue I no leyser to telle, all &yogh;if I kou&yogh;de, what chefesaunce 
<PB REF="00000449.tif" N="383"> and costis &thorn;e clergi maki&thorn;, &amp; what werris &thorn;ai holden to con|tynu &thorn;is symony &amp; heresi so vnauysely brou&yogh;te in-to &thorn;e chirche. And &yogh;it &thorn;ai sechen alle &thorn;e ways &thorn;erto &thorn;at &thorn;ai kan, &yogh;he in so myche &thorn;at [&thorn;ai] gone openli armyd into &thorn;e felde to kill cristen men for to gete and holde siche lordeschipe. And not-wi&thorn;stondynge &thorn;at seynt petir was so pore &thorn;at he had<NOTE PLACE="marg">Acts iii. [6.]</NOTE> ne&thorn;er golde <MILESTONE N="32b" UNIT="page">ne siluer, as he sai&thorn; in &thorn;e dedis of &thorn;e apostles. And his o&thorn;er worldly goode he lefte whan he began to sue criste. And as tochyng &thorn;e tytle of worldly lawe &thorn;at he had to &thorn;at goode, he made neuer clayme, ne neuer resseyued aftir worldly lordeschip. And &yogh;it &thorn;ai callen alle her hoole lorde|schip seynt petirs grounde or lordeschip. And &thorn;erfore saynt bernerd writi&thorn; to ewgeny &thorn;e pope, saiynge &thorn;us: "&yogh;if &thorn;u wilt be a lorde, sike it by an o&thorn;er title but not by &thorn;e apostles<NOTE PLACE="marg">libro ii. [cap. 6.]</NOTE> ry&yogh;te, for he my&yogh;t not &yogh;eue &thorn;e &thorn;at he hadde not: &thorn;at he hadde he &yogh;aue, &thorn;e whiche was bissynes vp-on chirchis; whe&thorn;ir he &yogh;aue lordeschip, here what he sai&thorn;: 'Be ye not lordis in &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="marg">1 Peter v. [3.]</NOTE> clergi, but be &yogh;e made fourme &amp; ensaumple of cristis <MILESTONE N="33" UNIT="page">flokke.' And lest &thorn;u trow &thorn;is to be sayde not of trow&thorn;e, take kepe what crist sai&thorn; in &thorn;e gospelle: '&thorn;e kyngis of he&thorn;en han lorde|schip vp-on hem, forso&thorn;e &yogh;e not so.' Se how pleynly lordeschip is forbodyn to alle apostles; for &yogh;if &thorn;u be a lorde, how darst &thorn;u take vp-on &thorn;e apostilhede? or if &thorn;u be a bischop, how darst &thorn;u take vp-on &thorn;e lordeschip? playnly &thorn;u art forbodyn bo&thorn;e; and &yogh;if &thorn;u wilt haue bo&thorn;e to-gydire, &thorn;u schalt lose bo&thorn;e, and be of &thorn;at noumbre of whiche god pleni&thorn; be &thorn;e prophete ose,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Hosea viii. [4.]</NOTE> saiynge, '&thorn;ai regneden but not be me, sai&thorn; god.' And &yogh;if we holden &thorn;at &thorn;at is forboden, here we &thorn;at is bodyn of criste: 'he &thorn;at is gratter of &yogh;ow, loke &thorn;at he be made as &yogh;ongar <MILESTONE N="33b" UNIT="page">in sympilnes; and he &thorn;at is forgoer, loke he be a seruant.' &thorn;is is &thorn;e forme of &thorn;e apostles lijfe; lordeschip is forbodon, &amp; seruyse is boden." &thorn;is sai&thorn; saynt bernarde &thorn;ere. And &thorn;erfore no man may putt an o&thorn;ere grownde bisidis &thorn;at &thorn;at is putt, &thorn;e whiche is criste ihesu.
</P>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="8" TYPE="chapter"><PB REF="00000450.tif" N="384">
<HEAD>Capitulum viij.</HEAD>
<P>bVt &yogh;it I wote welle &thorn;at and clerkis &amp; religious folke &thorn;at louen unkyndely &thorn;es lordlynes, willen glose here &amp; say &thorn;at &thorn;ai occupien not siche lordeschipis in propir, as seculer lordis done, but in comoun, like as &thorn;e apostles &amp; &thorn;e perfite<NOTE PLACE="foot">profite MS.</NOTE> peple<NOTE PLACE="marg">Acts iv. 32.</NOTE> diden in &thorn;e begynnynge of cristis chirche, &thorn;e whiche hadden alle &thorn;inge in comoun, like as suche clerkis &amp; religious saien &thorn;ai han nowe. In tokenyng wherof as no man sayd of eny <MILESTONE N="34" UNIT="page">&thorn;inge &thorn;at tyme, "&thorn;is is myne;" so oure clerkis &amp; religious, namely, whan &thorn;ai will speke in termis of her religion. A pri|uate persone wille not say, "&thorn;is or &thorn;is is myne," but in persone of alle his bre&thorn;ern he wille say, "&thorn;is is oure." And ouer alle &thorn;is &thorn;ai saien, more sutilly, &thorn;at &thorn;ai occupie not &thorn;is bi title of seculer lordeschip, but be title of perpetual almes. But whateuer &thorn;is peple saien here, we mot take hede to &thorn;e rewle of prefe &thorn;at fayli&thorn; not, &thorn;e whiche rule criste techi&thorn; vs in &thorn;e gospel in dyuers placis, wher he sai&thorn;: "leue &yogh;e &thorn;e werkis, for whi by<NOTE PLACE="marg">John x. [38], and xiv. [11.]</NOTE> her werkis &yogh;e schul knowe hem." And &thorn;is rule is wondir nedefulle to a man &thorn;at ha&thorn; a do wi&thorn; eny men of &thorn;e pha<MILESTONE N="34b" UNIT="page"> riseis condicions; For, as criste sai&thorn;, "&thorn;ai saien but &thorn;ai done not."<NOTE PLACE="marg">Matt. xxiii. [3.]</NOTE> And so as cristis werkis beren witnes of hym, as he hym sijlfe sai&thorn;, &amp; schewdyn what he was &amp; how he lyued; so &thorn;e dedis &amp; &thorn;e maner of lyuynge, or &thorn;e &thorn;inge in it sijlfe beri&thorn; witnesse wi&thorn;-oute fayle how it stondi&thorn; amonge hem in &thorn;is poynte. And if we take hede &thorn;us bi &thorn;is rule we schal se at y&yogh;e how &thorn;e clergie sai&thorn; here o&thorn;er-wyse &thorn;an it is. For in sum place in priuate persone, and in sum place in comunte, or persone aggregate, whiche is alle oone, as saynt austyn sai&thorn; vp &thorn;e sawter, &thorn;e clergi occupie&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">occupier MS.</NOTE> &thorn;e seculer lordeschip seculerli, &amp; so in propre. For in &thorn;e same wise as &thorn;e baron or &thorn;e kny&yogh;te occupie&thorn; &amp; gouerne&thorn; his baronrye or his kny&yogh;tte, 
<PB REF="00000451.tif" N="385"> so after &thorn;e amor<MILESTONE N="35" UNIT="page">tesynge occupie&thorn; &thorn;e clerke, &thorn;e monke or chanon, &thorn;e colage or &thorn;e couente &thorn;e same lordeschip, and gouerni&thorn; it by &thorn;e same lawis in iugement &amp; ponyschinge; as prisonynge &amp; hangynge, wi&thorn; siche o&thorn;er worldly turmentynge, &thorn;e whiche sum-tyme bylongyd oonly to &thorn;e seculer arme of &thorn;e chirche. &yogh;he, oft-tymys we may se how &thorn;ai bissyen hem to be kyngis in her owne, &amp; reioycen hem fulle myche in &thorn;at cyuylite or seculerte, &yogh;if &thorn;ai may gete it. And &thorn;is is an euydence &thorn;at &thorn;ai wold gladly be kyngis of alle &thorn;e rewme or &thorn;e worlde. For wher her londis &amp; seculer mennys franchisen to-gydir, &thorn;ai stryuen who schal haue &thorn;e galows or o&thorn;er maner turmentis for felouns. &thorn;ei kepen also vndir bondage her tenauntis &amp; her <MILESTONE N="35b" UNIT="page">issue wi&thorn; her londis. And &thorn;is is &thorn;e mooste cyuylite or seculer lordeschipinge &thorn;at eny kynge or lorde ha&thorn; on his tenauntis. And &thorn;erfore we may se hou &thorn;ai claymen in her goodis a maner of propre possession, contrary to &thorn;e comounynge of &thorn;e comon goodis in tyme of &thorn;e perfyte men in &thorn;e begynnynge of cristis chirche. And what-so-euer &thorn;e clergye sayen, &thorn;air dedis schewyn welle &thorn;at &thorn;ai han not her goodis in comoun, lyke as criste wi&thorn; his apostles &amp; perfyte men hadden in &thorn;e begynnynge of cristis chirche. For in holdynge or havynge of her goodis is propir of possessyon &amp; seculer lordeschipynge, &thorn;e whiche stondi&thorn; not wi&thorn; &thorn;e plente of cristis perfeccion in prestis; as it sue&thorn; of &thorn;is processe <MILESTONE N="36" UNIT="page">and of &thorn;at &thorn;at is declarid before. And as for &thorn;at o&thorn;er glose &thorn;at clerkis han here, where &thorn;ai saien &thorn;at &thorn;ai holden &thorn;es lordeschipis by title of perpetual almes. But here &yogh;e schul undirstonde &thorn;at mercy or almes is a wille of relevynge of a wreche oute of his mysese, as lyncolnyence sai&thorn; in &thorn;e bygynnynge of his <SUP>*</SUP>dictis. So &thorn;at &yogh;if a man schuld do effectualy almes, he most loke &thorn;at he to whom he schuld do almes wer in mysese and had nede to be releuyd. In<NOTE PLACE="marg">Dicto ii.</NOTE> tokenynge wherof criste oonly assigne&thorn; almes to &thorn;o in whom<NOTE PLACE="marg">Luke xiv. [14.]</NOTE> he marki&thorn; mysese. And so of &thorn;is it wille sue, &thorn;at &yogh;if a man releue oo wreche &amp; maki&thorn; an o&thorn;ere or mo, he do&thorn;e noon almes, <MILESTONE N="36b" UNIT="page">but ra&thorn;er maki&thorn; mysese. And myche more he do&thorn;e 
<PB REF="00000452.tif" N="386"> noone almes &yogh;if he make riche &thorn;o &thorn;at han noone nede, for als myche as &thorn;ai ben sufficiente to hem sijlf. &thorn;is ha&thorn; no coloure of almesse, for &thorn;is may bettir be callid a woodnesse or a wastyng of goddis goodis. And ouer &thorn;is, if a man take &thorn;o goodis &thorn;e whiche god in &thorn;e best wise, euen &amp; wi&thorn;-owte errouris, ha&thorn; assigned to &thorn;e state of seculer lordis, &amp; &yogh;eue &thorn;o goodis to eny peple &thorn;at ha&thorn; noone nede of hem, &yogh;he, to whiche peple siche goodis ben forfendit, &thorn;is schuld be callid noone almesse, but peruertynge of goddis ordynance, &amp; &thorn;e destruccyon of &thorn;e state of seculer lordis, &thorn;e whiche god ha&thorn; aprouyd in his chirche. for as <MILESTONE N="37" UNIT="page">saynt poule sai&thorn;, "Almes-dede schuld be so<NOTE PLACE="marg">[2] Cor. viii. [13, etc.]</NOTE> rewlid &thorn;at it wer relevynge to &thorn;o &thorn;at ressavyn it, and no tribulacion to &thorn;o &thorn;at &yogh;euen it." And myche ra&thorn;er it schuld not be vndoynge of &thorn;o &thorn;at done it. And herfore criste techi&thorn; in &thorn;e gospelle to do almes of &thorn;o &thorn;inges &thorn;at ben needeles or<NOTE PLACE="marg">Luke xi. [41.]</NOTE> superflue. And in &thorn;is dede a man schulde haue rewarde to &thorn;e nede of hym &thorn;at he do&thorn; almes to, and to &thorn;e charge of his owne house. what almes &thorn;an I pray &thorn;e was it to vndo &thorn;e state of &thorn;e emperoure, &amp; make &thorn;e clerkis riche wi&thorn; his lordechipis? namely, si&thorn; crist confermyd to &thorn;e emperour his state wi&thorn; &thorn;o &thorn;ingis &thorn;at longyd &thorn;er-to, not-wi&thorn;stondynge &thorn;at &thorn;e emperoure &thorn;at tyme was he&thorn;en. And he ha&thorn; forfen <MILESTONE N="37b" UNIT="page">dit expresly his clergy in worde &amp; in ensaumple siche lordeschip. And as &thorn;is was noone almes, so we mote say of o&thorn;er kyngys, dukis &amp; erlis, barons &amp; kny&yogh;tis, &thorn;at ben vndo herby, &amp; &thorn;e clerkis made riche &amp; worldely lordis wi&thorn; her goodis. wher|fore it may ri&yogh;tfully be sayde: "No man may putt an-o&thorn;er grounde bi-sidis &thorn;at &thorn;at is putt &thorn;e whiche is crist ihesu."</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="9" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum ix.</HEAD>
<P>hEre we may se, bi &thorn;e grounde of &thorn;e gospelle and be &thorn;e ordenance of criste, &thorn;at &thorn;e clergy was sufficyently purveyed for lyfelode. For god is so parfyte in alle his worchynge &thorn;at he may ordeyn no state in his chirche but if he ordeyn sufficient liflode to &thorn;e sa<MILESTONE N="38" UNIT="page">me state. And &thorn;is 
<PB REF="00000453.tif" N="387"> is open in goddis lawe whoso taki&thorn; heede. And &thorn;at vndir euery lawe of god as vndir &thorn;e law of innocens &amp; of kynde, vndir &thorn;e lawe &yogh;eue by moyses, and also vndir &thorn;e lawe &yogh;ouen by criste. In &thorn;e tyme of &thorn;e state of innocence, we know wel by bileue &thorn;at god had so ordeyned for mankynde, &thorn;at it schulde haue had lyflode I-now; &yogh;he, wi&thorn;-owte eny tenefulle laboure. And of &thorn;e lawe of kynde criste speki&thorn; in &thorn;e gospelle, seyinge &thorn;us: "Alle &thorn;inges &thorn;at &yogh;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">we MS.</NOTE> wollen &thorn;at o&thorn;er<NOTE PLACE="marg">Matt. vii. [12.]</NOTE> men done to &yogh;ou, do &yogh;e to hem." And if &thorn;is lawe had be kepte, &thorn;er schuld no man haue be mischeuously nedy. And in &thorn;e tyme of &thorn;e lawe &yogh;eue by moyses god <MILESTONE N="38b" UNIT="page">made a fulle &amp; sufficient ordenance for alle his peple, and assigned &thorn;e fyrste fruytis and ti&thorn;is to &thorn;e prestis &amp; deeknes. And alle-&thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;at he wolde &thorn;at &thorn;er schulde be alleway pore men in &thorn;e londe of israelle, &yogh;it he made an ordenance a&yogh;ens myschevous nedis, &amp; commaundit alle &thorn;e peple &thorn;at &thorn;er schulde be on no wyse a nedy man and a beggere amonge hem; as it is wryten.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Deut. xv. [4.]</NOTE> And so in &thorn;is lawe he ordeynyd sufficiently I-now for his peple. And in &thorn;e tyme of &thorn;e new lawe criste assignyd &thorn;e seculer lordeschipis to temporalle lordes, as it is tau&yogh;te byfore, and alowid &thorn;e comonte her liflode goten bi true merchandise &amp; hosbondrie and o&thorn;er craftis, and in worde &amp; ensaumple he tau&yogh;te his prestis <MILESTONE N="39" UNIT="page">to be procuratouris for nedy peple &amp; pore at &thorn;e ryche men, &amp; specifyed &thorn;es pore, &amp; tau&yogh;te how &thorn;ai &thorn;at wer my&yogh;ty schuld make a purviance for syche pore folke, &thorn;at &thorn;ai wer not constrenyd by nede for to begge; as grete clerkis merken vp-on &thorn;is worde of &thorn;e gospelle where criste sai&thorn; &thorn;us; "When &thorn;u makist &thorn;ine feeste," &thorn;at is, of almes,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Luke xiv. [12.]</NOTE> "calle pore, feble, lame &amp; blynde." He sai&thorn; not "latt siche pore men calle vp-on &thorn;e," but: "calle &thorn;u;" menynge in &thorn;at, &thorn;at &thorn;u schuldist make a purvyance for siche peple &thorn;at &thorn;ai be not myschevously fau&yogh;ty. And for &thorn;e clergy he ordenyd sufficiently, techinge hem in worde and in ensaumple hou &thorn;ai schuld holde hem apayde wi&thorn; lyflode &amp; helynge, mynystred to 
<PB REF="00000454.tif" N="388"> hem for her true labour <MILESTONE N="39b" UNIT="page">in &thorn;e gospelle, as it is wryten to-fore. Of &thorn;is &thorn;an &thorn;u mayst se hou&yogh; god in alle his lawis ha&thorn; sufficiently ordend for alle &thorn;e statis &thorn;at he foundit and aproued. And hou&yogh; it were a&yogh;ens &thorn;e goodnes and &thorn;e wisdome of god to orden eny state but if he ordend sufficyent liflode &thorn;erto. Si&thorn; &thorn;en &thorn;is ordenance of god was sufficyent, als welle for &thorn;e clergi as for o&thorn;er men, it semi&thorn; a foule presumpcyon to brynge in a new and a contrary ordenance of liflode for clerkis, vp-on &thorn;at ordenance &thorn;at crist had made for hem by-fore. Of &thorn;e whiche ordenance &thorn;e clergy fulle many yere aftir &thorn;e bi|gynnynge of cristis chirche, whan it was best gouernyd, helden hem a-payde. For &thorn;is mene&thorn; &thorn;at cristis <MILESTONE N="40" UNIT="page">ordenance was insufficyent &amp; worthi to be vndo. And if we take goode heede, &thorn;ai hadden no more nede to plene hem of &thorn;is orde|naunce &thorn;an hadden &thorn;e o&thorn;er two statis of his chirche, &thorn;e whiche in-to &thorn;is day holden hem apayde wi&thorn; &thorn;is ordenance of criste, and desyren in grete party &thorn;at &thorn;is fayre and sufficient ordenaunce of criste were fully kepte. And more sikirnes or ensurance may no man make of eny-&thorn;inge &thorn;an criste ha&thorn; of &thorn;is liflode to &thorn;e clergy. For crist not oonly affermi&thorn; to &thorn;e peple &thorn;at he wille not fayle hem in liflode &amp; helynge, but also preue&thorn; &thorn;is by argumentis &thorn;at may not be asoylyd, so &thorn;at &thorn;ai be true seruandis to hym. For crist meni&thorn; &thorn;us in his arguynge &thorn;er: "Si&thorn; god fayle&thorn; not briddis<NOTE PLACE="marg">Matt. vi. [26.]</NOTE> <MILESTONE N="40b" UNIT="page">and lilyes and grasse &thorn;at growen in &thorn;e felde, nei&thorn;er he&thorn;en men, hou myche ra&thorn;er schal he not fayle his true seruandis." And so &thorn;is purvyance of perpetual almes, &thorn;at oure clerkis speken of, meni&thorn; fawte of bileue &amp; dispeire of &thorn;e gracious gouernance of god. Si&thorn; &thorn;an, as it is sayde bifore, it is noone almes to releue oo wreche and make an o&thorn;er or mo; and to make hem riche wi&thorn; temporalle lordeschip, &thorn;e whiche ben forfendit to siche peple; and namely if siche almes-&yogh;evynge be distroynge or apeyrynge of eny state aprevyd of god in his chirche, it wille sue &thorn;at &thorn;e endowynge of &thorn;e clergy wi&thorn; worldly lordeschipe ow&yogh;t not to be callid almes, but ra&thorn;er alle a mysse, or wastynge of goddis goodes, <MILESTONE N="41" UNIT="page">or distroynge of his 
<PB REF="00000455.tif" N="389"> ordenance, For as myche as &thorn;e clergi was sufficiently ordeynyd by criste. For whi &thorn;is almes &thorn;at clerkis speken of here made many wrechis, And it was &yogh;oue to hem &thorn;at hadde no nede. And &thorn;us it is enpeyringe not oonly of oone estate of &thorn;e chirche, but of alle &thorn;re, of &thorn;e whiche I spoke of in &thorn;e bigynnynge. And so &thorn;is almes-&yogh;evynge ha&thorn; made alle owre rewme, &yogh;he, &amp; as I suppose, fulle nye all crestyndome, full pore and nedy and myscheuous ouer &thorn;at it schuld have be if &thorn;e clergy had holde hem payde wi&thorn; cristis ordenance. But now &thorn;orou &thorn;is perpetual alamysse &thorn;at &thorn;e clerkis and religious folke callen almes, cristis ordenaunce is vndo in sum londis hooly, &amp; in ynglonde for &thorn;e more party. <MILESTONE N="41b" UNIT="page">And it is likly to be alle vndo in processe of tyme. For by amortesynge of lordeschipis &thorn;e lordis ben vndo in grete party. And &thorn;o &thorn;at ben lefte, by-cause &thorn;at hem lakki&thorn; her owne party &thorn;orow foly &yogh;ifte of her auncetreris, ben ful nedi. Fer&thorn;irmore it may be vndirstonde of &thorn;is processe &thorn;at wi&thorn;drawynge of &thorn;es lordeschipis from &thorn;e clergi, and restorynge of hem to &thorn;e statis &thorn;at god ha&thorn; assignyd hem to, schuld not be callid robbery of holy chirche, as oure clerkis sayen, but ra&thorn;er ri&yogh;twise restitucioun of goode wrongfully and &thorn;euely wi&thorn;holde. And &thorn;erfore &thorn;er may noon o&thorn;e or a-vow bynde eny man to mayntene &thorn;is &thorn;efte and distryinge of goddis ordenance, and &thorn;is greete harmynge of cristis chirche, as &thorn;e vow of iepte<NOTE PLACE="marg">Judges xi.</NOTE> schulde not have bounde <MILESTONE N="42" UNIT="page">him to kille &amp; to sacrifice his owne dou&yogh;ter. Ne &thorn;e o&thorn;e of herode schuld not haue bounde hym<NOTE PLACE="marg">Mark vi. [26.]</NOTE> to kill innocent Ion. But as Jepte schulde have broken his o&thorn;e or avow, and han offred an-o&thorn;er &thorn;inge &thorn;at had be plesynge to god and acordynge wi&thorn; his lawe, as saynt awstyn sai&thorn; vp-on &thorn;e same storie, so herode schuld have broke his o&thorn;e, and a-savyd innocent blode, and sore a|repentid hym for his vnavysid swerynge. And so schulden lordis nowe breke her o&thorn;is, &thorn;at &thorn;ai han unavisely and wi&thorn;oute cowncel of holy scripture sworne to mayntene &thorn;is &thorn;efte; &yogh;he, heresye and symonye, as it is proued bifore, &thorn;e whiche oure clerkis callen perpetual almes. And not &thorn;us sue 
<PB REF="00000456.tif" N="390"> her predecessouris or progenitouris in <MILESTONE N="42b" UNIT="page">her foly dedis and o&thorn;is &thorn;at &thorn;ai han made to mayntene &thorn;is mischeuous per|uertynge of cristis ordenance; for as &thorn;e state of &thorn;e clergi ha&thorn; no power ne leve to make &thorn;e peple or &thorn;e lordis to synne deedly, or to distroye goddis ordenance in his chirche, so &thorn;ai have no leve or power of god to cowncelle or to constreyne in eny case &thorn;e lordis or &thorn;e peple to swere to mayntene &thorn;is endowynge of &thorn;e clerkis and religyous folke, &thorn;e whiche is fulle grete &thorn;efte, heresy &amp; symony, and wondir harmfulle to cristis chirche; as it is schewyd in &thorn;is procese and in o&thorn;er writen bifore. But &thorn;e lordis specialy schulde se here what wer plesynge not to &thorn;es clerkis but to god. And &thorn;at schulde &thorn;ai do; for her-to &thorn;ai ben bounden by vertu of her office vp payne of dampnacion. And &thorn;er may no man dispence <MILESTONE N="43" UNIT="page">wi&thorn; hem of &thorn;at boonde, stondynge her state. for no man schuld putt an o&thorn;er grounde bisidis &thorn;at &thorn;at is putt, &thorn;e whiche is criste ihesu.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="10" TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Capitulum x.</HEAD>
<P>aNd &thorn;erfore men demen it a grete synne to &yogh;eue lande entaylid by mannys lawe fro &thorn;e persone or &thorn;e kynred &thorn;at it is entaylid to; &yogh;he, alle-&thorn;ou&yogh; it be not so &yogh;ouen for euer but for a litille tyme. And &thorn;ou&yogh; it be so &thorn;at &thorn;e persone or kynred, &thorn;at siche londe is &yogh;eue to, be nedy and haue leue by goddis lawe to occupie siche maner londe or lordeschip. and &thorn;is [is] demyd fulle grete synne amonge &thorn;e peple, not oonly to &thorn;e &yogh;euer, but also to &thorn;e takere, for bo&thorn;e &thorn;ai done dampnable wronge to hem &thorn;at it is entaylid to, as &thorn;e peple demi&thorn;; &yogh;he, alle-&thorn;ou&yogh; it be &yogh;oue for goode and true seruyce &thorn;at &thorn;e ressey|uour <MILESTONE N="43b" UNIT="page">ha&thorn; done to &thorn;e &yogh;euer bifore, or ellis bi way of almes of relevynge of &thorn;e persone or kynred &thorn;at is &yogh;eue to. Hou&yogh; myche ra&thorn;er &thorn;an, I pray &thorn;e, wi&thorn;-owte comparyson, is it a grete synne, as wel to &thorn;e ressaueris as to &thorn;e &yogh;eueris, to take &thorn;e lordeschip &thorn;e whiche god, &thorn;at ha&thorn; fulle lordeschip up-on alle &thorn;e worlde, ha&thorn; 
<PB REF="00000457.tif" N="391"> &yogh;oue bi perpetual lawe or ri&yogh;te to &thorn;e stade of seculer lordis, and &yogh;eue &thorn;is fro &thorn;at state, to &thorn;e whiche god entaylid &thorn;is lordeschip, to an-o&thorn;er straunge peple of an-o&thorn;ir lyne, &thorn;e whiche ha&thorn; ne&thorn;er nede ne leue of god for to ocupie it. And if oure prestis clayme ti&thorn;is as goodis in a maner entaylid to hem, for als myche as god in &thorn;e olde lawe had &yogh;oue &amp; entailed siche ti&thorn;is to &thorn;e kynred of levy and to noone o&thorn;er lyne; For criste cam of &thorn;e lynyage of <MILESTONE N="44" UNIT="page">Juda, to whiche lyne was no ti&thorn;is grauntid; And so as men supposen &thorn;is entaile was not expresly confermyd bi criste and his apostles to his prestis in &thorn;e new lawe. For as it is writen in policronicon, &thorn;e seven&thorn;e boke, gregor &thorn;e sexte ordenyd first ti&thorn;is to be payde to curatis oonly. And &yogh;itt &thorn;ai claymen so ferfor&thorn;li &thorn;es ti&thorn;is, &thorn;at no man lawfully may wi&thorn;-holde hem or minystre hem save &thorn;ai. Ne &thorn;ai may be turnyd or &yogh;ouen to eny o&thorn;er state or kynred saue oonly to hem, all-&thorn;ou&yogh; men wolden do &thorn;at undir coloure or bi titille of perpetualle almes; for &thorn;is schulde be demyd of &thorn;e clergy a dampnable synne &amp; dis|troynge of holy chirche &amp; sacrilege. Hou myche ra&thorn;er &thorn;en is it an hidous and a <MILESTONE N="44b" UNIT="page">dampnable synne, to &yogh;eue or to take away &thorn;e seculer lordeschipis fro &thorn;e state of seculer lordis, &thorn;e whiche god had &yogh;eue &amp; entaylid to hem, bi &thorn;e same lawe &amp; ri&yogh;te by &thorn;e whiche he had &yogh;ouen &thorn;e ti&thorn;is to &thorn;e prestis in &thorn;e olde lawe? and &thorn;is entaile was neuer interrupte or y-broken in-to cristis tyme &amp; his apostles; and &thorn;en &thorn;ai confermyd &thorn;is entayle bi lawe so stronge to &thorn;e seculer party &thorn;at no man, safe anticriste and his disciples, may openly enpugne &thorn;is entaile, as it is schewid bifore. And so as no man schuld presume to wi&thorn;drawe, wi&thorn;holde or turne &thorn;e ti&thorn;is fro &thorn;e state of presthode, as &thorn;ai sayne; so myche ra&thorn;er schuld no man presume bi &yogh;euynge or takynge to aliene &thorn;e temporal lorde|schips<MILESTONE N="45" UNIT="page"> fro &thorn;e state of seculer lordis. And &thorn;us clerkis han not so myche coloure to sai &thorn;at &thorn;e lordis &amp; &thorn;e lay peple robben holy chirche, if &thorn;ai wi&thorn;drew &thorn;e ti&thorn;is fro hem, for als miche as &thorn;ai han take her temporaltes fro hem. And &thorn;is takynge of &thorn;es temporaltes in-to &thorn;e handis of &thorn;e clergi ha&thorn; 
<PB REF="00000458.tif" N="392"> neuer &thorn;e lesse malice of robrye &amp; cause of malice in it sijlfe, for als miche as it is done by symylacion of holynes, &thorn;e whiche is double wickidnes. For &thorn;us lucifer robbid Adam<NOTE PLACE="marg">Gen. iii.</NOTE> bo&thorn;e of goodis of fortune, of kynde, and of grace. As &thorn;e clergi ha&thorn; robbid, and &yogh;it do&thorn;e, &thorn;e chirche of &thorn;es &thorn;re maner goodis; For ri&yogh;t as lucifer did &thorn;is harme to adam &amp; eue, vndir coloure of loue &amp; frendischip &amp; helpynge of hem, so done now&yogh; <MILESTONE N="45b" UNIT="page">his awngelis, &thorn;es ypocritis, &thorn;at transfigure hem sijlf in-to awngellis of li&yogh;t, and disseyuen &thorn;e pepill by fals by-heest of heuenly help, &thorn;at &thorn;ai willen procure to hem for her goodis as &thorn;ai sayen. And if a bischop and his colage, or an abbot and his couent, may not alien fro hem eny of &thorn;e temporalateis &thorn;at &thorn;ai han, ne &yogh;eue to her founder eny of &thorn;o possessions &thorn;at he ha&thorn; &yogh;oue hem, what nede &thorn;at euer he haue, I-bounden oonly by a posityue lawe or a tradycion &thorn;at &thorn;ai han hem sijlfe made; And if eny siche lordeschips be wi&thorn;|drawe, Alienyd or take fro hem by rechelesnes of her pre|decessouris, &thorn;ai ow&yogh;ten on all wise, &yogh;he, in-to &thorn;e de&thorn;e, labore to [gete] &thorn;o possessions in-to her hondis <MILESTONE N="46" UNIT="page">a&yogh;en, as &thorn;ai saien; Hou myche more &thorn;an schuld not a seculere lorde or a layman aliene fro hym &amp; his issue, or fro &thorn;e state of seculere lordis &thorn;e seculer lordeschippis &thorn;e whiche god ha&thorn; lymytid to &thorn;at state? Si&thorn; he is bounden by &thorn;e lawe of kynde for to ordeyne for his children. And ouer &thorn;is he is bounden by goddis lawe to susteyne &thorn;e state of seculer lordis, &thorn;e whiche is autorisid in &thorn;e chirche bi criste and his apostelis. Of &thorn;is processe &thorn;en, if a man take hede, he schal perceyue &thorn;e falsnes of &thorn;is glose, whan oure clerkis and religious folke saien &thorn;at &thorn;ai holden &thorn;es lordeschipis oonly by tytille of perpetual almes. For certis si&thorn; &thorn;es ti&thorn;is &amp; &thorn;is offryngis, &thorn;e whiche as I suppose cowntirvaylen &thorn;e seculer lordis rentis of &thorn;e rewme or <MILESTONE N="46b" UNIT="page">ellis passen as it is full likly (For &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;ai be lesse in oo chirche, &thorn;ai passen in an-o&thorn;er) and ben sufficient for alle &thorn;e prestis in cristendome, &amp; &thorn;ai wer euen delyd; &thorn;en it wer no nede to amortise seculer lordeschipis to &thorn;e state of &thorn;e clergi; &thorn;e whiche amortesynge is vndoynge of lordis &amp; apostasie of &thorn;e 
<PB REF="00000459.tif" N="393"> clergy. And if &thorn;is amortasynge wer not nedefulle, &thorn;en wer it noone almes, as it is declarid. And ouer &thorn;e ti&thorn;ingis and offeringes &thorn;at ben now of certeyne, &thorn;e clerkis han many grete &amp; smale perquisitiuys, &thorn;e whiche smachen of symony and extorcion; as &thorn;e first fruytis of vacant beneficis, prouynge of testamentis, for halowynge of chapels, chirchis, chauncellis and o&thorn;er ournementis of &thorn;e chirche, &amp; for sacrynge of ordres, &amp; fulle many mo &thorn;at for multitude may not <MILESTONE N="47" UNIT="page">wel be nowmbred. For welle ni&yogh; alle her blessyngis ben sett to sale and to prise in-to crystenynge &amp; confirmacion. wherfor I may now sai, as I sayd at &thorn;e bigynnynge; "Fundamentum aliud," &amp;cetera&mdash; "No man may putt an-o&thorn;er ground bysidis &thorn;at &thorn;at is putt, &thorn;e whiche is criste ihesu." &THORN;e whiche grounde of lyvynge criste graunte vs to kepe, &thorn;at we may ascape &thorn;e euerlastynge paynys of helle. Amen.</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="appendix">
<HEAD>[Appendix.]</HEAD>
<HEAD>[On the Wrongfulness of the Clergy holding Secular Office.]</HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="item">
<HEAD>Here-aftir it schal be schewid what peryl it is to prestis to be in seculer office, and to lordis to suffre hem &thorn;er-inne, or to excite hem &thorn;er-to.</HEAD>
<P>sEynt Cypriane sai&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;orow &thorn;e councelle of bischopis &thorn;er<NOTE PLACE="marg">xxj q. iij cap. Ciprianus.</NOTE> is made a statute, &thorn;at alle &thorn;at ben charchid wi&thorn; presthode <MILESTONE N="47b" UNIT="page">and ordeynyd in &thorn;e service of clerkis schulde not serue but to &thorn;e auter, and to mynystre sacramentis, and to take hede to prayers and orysons. Hit is for-so&thorn;e writen: "no man<NOTE PLACE="marg">2 Tim. ii. [4.]</NOTE> berynge his kny&yogh;thode to god entrike hym wi&thorn; seculer nedis;" &thorn;e whiche oure bischopis and oure predecessouris biholdynge religiously &amp; purveynge hoolsumly, dempten &thorn;at who so euer take mynystres of &thorn;e chirche fro spiritualle office to seculere, &thorn;at &thorn;er be noone offrynge done for hym, ne eny sacrifice halowyd for his sepulture. For &thorn;ai disserven not to be 
<PB REF="00000460.tif" N="394"> nempnyd byfore &thorn;e auter of god in &thorn;e prayer of prestis, &thorn;e whiche willen clepe away prestis &amp; mynystres of &thorn;e chirche fro &thorn;e auter. &THORN;is sai&thorn; saynte Cipriane. Here men mow se how perylous it is to &thorn;e kynge &amp; seculer lor<MILESTONE N="48" UNIT="page"> dis to wi&thorn;holde eny preste in seculer bissynes. &THORN;is is preuyd &thorn;us, for euery seculere lorde by &thorn;e lawe of &thorn;e gospelle is goddis bayly. But<NOTE PLACE="marg">Luke xvi. [1.]</NOTE> if eny bayly hiryd a werkeman wi&thorn; his lordis goode and putt hym to his owne seruyce, he must nede be vntrue to his lorde. Ri&yogh;t so is euery seculere lorde to oure lorde ihesu criste, but if he amende hym, &thorn;at taki&thorn; a preste and putti&thorn; hym in his seculer office; brekynge &thorn;e heest of his lorde god &thorn;at commaundi&thorn;: "&thorn;u schalt couett noon o&thorn;er mannys seruande." And he wi&thorn;drawi&thorn; hym fro &thorn;e seruyce of god &amp; fro &thorn;e kepynge of cristen mennys soulis, &thorn;e whiche he ha&thorn; take charge of, for whiche soulis oure lorde ihesu criste toke fleisch and blode, and suffred <MILESTONE N="48b" UNIT="page">harde de&thorn;e, and schedde his owne hert blode. &THORN;is perylous doynge of seculer lordis is bo&thorn;e a&yogh;ens goddis lawe and mannys. It is a&yogh;en goddis lawe; For as saynt poule sai&thorn;: "No man &thorn;at is a parfyte kny&yogh;te of god,<NOTE PLACE="marg">2 Tim. ii. [4.]</NOTE> as euery prest schulde be bi his ordre, entirmete hym wi&thorn; worldly nedis &amp; bissynessis." And for &thorn;is ende, &thorn;at he may so plese &thorn;at lorde to whose service he ha&thorn; putt hym-silfe, and &thorn;at is god. For siche worldly bissynes in clerkis is a&yogh;ens her ordre, and &thorn;erfore &thorn;e apostles sayden, as it is wryten in &thorn;e deedis of &thorn;e apostles: "It is not euen vs to forsake &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="marg">Acts vi. [2.]</NOTE> worde of god and mynystir to bordis of pore folke." And if it was vnequite, as &thorn;e apostles sayden in her common decre, hem for to leue &thorn;e prechynge of goddis worde &amp; ministre to &thorn;e <MILESTONE N="49" UNIT="page">bordis of pore men; hou myche more vnequite and wronge to god &amp; man is it, prestis to leve contemplacion, studie, preyere &amp; prechinge of goddis worde, and mynistrynge to pore folke, for &thorn;e service of a seculere lorde. Hit is also<NOTE PLACE="marg">iii. decre in fine.</NOTE> a&yogh;ens &thorn;e popis lawe; For he speki&thorn; to a bischop and biddi&thorn; hym &thorn;at [he] warne openly prestis and clerkis &thorn;at &thorn;ai be not occupied in seculer office, ne procuratouris of seculer lordis nedis &amp; her goodis. And if prestis and clerkis ben so bolde 
<PB REF="00000461.tif" N="395"> to occupie hem in siche bissynes, and if &thorn;ai falle aftir bi losse of lordis goodis; &thorn;an sai&thorn; &thorn;e lawe, it is not wor&thorn;i &thorn;at &thorn;ai be holpen and socoured of holy chirche, si&thorn; &thorn;orou hem holy chirche is sclaundred. And saynte gregori wrote to &thorn;e defen|soure of rome in &thorn;is maner: "It is tolde to vs &thorn;at oure moost reue<MILESTONE N="49b" UNIT="page">rent bro&thorn;er basile &thorn;e bischop is occupied in seculer causis, and kepi&thorn; vnprofetably moote hallis; whiche &thorn;inge maki&thorn; hym foule and distrye&thorn; &thorn;e reuerence of presthode. &THORN;erfore a-noone as &thorn;u hast ressayvid &thorn;is maundement, co[m]pell hym wi&thorn; scharp execucion to turne a&yogh;en. So &thorn;at it be not lefulle to &thorn;e by noone excusacion to tarye it fyve days; lest if in eny maner &thorn;u suffir hym eny langer to tary &thorn;er-inne, &thorn;u to be coupable wi&thorn; hym anentis vs." And so bischoppis &amp; o&thorn;ir prelatis ben holden to teche and enforme lordis to wi&thorn;draw hem fro &thorn;is synne, and scharply to repreue prestis and curatis vndir hem &thorn;at &thorn;ai ocupie no seculer office. &THORN;is is prouyd &thorn;us. &thorn;e holy prophete Ezechiel sai&thorn;: "If &thorn;e <MILESTONE N="50" UNIT="page">wayte or &thorn;e wacche-man se ennemys cum, and if &thorn;e peple be not warnyd &amp; kepe not hem sijlfe, but ennemys cummen &amp; sle &thorn;e peple; &thorn;en sai&thorn; god &thorn;at &thorn;e pepille is take in her wickidnes. And of &thorn;e waite &thorn;at schuld have blowe in his horne wille god axe acountis and reknynge of &thorn;e blode and of &thorn;e de&thorn;e of &thorn;e peple." But now to goostly vndirston[din]ge euery bischop schuld be a waite or a waccheman, to telle &amp; to warne byfore to alle &thorn;e peple by his goode lyvynge and techynge &thorn;e perelle of synne. And &thorn;is is &thorn;e reson whi bischoppis and o&thorn;ir prelatis &amp; prestis schulde not be occupied wi&thorn; worldly nedis and causis; For siche occupacions and chargis maken prestis slepynge &amp; slumbrynge in synne. And &thorn;erfore it is grete perelle to lordis to make <MILESTONE N="50b" UNIT="page">ouer hem goostly waytis and wacchemen, as bischoppis, persones and vikers, &thorn;at ben slepers &amp; slombreris in lustis of &thorn;e fleysch, &amp; blyndid wi&thorn; poudir of couetise of worldly riches, and so occupied in worldly nedis &thorn;at &thorn;ai nei&thorn;er kan ne may kepe hem sijlfe, ne noone o&thorn;er man. For of &thorn;is perelle &amp; siche o&thorn;ir a prelate &thorn;at ha&thorn; witt and kunnynge schuld scharply 
<PB REF="00000462.tif" N="396"> repreue &amp; warne alle maner men, to &thorn;e schedynge of his owne blode, as criste did; and if he leue &amp; blame not, &thorn;en he assenti&thorn; to her trespassis and synne&thorn; deedly. For as sai&thorn; &thorn;e prophete malachie: "prestis lippis kepyn kunynge, and &thorn;e <NOTE PLACE="marg">Malachi ii. [7.]</NOTE> pepille schal axe &thorn;e lawe of god of his mou&thorn;e; for he is &thorn;e awngelle of god if he kepe welle &thorn;e ordre &amp; &thorn;e degre of prest<MILESTONE N="51" UNIT="page">hode." And &thorn;erfore it is not lefulle to eny man to drawe to seculere office &thorn;e messangeris of criste, &thorn;at ha&thorn; so vttirly forfendit hem bo&thorn;e in worde and in dede seculere office in presthode.</P>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="authorities">
<HEAD>If eny man stonde in doute of &thorn;is sentence before; here suen autoritees of holy scripture and holy doctouris in latyn a&yogh;ens &thorn;e seculer lordeschip of prestis.</HEAD>
<P>cIvilis aut secularis possessio fuit interdicta sacerdotibus &amp; leuitis, ut patet Numer. xviii. Dixit dominus ad Aaron: <NOTE PLACE="marg">[Num. xviii.20.]</NOTE> In terra eorum nichil possidebitis, nec habebitis partem inter eos: Ego pars et hereditas tua in medio filiorum israell. ffilijs autem leui dedi omnes decimas israelis in possessionem, pro <MILESTONE N="51b" UNIT="page">ministerio quo seruiunt mihi in tabernaculo federis. Sequitur: Solis filiis leui mihi in tabernaculo seruientibus, &amp; portantibus peccata populi, legittimum sempiternum erit in generacionibus vestris. Nichil aliud possidebunt, deci|marum oblacione contenti, quas in usus eorum<NOTE PLACE="foot">earum MS.</NOTE> et necessaria separaui. Item Deut. xviii<SUP>o</SUP>: Non habebunt sacerdotes et <NOTE PLACE="marg">[Deut. xviii. 1.]</NOTE> leuite &amp; omnes qui de eadem tribu sunt partem &amp; hereditatem cum reliquo populo israel; quia sacrificia domini et oblaciones eius comedent, et nihil aliud accipient de possessione fratrum suorum. Deus enim ipse est hereditas eorum, sicut locutus est illis. Super quo glosa: Ministris altaris nec terrenis possessionibus adquirendis concessum est inhiare. vnde Matt. x<SUP>o</SUP>: Nolite possidere aurum, neque argentum, neque <NOTE PLACE="marg">[Matt. x. 9.]</NOTE> 
<PB REF="00000463.tif" N="397"> pecuniam &amp;c<SUP>a</SUP>. et post pauca: dignus est operarius cibo suo. Et alibi, Qui altari deseruiunt cum altare <MILESTONE N="52" UNIT="page">participant. Non<NOTE PLACE="marg">[1 Cor. ix. 13.]</NOTE> enim opertum, quod qui semper altari debent seruire officio diuino, inhient terreno lucro, quibus dominus hereditas est. Quid ergo illi deesse potest qui omnia habentem habet. hec ibi. Item ezechiel xliiii: Non autem erit eis hereditas,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Ezek. xliv. 28.]</NOTE> ego hereditas eorum: et possessionem non dabitis eis in israel, ego enim possessio eorum. Victimam pro peccato et pro delicto ipsi comedent, et omne votum in israel ipsorum erit. Super quo Jeronimus, libro xiii<SUP>o</SUP> super ezechielem: Qui autem talis extiterit ut ministret in sanctuario, et ingrediatur atrium interius, et offerat deo sacrificium, ita ut verus sacerdos sit, ymmo imitator eius de quo scriptum est, tu es sacerdos in eternum secundum ordinem melchisedech; iste nullam habebit partem nisi deum, qui est hereditas eius, nec accipiet possessionem in israel, hoc est inter vulgus ignobile, sed sacerdotalem, ut dicat de eo dominus: ego sum possessio et hereditas eius; quem cum venerit loquatur ac dicat, <MILESTONE N="52b" UNIT="page">tenebo illum nec dimittam illum; et psallet cum propheta, pars mea dominus. hec ille. Item, deut<SUP>o</SUP> x<SUP>o</SUP>: Non<NOTE PLACE="marg">Deut. [x. 9.]</NOTE> habuit leui partem in possessionibus cum fratribus suis, quia ipse dominus possessio eius, sicut promisit ei. Item, Josue<NOTE PLACE="marg">Josh. [xiv. 4.]</NOTE> xiiii: non acceperunt aliam in terra partem nisi urbes ad habitandum, et suburbana earum ad alenda iumenta et pecora. Item, eccl. xlv<SUP>o</SUP>: Nam sacrificia domini edent, que<NOTE PLACE="marg">Ecclus. [xlv. 26.]</NOTE> dedit ipsi et semini eius. ceterum in terra gens<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>sic.</I> MS. Vulgate, gentis.</NOTE> non hereditabit, et pars non est illi in gente. ipse enim pars eius est et hereditas. Item, Mat. xx<SUP>o</SUP>: Scitis quia principes<NOTE PLACE="marg">Matt. [xx. 25.]</NOTE> gencium dominantur eorum, et qui maiores sunt potestatem exercent in eos; non ita erit inter vos, sed quicumque voluerit inter vos maior esse, sit vester minister. Et quicumque voluerit inter vos primus esse, erit vester seruus. Sicut filius hominis non venit ministrari sed ministrare, et dare animam suam redempcionem pro multis. Idem patet 
<PB REF="00000464.tif" N="398"> Mat x<SUP>o</SUP> et luce xxii<SUP>o</SUP>. Item prima petri quinto: <MILESTONE N="53" UNIT="page">Pascite qui<NOTE PLACE="marg">[1 Pet. v. 2.]</NOTE> in vobis est gregem domini, prouidentes non coacti sed spontanee secundum deum: neque turpis lucri gracia, sed voluntarie: neque dominantes in clero, sed forma facti gregis ex animo. Item ad Thi<SUP>m</SUP> vi<SUP>o</SUP>: Habentes autem alimenta et<NOTE PLACE="marg">[1 Tim. vi. 8.]</NOTE> quibus tegamur, hijs contenti simus. Nam qui volunt diuites fieri incidunt in temptacionem et in laqueum diaboli. Item, luce xiv: Sic ergo omnis ex vobis qui non renunciat omnibus<NOTE PLACE="marg">Luke [xiv. 33.]</NOTE> que possidet, non potest meus esse discipulus. Item, Bernardus libro ij ad Eugenium papam: Esto, ut alia<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Bernardus de Consideratione, lib. ii. cap. vi.]</NOTE> quacumque racione hec tibi vendices; sed non apostolico iure. nec enim ille tibi dare potuit quod non habuit: quod autem habuit, hoc dedit, sollicitudinem super ecclesias, numquid dominacionem. Audi ipsum. Non dominantes in clero, sed forma facti gregis ex animo. Et ne dictum sola humilitate putes; nonne eciam veritate. Vox enim domini est in euangelio. luce xxij<SUP>o</SUP>: Reges gencium dominantur<NOTE PLACE="marg">Luke [xxii. 25.]</NOTE> eorum; et infert, vos autem non sic. Planum est, apostolis interdicitur dominatus. Ergo tu et tibi usurpare audes aut dominans apostolatum, aut apostolicus<NOTE PLACE="foot">apostolatus MS.</NOTE> dominatum. Plane ab alterutro prohiberis. Si utrumque simul habere velis, perdis utrumque. Alioquin non te exceptum putes de illo numero, de quibus sic conqueritur deus, Osee octavo: Ipsi<NOTE PLACE="marg">Hosea [viii. 4.]</NOTE> regnauerunt sed non ex me. At si interdictum tenemus, audiamus edictum. luce xxii. Qui maior est vestrum, ait,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Luke [xxii. 26.]</NOTE> fiat sicut iunior, et qui precessor est sicut qui ministrat. fforma apostolica hec est; Dominacio interdicitur, indicitur ministracio. hec ibi. Item, Origenes super gen. omelia xvi<SUP>o</SUP>. Denique vis scire quid intersit inter sacerdotes domini et sacerdotes pharaonis. Pharao terras concedit sacerdotibus suis, dominus autem sacerdotibus suis partem non concedit in terra, sed dicit eis: Ego pars vestra. Obseruate ergo qui hec legitis, omnes domini sacerdotes, et videte que sit differencia sacerdotum, ne forte qui partem habent in terra, 
<PB REF="00000465.tif" N="399"> et terrenis cultibus <MILESTONE N="54" UNIT="page">ac studijs vacant, non tam domini quam pharaonis sacerdotes esse videantur. Ille enim est qui vult sacerdotes suos habere possessiones, et exercere agri non anime culturam, Ruri sed non legi operam dare. Christus autem, dominus noster, sacerdotibus suis quid precipit audiamus: Qui non, inquit, renunciauerit omnibus que possidet, non potest meus esse discipulus. Negat christus suum esse discipulum quem viderit aliquid possidentem, et eum qui non renunciat omnibus que possidet. Et quid agimus? qui hec aut ipsi legimus, aut populis exponimus, qui non solum non renunciamus hijs que possidemus, sed &amp; adquirere volumus ea que nunquam habuimus antequam veniremus ad papatum.<NOTE PLACE="foot">'Christum' Origen.</NOTE> &amp;c<SUP>a</SUP>. per processum. Item, parysiensis libro de vicijs, titulo de auaricia mercenariorum: Sciebat dominus oculum ecclesie impediendum esse temporalibus istis ab officio suo; Modicum enim pulueris vel <MILESTONE N="54b" UNIT="page">palee oculum omnino cessare facit ab officio suo. Immo voluit duces ecclesie pauperes esse, eo quod paupertas expedita est, sicut seneca dicit, et subdit: Si vis omnino vacare ut pauper sis, ora ut pauperi sis similis. Et si cetera membra corporis ad plura officia conueniant, ut lingua ad gustum et loquelam, et manus ad multa similiter, oculus tantum vnum habet, et contactum terre maxime timet. Sic oculus ecclesie con|templatiuus legi diuine debuit intendere, et a terrenis istis seperari. licet pes hominis a ceteris membris eius seperatus non sit, tamen habet seperatam artem que ei deseruit, &amp; artifices qui ei totaliter circa calciamenta eius intenti sunt. Quanto magis debent esse aliqui qui totaliter spiritualibus sint intenti. Sed hodie magis occupata est ecclesia in temporalibus, quo ad magnam partem suam, quam fuerat sinagoga. vnde quum fuit datum a <MILESTONE N="55" UNIT="page">constantino imperium occidentali ecclesie, facta est vox de celo, dicens: hodie infusum est venenum ecclesie dei. hec ille. Item Odo in sermone, Estote misericordes: Stercora putredinis sunt diuicie, 
<PB REF="00000466.tif" N="400"> quibus volucres celi, i. demones, excecant oculos cupidorum. Et bene dicuntur diuicie stercora demonum, quum omnes diuicias reputant tanquam stercora, nec querunt nisi animam, vnde diues quum moritur quasi in tres porciones diuiditur; mundus rapit diuicias, vermes cadauer, et demones animam. Et quilibet contentus sua porcione alterius partem non desiderat; vnde versus:</P>
<P>Spiritus est sathane, caro vermis, mammona mundi; Vnica plus duplici pars sua cuique<NOTE PLACE="foot">cuilibet MS.</NOTE> placet.</P>
<P>Item non tantum a demonibus sed a perfectis diuicie stercora reputantur; vnde apostolus: Omnia reputaui tamquam<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Phil. iii. 8.]</NOTE> stercora ut christum lucrifacerem. Pro hijs stercoribus causidici clamant in foro; clerici quoque cantant in choro; medici cum egrotis vigilant <MILESTONE N="55b" UNIT="page">in thalamo. Pro hijs stercoribus frequenter illicita committuntur in mundo. Sequitur: pocius cum thobia gaudeamus, qui, curata cecitate quam per stercora contraxerat, visum recuperauit. Sic cum diuicie auferuntur oculum iusticie recuperamus. Cum gladius furioso aufertur, sanitate restituta, gracias refert illi qui abstulit. Similiter si dolemus pro ablacione temporalium, quibus excecamur, quibus interficimur, furiosi sumus. Et reddita nobis dis|crecione, saltem in alia vita, illi qui nobis stercora ab oculis nostris extersit, illi qui gladium abstulit gracias referemus. Alibi appellantur venenum; vnde eodem die quo a constantino dotata est ecclesia, in aere audita est vox angelica, dicens; hodie infusum est venenum in ecclesia; maior quidem effecta est in dignitate, sed minor religione. Item Odo in sermone Ecce nos reliquimus omnia: Abel moritur i. cura pastoralis, luctus spiritualis interimitur, set <MILESTONE N="56" UNIT="page">caym, i. possessio, conser|uatur; ymmo pastor animarum caym agricola efficitur. Non enim in ecclesia queritur si sciat bene docere, pro peccatis lugere, set si sit caym, i. agricola; si sciat terras bene colere. Nec mirum si multos interficit possessio, cum sit venenum; 
<PB REF="00000467.tif" N="401"> vnde eodem die quo dotata est ecclesia a constantino audita est vox in aere: hodie infusum est venenum in ecclesia; maior quidem dignitate, set minor religione. Si queritur: vbi est ouis tibi commissa? respondet: Numquid custos fratris mei sum? quasi, Que cura est mihi de animabus, dummodo disponatur bene de temporalibus. Tales sicut caim sunt maledicti qui educunt ouem abel, et non reducunt, set seducunt. vnde Ezechiel: Pastores eorum seduxerunt eos. Item Gorham super illo Apoc. xii<SUP>o</SUP>: Misit serpens ex ore suo post mulierem aquam tanquam flumen, &amp;c. Per aquam fluminis significatur <MILESTONE N="56b" UNIT="page">abundancia temporalis, que fluit cotidie sicut aqua. vnde psalmista: diuicie si affluant, nolite cor apponere. hanc aquam habundantissime misit draco in ecclesiam dei, domino permittente, quum a constantino datum est imperium occidentali ecclesie; vnde tunc audita est vox angelorum<NOTE PLACE="foot">anglorum MS.</NOTE> in aere dicencium: hodie infusum est venenum in ecclesia dei; sicut legitur in apocrifo Siluestri. Et quia iam appropinquat venenum hoc ad cor ecclesie, ita ut iam sit suffocacio proxima, clamat ipsa ecclesia cum psalmista: Saluum me fac, deus, quoniam intrauerunt aque usque ad animam meam. Et deus de sua bonitate nunc primo incipit audire ecclesiam suam, et misit adiutorem suum, scilicet terram, que absorbere vult totum flumen; vel principem terrenum, qui vult auferre ab ecclesia omnia temporalia sua, licet intencio non eadem sit cum domino, qui propter bonum ecclesie mittit illum ex misericordia. hec ille. Item Jeronymus in vitis patrum: Ecclesia ex quo creuit in possessionibus, decreuit in virtutibus. Item Jeronimus ad ne<MILESTONE N="57" UNIT="page">pocianum ep. xxxiiii: Aut aurum repudiemus nos, sc. clerici, cum ceteris supersticionibus iudeorum, aut si aurum placeat, placeant et iudei, quos cum auro aut probare necesse est nobis aut dampnare. Item Jeronymus ad nepocianum: Clericus qui christi seruit ecclesie primo interpretetur vocab[u]lum suum, et nominis diffinicione prolata, nitatur esse quod dicitur. Si enim cleros grece latine 
<PB REF="00000468.tif" N="402"> sors appellatur, propterea clerici dicuntur quia de sorte sunt domini, vel quia dominus ipse sors, i. pars, clericorum est. Et quia et ipse pars domini est, et dominum partem habet, talem se exhibere debet, ut ipse possideat dominum et possideatur a domino. Qui enim dominum possidet, et cum propheta dicit: pars mea dominus, nichil extra dominum possidere potest; nam si quippiam aliud habuerit preter dominum, pars eius non erit dominus. verbi gracia, si aurum, si argentum, si possessionem, si variam suppellectilem habuerit, cum istis partibus dominus pars eius fieri non dignatur. Et paulo post: habens victum et vestitum hijs contentus ero, <MILESTONE N="57b" UNIT="page">et nudus nudam crucem sequar. Obsecro te itaque repetens, iterum iterumque monebo, ne officium clericatus genus antique milicie puteo, ne lucrum seculi in christi queras milicia, ne plus habeas quam quando clericus esse cepisti.</P>
<P>Here suen autorites in latyn of holy scripture and doctouris a&yogh;ens seculeris office of prestis.</P>
<P>pAulus apostolus dicit ij thi. ij<SUP>o</SUP> ad excludendum prelatos<NOTE PLACE="marg">[2 Tim. ii. 4.]</NOTE> et sacerdotes ab omni seculari officio isto modo: Nemo militans deo implicat se negocijs secularibus, ut ei placeat cui se probauit. Iste autem textus breuis et compendiosus apostoli, ex fide quam importat, excluderet omnes sacerdotes et pure clericos ab omni officio seculari. Quum seculare officium est destructiuum cure pastoralis. Immo ex canone apostolorum dicitur: <MILESTONE N="58" UNIT="page">Episcopus aut sacerdos aut diaconus nequaquam<NOTE PLACE="marg">lxxxviij. de cap<SUP>o</SUP>. Eps.</NOTE> seculares curas assumant. Sin autem assumpserint deiciantur; quia, ut dicit gregorius ibidem, Inutile et valde laboriosum est hominem litteratum raciocinacionum causas assumere, et in eis que non expedit se obligare. Item, ibidem dicit beatus ciprianus, cap<SUP>o</SUP> neque: In dispensacione ecclesie hanc regulam obseruandam nouerit unusquisque, ut nulli quantumlibet exercitate persone duo simul officia committat. Immo nomine sacerdotis careat qui dei ministros a suis evocet officiis. Et idem Ciprianus dicit quod ministri ecclesie debent solum 
<PB REF="00000469.tif" N="403"> altari et sacrificiis deseruire, et precibus, studijs et oracionibus vacare. Et si quis eos a spirituali officio ad seculare duxeret, non offeretur pro eo oblacio, nec sacrificium pro sepultura eius celebrabitur; non enim ante altare dei merentur nominari in sacerdotum prece qui sacerdotes et ministros ecclesie ab altari volunt avocare. Immo dicit beatus Augustinus: ffornicari hominibus nunquam licet, negociari autem <MILESTONE N="58b" UNIT="page">aliquibus<NOTE PLACE="marg">lxxxviij. de c<SUP>o</SUP>. ffornicari.</NOTE> licet, aliis non licet. Antequam enim ecclesiasticus quis sit, licet ei negociari; facto ecclesiastico iam non licet. Item ibidem scribitur sic: Tuicionem testamentorum episcopus non suscipiat. episcopus nullam rei familiaris curam ad se reuocet, set leccioni et oracioni et verbo predicacionis tantummodo vacet. Item beatus petrus in epistola ad clementem dicit<NOTE PLACE="marg">xi. q. 1<SUP>o</SUP>. c<SUP>o</SUP>.</NOTE> Sicut enim impietatis est crimen tibi, o clemens, neglectis verbi dei studijs sollicitudines seculares suscipere, ita vnicuique laicorum peccatum est nisi inuicem sibi ecclesiam in hijs que ad communis vsum vite pertinent operam fideliter dederint. Ideo concludit lex canonica apostolorum statuta sunt que dicunt: Nemo militans deo implicat se &amp;c<SUP>a</SUP>. Proinde aut<NOTE PLACE="marg">xi. q. iij. co. Credo.</NOTE> clerici sint sine accionibus dominorum aut actores sine officio clericorum. Et uniuersi dixerunt; hec obseruemus. Item ibidem sic scribitur hij qui in ecclesia domini ad ordinem promouentur clericorum, in nullo <MILESTONE N="59" UNIT="page">ab administracione diuina auocentur, nec molestiis et negociis secularibus alligentur ut ab altaribus &amp; sacrificijs recedant; set die ac nocte celestibus rebus et spiritualibus seruiant Item beatus petrus in epistola ad clementem sic scribit: Te quidem oportet irreprehensibilem<NOTE PLACE="marg">xi. q. 1<SUP>o</SUP>. c<SUP>o</SUP> Te quidem.</NOTE> viuere, et summo studio niti ut omnes vite huius occupaciones abicias. Non fide-iussor existas nec aduocatus licium fias, ne in ulla occupacione prorsus inueniaris mundialis negocii occasione perplexus. Neque enim iudicem neque cognitorem secularium negociacionum te ordinare vult christus, ne pre|focatus presentibus hominum curis, non possis verbo dei vacare. Hec vero opera que minus tibi congruere diximus exhibeant sibi inuicem vacantes laici, et te nemo occupet ab hijs studijs per que salus datur hominibus &amp;c<SUP>a</SUP>. Item 
<PB REF="00000470.tif" N="404"> gregorius Romano defensori: perlatum est, inquit, ad nos<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Decreti pars la. Dist. lxxxviii. cap. 4.]</NOTE> reuerendissimum fratrem nostrum, basilium episcopum, velut vnum de laicis in causis secularibus <MILESTONE N="59b" UNIT="page">occupari, et pretorijs inutiliter obseruire; que res quidem et ipsum vilem reddit, et reuerentiam sacerdotalem adnichilat. statim ut experiencia tua hoc preceptum susceperit, ad reuertendum eum districta executione compellat, Quatenus te illic consistente quinque diebus sub qualibet excusatione immorari non liceat. Ne si quolibet modo eum ibidem amplius moram habere permiseris, cum ipso apud nos grauiter incipias esse culpabilis, &amp;c.</P>
<P>Ista ad presens sufficiunt cum diligenti scripturarum excercitatione ad excitandum sacerdotes ne curis secularibus se subiciant; set oracioni, studio et predicacioni intendant, et sic, spiritualibus inimicis deuictis, soli deo placere studeant; ut cum ipso in celestibus regnare valeant; prestante domino nostro ihesu christo, qui cum patre et spiritu sancto vivit &amp; regnat deus. Amen.</P>


